"{\n    \"[1, 2]\": [\n        [\n            43415,\n            \"The children are all hanging about her already, as if she was an old acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44694,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have a notion,\\u201dsaid Lucy, \\u201cyou think the little Middletons rather too much indulged;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44889,\n            \"\\u201cWe have heard Sir John admire it excessively,\\u201dsaid Lucy, who seemed to think some apology necessary for the freedom of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45325,\n            \"Anne,\\u201dcried her sister, \\u201cyou can talk of nothing but beaux;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46356,\n            \"and to the invariable coldness of her behaviour towards them, which checked every endeavour at intimacy on their side, Elinor principally attributed that preference of herself which soon became evident in the manners of both, but especially of Lucy, who missed no opportunity of engaging her in conversation, or of striving to improve their acquaintance by an easy and frank communication of her sentiments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46469,\n            \"and her deficiency of all mental improvement, her want of information in the most common particulars, could not be concealed from Miss Dashwood, in spite of her constant endeavour to appear to advantage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46583,\n            \"whose want of instruction prevented their meeting in conversation on terms of equality, and whose conduct toward others made every show of attention and deference towards herself perfectly valueless.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46614,\n            \"\\u201cYou will think my question an odd one, I dare say,\\u201dsaid Lucy to her one day, as they were walking together from the park to the cottage \\u2014 \\u201cbut pray, are you personally acquainted with your sister-in-law\\u2019s mother, Mrs. Ferrars?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46847,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor made her a civil reply, and they walked on for a few minutes in silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47028,\n            \"But really I never understood that you were at all connected with that family, and therefore I am a little surprised, I confess, at so serious an inquiry into her character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47084,\n            \"But if I dared tell you all, you would not be so much surprised.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47100,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars is certainly nothing to me at present \\u2014 but the time _ may _ come \\u2014 how soon it will come must depend upon herself \\u2014 when we may be very intimately connected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47355,\n            \"for I dare say he never dropped the smallest hint of it to you or any of your family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47401,\n            \"Not a soul of all my relations know of it but Anne, and I never should have mentioned it to you, if I had not felt the greatest dependence in the world upon your secrecy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47466,\n            \"And I do not think Mr. Ferrars can be displeased, when he knows I have trusted you, because I know he has the highest opinion in the world of all your family, and looks upon yourself and the other Miss Dashwoods quite as his own sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47619,\n            \"\\u201cI did not know,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cthat you were even acquainted till the other day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47735,\n            \"It was there our acquaintance begun, for my sister and me was often staying with my uncle, and it was there our engagement was formed, though not till a year after he had quitted as a pupil;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47785,\n            \"I was very unwilling to enter into it, as you may imagine, without the knowledge and approbation of his mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47831,\n            \"Though you do not know him so well as me, Miss Dashwood, you must have seen enough of him to be sensible he is very capable of making a woman sincerely attached to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47961,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe can mean no other,\\u201dcried Lucy, smiling.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48092,\n            \"You knew nothing of me, or my family, and, therefore, there could be no _ occasion _ for ever mentioning my name to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48428,\n            \"\\u201cI am sure,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cI have no doubt in the world of your faithfully keeping this secret, because you must know of what importance it is to us, not to have it reach his mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48472,\n            \"for she would never approve of it, I dare say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48484,\n            \"I shall have no fortune, and I fancy she is an exceeding proud woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48615,\n            \"\\u201cI was afraid you would think I was taking a great liberty with you,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cin telling you all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48753,\n            \"indeed, she does me a great deal more harm than good, for I am in constant fear of her betraying me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48777,\n            \"She does not know how to hold her tongue, as you must perceive, and I am sure I was in the greatest fright in the world t\\u2019other day, when Edward\\u2019s name was mentioned by Sir John, lest she should out with it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48829,\n            \"You can\\u2019t think how much I go through in my mind from it altogether.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48923,\n            \"\\u201d continued Lucy, after wiping her eyes, \\u201cI think whether it would not be better for us both to break off the matter entirely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49083,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTo be sure,\\u201dcontinued Lucy, after a few minutes silence on both sides, \\u201chis mother must provide for him sometime or other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49138,\n            \"He was so miserable when he left us at Longstaple, to go to you, that I was afraid you would think him quite ill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49310,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI begged him to exert himself for fear you should suspect what was the matter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49328,\n            \"but it made him so melancholy, not being able to stay more than a fortnight with us, and seeing me so much affected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49401,\n            \"\\u201cYou know his hand, I dare say, \\u2014 a charming one it is;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49569,\n            \"\\u201cWriting to each other,\\u201dsaid Lucy, returning the letter into her pocket, \\u201cis the only comfort we have in such long separations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50389,\n            \"If in the supposition of his seeking to marry herself, his difficulties from his mother had seemed great, how much greater were they now likely to be, when the object of his engagement was undoubtedly inferior in connections, and probably inferior in fortune to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50891,\n            \"She wanted to hear many particulars of their engagement repeated again, she wanted more clearly to understand what Lucy really felt for Edward, whether there were any sincerity in her declaration of tender regard for him, and she particularly wanted to convince Lucy, by her readiness to enter on the matter again, and her calmness in conversing on it, that she was no otherwise interested in it than as a friend, which she very much feared her involuntary agitation, in their morning discourse, must have left at least doubtful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51637,\n            \"it produced not one novelty of thought or expression, and nothing could be less interesting than the whole of their discourse both in the dining parlour and drawing room: to the latter, the children accompanied them, and while they remained there, she was too well convinced of the impossibility of engaging Lucy\\u2019s attention to attempt it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51875,\n            \"I would not disappoint the little angel for all the world: and if you want me at the card-table now, I am resolved to finish the basket after supper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51936,\n            \"My poor little girl would be sadly disappointed, I know, if the basket was not finished tomorrow, for though I told her it certainly would not, I am sure she depends upon having it done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51976,\n            \"\\u201d Lucy directly drew her work table near her and reseated herself with an alacrity and cheerfulness which seemed to infer that she could taste no greater delight than in making a filigree basket for a spoilt child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52183,\n            \"\\u201cPerhaps,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cif I should happen to cut out, I may be of some use to Miss Lucy Steele, in rolling her papers for her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52430,\n            \"Lucy made room for her with ready attention, and the two fair rivals were thus seated side by side at the same table, and, with the utmost harmony, engaged in forwarding the same work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52554,\n            \"\\u201cI should be undeserving of the confidence you have honoured me with, if I felt no desire for its continuance, or no farther curiosity on its subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52885,\n            \"you seem to me to be surrounded with difficulties, and you will have need of all your mutual affection to support you under them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52911,\n            \"Mr. Ferrars, I believe, is entirely dependent on his mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52984,\n            \"but I love him too well to be the selfish means of robbing him, perhaps, of all that his mother might give him if he married to please her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53147,\n            \"\\u201cEdward\\u2019s love for me,\\u201dsaid Lucy, \\u201chas been pretty well put to the test, by our long, very long absence since we were first engaged, and it has stood the trial so well, that I should be unpardonable to doubt it now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53240,\n            \"\\u201cI am rather of a jealous temper too by nature, and from our different situations in life, from his being so much more in the world than me, and our continual separation, I was enough inclined for suspicion, to have found out the truth in an instant, if there had been the slightest alteration in his behaviour to me when we met, or any lowness of spirits that I could not account for, or if he had talked more of one lady than another, or seemed in any respect less happy at Longstaple than he used to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53506,\n            \"But Mrs. Ferrars is a very headstrong proud woman, and in her first fit of anger upon hearing it, would very likely secure every thing to Robert, and the idea of that, for Edward\\u2019s sake, frightens away all my inclination for hasty measures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53668,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo sister,\\u201dcried Lucy, \\u201cyou are mistaken there, our favourite beaux are _ not _ great coxcombs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53758,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh,\\u201dcried Miss Steele, looking significantly round at them, \\u201cI dare say Lucy\\u2019s beau is quite as modest and pretty behaved as Miss Dashwood\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53802,\n            \"Lucy bit her lip, and looked angrily at her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53823,\n            \"Lucy first put an end to it by saying in a lower tone, though Marianne was then giving them the powerful protection of a very magnificent concerto, \\u2014 \\u201cI will honestly tell you of one scheme which has lately come into my head, for bringing matters to bear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53916,\n            \"now my plan is that he should take orders as soon as he can, and then through your interest, which I am sure you would be kind enough to use out of friendship for him, and I hope out of some regard to me, your brother might be persuaded to give him Norland living;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54282,\n            \"and I do really believe, that if you was to say to me, \\u2018 I advise you by all means to put an end to your engagement with Edward Ferrars, it will be more for the happiness of both of you,\\u2019I should resolve upon doing it immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54396,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201c\\u2019Tis because you are an indifferent person,\\u201dsaid Lucy, with some pique, and laying a particular stress on those words, \\u201cthat your judgment might justly have such weight with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54641,\n            \"Anne and me are to go the latter end of January to some relations who have been wanting us to visit them these several years!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55255,\n            \"I am sure your mother can spare you very well, and I _ do _ beg you will favour me with your company, for I\\u2019ve quite set my heart upon it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55291,\n            \"Don\\u2019t fancy that you will be any inconvenience to me, for I shan\\u2019t put myself at all out of my way for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55320,\n            \"It will only be sending Betty by the coach, and I hope I can afford _ that _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55353,\n            \"and when we are in town, if you do not like to go wherever I do, well and good, you may always go with one of my daughters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55385,\n            \"I am sure your mother will not object to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55396,\n            \"for I have had such good luck in getting my own children off my hands that she will think me a very fit person to have the charge of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55427,\n            \"and if I don\\u2019t get one of you at least well married before I have done with you, it shall not be my fault.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55455,\n            \"I shall speak a good word for you to all the young men, you may depend upon it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55475,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have a notion,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cthat Miss Marianne would not object to such a scheme, if her elder sister would come into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55560,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cI am sure I shall be monstrous glad of Miss Marianne\\u2019s company, whether Miss Dashwood will go or not, only the more the merrier say I, and I thought it would be more comfortable for them to be together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55616,\n            \"because, if they got tired of me, they might talk to one another, and laugh at my odd ways behind my back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55642,\n            \"But one or the other, if not both of them, I must have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55662,\n            \"how do you think I can live poking by myself, I who have been always used till this winter to have Charlotte with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55776,\n            \"But my mother, my dearest, kindest mother, \\u2014 I feel the justice of what Elinor has urged, and if she were to be made less happy, less comfortable by our absence \\u2014 Oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57091,\n            \"and as for the Miss Steeles, especially Lucy, they had never been so happy in their lives as this intelligence made them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80744,\n            \"but for my part I declare I never think about him from one hour\\u2019s end to another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80817,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAye, aye, that is very pretty talking \\u2014 but it won\\u2019t do \\u2014 the Doctor is the man, I see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80903,\n            \"\\u201cI suppose you will go and stay with your brother and sister, Miss Dashwood, when they come to town,\\u201dsaid Lucy, returning, after a cessation of hostile hints, to the charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80953,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh, yes, I dare say you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81119,\n            \"but such old friends as Lucy and me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81225,\n            \"but she was saved the trouble of checking it, by Lucy\\u2019s sharp reprimand, which now, as on many occasions, though it did not give much sweetness to the manners of one sister, was of advantage in governing those of the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85671,\n            \"So well had they recommended themselves to Lady Middleton, so agreeable had their assiduities made them to her, that though Lucy was certainly not so elegant, and her sister not even genteel, she was as ready as Sir John to ask them to spend a week or two in Conduit Street;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85820,\n            \"and Lucy, who had long wanted to be personally known to the family, to have a nearer view of their characters and her own difficulties, and to have an opportunity of endeavouring to please them, had seldom been happier in her life, than she was on receiving Mrs. John Dashwood\\u2019s card.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85968,\n            \"They were relieved however, not by her own recollection, but by the good will of Lucy, who believed herself to be inflicting a severe disappointment when she told her that Edward certainly would not be in Harley Street on Tuesday, and even hoped to be carrying the pain still farther by persuading her that he was kept away by the extreme affection for herself, which he could not conceal when they were together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86076,\n            \"\\u201d said Lucy, as they walked up the stairs together \\u2014 for the Middletons arrived so directly after Mrs. Jennings, that they all followed the servant at the same time: \\u2014 \\u201cthere is nobody here but you, that can feel for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86135,\n            \"In a moment I shall see the person that all my happiness depends on \\u2014 that is to be my mother!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86157,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor could have given her immediate relief by suggesting the possibility of its being Miss Morton\\u2019s mother, rather than her own, whom they were about to behold;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86190,\n            \"but instead of doing that, she assured her, and with great sincerity, that she did pity her \\u2014 to the utter amazement of Lucy, who, though really uncomfortable herself, hoped at least to be an object of irrepressible envy to Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86443,\n            \"She could not but smile to see the graciousness of both mother and daughter towards the very person \\u2014 for Lucy was particularly distinguished \\u2014 whom of all others, had they known as much as she did, they would have been most anxious to mortify;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86566,\n            \"and Miss Steele wanted only to be teazed about Dr. Davies to be perfectly happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86978,\n            \"Lucy, who was hardly less anxious to please one parent than the other, thought the boys were both remarkably tall for their age, and could not conceive that there could be the smallest difference in the world between them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87947,\n            \"and Sir John felt so desperately enraged against the author of this nervous distress, that he instantly changed his seat to one close by Lucy Steele, and gave her, in a whisper, a brief account of the whole shocking affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88282,\n            \"Or at least, if she did not bring herself quite to rejoice in Edward\\u2019s being fettered to Lucy, she determined, that had Lucy been more amiable, she _ ought _ to have rejoiced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88322,\n            \"She wondered that Lucy\\u2019s spirits could be so very much elevated by the civility of Mrs. Ferrars;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88343,\n            \"\\u2014 that her interest and her vanity should so very much blind her as to make the attention which seemed only paid her because she was _ not Elinor _, appear a compliment to herself \\u2014 or to allow her to derive encouragement from a preference only given her, because her real situation was unknown.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88487,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear friend,\\u201dcried Lucy, as soon as they were by themselves, \\u201cI come to talk to you of my happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88515,\n            \"Could anything be so flattering as Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s way of treating me yesterday?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88539,\n            \"You know how I dreaded the thoughts of seeing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88550,\n            \"but the very moment I was introduced, there was such an affability in her behaviour as really should seem to say, she had quite took a fancy to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88602,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe was certainly very civil to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88633,\n            \"Such kindness as fell to the share of nobody but me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88664,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor wished to talk of something else, but Lucy still pressed her to own that she had reason for her happiness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88696,\n            \"\\u201cUndoubtedly, if they had known your engagement,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cnothing could be more flattering than their treatment of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88722,\n            \"\\u2014 but as that was not the case \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cI guessed you would say so,\\u201d\\u2014 replied Lucy quickly \\u2014 \\u201cbut there was no reason in the world why Mrs. Ferrars should seem to like me, if she did not, and her liking me is every thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88836,\n            \"\\u2014 I wonder I should never hear you say how agreeable Mrs. Dashwood was!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88924,\n            \"I should be sorry to have _ you _ ill;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88976,\n            \"But it seemed to satisfy Lucy, for she directly replied, \\u201cIndeed I am perfectly convinced of your regard for me, and next to Edward\\u2019s love, it is the greatest comfort I have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89019,\n            \"But now there is one good thing, we shall be able to meet, and meet pretty often, for Lady Middleton\\u2019s delighted with Mrs. Dashwood, so we shall be a good deal in Harley Street, I dare say, and Edward spends half his time with his sister \\u2014 besides, Lady Middleton and Mrs. Ferrars will visit now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89087,\n            \"\\u2014 and Mrs. Ferrars and your sister were both so good to say more than once, they should always be glad to see me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89523,\n            \"She would not allow the presence of Lucy, nor the consciousness of some injustice towards herself, to deter her from saying that she was happy to see him, and that she had very much regretted being from home, when he called before in Berkeley Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89573,\n            \"She would not be frightened from paying him those attentions which, as a friend and almost a relation, were his due, by the observant eyes of Lucy, though she soon perceived them to be narrowly watching her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89686,\n            \"Lucy, with a demure and settled air, seemed determined to make no contribution to the comfort of the others, and would not say a word;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89983,\n            \"while Marianne was looking with the most speaking tenderness, sometimes at Edward and sometimes at Elinor, regretting only that their delight in each other should be checked by Lucy\\u2019s unwelcome presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90437,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, Miss Marianne,\\u201dcried Lucy, eager to take some revenge on her, \\u201cyou think young men never stand upon engagements, if they have no mind to keep them, little as well as great.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90709,\n            \"\\u201d And drawing him a little aside, she whispered her persuasion that Lucy could not stay much longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90779,\n            \"\\u201cCould not she see that we wanted her gone!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90801,\n            \"\\u2014 we were all his friends, and Lucy has been the longest known to him of any.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90820,\n            \"It is but natural that he should like to see her as well as ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90923,\n            \"and Elinor dared not follow her to say more, for bound as she was by her promise of secrecy to Lucy, she could give no information that would convince Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91388,\n            \"Their presence was a restraint both on her and on Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91414,\n            \"Lady Middleton was ashamed of doing nothing before them, and the flattery which Lucy was proud to think of and administer at other times, she feared they would despise her for offering.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91449,\n            \"Miss Steele was the least discomposed of the three, by their presence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91532,\n            \"for though she often threw out expressions of pity for her sister to Elinor, and more than once dropt a reflection on the inconstancy of beaux before Marianne, no effect was produced, but a look of indifference from the former, or of disgust in the latter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91726,\n            \"but wherever it was, she always came in excellent spirits, full of delight and importance, attributing Charlotte\\u2019s well doing to her own care, and ready to give so exact, so minute a detail of her situation, as only Miss Steele had curiosity enough to desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92055,\n            \"and this misconstruction produced within a day or two afterwards, cards of invitation for them as well as for their brother and sister, to a small musical party at her house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94254,\n            \"Fanny, rejoicing in her escape, and proud of the ready wit that had procured it, wrote the next morning to Lucy, to request her company and her sister\\u2019s, for some days, in Harley Street, as soon as Lady Middleton could spare them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94339,\n            \"Such an opportunity of being with Edward and his family was, above all things, the most material to her interest, and such an invitation the most gratifying to her feelings!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95201,\n            \"Mr. Edward Ferrars, the very young man I used to joke with you about (but however, as it turns out, I am monstrous glad there was never any thing in it), Mr. Edward Ferrars, it seems, has been engaged above this twelvemonth to my cousin Lucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95409,\n            \"\\u2019 thinks she to herself, \\u2018 they are all so fond of Lucy, to be sure they will make no difficulty about it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95560,\n            \"So up he flew directly, and a terrible scene took place, for Lucy was come to them by that time, little dreaming what was going on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95593,\n            \"I pity _ her _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95599,\n            \"And I must say, I think she was used very hardly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95612,\n            \"for your sister scolded like any fury, and soon drove her into a fainting fit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95766,\n            \"poor Lucy in such a condition, he says, she could hardly walk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96013,\n            \"for I am sure Mrs. Ferrars may afford to do very well by her son, and though Lucy has next to nothing herself, she knows better than any body how to make the most of every thing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96765,\n            \"As for Lucy Steele, she considered her so totally unamiable, so absolutely incapable of attaching a sensible man, that she could not be persuaded at first to believe, and afterwards to pardon, any former affection of Edward for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96960,\n            \"When Lucy first came to Barton Park last November, she told me in confidence of her engagement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97104,\n            \"\\u2014 My promise to Lucy, obliged me to be secret.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97116,\n            \"I owed it to her, therefore, to avoid giving any hint of the truth;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 She listened to her praise of Lucy with only moving from one chair to another, and when Mrs. Jennings talked of Edward\\u2019s affection, it cost her only a spasm in her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99277,\n            \"Miss Lucy Steele is, I dare say, a very deserving young woman, but in the present case you know, the connection must be impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100972,\n            \"I never saw Lucy in such a rage in my life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100984,\n            \"She vowed at first she would never trim me up a new bonnet, nor do any thing else for me again, so long as she lived;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101013,\n            \"but now she is quite come to, and we are as good friends as ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101030,\n            \"Look, she made me this bow to my hat, and put in the feather last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101176,\n            \"\\u201cWell, but Miss Dashwood,\\u201dspeaking triumphantly, \\u201cpeople may say what they chuse about Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s declaring he would not have Lucy, for it is no such thing I can tell you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101235,\n            \"Whatever Lucy might think about it herself, you know, it was no business of other people to set it down for certain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101308,\n            \"for Miss Godby told Miss Sparks, that nobody in their senses could expect Mr. Ferrars to give up a woman like Miss Morton, with thirty thousand pounds to her fortune, for Lucy Steele that had nothing at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101408,\n            \"and I believe in my heart Lucy gave it up all for lost;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101458,\n            \"Once Lucy thought to write to him, but then her spirits rose against that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101487,\n            \"and then it all came out, how he had been sent for Wednesday to Harley Street, and been talked to by his mother and all of them, and how he had declared before them all that he loved nobody but Lucy, and nobody but Lucy would he have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101607,\n            \"And after thinking it all over and over again, he said, it seemed to him as if, now he had no fortune, and no nothing at all, it would be quite unkind to keep her on to the engagement, because it must be for her loss, for he had nothing but two thousand pounds, and no hope of any thing else;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102017,\n            \"so I was forced to go into the room and interrupt them, to ask Lucy if she would like to go, but she did not care to leave Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102274,\n            \"And I am sure Lucy would have done just the same by me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102288,\n            \"for a year or two back, when Martha Sharpe and I had so many secrets together, she never made any bones of hiding in a closet, or behind a chimney-board, on purpose to hear what we said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103053,\n            \"but as Elinor wished to spread as little as possible intelligence that had in the first place been so unfairly obtained, she confined herself to the brief repetition of such simple particulars, as she felt assured that Lucy, for the sake of her own consequence, would choose to have known.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103153,\n            \"\\u2014 ay, we all know how _ that _ will end: \\u2014 they will wait a twelvemonth, and finding no good comes of it, will set down upon a curacy of fifty pounds a-year, with the interest of his two thousand pounds, and what little matter Mr. Steele and Mr. Pratt can give her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103884,\n            \"She calls me dear Mrs. Jennings, you see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103895,\n            \"She is a good-hearted girl as ever lived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103919,\n            \"Yes, yes, I will go and see her, sure enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103956,\n            \"It is as pretty a letter as ever I saw, and does Lucy\\u2019s head and heart great credit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104210,\n            \"\\u2014 but it was inforced with so much real politeness by Mr. Palmer himself, as, joined to the very great amendment of his manners towards them since her sister had been known to be unhappy, induced her to accept it with pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104771,\n            \"for, on Elinor\\u2019s moving to the window to take more expeditiously the dimensions of a print, which she was going to copy for her friend, he followed her to it with a look of particular meaning, and conversed with her there for several minutes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106959,\n            \"\\u201cThen you would not have me tell it to Lucy, for I think of going as far as Holborn to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106984,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, ma\\u2019am, not even Lucy if you please.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109610,\n            \"and I am sure I shan\\u2019t go if Lucy an\\u2019t there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109650,\n            \"Edward, having carried his thanks to Colonel Brandon, proceeded with his happiness to Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109735,\n            \"and she joined Mrs. Jennings most heartily in her expectation of their being all comfortably together in Delaford Parsonage before Michaelmas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109758,\n            \"So far was she, at the same time, from any backwardness to give Elinor that credit which Edward _ would _ give her, that she spoke of her friendship for them both with the most grateful warmth, was ready to own all their obligation to her, and openly declared that no exertion for their good on Miss Dashwood\\u2019s part, either present or future, would ever surprise her, for she believed her capable of doing any thing in the world for those she really valued.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113297,\n            \"She had no such object for her lingering thoughts to fix on, she left no creature behind, from whom it would give her a moment\\u2019s regret to be divided for ever, she was pleased to be free herself from the persecution of Lucy\\u2019s friendship, she was grateful for bringing her sister away unseen by Willoughby since his marriage, and she looked forward with hope to what a few months of tranquility at Barton might do towards restoring Marianne\\u2019s peace of mind, and confirming her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134325,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThey come straight from town, as Miss Lucy \\u2014 Mrs. Ferrars told me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134403,\n            \"She recognised the whole of Lucy in the message, and was very confident that Edward would never come near them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134914,\n            \"She now found, that in spite of herself, she had always admitted a hope, while Edward remained single, that something would occur to prevent his marrying Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134946,\n            \"that some resolution of his own, some mediation of friends, or some more eligible opportunity of establishment for the lady, would arise to assist the happiness of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135042,\n            \"But she soon saw how likely it was that Lucy, in her self-provident care, in her haste to secure him, should overlook every thing but the risk of delay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135095,\n            \"What had Edward felt on being within four miles from Barton, on seeing her mother\\u2019s servant, on hearing Lucy\\u2019s message!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135211,\n            \"\\u2014 pursuing her own interest in every thought, courting the favour of Colonel Brandon, of Mrs. Jennings, and of every wealthy friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136212,\n            \"took up a pair of scissors that lay there, and while spoiling both them and their sheath by cutting the latter to pieces as he spoke, said, in a hurried voice, \\u2014 \\u201cPerhaps you do not know: you may not have heard that my brother is lately married to \\u2014 to the youngest \\u2014 to Miss Lucy Steele.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137226,\n            \"and accordingly I spent the greatest part of my time there from eighteen to nineteen: Lucy appeared everything that was amiable and obliging.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137251,\n            \"She was pretty too \\u2014 at least I thought so _ then;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137446,\n            \"and her joy, though sincere as her love for her sister, was of a kind to give her neither spirits nor language.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137484,\n            \"From the moment of learning that Lucy was married to another, that Edward was free, to the moment of his justifying the hopes which had so instantly followed, she was every thing by turns but tranquil.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137775,\n            \"Lucy\\u2019s marriage, the unceasing and reasonable wonder among them all, formed of course one of the earliest discussions of the lovers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138112,\n            \"for at Oxford, where he had remained for choice ever since his quitting London, he had had no means of hearing of her but from herself, and her letters to the very last were neither less frequent, nor less affectionate than usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138498,\n            \"\\u2014 \\u201cFor worlds would not I have had a letter of hers seen by _ you _ in former days.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138534,\n            \"\\u2014 how I have blushed over the pages of her writing!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138546,\n            \"\\u2014 and I believe I may say that since the first half year of our foolish \\u2014 business \\u2014 this is the only letter I ever received from her, of which the substance made me any amends for the defect of the style.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138681,\n            \"She will hardly be less hurt, I suppose, by Robert\\u2019s marrying Lucy, than she would have been by your marrying her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138958,\n            \"That Lucy had certainly meant to deceive, to go off with a flourish of malice against him in her message by Thomas, was perfectly clear to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139138,\n            \"\\u201cI thought it my duty,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cindependent of my feelings, to give her the option of continuing the engagement or not, when I was renounced by my mother, and stood to all appearance without a friend in the world to assist me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139190,\n            \"In such a situation as that, where there seemed nothing to tempt the avarice or the vanity of any living creature, how could I suppose, when she so earnestly, so warmly insisted on sharing my fate, whatever it might be, that any thing but the most disinterested affection was her inducement?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139248,\n            \"And even now, I cannot comprehend on what motive she acted, or what fancied advantage it could be to her, to be fettered to a man for whom she had not the smallest regard, and who had only two thousand pounds in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139297,\n            \"She could not foresee that Colonel Brandon would give me a living.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139314,\n            \"but she might suppose that something would occur in your favour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139362,\n            \"The connection was certainly a respectable one, and probably gained her consideration among her friends;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139610,\n            \"and till I began to make comparisons between yourself and Lucy, I did not know how far I was got.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140281,\n            \"No rumour of Lucy\\u2019s marriage had yet reached him: \\u2014 he knew nothing of what had passed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140640,\n            \"for Lucy it seems borrowed all her money before she went off to be married, on purpose we suppose to make a show with, and poor Nancy had not seven shillings in the world;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140677,\n            \"so I was very glad to give her five guineas to take her down to Exeter, where she thinks of staying three or four weeks with Mrs. Burgess, in hopes, as I tell her, to fall in with the Doctor again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140724,\n            \"And I must say that Lucy\\u2019s crossness not to take them along with them in the chaise is worse than all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140855,\n            \"and even, if she might hereafter be induced to forgive her son, his wife should never be acknowledged as her daughter, nor be permitted to appear in her presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140932,\n            \"and he called on Elinor to join with him in regretting that Lucy\\u2019s engagement with Edward had not rather been fulfilled, than that she should thus be the means of spreading misery farther in the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141015,\n            \"Perhaps, however, he is kept silent by his fear of offending, and I shall, therefore, give him a hint, by a line to Oxford, that his sister and I both think a letter of proper submission from him, addressed perhaps to Fanny, and by her shown to her mother, might not be taken amiss;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141755,\n            \"\\u2014 told him, that in Miss Morton he would have a woman of higher rank and larger fortune;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141775,\n            \"\\u2014 and enforced the assertion, by observing that Miss Morton was the daughter of a nobleman with thirty thousand pounds, while Miss Dashwood was only the daughter of a private gentleman with no more than _ three;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142345,\n            \"\\u201cI will not say that I am disappointed, my dear sister,\\u201dsaid John, as they were walking together one morning before the gates of Delaford House, \\u201c_ that _ would be saying too much, for certainly you have been one of the most fortunate young women in the world, as it is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142864,\n            \"for though Lucy soon gave him hopes that his eloquence would convince her in _ time _, another visit, another conversation, was always wanted to produce this conviction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143062,\n            \"\\u2014 and from thence returning to town, procured the forgiveness of Mrs. Ferrars, by the simple expedient of asking it, which, at Lucy\\u2019s instigation, was adopted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143198,\n            \"Lucy became as necessary to Mrs. Ferrars, as either Robert or Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143291,\n            \"and setting aside the jealousies and ill-will continually subsisting between Fanny and Lucy, in which their husbands of course took a part, as well as the frequent domestic disagreements between Robert and Lucy themselves, nothing could exceed the harmony in which they all lived together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143498,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s marriage divided her as little from her family as could well be contrived, without rendering the cottage at Barton entirely useless, for her mother and sisters spent much more than half their time with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143593,\n            \"Precious as was the company of her daughter to her, she desired nothing so much as to give up its constant enjoyment to her valued friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144380,\n            \"and among the merits and the happiness of Elinor and Marianne, let it not be ranked as the least considerable, that though sisters, and living almost within sight of each other, they could live without disagreement between themselves, or producing coolness between their husbands.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 3]\": [\n        [\n            118,\n            \"for to supply her loss, he invited and received into his house the family of his nephew Mr. Henry Dashwood, the legal inheritor of the Norland estate, and the person to whom he intended to bequeath it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            435,\n            \"He was neither so unjust, nor so ungrateful, as to leave his estate from his nephew;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            454,\n            \"\\u2014 but he left it to him on such terms as destroyed half the value of the bequest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            473,\n            \"Mr. Dashwood had wished for it more for the sake of his wife and daughters than for himself or his son;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            496,\n            \"\\u2014 but to his son, and his son\\u2019s son, a child of four years old, it was secured, in such a way, as to leave to himself no power of providing for those who were most dear to him, and who most needed a provision by any charge on the estate, or by any sale of its valuable woods.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            565,\n            \"The whole was tied up for the benefit of this child, who, in occasional visits with his father and mother at Norland, had so far gained on the affections of his uncle, by such attractions as are by no means unusual in children of two or three years old;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            775,\n            \"He survived his uncle no longer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            802,\n            \"His son was sent for as soon as his danger was known, and to him Mr. Dashwood recommended, with all the strength and urgency which illness could command, the interest of his mother-in-law and sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1235,\n            \"the house was her husband\\u2019s from the moment of his father\\u2019s decease;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1380,\n            \"So acutely did Mrs. Dashwood feel this ungracious behaviour, and so earnestly did she despise her daughter-in-law for it, that, on the arrival of the latter, she would have quitted the house for ever, had not the entreaty of her eldest girl induced her first to reflect on the propriety of going, and her own tender love for all her three children determined her afterwards to stay, and for their sakes avoid a breach with their brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2084,\n            \"To take three thousand pounds from the fortune of their dear little boy would be impoverishing him to the most dreadful degree.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2117,\n            \"How could he answer it to himself to rob his child, and his only child too, of so large a sum?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2202,\n            \"and why was he to ruin himself, and their poor little Harry, by giving away all his money to his half sisters?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2283,\n            \"Had he been in his right senses, he could not have thought of such a thing as begging you to give away half your fortune from your own child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2498,\n            \"If, indeed, it could be restored to our poor little boy \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cWhy, to be sure,\\u201dsaid her husband, very gravely, \\u201cthat would make great difference.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2552,\n            \"If he should have a numerous family, for instance, it would be a very convenient addition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4402,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood had been informed by her husband of the solemn promise on the part of his son in their favour, which gave comfort to his last earthly reflections.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4483,\n            \"For their brother\\u2019s sake, too, for the sake of his own heart, she rejoiced;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4503,\n            \"and she reproached herself for being unjust to his merit before, in believing him incapable of generosity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4522,\n            \"His attentive behaviour to herself and his sisters convinced her that their welfare was dear to him, and, for a long time, she firmly relied on the liberality of his intentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8366,\n            \"No sooner was her answer dispatched, than Mrs. Dashwood indulged herself in the pleasure of announcing to her son-in-law and his wife that she was provided with a house, and should incommode them no longer than till every thing were ready for her inhabiting it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8432,\n            \"but her husband civilly hoped that she would not be settled far from Norland.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8678,\n            \"and she wished to show Mrs. John Dashwood, by this pointed invitation to her brother, how totally she disregarded her disapprobation of the match.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9050,\n            \"The man and one of the maids were sent off immediately into Devonshire, to prepare the house for their mistress\\u2019 s arrival;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9102,\n            \"and she relied so undoubtingly on Sir John\\u2019s description of the house, as to feel no curiosity to examine it herself till she entered it as her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9184,\n            \"Now was the time when her son-in-law\\u2019s promise to his father might with particular propriety be fulfilled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9208,\n            \"Since he had neglected to do it on first coming to the estate, their quitting his house might be looked on as the most suitable period for its accomplishment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9239,\n            \"But Mrs. Dashwood began shortly to give over every hope of the kind, and to be convinced, from the general drift of his discourse, that his assistance extended no farther than their maintenance for six months at Norland.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9339,\n            \"In a very few weeks from the day which brought Sir John Middleton\\u2019s first letter to Norland, every thing was so far settled in their future abode as to enable Mrs. Dashwood and her daughters to begin their journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10850,\n            \"Conversation however was not wanted, for Sir John was very chatty, and Lady Middleton had taken the wise precaution of bringing with her their eldest child, a fine little boy about six years old, by which means there was one subject always to be recurred to by the ladies in case of extremity, for they had to enquire his name and age, admire his beauty, and ask him questions which his mother answered for him, while he hung about her and held down his head, to the great surprise of her ladyship, who wondered at his being so shy before company, as he could make noise enough at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11040,\n            \"An opportunity was soon to be given to the Dashwoods of debating on the rest of the children, as Sir John would not leave the house without securing their promise of dining at the park the next day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11240,\n            \"Sir John was a sportsman, Lady Middleton a mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12660,\n            \"and this kind of discernment enabled her soon after her arrival at Barton decisively to pronounce that Colonel Brandon was very much in love with Marianne Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13511,\n            \"But I must object to your dooming Colonel Brandon and his wife to the constant confinement of a sick chamber, merely because he chanced to complain yesterday (a very cold damp day) of a slight rheumatic feel in one of his shoulders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13978,\n            \"And Elinor, in quitting Norland and Edward, cried not as I did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14042,\n            \"The house and the garden, with all the objects surrounding them, were now become familiar, and the ordinary pursuits which had given to Norland half its charms were engaged in again with far greater enjoyment than Norland had been able to afford, since the loss of their father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19341,\n            \"and had Elinor\\u2019s memory been equal to her means of improvement, she might have known very early in their acquaintance all the particulars of Mr. Jennings\\u2019 s last illness, and what he said to his wife a few minutes before he died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22724,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps it is to tell you that your cousin Fanny is married?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22903,\n            \"but I am the more concerned, as I fear my presence is necessary to gain your admittance at Whitwell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22934,\n            \"\\u201cBut if you write a note to the housekeeper, Mr. Brandon,\\u201dsaid Marianne, eagerly, \\u201cwill it not be sufficient?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23033,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you would but let us know what your business is,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cwe might see whether it could be put off or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23066,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou would not be six hours later,\\u201dsaid Willoughby, \\u201cif you were to defer your journey till our return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23131,\n            \"Brandon is one of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23137,\n            \"He was afraid of catching cold I dare say, and invented this trick for getting out of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23157,\n            \"I would lay fifty guineas the letter was of his own writing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23183,\n            \"\\u201cThere is no persuading you to change your mind, Brandon, I know of old,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cwhen once you are determined on anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23215,\n            \"But, however, I hope you will think better of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23271,\n            \"\\u201d Colonel Brandon again repeated his sorrow at being the cause of disappointing the party;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23310,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI hope we shall see you at Barton,\\u201dadded her ladyship, \\u201cas soon as you can conveniently leave town;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23336,\n            \"and we must put off the party to Whitwell till you return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23447,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not want to pry into other men\\u2019s concerns.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23462,\n            \"I suppose it is something he is ashamed of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23512,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, as you are resolved to go, I wish you a good journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23550,\n            \"\\u201d He then took leave of the whole party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23560,\n            \"\\u201cIs there no chance of my seeing you and your sisters in town this winter, Miss Dashwood?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23590,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen I must bid you farewell for a longer time than I should wish to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23620,\n            \"\\u201cCome Colonel,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cbefore you go, do let us know what you are going about.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24597,\n            \"for if there had been any real impropriety in what I did, I should have been sensible of it at the time, for we always know when we are acting wrong, and with such a conviction I could have had no pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25318,\n            \"It is not so very likely he should be distressed in his circumstances _ now _, for he is a very prudent man, and to be sure must have cleared the estate by this time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25391,\n            \"Well, I wish him out of all his trouble with all my heart, and a good wife into the bargain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26039,\n            \"But you may be assured that I would not sacrifice one sentiment of local attachment of yours, or of any one whom I loved, for all the improvements in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38337,\n            \"I thought of nothing but whether it might not be Colonel Brandon come back again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40022,\n            \"\\u201cOh, my love,\\u201dcried Mrs. Palmer to her husband, who just then entered the room \\u2014 \\u201cyou must help me to persuade the Miss Dashwoods to go to town this winter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40226,\n            \"\\u201cfor we know all about it, I assure you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40254,\n            \"We do not live a great way from him in the country, you know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40540,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI did not know I contradicted any body in calling your mother ill-bred.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40621,\n            \"and exultingly said, she did not care how cross he was to her, as they must live together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40971,\n            \"\\u2014 My love,\\u201dapplying to her husband, \\u201cdon\\u2019t you long to have the Miss Dashwoods come to Cleveland?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41018,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere now,\\u201d\\u2014 said his lady, \\u201cyou see Mr. Palmer expects you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41272,\n            \"\\u201cHe cannot bear writing, you know,\\u201dshe continued \\u2014 \\u201che says it is quite shocking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42194,\n            \"He seems an excellent man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42502,\n            \"You can\\u2019t think how much I longed to see you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42650,\n            \"But mama did not think the match good enough for me, otherwise Sir John would have mentioned it to the Colonel, and we should have been married immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42681,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not Colonel Brandon know of Sir John\\u2019s proposal to your mother before it was made?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42717,\n            \"but if mama had not objected to it, I dare say he would have liked it of all things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58538,\n            \"and she felt particularly hurt that a man so partial to her sister should perceive that she experienced nothing but grief and disappointment in seeing him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58656,\n            \"He heard her with the most earnest attention, but seeming to recollect himself, said no more on the subject, and began directly to speak of his pleasure at seeing them in London, making the usual inquiries about their journey, and the friends they had left behind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59038,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI had the pleasure of hearing it at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s, where I have been dining.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59084,\n            \"I warrant you she is a fine size by this time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59096,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMrs. Palmer appeared quite well, and I am commissioned to tell you, that you will certainly see her to-morrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59136,\n            \"Well, Colonel, I have brought two young ladies with me, you see \\u2014 that is, you see but one of them now, but there is another somewhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59273,\n            \"But Colonel, where have you been to since we parted?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63314,\n            \"she was left, on the contrary, with a melancholy impression of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s unhappiness, and was prevented even from wishing it removed, by her anxiety for the very event that must confirm it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73471,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, who had watched them with pleasure while they were talking, and who expected to see the effect of Miss Dashwood\\u2019s communication, in such an instantaneous gaiety on Colonel Brandon\\u2019s side, as might have become a man in the bloom of youth, of hope and happiness, saw him, with amazement, remain the whole evening more serious and thoughtful than usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74695,\n            \"\\u201cWe are never safe from _ him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74788,\n            \"and Elinor, who was convinced that solicitude for Marianne brought him thither, and who saw _ that _ solicitude in his disturbed and melancholy look, and in his anxious though brief inquiry after her, could not forgive her sister for esteeming him so lightly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74865,\n            \"and I was the more easily encouraged, because I thought it probable that I might find you alone, which I was very desirous of doing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74923,\n            \"\\u2014 no, I must not say comfort \\u2014 not present comfort \\u2014 but conviction, lasting conviction to your sister\\u2019s mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74948,\n            \"My regard for her, for yourself, for your mother \\u2014 will you allow me to prove it, by relating some circumstances which nothing but a _ very _ sincere regard \\u2014 nothing but an earnest desire of being useful \\u2014 I think I am justified \\u2014 though where so many hours have been spent in convincing myself that I am right, is there not some reason to fear I may be wrong?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75029,\n            \"\\u201cI understand you,\\u201dsaid Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75038,\n            \"\\u201cYou have something to tell me of Mr. Willoughby, that will open his character farther.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75114,\n            \"and, to be brief, when I quitted Barton last October, \\u2014 but this will give you no idea \\u2014 I must go farther back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75142,\n            \"You will find me a very awkward narrator, Miss Dashwood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75221,\n            \"\\u201cYou have probably entirely forgotten a conversation \\u2014 (it is not to be supposed that it could make any impression on you) \\u2014 a conversation between us one evening at Barton Park \\u2014 it was the evening of a dance \\u2014 in which I alluded to a lady I had once known, as resembling, in some measure, your sister Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75305,\n            \"\\u201d He looked pleased by this remembrance, and added, \\u201cIf I am not deceived by the uncertainty, the partiality of tender recollection, there is a very strong resemblance between them, as well in mind as person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75362,\n            \"This lady was one of my nearest relations, an orphan from her infancy, and under the guardianship of my father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75415,\n            \"and my affection for her, as we grew up, was such, as perhaps, judging from my present forlorn and cheerless gravity, you might think me incapable of having ever felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75451,\n            \"Hers, for me, was, I believe, fervent as the attachment of your sister to Mr. Willoughby and it was, though from a different cause, no less unfortunate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75618,\n            \"I have never told you how this was brought on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75657,\n            \"I was banished to the house of a relation far distant, and she was allowed no liberty, no society, no amusement, till my father\\u2019s point was gained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75820,\n            \"and happy had it been if she had not lived to overcome those regrets which the remembrance of me occasioned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75841,\n            \"But can we wonder that, with such a husband to provoke inconstancy, and without a friend to advise or restrain her (for my father lived only a few months after their marriage, and I was with my regiment in the East Indies) she should fall?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75892,\n            \"Had I remained in England, perhaps \\u2014 but I meant to promote the happiness of both by removing from her for years, and for that purpose had procured my exchange.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75925,\n            \"The shock which her marriage had given me,\\u201dhe continued, in a voice of great agitation, \\u201cwas of trifling weight \\u2014 was nothing to what I felt when I heard, about two years afterwards, of her divorce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76009,\n            \"Elinor, affected by his relation, and still more by his distress, could not speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76027,\n            \"He saw her concern, and coming to her, took her hand, pressed it, and kissed it with grateful respect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76081,\n            \"My first care, when I _ did _ arrive, was of course to seek for her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76111,\n            \"I could not trace her beyond her first seducer, and there was every reason to fear that she had removed from him only to sink deeper in a life of sin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76144,\n            \"Her legal allowance was not adequate to her fortune, nor sufficient for her comfortable maintenance, and I learnt from my brother that the power of receiving it had been made over some months before to another person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76214,\n            \"At last, however, and after I had been six months in England, I _ did _ find her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76236,\n            \"Regard for a former servant of my own, who had since fallen into misfortune, carried me to visit him in a spunging-house, where he was confined for debt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76335,\n            \"What I endured in so beholding her \\u2014 but I have no right to wound your feelings by attempting to describe it \\u2014 I have pained you too much already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76418,\n            \"I saw her placed in comfortable lodgings, and under proper attendants;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76431,\n            \"I visited her every day during the rest of her short life: I was with her in her last moments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76481,\n            \"\\u201cYour sister, I hope, cannot be offended,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cby the resemblance I have fancied between her and my poor disgraced relation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76566,\n            \"I seem to have been distressing you for nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76612,\n            \"She left to my care her only child, a little girl, the offspring of her first guilty connection, who was then about three years old.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76665,\n            \"and gladly would I have discharged it in the strictest sense, by watching over her education myself, had the nature of our situations allowed it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76712,\n            \"I saw her there whenever I could, and after the death of my brother, (which happened about five years ago, and which left to me the possession of the family property,) she visited me at Delaford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76755,\n            \"I called her a distant relation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76839,\n            \"and for two years I had every reason to be pleased with her situation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76867,\n            \"I had allowed her, (imprudently, as it has since turned out,) at her earnest desire, to go to Bath with one of her young friends, who was attending her father there for his health.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76909,\n            \"I knew him to be a very good sort of man, and I thought well of his daughter \\u2014 better than she deserved, for, with a most obstinate and ill-judged secrecy, she would tell nothing, would give no clue, though she certainly knew all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76962,\n            \"He, her father, a well-meaning, but not a quick-sighted man, could really, I believe, give no information;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77015,\n            \"and he tried to convince me, as thoroughly as he was convinced himself, of his daughter\\u2019s being entirely unconcerned in the business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77042,\n            \"In short, I could learn nothing but that she was gone;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77092,\n            \"\\u201d cried Elinor, \\u201ccould it be \\u2014 could Willoughby!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77104,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 \\u201cThe first news that reached me of her,\\u201dhe continued, \\u201ccame in a letter from herself, last October.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77131,\n            \"It was forwarded to me from Delaford, and I received it on the very morning of our intended party to Whitwell;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77368,\n            \"Knowing all this, as I have now known it many weeks, guess what I must have felt on seeing your sister as fond of him as ever, and on being assured that she was to marry him: guess what I must have felt for all your sakes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77420,\n            \"When I came to you last week and found you alone, I came determined to know the truth;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77452,\n            \"My behaviour must have seemed strange to you then;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77478,\n            \"to see your sister \\u2014 but what could I do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77498,\n            \"and sometimes I thought your sister\\u2019s influence might yet reclaim him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77684,\n            \"Use your own discretion, however, in communicating to her what I have told you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77711,\n            \"but had I not seriously, and from my heart believed it might be of service, might lessen her regrets, I would not have suffered myself to trouble you with this account of my family afflictions, with a recital which may seem to have been intended to raise myself at the expense of others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77887,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes,\\u201dhe replied gravely, \\u201conce I have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78024,\n            \"\\u201cSuch,\\u201dsaid Colonel Brandon, after a pause, \\u201chas been the unhappy resemblance between the fate of mother and daughter!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78244,\n            \"But though this behaviour assured Elinor that the conviction of this guilt _ was _ carried home to her mind, though she saw with satisfaction the effect of it, in her no longer avoiding Colonel Brandon when he called, in her speaking to him, even voluntarily speaking, with a kind of compassionate respect, and though she saw her spirits less violently irritated than before, she did not see her less wretched.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79743,\n            \"and having thus supported the dignity of her own sex, and spoken her decided censure of what was wrong in the other, she thought herself at liberty to attend to the interest of her own assemblies, and therefore determined (though rather against the opinion of Sir John) that as Mrs. Willoughby would at once be a woman of elegance and fortune, to leave her card with her as soon as she married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79838,\n            \"He had abundantly earned the privilege of intimate discussion of her sister\\u2019s disappointment, by the friendly zeal with which he had endeavoured to soften it, and they always conversed with confidence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79963,\n            \"but Mrs. Jennings, who knew nothing of all this, who knew only that the Colonel continued as grave as ever, and that she could neither prevail on him to make the offer himself, nor commission her to make it for him, began, at the end of two days, to think that, instead of Midsummer, they would not be married till Michaelmas, and by the end of a week that it would not be a match at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80052,\n            \"The good understanding between the Colonel and Miss Dashwood seemed rather to declare that the honours of the mulberry-tree, the canal, and the yew arbour, would all be made over to _ her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82486,\n            \"and on Colonel Brandon\\u2019s coming in soon after himself, he eyed him with a curiosity which seemed to say, that he only wanted to know him to be rich, to be equally civil to _ him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82616,\n            \"He seems a most gentlemanlike man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82661,\n            \"I observed him narrowly, and am convinced of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82810,\n            \"his friends may all advise him against it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82907,\n            \"Colonel Brandon must be the man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82914,\n            \"and no civility shall be wanting on my part to make him pleased with you and your family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83142,\n            \"He has a most excellent mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84594,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor tried very seriously to convince him that there was no likelihood of her marrying Colonel Brandon;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84613,\n            \"but it was an expectation of too much pleasure to himself to be relinquished, and he was really resolved on seeking an intimacy with that gentleman, and promoting the marriage by every possible attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84677,\n            \"and an offer from Colonel Brandon, or a legacy from Mrs. Jennings, was the easiest means of atoning for his own neglect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85208,\n            \"but nothing would have induced Fanny voluntarily to mention his name before her, till able to tell her that his marriage with Miss Morton was resolved on, or till her husband\\u2019s expectations on Colonel Brandon were answered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85483,\n            \"Their sisters and Mrs. Jennings were invited likewise, and John Dashwood was careful to secure Colonel Brandon, who, always glad to be where the Miss Dashwoods were, received his eager civilities with some surprise, but much more pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85671,\n            \"So well had they recommended themselves to Lady Middleton, so agreeable had their assiduities made them to her, that though Lucy was certainly not so elegant, and her sister not even genteel, she was as ready as Sir John to ask them to spend a week or two in Conduit Street;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87703,\n            \"but Colonel Brandon\\u2019s eyes, as they were fixed on Marianne, declared that he noticed only what was amiable in it, the affectionate heart which could not bear to see a sister slighted in the smallest point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87910,\n            \"\\u2014 Colonel Brandon rose up and went to them without knowing what he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87947,\n            \"and Sir John felt so desperately enraged against the author of this nervous distress, that he instantly changed his seat to one close by Lucy Steele, and gave her, in a whisper, a brief account of the whole shocking affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88037,\n            \"\\u201d said her brother to Colonel Brandon, in a low voice, as soon as he could secure his attention: \\u201cShe has not such good health as her sister, \\u2014 she is very nervous, \\u2014 she has not Elinor\\u2019s constitution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104635,\n            \"Colonel, I do not know what you and I shall do without the Miss Dashwoods;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104652,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 was Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s address to him when he first called on her, after their leaving her was settled \\u2014 \\u201cfor they are quite resolved upon going home from the Palmers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104720,\n            \"\\u201d Perhaps Mrs. Jennings was in hopes, by this vigorous sketch of their future ennui, to provoke him to make that offer, which might give himself an escape from it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104771,\n            \"for, on Elinor\\u2019s moving to the window to take more expeditiously the dimensions of a print, which she was going to copy for her friend, he followed her to it with a look of particular meaning, and conversed with her there for several minutes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104822,\n            \"The effect of his discourse on the lady too, could not escape her observation, for though she was too honorable to listen, and had even changed her seat, on purpose that she might _ not _ hear, to one close by the piano forte on which Marianne was playing, she could not keep herself from seeing that Elinor changed colour, attended with agitation, and was too intent on what he said to pursue her employment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104906,\n            \"Still farther in confirmation of her hopes, in the interval of Marianne\\u2019s turning from one lesson to another, some words of the Colonel\\u2019s inevitably reached her ear, in which he seemed to be apologising for the badness of his house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104962,\n            \"She wondered, indeed, at his thinking it necessary to do so;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105030,\n            \"They then talked on for a few minutes longer without her catching a syllable, when another lucky stop in Marianne\\u2019s performance brought her these words in the Colonel\\u2019s calm voice, \\u2014 \\u201cI am afraid it cannot take place very soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105211,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings was delighted with her gratitude, and only wondered that after hearing such a sentence, the Colonel should be able to take leave of them, as he immediately did, with the utmost _ sang-froid _, and go away without making her any reply!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105291,\n            \"\\u201cI have heard,\\u201dsaid he, with great compassion, \\u201cof the injustice your friend Mr. Ferrars has suffered from his family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105319,\n            \"for if I understand the matter right, he has been entirely cast off by them for persevering in his engagement with a very deserving young woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105444,\n            \"He is not a young man with whom one can be intimately acquainted in a short time, but I have seen enough of him to wish him well for his own sake, and as a friend of yours, I wish it still more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105500,\n            \"Will you be so good as to tell him that the living of Delaford, now just vacant, as I am informed by this day\\u2019s post, is his, if he think it worth his acceptance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105583,\n            \"the late incumbent, I believe, did not make more than 200\\u00a3 per annum, and though it is certainly capable of improvement, I fear, not to such an amount as to afford him a very comfortable income.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105625,\n            \"Such as it is, however, my pleasure in presenting it to him, will be very great.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105651,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s astonishment at this commission could hardly have been greater, had the Colonel been really making her an offer of his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105738,\n            \"but whatever minor feelings less pure, less pleasing, might have a share in that emotion, her esteem for the general benevolence, and her gratitude for the particular friendship, which together prompted Colonel Brandon to this act, were strongly felt, and warmly expressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105788,\n            \"She thanked him for it with all her heart, spoke of Edward\\u2019s principles and disposition with that praise which she knew them to deserve;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105899,\n            \"but Colonel Brandon, on motives of equal delicacy, declining it likewise, still seemed so desirous of its being given through her means, that she would not on any account make farther opposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105974,\n            \"After this had been settled, Colonel Brandon began to talk of his own advantage in securing so respectable and agreeable a neighbour, and _ then _ it was that he mentioned with regret, that the house was small and indifferent;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106318,\n            \"but after this narration of what really passed between Colonel Brandon and Elinor, while they stood at the window, the gratitude expressed by the latter on their parting, may perhaps appear in general, not less reasonably excited, nor less properly worded than if it had arisen from an offer of marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106378,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, sagaciously smiling, as soon as the gentleman had withdrawn, \\u201cI do not ask you what the Colonel has been saying to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou judged from your knowledge of the Colonel\\u2019s general benevolence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107196,\n            \"\\u2014 sure, he is the proper person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107238,\n            \"\\u201cColonel Brandon is so delicate a man, that he rather wished any one to announce his intentions to Mr. Ferrars than himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108041,\n            \"Allow me to congratulate you on having so respectable and well-judging a friend, and to join in his wish that the living \\u2014 it is about two hundred a-year \\u2014 were much more considerable, and such as might better enable you to \\u2014 as might be more than a temporary accommodation to yourself \\u2014 such, in short, as might establish all your views of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108176,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, gathering more resolution, as some of the worst was over, \\u201cColonel Brandon means it as a testimony of his concern for what has lately passed \\u2014 for the cruel situation in which the unjustifiable conduct of your family has placed you \\u2014 a concern which I am sure Marianne, myself, and all your friends, must share;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108418,\n            \"I did not even know, till I understood his design, that the living was vacant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108436,\n            \"nor had it ever occurred to me that he might have had such a living in his gift.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108455,\n            \"As a friend of mine, of my family, he may, perhaps \\u2014 indeed I know he _ has _, still greater pleasure in bestowing it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108568,\n            \"\\u2014 at last, and as if it were rather an effort, he said, \\u201cColonel Brandon seems a man of great worth and respectability.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108596,\n            \"I have always heard him spoken of as such, and your brother I know esteems him highly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108615,\n            \"He is undoubtedly a sensible man, and in his manners perfectly the gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108630,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cI believe that you will find him, on farther acquaintance, all that you have heard him to be, and as you will be such very near neighbours (for I understand the parsonage is almost close to the mansion-house,) it is particularly important that he _ should _ be all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108749,\n            \"\\u201cColonel Brandon, I think, lodges in St.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108807,\n            \"_ to assure him that he has made me a very \\u2014 an exceedingly happy man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110516,\n            \"_ Now _, indeed it would be too late to sell it, but a man of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s sense!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114045,\n            \"they talked of the friends they had left behind, arranged Lady Middleton\\u2019s engagements, and wondered whether Mr. Palmer and Colonel Brandon would get farther than Reading that night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114531,\n            \"Of Edward, or at least of some of his concerns, she now received intelligence from Colonel Brandon, who had been into Dorsetshire lately;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116785,\n            \"and as soon she had rung up the maid to take her place by her sister, she hastened down to the drawing-room, where she knew he was generally to be found at a much later hour than the present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116836,\n            \"Her fears and her difficulties were immediately before him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116846,\n            \"Her fears, he had no courage, no confidence to attempt the removal of: \\u2014 he listened to them in silent despondence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116871,\n            \"\\u2014 but her difficulties were instantly obviated, for with a readiness that seemed to speak the occasion, and the service pre-arranged in his mind, he offered himself as the messenger who should fetch Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116923,\n            \"She thanked him with brief, though fervent gratitude, and while he went to hurry off his servant with a message to Mr. Harris, and an order for post-horses directly, she wrote a few lines to her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116968,\n            \"The comfort of such a friend at that moment as Colonel Brandon \\u2014 or such a companion for her mother, \\u2014 how gratefully was it felt!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117016,\n            \"\\u2014 as far as the shock of such a summons _ could _ be lessened to her, his presence, his manners, his assistance, would lessen it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117047,\n            \"_ He _, meanwhile, whatever he might feel, acted with all the firmness of a collected mind, made every necessary arrangement with the utmost despatch, and calculated with exactness the time in which she might look for his return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117103,\n            \"The horses arrived, even before they were expected, and Colonel Brandon only pressing her hand with a look of solemnity, and a few words spoken too low to reach her ear, hurried into the carriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117143,\n            \"It was then about twelve o\\u2019clock, and she returned to her sister\\u2019s apartment to wait for the arrival of the apothecary, and to watch by her the rest of the night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117414,\n            \"His opinion, however, made some little amends for his delay, for though acknowledging a very unexpected and unpleasant alteration in his patient, he would not allow the danger to be material, and talked of the relief which a fresh mode of treatment must procure, with a confidence which, in a lesser degree, was communicated to Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117479,\n            \"He promised to call again in the course of three or four hours, and left both the patient and her anxious attendant more composed than he had found them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117790,\n            \"But he judged it unnecessary: he had still something more to try, some more fresh application, of whose success he was as confident as the last, and his visit concluded with encouraging assurances which reached the ear, but could not enter the heart of Miss Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132055,\n            \"Nothing could replace him, therefore, in her former esteem, nor injure the interests of Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135211,\n            \"\\u2014 pursuing her own interest in every thought, courting the favour of Colonel Brandon, of Mrs. Jennings, and of every wealthy friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135341,\n            \"\\u201cWhen do you write to Colonel Brandon, ma\\u2019am?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135372,\n            \"\\u201cI wrote to him, my love, last week, and rather expect to see, than to hear from him again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135397,\n            \"I earnestly pressed his coming to us, and should not be surprised to see him walk in today or tomorrow, or any day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135474,\n            \"It was a gentleman, it was Colonel Brandon himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139248,\n            \"And even now, I cannot comprehend on what motive she acted, or what fancied advantage it could be to her, to be fettered to a man for whom she had not the smallest regard, and who had only two thousand pounds in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139297,\n            \"She could not foresee that Colonel Brandon would give me a living.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140089,\n            \"About four days after Edward\\u2019s arrival Colonel Brandon appeared, to complete Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s satisfaction, and to give her the dignity of having, for the first time since her living at Barton, more company with her than her house would hold.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140165,\n            \"from whence he usually returned in the morning, early enough to interrupt the lovers\\u2019 first t\\u00eate-\\u00e0-t\\u00eate before breakfast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140190,\n            \"A three weeks\\u2019 residence at Delaford, where, in his evening hours at least, he had little to do but to calculate the disproportion between thirty-six and seventeen, brought him to Barton in a temper of mind which needed all the improvement in Marianne\\u2019s looks, all the kindness of her welcome, and all the encouragement of her mother\\u2019s language, to make it cheerful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140267,\n            \"Among such friends, however, and such flattery, he did revive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141449,\n            \"\\u201d After a visit on Colonel Brandon\\u2019s side of only three or four days, the two gentlemen quitted Barton together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141473,\n            \"They were to go immediately to Delaford, that Edward might have some personal knowledge of his future home, and assist his patron and friend in deciding on what improvements were needed to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142046,\n            \"With an income quite sufficient to their wants thus secured to them, they had nothing to wait for after Edward was in possession of the living, but the readiness of the house, to which Colonel Brandon, with an eager desire for the accommodation of Elinor, was making considerable improvements;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142269,\n            \"They had in fact nothing to wish for, but the marriage of Colonel Brandon and Marianne, and rather better pasturage for their cows.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142469,\n            \"And though, perhaps, Marianne may not seem exactly the person to attract him, yet I think it would altogether be advisable for you to have them now frequently staying with you, for as Colonel Brandon seems a great deal at home, nobody can tell what may happen;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143561,\n            \"for her wish of bringing Marianne and Colonel Brandon together was hardly less earnest, though rather more liberal than what John had expressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143593,\n            \"Precious as was the company of her daughter to her, she desired nothing so much as to give up its constant enjoyment to her valued friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143666,\n            \"With such a confederacy against her \\u2014 with a knowledge so intimate of his goodness \\u2014 with a conviction of his fond attachment to herself, which at last, though long after it was observable to everybody else \\u2014 burst on her \\u2014 what could she do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143968,\n            \"\\u2014 her regard and her society restored his mind to animation, and his spirits to cheerfulness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143986,\n            \"and that Marianne found her own happiness in forming his, was equally the persuasion and delight of each observing friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144015,\n            \"and her whole heart became, in time, as much devoted to her husband, as it had once been to Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144039,\n            \"Willoughby could not hear of her marriage without a pang;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144050,\n            \"and his punishment was soon afterwards complete in the voluntary forgiveness of Mrs. Smith, who, by stating his marriage with a woman of character, as the source of her clemency, gave him reason for believing that had he behaved with honour towards Marianne, he might at once have been happy and rich.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144199,\n            \"His wife was not always out of humour, nor his home always uncomfortable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144239,\n            \"For Marianne, however, in spite of his incivility in surviving her loss, he always retained that decided regard which interested him in every thing that befell her, and made her his secret standard of perfection in woman;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144281,\n            \"and many a rising beauty would be slighted by him in after-days as bearing no comparison with Mrs. Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144323,\n            \"and fortunately for Sir John and Mrs. Jennings, when Marianne was taken from them, Margaret had reached an age highly suitable for dancing, and not very ineligible for being supposed to have a lover.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 4]\": [\n        [\n            9075,\n            \"for as Lady Middleton was entirely unknown to Mrs. Dashwood, she preferred going directly to the cottage to being a visitor at Barton Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10654,\n            \"Lady Middleton had sent a very civil message by him, denoting her intention of waiting on Mrs. Dashwood as soon as she could be assured that her visit would be no inconvenience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10689,\n            \"and as this message was answered by an invitation equally polite, her ladyship was introduced to them the next day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10711,\n            \"They were, of course, very anxious to see a person on whom so much of their comfort at Barton must depend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10735,\n            \"and the elegance of her appearance was favourable to their wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10803,\n            \"and her visit was long enough to detract something from their first admiration, by showing that, though perfectly well-bred, she was reserved, cold, and had nothing to say for herself beyond the most common-place inquiry or remark.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10850,\n            \"Conversation however was not wanted, for Sir John was very chatty, and Lady Middleton had taken the wise precaution of bringing with her their eldest child, a fine little boy about six years old, by which means there was one subject always to be recurred to by the ladies in case of extremity, for they had to enquire his name and age, admire his beauty, and ask him questions which his mother answered for him, while he hung about her and held down his head, to the great surprise of her ladyship, who wondered at his being so shy before company, as he could make noise enough at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11240,\n            \"Sir John was a sportsman, Lady Middleton a mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11251,\n            \"He hunted and shot, and she humoured her children;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11269,\n            \"Lady Middleton had the advantage of being able to spoil her children all the year round, while Sir John\\u2019s independent employments were in existence only half the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11356,\n            \"and from this kind of vanity was her greatest enjoyment in any of their parties.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12178,\n            \"Lady Middleton seemed to be roused to enjoyment only by the entrance of her four noisy children after dinner, who pulled her about, tore her clothes, and put an end to every kind of discourse except what related to themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12240,\n            \"The instrument was unlocked, every body prepared to be charmed, and Marianne, who sang very well, at their request went through the chief of the songs which Lady Middleton had brought into the family on her marriage, and which perhaps had lain ever since in the same position on the pianoforte, for her ladyship had celebrated that event by giving up music, although by her mother\\u2019s account, she had played extremely well, and by her own was very fond of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18049,\n            \"Who would submit to the indignity of being approved by such a woman as Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, that could command the indifference of any body else?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18080,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut perhaps the abuse of such people as yourself and Marianne will make amends for the regard of Lady Middleton and her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19299,\n            \"although the latter was an everlasting talker, and from the first had regarded her with a kindness which ensured her a large share of her discourse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19390,\n            \"Lady Middleton was more agreeable than her mother only in being more silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21989,\n            \"\\u201d Most grateful did Elinor feel to Lady Middleton for observing, at this moment, \\u201cthat it rained very hard,\\u201dthough she believed the interruption to proceed less from any attention to her, than from her ladyship\\u2019s great dislike of all such inelegant subjects of raillery as delighted her husband and mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38401,\n            \"Lady Middleton introduced the two strangers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39327,\n            \"When Lady Middleton rose to go away, Mr. Palmer rose also, laid down the newspaper, stretched himself and looked at them all around.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39539,\n            \"Lady Middleton too, though she did not press their mother, pressed them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42951,\n            \"Their engagements at Exeter instantly gave way before such an invitation, and Lady Middleton was thrown into no little alarm on the return of Sir John, by hearing that she was very soon to receive a visit from two girls whom she had never seen in her life, and of whose elegance, \\u2014 whose tolerable gentility even, she could have no proof;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43036,\n            \"Their being her relations too made it so much the worse;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43048,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s attempts at consolation were therefore unfortunately founded, when she advised her daughter not to care about their being so fashionable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43089,\n            \"As it was impossible, however, now to prevent their coming, Lady Middleton resigned herself to the idea of it, with all the philosophy of a well-bred woman, contenting herself with merely giving her husband a gentle reprimand on the subject five or six times every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43158,\n            \"Their dress was very smart, their manners very civil, they were delighted with the house, and in raptures with the furniture, and they happened to be so doatingly fond of children that Lady Middleton\\u2019s good opinion was engaged in their favour before they had been an hour at the Park.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43215,\n            \"She declared them to be very agreeable girls indeed, which for her ladyship was enthusiastic admiration.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43710,\n            \"Their manners were particularly civil, and Elinor soon allowed them credit for some kind of sense, when she saw with what constant and judicious attention they were making themselves agreeable to Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43768,\n            \"and such of their time as could be spared from the importunate demands which this politeness made on it, was spent in admiration of whatever her ladyship was doing, if she happened to be doing any thing, or in taking patterns of some elegant new dress, in which her appearance the day before had thrown them into unceasing delight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43882,\n            \"and the excessive affection and endurance of the Miss Steeles towards her offspring were viewed therefore by Lady Middleton without the smallest surprise or distrust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43908,\n            \"She saw with maternal complacency all the impertinent encroachments and mischievous tricks to which her cousins submitted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43926,\n            \"She saw their sashes untied, their hair pulled about their ears, their work-bags searched, and their knives and scissors stolen away, and felt no doubt of its being a reciprocal enjoyment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43997,\n            \"\\u201d said she, on his taking Miss Steeles\\u2019 s pocket handkerchief, and throwing it out of window \\u2014 \\u201cHe is full of monkey tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44026,\n            \"\\u201d And soon afterwards, on the second boy\\u2019s violently pinching one of the same lady\\u2019s fingers, she fondly observed, \\u201cHow playful William is!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44113,\n            \"\\u201d But unfortunately in bestowing these embraces, a pin in her ladyship\\u2019s head dress slightly scratching the child\\u2019s neck, produced from this pattern of gentleness such violent screams, as could hardly be outdone by any creature professedly noisy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44209,\n            \"She was seated in her mother\\u2019s lap, covered with kisses, her wound bathed with lavender-water, by one of the Miss Steeles, who was on her knees to attend her, and her mouth stuffed with sugar plums by the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44275,\n            \"She still screamed and sobbed lustily, kicked her two brothers for offering to touch her, and all their united soothings were ineffectual till Lady Middleton luckily remembering that in a scene of similar distress last week, some apricot marmalade had been successfully applied for a bruised temple, the same remedy was eagerly proposed for this unfortunate scratch, and a slight intermission of screams in the young lady on hearing it, gave them reason to hope that it would not be rejected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44363,\n            \"She was carried out of the room therefore in her mother\\u2019s arms, in quest of this medicine, and as the two boys chose to follow, though earnestly entreated by their mother to stay behind, the four young ladies were left in a quietness which the room had not known for many hours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44427,\n            \"\\u201d said Miss Steele, as soon as they were gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44547,\n            \"She did her best when thus called on, by speaking of Lady Middleton with more warmth than she felt, though with far less than Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51494,\n            \"Elinor, who foresaw a fairer opening for the point she had in view, in such a party as this was likely to be, more at liberty among themselves under the tranquil and well-bred direction of Lady Middleton than when her husband united them together in one noisy purpose, immediately accepted the invitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51604,\n            \"The young ladies went, and Lady Middleton was happily preserved from the frightful solitude which had threatened her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51798,\n            \"And we will make the dear little love some amends for her disappointment to-morrow, and then I hope she will not much mind it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51875,\n            \"I would not disappoint the little angel for all the world: and if you want me at the card-table now, I am resolved to finish the basket after supper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51936,\n            \"My poor little girl would be sadly disappointed, I know, if the basket was not finished tomorrow, for though I told her it certainly would not, I am sure she depends upon having it done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52015,\n            \"Lady Middleton proposed a rubber of Casino to the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52026,\n            \"No one made any objection but Marianne, who with her usual inattention to the forms of general civility, exclaimed, \\u201cYour Ladyship will have the goodness to excuse _ me _ \\u2014 you know I detest cards.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56518,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is very true,\\u201dreplied her mother, \\u201cbut of her society, separately from that of other people, you will scarcely have any thing at all, and you will almost always appear in public with Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57071,\n            \"Even Lady Middleton took the trouble of being delighted, which was putting herself rather out of her way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60964,\n            \"Every thing in her household arrangements was conducted on the most liberal plan, and excepting a few old city friends, whom, to Lady Middleton\\u2019s regret, she had never dropped, she visited no one to whom an introduction could at all discompose the feelings of her young companions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61640,\n            \"It was from Lady Middleton, announcing their arrival in Conduit Street the night before, and requesting the company of her mother and cousins the following evening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61669,\n            \"Business on Sir John\\u2019s part, and a violent cold on her own, prevented their calling in Berkeley Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61920,\n            \"from the former, whom they had not seen before since their arrival in town, as he was careful to avoid the appearance of any attention to his mother-in-law, and therefore never came near her, they received no mark of recognition on their entrance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62524,\n            \"He looked more than usually grave, and though expressing satisfaction at finding Miss Dashwood alone, as if he had somewhat in particular to tell her, sat for some time without saying a word.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62598,\n            \"for, more than once before, beginning with the observation of \\u201cyour sister looks unwell to-day,\\u201dor \\u201cyour sister seems out of spirits,\\u201dhe had appeared on the point, either of disclosing, or of inquiring, something particular about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62650,\n            \"After a pause of several minutes, their silence was broken, by his asking her in a voice of some agitation, when he was to congratulate her on the acquisition of a brother?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63389,\n            \"They were engaged about the end of that time to attend Lady Middleton to a party, from which Mrs. Jennings was kept away by the indisposition of her youngest daughter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63508,\n            \"and when at last they were told that Lady Middleton waited for them at the door, she started as if she had forgotten that any one was expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63645,\n            \"After some time spent in saying little or doing less, Lady Middleton sat down to Cassino, and as Marianne was not in spirits for moving about, she and Elinor luckily succeeding to chairs, placed themselves at no great distance from the table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64636,\n            \"Lady Middleton, though in the middle of a rubber, on being informed that Marianne was unwell, was too polite to object for a moment to her wish of going away, and making over her cards to a friend, they departed as soon as the carriage could be found.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79666,\n            \"Lady Middleton expressed her sense of the affair about once every day, or twice, if the subject occurred very often, by saying, \\u201cIt is very shocking, indeed!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82529,\n            \"After staying with them half an hour, he asked Elinor to walk with him to Conduit Street, and introduce him to Sir John and Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84703,\n            \"They were lucky enough to find Lady Middleton at home, and Sir John came in before their visit ended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84732,\n            \"Sir John was ready to like anybody, and though Mr. Dashwood did not seem to know much about horses, he soon set him down as a very good-natured fellow: while Lady Middleton saw enough of fashion in his appearance to think his acquaintance worth having;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84818,\n            \"\\u201cLady Middleton is really a most elegant woman!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85026,\n            \"and as for Lady Middleton, she found her one of the most charming women in the world!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85092,\n            \"The same manners, however, which recommended Mrs. John Dashwood to the good opinion of Lady Middleton did not suit the fancy of Mrs. Jennings, and to _ her _ she appeared nothing more than a little proud-looking woman of uncordial address, who met her husband\\u2019s sisters without any affection, and almost without having anything to say to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85671,\n            \"So well had they recommended themselves to Lady Middleton, so agreeable had their assiduities made them to her, that though Lucy was certainly not so elegant, and her sister not even genteel, she was as ready as Sir John to ask them to spend a week or two in Conduit Street;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85763,\n            \"Their claims to the notice of Mrs. John Dashwood, as the nieces of the gentleman who for many years had had the care of her brother, might not have done much, however, towards procuring them seats at her table;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85808,\n            \"but as Lady Middleton\\u2019s guests they must be welcome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85820,\n            \"and Lucy, who had long wanted to be personally known to the family, to have a nearer view of their characters and her own difficulties, and to have an opportunity of endeavouring to please them, had seldom been happier in her life, than she was on receiving Mrs. John Dashwood\\u2019s card.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86076,\n            \"\\u201d said Lucy, as they walked up the stairs together \\u2014 for the Middletons arrived so directly after Mrs. Jennings, that they all followed the servant at the same time: \\u2014 \\u201cthere is nobody here but you, that can feel for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86342,\n            \"and of the few syllables that did escape her, not one fell to the share of Miss Dashwood, whom she eyed with the spirited determination of disliking her at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87244,\n            \"\\u201d The Colonel, though disclaiming all pretensions to connoisseurship, warmly admired the screens, as he would have done any thing painted by Miss Dashwood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87313,\n            \"and after they had received gratifying testimony of Lady Middletons\\u2019 s approbation, Fanny presented them to her mother, considerately informing her, at the same time, that they were done by Miss Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89019,\n            \"But now there is one good thing, we shall be able to meet, and meet pretty often, for Lady Middleton\\u2019s delighted with Mrs. Dashwood, so we shall be a good deal in Harley Street, I dare say, and Edward spends half his time with his sister \\u2014 besides, Lady Middleton and Mrs. Ferrars will visit now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90437,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, Miss Marianne,\\u201dcried Lucy, eager to take some revenge on her, \\u201cyou think young men never stand upon engagements, if they have no mind to keep them, little as well as great.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91225,\n            \"Their hours were therefore made over to Lady Middleton and the two Miss Steeles, by whom their company, in fact was as little valued, as it was professedly sought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91301,\n            \"Though nothing could be more polite than Lady Middleton\\u2019s behaviour to Elinor and Marianne, she did not really like them at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91327,\n            \"Because they neither flattered herself nor her children, she could not believe them good-natured;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91345,\n            \"and because they were fond of reading, she fancied them satirical: perhaps without exactly knowing what it was to be satirical;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91388,\n            \"Their presence was a restraint both on her and on Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91414,\n            \"Lady Middleton was ashamed of doing nothing before them, and the flattery which Lucy was proud to think of and administer at other times, she feared they would despise her for offering.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93088,\n            \"\\u2018 My dear Madam,\\u2019I always say to her, \\u2018 you must make yourself easy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93122,\n            \"Why would you be persuaded by my uncle, Sir Robert, against your own judgment, to place Edward under private tuition, at the most critical time of his life?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93155,\n            \"If you had only sent him to Westminster as well as myself, instead of sending him to Mr. Pratt\\u2019s, all this would have been prevented.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93186,\n            \"\\u2019 This is the way in which I always consider the matter, and my mother is perfectly convinced of her error.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93814,\n            \"The consideration of Mrs. Dennison\\u2019s mistake, in supposing his sisters their guests, had suggested the propriety of their being really invited to become such, while Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s engagements kept her from home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93902,\n            \"\\u201cI do not see how it can be done,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwithout affronting Lady Middleton, for they spend every day with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93965,\n            \"But they are Lady Middleton\\u2019s visitors.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93974,\n            \"How can I ask them away from her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94001,\n            \"\\u201cThey had already spent a week in this manner in Conduit Street, and Lady Middleton could not be displeased at their giving the same number of days to such near relations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94153,\n            \"indeed, you _ do _ like them, you know, very much already, and so does my mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94254,\n            \"Fanny, rejoicing in her escape, and proud of the ready wit that had procured it, wrote the next morning to Lucy, to request her company and her sister\\u2019s, for some days, in Harley Street, as soon as Lady Middleton could spare them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94512,\n            \"Her flattery had already subdued the pride of Lady Middleton, and made an entry into the close heart of Mrs. John Dashwood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94700,\n            \"and, contenting herself with visiting her once or twice a day, returned from that period to her own home, and her own habits, in which she found the Miss Dashwoods very ready to resume their former share.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94742,\n            \"About the third or fourth morning after their being thus resettled in Berkeley Street, Mrs. Jennings, on returning from her ordinary visit to Mrs. Palmer, entered the drawing-room, where Elinor was sitting by herself, with an air of such hurrying importance as prepared her to hear something wonderful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100802,\n            \"You see I cannot leave Mrs. Clarke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100939,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI cannot suppose it possible that she should be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102763,\n            \"I have not time to speak to Mrs. Jennings about it myself, but pray tell her I am quite happy to hear she is not in anger against us, and Lady Middleton the same;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102845,\n            \"I suppose Lady Middleton won\\u2019t ask us any more this bout.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103740,\n            \"and begging to be most gratefully and respectfully remembered to her, and to Sir John, and Lady Middleton, and the dear children, when you chance to see them, and love to Miss Marianne, \\u201cI am, & c.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 6]\": [\n        [\n            10391,\n            \"In such employments as these they were interrupted soon after breakfast the next day by the entrance of their landlord, who called to welcome them to Barton, and to offer them every accommodation from his own house and garden in which theirs might at present be deficient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10452,\n            \"He had formerly visited at Stanhill, but it was too long for his young cousins to remember him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10493,\n            \"Their arrival seemed to afford him real satisfaction, and their comfort to be an object of real solicitude to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10515,\n            \"He said much of his earnest desire of their living in the most sociable terms with his family, and pressed them so cordially to dine at Barton Park every day till they were better settled at home, that, though his entreaties were carried to a point of perseverance beyond civility, they could not give offence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10583,\n            \"for within an hour after he left them, a large basket full of garden stuff and fruit arrived from the park, which was followed before the end of the day by a present of game.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10621,\n            \"He insisted, moreover, on conveying all their letters to and from the post for them, and would not be denied the satisfaction of sending them his newspaper every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10654,\n            \"Lady Middleton had sent a very civil message by him, denoting her intention of waiting on Mrs. Dashwood as soon as she could be assured that her visit would be no inconvenience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11251,\n            \"He hunted and shot, and she humoured her children;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11269,\n            \"Lady Middleton had the advantage of being able to spoil her children all the year round, while Sir John\\u2019s independent employments were in existence only half the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11385,\n            \"he delighted in collecting about him more young people than his house would hold, and the noisier they were the better was he pleased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11411,\n            \"He was a blessing to all the juvenile part of the neighbourhood, for in summer he was for ever forming parties to eat cold ham and chicken out of doors, and in winter his private balls were numerous enough for any young lady who was not suffering under the unsatiable appetite of fifteen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11576,\n            \"In showing kindness to his cousins therefore he had the real satisfaction of a good heart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11593,\n            \"and in settling a family of females only in his cottage, he had all the satisfaction of a sportsman;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11650,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and her daughters were met at the door of the house by Sir John, who welcomed them to Barton Park with unaffected sincerity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11678,\n            \"and as he attended them to the drawing room repeated to the young ladies the concern which the same subject had drawn from him the day before, at being unable to get any smart young men to meet them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11719,\n            \"They would see, he said, only one gentleman there besides himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11753,\n            \"He hoped they would all excuse the smallness of the party, and could assure them it should never happen so again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11776,\n            \"He had been to several families that morning in hopes of procuring some addition to their number, but it was moonlight and every body was full of engagements.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11806,\n            \"Luckily Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother had arrived at Barton within the last hour, and as she was a very cheerful agreeable woman, he hoped the young ladies would not find it so very dull as they might imagine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12063,\n            \"His appearance however was not unpleasing, in spite of his being in the opinion of Marianne and Margaret an absolute old bachelor, for he was on the wrong side of five and thirty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12341,\n            \"Sir John was loud in his admiration at the end of every song, and as loud in his conversation with the others while every song lasted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12432,\n            \"and she felt a respect for him on the occasion, which the others had reasonably forfeited by their shameless want of taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12456,\n            \"His pleasure in music, though it amounted not to that ecstatic delight which alone could sympathize with her own, was estimable when contrasted against the horrible insensibility of the others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14095,\n            \"Sir John Middleton, who called on them every day for the first fortnight, and who was not in the habit of seeing much occupation at home, could not conceal his amazement on finding them always employed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14148,\n            \"for, in spite of Sir John\\u2019s urgent entreaties that they would mix more in the neighbourhood, and repeated assurances of his carriage being always at their service, the independence of Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s spirit overcame the wish of society for her children;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14884,\n            \"Elinor and her mother rose up in amazement at their entrance, and while the eyes of both were fixed on him with an evident wonder and a secret admiration which equally sprung from his appearance, he apologized for his intrusion by relating its cause, in a manner so frank and so graceful that his person, which was uncommonly handsome, received additional charms from his voice and expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14957,\n            \"Had he been even old, ugly, and vulgar, the gratitude and kindness of Mrs. Dashwood would have been secured by any act of attention to her child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15013,\n            \"She thanked him again and again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15020,\n            \"and, with a sweetness of address which always attended her, invited him to be seated.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15063,\n            \"His name, he replied, was Willoughby, and his present home was at Allenham, from whence he hoped she would allow him the honour of calling tomorrow to enquire after Miss Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15158,\n            \"Marianne herself had seen less of his person than the rest, for the confusion which crimsoned over her face, on his lifting her up, had robbed her of the power of regarding him after their entering the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15200,\n            \"But she had seen enough of him to join in all the admiration of the others, and with an energy which always adorned her praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15284,\n            \"His name was good, his residence was in their favourite village, and she soon found out that of all manly dresses a shooting-jacket was the most becoming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15336,\n            \"Sir John called on them as soon as the next interval of fair weather that morning allowed him to get out of doors;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15426,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou know him then,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15573,\n            \"But he is a pleasant, good humoured fellow, and has got the nicest little black bitch of a pointer I ever saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15673,\n            \"and he told them that Mr. Willoughby had no property of his own in the country;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15721,\n            \"adding, \\u201cYes, yes, he is very well worth catching I can tell you, Miss Dashwood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15755,\n            \"and if I were you, I would not give him up to my younger sister, in spite of all this tumbling down hills.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15806,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not believe,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, with a good humoured smile, \\u201cthat Mr. Willoughby will be incommoded by the attempts of either of _ my _ daughters towards what you call _ catching him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15879,\n            \"I am glad to find, however, from what you say, that he is a respectable young man, and one whose acquaintance will not be ineligible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16293,\n            \"with a kindness which Sir John\\u2019s account of him and her own gratitude prompted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17830,\n            \"Sir John had dropped hints of past injuries and disappointments, which justified her belief of his being an unfortunate man, and she regarded him with respect and compassion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19659,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, unfortunately for himself, had no such encouragement to think only of Marianne, and in conversing with Elinor he found the greatest consolation for the indifference of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19720,\n            \"This suspicion was given by some words which accidentally dropped from him one evening at the park, when they were sitting down together by mutual consent, while the others were dancing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20014,\n            \"\\u201d After a short pause he resumed the conversation by saying, \\u2014 \\u201cDoes your sister make no distinction in her objections against a second attachment?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20194,\n            \"I once knew a lady who in temper and mind greatly resembled your sister, who thought and judged like her, but who from an enforced change \\u2014 from a series of unfortunate circumstances \\u2014\\u201dHere he stopt suddenly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20821,\n            \"Of John I know very little, though we have lived together for years;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22968,\n            \"\\u201cWe must go,\\u201dsaid Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23183,\n            \"\\u201cThere is no persuading you to change your mind, Brandon, I know of old,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cwhen once you are determined on anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24054,\n            \"Some more of the Careys came to dinner, and they had the pleasure of sitting down nearly twenty to table, which Sir John observed with great contentment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30256,\n            \"\\u201cRemember, Elinor,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201chow very often Sir John fetches our letters himself from the post, and carries them to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30285,\n            \"We have already agreed that secrecy may be necessary, and we must acknowledge that it could not be maintained if their correspondence were to pass through Sir John\\u2019s hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35567,\n            \"Before the middle of the day, they were visited by Sir John and Mrs. Jennings, who, having heard of the arrival of a gentleman at the cottage, came to take a survey of the guest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35697,\n            \"Sir John never came to the Dashwoods without either inviting them to dine at the park the next day, or to drink tea with them that evening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35726,\n            \"On the present occasion, for the better entertainment of their visitor, towards whose amusement he felt himself bound to contribute, he wished to engage them for both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35757,\n            \"\\u201cYou _ must _ drink tea with us to night,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cfor we shall be quite alone \\u2014 and tomorrow you must absolutely dine with us, for we shall be a large party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35886,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI wish with all my soul,\\u201dcried Sir John, \\u201cthat Willoughby were among us again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38014,\n            \"She was sitting near the window, and as soon as Sir John perceived her, he left the rest of the party to the ceremony of knocking at the door, and stepping across the turf, obliged her to open the casement to speak to him, though the space was so short between the door and the window, as to make it hardly possible to speak at one without being heard at the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38093,\n            \"\\u201cWell,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cwe have brought you some strangers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38118,\n            \"they will hear you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38137,\n            \"Charlotte is very pretty, I can tell you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38353,\n            \"so I said to Sir John, I do think I hear a carriage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38408,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and Margaret came down stairs at the same time, and they all sat down to look at one another, while Mrs. Jennings continued her story as she walked through the passage into the parlour, attended by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39413,\n            \"Sir John had been very urgent with them all to spend the next day at the park.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39519,\n            \"But Sir John would not be satisfied \\u2014 the carriage should be sent for them and they must come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40381,\n            \"\\u201d When they were seated in the dining room, Sir John observed with regret that they were only eight all together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40404,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear,\\u201dsaid he to his lady, \\u201cit is very provoking that we should be so few.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41882,\n            \"\\u2014 I met Colonel Brandon Monday morning in Bond-street, just before we left town, and he told me of it directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41985,\n            \"When we met him, he turned back and walked with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42650,\n            \"But mama did not think the match good enough for me, otherwise Sir John would have mentioned it to the Colonel, and we should have been married immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42681,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not Colonel Brandon know of Sir John\\u2019s proposal to your mother before it was made?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42894,\n            \"In a morning\\u2019s excursion to Exeter, they had met with two young ladies, whom Mrs. Jennings had the satisfaction of discovering to be her relations, and this was enough for Sir John to invite them directly to the park, as soon as their present engagements at Exeter were over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42951,\n            \"Their engagements at Exeter instantly gave way before such an invitation, and Lady Middleton was thrown into no little alarm on the return of Sir John, by hearing that she was very soon to receive a visit from two girls whom she had never seen in her life, and of whose elegance, \\u2014 whose tolerable gentility even, she could have no proof;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43089,\n            \"As it was impossible, however, now to prevent their coming, Lady Middleton resigned herself to the idea of it, with all the philosophy of a well-bred woman, contenting herself with merely giving her husband a gentle reprimand on the subject five or six times every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43233,\n            \"Sir John\\u2019s confidence in his own judgment rose with this animated praise, and he set off directly for the cottage to tell the Miss Dashwoods of the Miss Steeles\\u2019 arrival, and to assure them of their being the sweetest girls in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43332,\n            \"Sir John wanted the whole family to walk to the Park directly and look at his guests.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43355,\n            \"It was painful to him even to keep a third cousin to himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43369,\n            \"\\u201cDo come now,\\u201dsaid he \\u2014 \\u201cpray come \\u2014 you must come \\u2014 I declare you shall come \\u2014 You can\\u2019t think how you will like them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43460,\n            \"and I have told them it is all very true, and a great deal more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43524,\n            \"_ You _ are my cousins, and they are my wife\\u2019s, so you must be related.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43553,\n            \"He could only obtain a promise of their calling at the Park within a day or two, and then left them in amazement at their indifference, to walk home and boast anew of their attractions to the Miss Steeles, as he had been already boasting of the Miss Steeles to them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43997,\n            \"\\u201d said she, on his taking Miss Steeles\\u2019 s pocket handkerchief, and throwing it out of window \\u2014 \\u201cHe is full of monkey tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44889,\n            \"\\u201cWe have heard Sir John admire it excessively,\\u201dsaid Lucy, who seemed to think some apology necessary for the freedom of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45438,\n            \"They came from Exeter, well provided with admiration for the use of Sir John Middleton, his family, and all his relations, and no niggardly proportion was now dealt out to his fair cousins, whom they declared to be the most beautiful, elegant, accomplished, and agreeable girls they had ever beheld, and with whom they were particularly anxious to be better acquainted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45509,\n            \"And to be better acquainted therefore, Elinor soon found was their inevitable lot, for as Sir John was entirely on the side of the Miss Steeles, their party would be too strong for opposition, and that kind of intimacy must be submitted to, which consists of sitting an hour or two together in the same room almost every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45581,\n            \"but he did not know that any more was required: to be together was, in his opinion, to be intimate, and while his continual schemes for their meeting were effectual, he had not a doubt of their being established friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45627,\n            \"To do him justice, he did every thing in his power to promote their unreserve, by making the Miss Steeles acquainted with whatever he knew or supposed of his cousins\\u2019 situations in the most delicate particulars;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45952,\n            \"But Sir John did not sport long with the curiosity which he delighted to raise, for he had at least as much pleasure in telling the name, as Miss Steele had in hearing it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46261,\n            \"\\u2014 But her curiosity was unavailing, for no farther notice was taken of Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s name by Miss Steele when alluded to, or even openly mentioned by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51494,\n            \"Elinor, who foresaw a fairer opening for the point she had in view, in such a party as this was likely to be, more at liberty among themselves under the tranquil and well-bred direction of Lady Middleton than when her husband united them together in one noisy purpose, immediately accepted the invitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52984,\n            \"but I love him too well to be the selfish means of robbing him, perhaps, of all that his mother might give him if he married to please her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54967,\n            \"Sir John would not hear of their going;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55475,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have a notion,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cthat Miss Marianne would not object to such a scheme, if her elder sister would come into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55530,\n            \"So I would advise you two, to set off for town, when you are tired of Barton, without saying a word to Miss Dashwood about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60326,\n            \"\\u201cIf this open weather holds much longer,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, when they met at breakfast the following morning, \\u201cSir John will not like leaving Barton next week;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61669,\n            \"Business on Sir John\\u2019s part, and a violent cold on her own, prevented their calling in Berkeley Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61773,\n            \"Elinor found, when the evening was over, that disposition is not materially altered by a change of abode, for although scarcely settled in town, Sir John had contrived to collect around him, nearly twenty young people, and to amuse them with a ball.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62251,\n            \"\\u201cSo my daughter Middleton told me, for it seems Sir John met him somewhere in the street this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71394,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt would be unnecessary I am sure, for you to caution Mrs. Palmer and Sir John against ever naming Mr. Willoughby, or making the slightest allusion to what has passed, before my sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71549,\n            \"No more would Sir John, nor my daughters, for they are all very thoughtful and considerate;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79150,\n            \"for neither Mrs. Jennings, nor Sir John, nor even Mrs. Palmer herself, ever spoke of him before her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81827,\n            \"Elinor lost no time in bringing her business forward, was on the point of concluding it, when another gentleman presented himself at her side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81854,\n            \"She turned her eyes towards his face, and found him with some surprise to be her brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81896,\n            \"John Dashwood was really far from being sorry to see his sisters again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81916,\n            \"and his inquiries after their mother were respectful and attentive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81940,\n            \"\\u201cI wished very much to call upon you yesterday,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cbut it was impossible, for we were obliged to take Harry to see the wild beasts at Exeter Exchange;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81995,\n            \"_ This _ morning I had fully intended to call on you, if I could possibly find a spare half hour, but one has always so much to do on first coming to town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82067,\n            \"I understand she is a woman of very good fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82078,\n            \"And the Middletons too, you must introduce me to _ them _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82092,\n            \"As my mother-in-law\\u2019s relations, I shall be happy to show them every respect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82113,\n            \"They are excellent neighbours to you in the country, I understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82222,\n            \"Edward brought us a most charming account of the place: the most complete thing of its kind, he said, that ever was, and you all seemed to enjoy it beyond any thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82285,\n            \"and was not sorry to be spared the necessity of answering him, by the arrival of Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s servant, who came to tell her that his mistress waited for them at the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82324,\n            \"Mr. Dashwood attended them down stairs, was introduced to Mrs. Jennings at the door of her carriage, and repeating his hope of being able to call on them the next day, took leave.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84703,\n            \"They were lucky enough to find Lady Middleton at home, and Sir John came in before their visit ended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84732,\n            \"Sir John was ready to like anybody, and though Mr. Dashwood did not seem to know much about horses, he soon set him down as a very good-natured fellow: while Lady Middleton saw enough of fashion in his appearance to think his acquaintance worth having;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93209,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor would not oppose his opinion, because, whatever might be her general estimation of the advantage of a public school, she could not think of Edward\\u2019s abode in Mr. Pratt\\u2019s family, with any satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93318,\n            \"\\u201cFor my own part,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cI am excessively fond of a cottage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93867,\n            \"and it was altogether an attention which the delicacy of his conscience pointed out to be requisite to its complete enfranchisement from his promise to his father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94035,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny paused a moment, and then, with fresh vigor, said, \\u201cMy love, I would ask them with all my heart, if it was in my power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94121,\n            \"We can ask your sisters some other year, you know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94145,\n            \"I am sure you will like them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94153,\n            \"indeed, you _ do _ like them, you know, very much already, and so does my mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94190,\n            \"He saw the necessity of inviting the Miss Steeles immediately, and his conscience was pacified by the resolution of inviting his sisters another year;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94574,\n            \"Sir John, who called on them more than once, brought home such accounts of the favour they were in, as must be universally striking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98305,\n            \"\\u201cYou have heard, I suppose,\\u201dsaid he with great solemnity, as soon as he was seated, \\u201cof the very shocking discovery that took place under our roof yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98370,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars too \\u2014 in short it has been a scene of such complicated distress \\u2014 but I will hope that the storm may be weathered without our being any of us quite overcome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98416,\n            \"But I would not alarm you too much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98656,\n            \"While she with the truest affection had been planning a most eligible connection for him, was it to be supposed that he could be all the time secretly engaged to another person!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99253,\n            \"He therefore replied, without any resentment, \\u201cI would by no means speak disrespectfully of any relation of yours, madam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99277,\n            \"Miss Lucy Steele is, I dare say, a very deserving young woman, but in the present case you know, the connection must be impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99349,\n            \"In short, I do not mean to reflect upon the behaviour of any person whom you have a regard for, Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99786,\n            \"\\u201cIf he would only have done as well by himself,\\u201dsaid John Dashwood, \\u201cas all his friends were disposed to do by him, he might now have been in his proper situation, and would have wanted for nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99974,\n            \"\\u201cCan anything be more galling to the spirit of a man,\\u201dcontinued John, \\u201cthan to see his younger brother in possession of an estate which might have been his own?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100036,\n            \"and with repeated assurances to his sisters that he really believed there was no material danger in Fanny\\u2019s indisposition, and that they need not therefore be very uneasy about it, he went away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103598,\n            \"and should it ever be in your power to recommend him to any body that has a living to bestow, am very sure you will not forget us, and dear Mrs. Jennings too, trust she will speak a good word for us to Sir John, or Mr. Palmer, or any friend that may be able to assist us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103740,\n            \"and begging to be most gratefully and respectfully remembered to her, and to Sir John, and Lady Middleton, and the dear children, when you chance to see them, and love to Miss Marianne, \\u201cI am, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111987,\n            \"\\u2014 and when to that was added the fanciful imagery of Edward reading prayers in a white surplice, and publishing the banns of marriage between John Smith and Mary Brown, he could conceive nothing more ridiculous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112946,\n            \"\\u2014 and a faint invitation from Fanny, to come to Norland whenever it should happen to be in their way, which of all things was the most unlikely to occur, with a more warm, though less public, assurance, from John to Elinor, of the promptitude with which he should come to see her at Delaford, was all that foretold any meeting in the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124948,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cLast night, in Drury Lane lobby, I ran against Sir John Middleton, and when he saw who I was, for the first time these two months, he spoke to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124986,\n            \"That he had cut me ever since my marriage, I had seen without surprise or resentment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125004,\n            \"Now, however, his good-natured, honest, stupid soul, full of indignation against me, and concern for your sister, could not resist the temptation of telling me what he knew ought to, though probably he did not think it _ would _, vex me horridly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125059,\n            \"As bluntly as he could speak it, therefore, he told me that Marianne Dashwood was dying of a putrid fever at Cleveland \\u2014 a letter that morning received from Mrs. Jennings declared her danger most imminent \\u2014 the Palmers are all gone off in a fright, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125112,\n            \"I was too much shocked to be able to pass myself off as insensible even to the undiscerning Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125133,\n            \"His heart was softened in seeing mine suffer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125142,\n            \"and so much of his ill-will was done away, that when we parted, he almost shook me by the hand while he reminded me of an old promise about a pointer puppy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131131,\n            \"To John, to Fanny, yes, even to them, little as they deserve, I had given less than their due.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133568,\n            \"and in the first of John\\u2019s, there had been this sentence: \\u2014 \\u201cWe know nothing of our unfortunate Edward, and can make no enquiries on so prohibited a subject, but conclude him to be still at Oxford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142345,\n            \"\\u201cI will not say that I am disappointed, my dear sister,\\u201dsaid John, as they were walking together one morning before the gates of Delaford House, \\u201c_ that _ would be saying too much, for certainly you have been one of the most fortunate young women in the world, as it is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142469,\n            \"And though, perhaps, Marianne may not seem exactly the person to attract him, yet I think it would altogether be advisable for you to have them now frequently staying with you, for as Colonel Brandon seems a great deal at home, nobody can tell what may happen;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142558,\n            \"In short, you may as well give her a chance: you understand me.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 7]\": [\n        [\n            92771,\n            \"and had just determined to find out his name from the latter, when they both came towards her, and Mr. Dashwood introduced him to her as Mr. Robert Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92944,\n            \"Why they _ were _ different, Robert explained to her himself in the course of a quarter of an hour\\u2019s conversation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93017,\n            \"while he himself, though probably without any particular, any material superiority by nature, merely from the advantage of a public school, was as well fitted to mix in the world as any other man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95201,\n            \"Mr. Edward Ferrars, the very young man I used to joke with you about (but however, as it turns out, I am monstrous glad there was never any thing in it), Mr. Edward Ferrars, it seems, has been engaged above this twelvemonth to my cousin Lucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111963,\n            \"The idea of Edward\\u2019s being a clergyman, and living in a small parsonage-house, diverted him beyond measure;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111987,\n            \"\\u2014 and when to that was added the fanciful imagery of Edward reading prayers in a white surplice, and publishing the banns of marriage between John Smith and Mary Brown, he could conceive nothing more ridiculous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112110,\n            \"\\u201cWe may treat it as a joke,\\u201dsaid he, at last, recovering from the affected laugh which had considerably lengthened out the genuine gaiety of the moment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138627,\n            \"The independence she settled on Robert, through resentment against you, has put it in his power to make his own choice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138681,\n            \"She will hardly be less hurt, I suppose, by Robert\\u2019s marrying Lucy, than she would have been by your marrying her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138708,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe will be more hurt by it, for Robert always was her favourite.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138725,\n            \"\\u2014 She will be more hurt by it, and on the same principle will forgive him much sooner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140855,\n            \"and even, if she might hereafter be induced to forgive her son, his wife should never be acknowledged as her daughter, nor be permitted to appear in her presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141160,\n            \"\\u201cwould they have me beg my mother\\u2019s pardon for Robert\\u2019s ingratitude to _ her _, and breach of honour to _ me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142612,\n            \"_ That _ was due to the folly of Robert, and the cunning of his wife;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142643,\n            \"The selfish sagacity of the latter, which had at first drawn Robert into the scrape, was the principal instrument of his deliverance from it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142670,\n            \"for her respectful humility, assiduous attentions, and endless flatteries, as soon as the smallest opening was given for their exercise, reconciled Mrs. Ferrars to his choice, and re-established him completely in her favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142782,\n            \"When Robert first sought her acquaintance, and privately visited her in Bartlett\\u2019s Buildings, it was only with the view imputed to him by his brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142812,\n            \"He merely meant to persuade her to give up the engagement;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142824,\n            \"and as there could be nothing to overcome but the affection of both, he naturally expected that one or two interviews would settle the matter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142864,\n            \"for though Lucy soon gave him hopes that his eloquence would convince her in _ time _, another visit, another conversation, was always wanted to produce this conviction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142896,\n            \"Some doubts always lingered in her mind when they parted, which could only be removed by another half hour\\u2019s discourse with himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142937,\n            \"Instead of talking of Edward, they came gradually to talk only of Robert, \\u2014 a subject on which he had always more to say than on any other, and in which she soon betrayed an interest even equal to his own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142982,\n            \"and in short, it became speedily evident to both, that he had entirely supplanted his brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143001,\n            \"He was proud of his conquest, proud of tricking Edward, and very proud of marrying privately without his mother\\u2019s consent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143042,\n            \"for she had many relations and old acquaintances to cut \\u2014 and he drew several plans for magnificent cottages;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143137,\n            \"But perseverance in humility of conduct and messages, in self-condemnation for Robert\\u2019s offence, and gratitude for the unkindness she was treated with, procured her in time the haughty notice which overcame her by its graciousness, and led soon afterwards, by rapid degrees, to the highest state of affection and influence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143198,\n            \"Lucy became as necessary to Mrs. Ferrars, as either Robert or Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143213,\n            \"and while Edward was never cordially forgiven for having once intended to marry her, and Elinor, though superior to her in fortune and birth, was spoken of as an intruder, _ she _ was in every thing considered, and always openly acknowledged, to be a favourite child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143291,\n            \"and setting aside the jealousies and ill-will continually subsisting between Fanny and Lucy, in which their husbands of course took a part, as well as the frequent domestic disagreements between Robert and Lucy themselves, nothing could exceed the harmony in which they all lived together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143342,\n            \"What Edward had done to forfeit the right of eldest son, might have puzzled many people to find out;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143363,\n            \"and what Robert had done to succeed to it, might have puzzled them still more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143439,\n            \"\\u2014 and if Edward might be judged from the ready discharge of his duties in every particular, from an increasing attachment to his wife and his home, and from the regular cheerfulness of his spirits, he might be supposed no less contented with his lot, no less free from every wish of an exchange.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143561,\n            \"for her wish of bringing Marianne and Colonel Brandon together was hardly less earnest, though rather more liberal than what John had expressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143640,\n            \"They each felt his sorrows, and their own obligations, and Marianne, by general consent, was to be the reward of all.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 8]\": [\n        [\n            1809,\n            \"Margaret, the other sister, was a good-humored, well-disposed girl;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1826,\n            \"but as she had already imbibed a good deal of Marianne\\u2019s romance, without having much of her sense, she did not, at thirteen, bid fair to equal her sisters at a more advanced period of life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12063,\n            \"His appearance however was not unpleasing, in spite of his being in the opinion of Marianne and Margaret an absolute old bachelor, for he was on the wrong side of five and thirty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14392,\n            \"and towards one of these hills did Marianne and Margaret one memorable morning direct their steps, attracted by the partial sunshine of a showery sky, and unable longer to bear the confinement which the settled rain of the two preceding days had occasioned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14563,\n            \"\\u2014 Margaret, we will walk here at least two hours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14575,\n            \"\\u201d Margaret agreed, and they pursued their way against the wind, resisting it with laughing delight for about twenty minutes longer, when suddenly the clouds united over their heads, and a driving rain set full in their face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18710,\n            \"Little had Mrs. Dashwood or her daughters imagined when they first came into Devonshire, that so many engagements would arise to occupy their time as shortly presented themselves, or that they should have such frequent invitations and such constant visitors as to leave them little leisure for serious employment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19125,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood entered into all their feelings with a warmth which left her no inclination for checking this excessive display of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21114,\n            \"and in the whole of the sentence, in his manner of pronouncing it, and in his addressing her sister by her Christian name alone, she instantly saw an intimacy so decided, a meaning so direct, as marked a perfect agreement between them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21162,\n            \"From that moment she doubted not of their being engaged to each other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21176,\n            \"and the belief of it created no other surprise than that she, or any of their friends, should be left by tempers so frank, to discover it by accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21317,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou have said so,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201calmost every day since they first met on High-church Down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21342,\n            \"and they had not known each other a week, I believe, before you were certain that Marianne wore his picture round her neck;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21392,\n            \"I am sure they will be married very soon, for he has got a lock of her hair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21448,\n            \"I am almost sure it is, for I saw him cut it off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21591,\n            \"Margaret\\u2019s sagacity was not always displayed in a way so satisfactory to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21608,\n            \"When Mrs. Jennings attacked her one evening at the park, to give the name of the young man who was Elinor\\u2019s particular favourite, which had been long a matter of great curiosity to her, Margaret answered by looking at her sister, and saying, \\u201cI must not tell, may I, Elinor?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21793,\n            \"\\u201d This increased the mirth of the company, and Margaret was eagerly pressed to say something more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21815,\n            \"pray, Miss Margaret, let us know all about it,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21893,\n            \"He is the curate of the parish I dare say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33012,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI wish,\\u201dsaid Margaret, striking out a novel thought, \\u201cthat somebody would give us all a large fortune apiece!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33098,\n            \"\\u201d cried Margaret, \\u201chow happy I should be!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35667,\n            \"But, as it was, she only learned, from some very significant looks, how far their penetration, founded on Margaret\\u2019s instructions, extended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38408,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and Margaret came down stairs at the same time, and they all sat down to look at one another, while Mrs. Jennings continued her story as she walked through the passage into the parlour, attended by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51553,\n            \"Margaret, with her mother\\u2019s permission, was equally compliant, and Marianne, though always unwilling to join any of their parties, was persuaded by her mother, who could not bear to have her seclude herself from any chance of amusement, to go likewise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56204,\n            \"Margaret and I shall be as much benefited by it as yourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56241,\n            \"You will find Margaret so improved when you come back again!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126876,\n            \"for so great was her uneasiness about Marianne, that she had already determined to set out for Cleveland on that very day, without waiting for any further intelligence, and had so far settled her journey before his arrival, that the Careys were then expected every moment to fetch Margaret away, as her mother was unwilling to take her where there might be infection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131448,\n            \"You, my mother, and Margaret, must henceforth be all the world to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133849,\n            \"By that time, Marianne was rather better, and her mother leaving her to the care of Margaret and the maid, returned to Elinor, who, though still much disordered, had so far recovered the use of her reason and voice as to be just beginning an inquiry of Thomas, as to the source of his intelligence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134595,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s and Elinor\\u2019s appetites were equally lost, and Margaret might think herself very well off, that with so much uneasiness as both her sisters had lately experienced, so much reason as they had often had to be careless of their meals, she had never been obliged to go without her dinner before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144323,\n            \"and fortunately for Sir John and Mrs. Jennings, when Marianne was taken from them, Margaret had reached an age highly suitable for dancing, and not very ineligible for being supposed to have a lover.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 9]\": [\n        [\n            26755,\n            \"\\u201d said Mrs. Dashwood, when he was leaving them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26767,\n            \"\\u201cI do not ask you to come in the morning, for we must walk to the park, to call on Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26809,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s visit to Lady Middleton took place the next day, and two of her daughters went with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26885,\n            \"On their return from the park they found Willoughby\\u2019s curricle and servant in waiting at the cottage, and Mrs. Dashwood was convinced that her conjecture had been just.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27125,\n            \"Mrs. Smith has this morning exercised the privilege of riches upon a poor dependent cousin, by sending me on business to London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27214,\n            \"\\u2014 and her business will not detain you from us long I hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27265,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd is Mrs. Smith your only friend?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28077,\n            \"I am persuaded that Mrs. Smith suspects his regard for Marianne, disapproves of it, (perhaps because she has other views for him,) and on that account is eager to get him away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28609,\n            \"It may be proper to conceal their engagement (if they _ are _ engaged) from Mrs. Smith \\u2014 and if that is the case, it must be highly expedient for Willoughby to be but little in Devonshire at present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29365,\n            \"and if he felt obliged, from a fear of offending Mrs. Smith, to resist the temptation of returning here soon, and yet aware that by declining your invitation, by saying that he was going away for some time, he should seem to act an ungenerous, a suspicious part by our family, he might well be embarrassed and disturbed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30412,\n            \"From you, her mother, and so kind, so indulgent a mother, the question could not give offence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30499,\n            \"I should never deserve her confidence again, after forcing from her a confession of what is meant at present to be unacknowledged to any one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30526,\n            \"I know Marianne\\u2019s heart: I know that she dearly loves me, and that I shall not be the last to whom the affair is made known, when circumstances make the revealment of it eligible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30687,\n            \"\\u2014 but one evening, Mrs. Dashwood, accidentally taking up a volume of Shakespeare, exclaimed, \\u201cWe have never finished Hamlet, Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32319,\n            \"They had begun to fail him before he entered the house, and they were quite overcome by the captivating manners of Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32432,\n            \"The whole family perceived it, and Mrs. Dashwood, attributing it to some want of liberality in his mother, sat down to table indignant against all selfish parents.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33131,\n            \"\\u201cI should be puzzled to spend so large a fortune myself,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, \\u201cif my children were all to be rich without my help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34275,\n            \"Do not you know she calls every one reserved who does not talk as fast, and admire what she admires as rapturously as herself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39977,\n            \"I am sure I shall be very happy to chaperon you at any time till I am confined, if Mrs. Dashwood should not like to go into public.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 10]\": [\n        [\n            2254,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe did not know what he was talking of, I dare say;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2314,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe did not stipulate for any particular sum, my dear Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3394,\n            \"If I were you, whatever I did should be done at my own discretion entirely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3411,\n            \"I would not bind myself to allow them any thing yearly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3444,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe you are right, my love;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3469,\n            \"whatever I may give them occasionally will be of far greater assistance than a yearly allowance, because they would only enlarge their style of living if they felt sure of a larger income, and would not be sixpence the richer for it at the end of the year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3529,\n            \"A present of fifty pounds, now and then, will prevent their ever being distressed for money, and will, I think, be amply discharging my promise to my father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3571,\n            \"Indeed, to say the truth, I am convinced within myself that your father had no idea of your giving them any money at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3598,\n            \"The assistance he thought of, I dare say, was only such as might be reasonably expected of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3660,\n            \"I\\u2019ll lay my life that he meant nothing farther;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3840,\n            \"I am sure I cannot imagine how they will spend half of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3884,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cUpon my word,\\u201dsaid Mr. Dashwood, \\u201cI believe you are perfectly right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3904,\n            \"My father certainly could mean nothing more by his request to me than what you say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3921,\n            \"I clearly understand it now, and I will strictly fulfil my engagement by such acts of assistance and kindness to them as you have described.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3948,\n            \"When my mother removes into another house my services shall be readily given to accommodate her as far as I can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4151,\n            \"And I must say this: that you owe no particular gratitude to him, nor attention to his wishes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5615,\n            \"it has none of that grace which I should expect in the man who could seriously attach my sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5653,\n            \"And besides all this, I am afraid, Mama, he has no real taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5964,\n            \"Mama, the more I know of the world, the more am I convinced that I shall never see a man whom I can really love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6047,\n            \"Why should you be less fortunate than your mother?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6480,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sure,\\u201dreplied Elinor, with a smile, \\u201cthat his dearest friends could not be dissatisfied with such commendation as that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6533,\n            \"\\u201cOf his sense and his goodness,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cno one can, I think, be in doubt, who has seen him often enough to engage him in unreserved conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6605,\n            \"But of his minuter propensities, as you call them you have from peculiar circumstances been kept more ignorant than myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6627,\n            \"He and I have been at times thrown a good deal together, while you have been wholly engrossed on the most affectionate principle by my mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6826,\n            \"When you tell me to love him as a brother, I shall no more see imperfection in his face, than I now do in his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7059,\n            \"\\u201cand be assured that I meant no offence to you, by speaking, in so quiet a way, of my own feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7161,\n            \"and till his sentiments are fully known, you cannot wonder at my wishing to avoid any encouragement of my own partiality, by believing or calling it more than it is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7237,\n            \"but, from Fanny\\u2019s occasional mention of her conduct and opinions, we have never been disposed to think her amiable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7261,\n            \"and I am very much mistaken if Edward is not himself aware that there would be many difficulties in his way, if he were to wish to marry a woman who had not either a great fortune or high rank.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35285,\n            \"I remember her promising to give you some.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35294,\n            \"But I should have thought her hair had been darker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35407,\n            \"the only difference in their conclusions was, that what Marianne considered as a free gift from her sister, Elinor was conscious must have been procured by some theft or contrivance unknown to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38976,\n            \"\\u201cbut, however, I can\\u2019t help wishing they had not travelled quite so fast, nor made such a long journey of it, for they came all round by London upon account of some business, for you know (nodding significantly and pointing to her daughter) it was wrong in her situation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40898,\n            \"\\u201cOh, my dear Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Palmer soon afterwards, \\u201cI have got such a favour to ask of you and your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41780,\n            \"I am monstrous glad of it, for then I shall have her for a neighbour you know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42235,\n            \"Mama says _ he _ was in love with your sister too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42330,\n            \"Nobody is more liked than Mr. Willoughby wherever he goes, and so you may tell your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42394,\n            \"However, I don\\u2019t think her hardly at all handsomer than you, I assure you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44889,\n            \"\\u201cWe have heard Sir John admire it excessively,\\u201dsaid Lucy, who seemed to think some apology necessary for the freedom of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50088,\n            \"Her mother, sisters, Fanny, all had been conscious of his regard for her at Norland;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83021,\n            \"And her mother too, Mrs. Ferrars, a very good-natured woman, I am sure it would give her great pleasure;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83063,\n            \"\\u201cIt would be something remarkable, now,\\u201dhe continued, \\u201csomething droll, if Fanny should have a brother and I a sister settling at the same time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83251,\n            \"To give you another instance of her liberality: \\u2014 The other day, as soon as we came to town, aware that money could not be very plenty with us just now, she put bank-notes into Fanny\\u2019s hands to the amount of two hundred pounds.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84460,\n            \"I remember Fanny used to say that she would marry sooner and better than you did;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84572,\n            \"and I think I can answer for your having Fanny and myself among the earliest and best pleased of your visitors.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84794,\n            \"\\u201cI shall have a charming account to carry to Fanny,\\u201dsaid he, as he walked back with his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84828,\n            \"Such a woman as I am sure Fanny will be glad to know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84920,\n            \"and Fanny and Mrs. Ferrars were both strongly prepossessed, that neither she nor her daughters were such kind of women as Fanny would like to associate with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85208,\n            \"but nothing would have induced Fanny voluntarily to mention his name before her, till able to tell her that his marriage with Miss Morton was resolved on, or till her husband\\u2019s expectations on Colonel Brandon were answered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87043,\n            \"Elinor, having once delivered her opinion on William\\u2019s side, by which she offended Mrs. Ferrars and Fanny still more, did not see the necessity of enforcing it by any farther assertion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87313,\n            \"and after they had received gratifying testimony of Lady Middletons\\u2019 s approbation, Fanny presented them to her mother, considerately informing her, at the same time, that they were done by Miss Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87379,\n            \"Perhaps Fanny thought for a moment that her mother had been quite rude enough, \\u2014 for, colouring a little, she immediately said, \\u201cThey are very pretty, ma\\u2019am \\u2014 an\\u2019t they?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87662,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny looked very angry too, and her husband was all in a fright at his sister\\u2019s audacity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93902,\n            \"\\u201cI do not see how it can be done,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwithout affronting Lady Middleton, for they spend every day with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93941,\n            \"You know I am always ready to pay them any attention in my power, as my taking them out this evening shows.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93974,\n            \"How can I ask them away from her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94035,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny paused a moment, and then, with fresh vigor, said, \\u201cMy love, I would ask them with all my heart, if it was in my power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94070,\n            \"But I had just settled within myself to ask the Miss Steeles to spend a few days with us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94101,\n            \"and I think the attention is due to them, as their uncle did so very well by Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94145,\n            \"I am sure you will like them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94254,\n            \"Fanny, rejoicing in her escape, and proud of the ready wit that had procured it, wrote the next morning to Lucy, to request her company and her sister\\u2019s, for some days, in Harley Street, as soon as Lady Middleton could spare them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98266,\n            \"The next morning brought a farther trial of it, in a visit from their brother, who came with a most serious aspect to talk over the dreadful affair, and bring them news of his wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98450,\n            \"She has borne it all, with the fortitude of an angel!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98463,\n            \"She says she never shall think well of anybody again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98507,\n            \"It was quite out of the benevolence of her heart, that she had asked these young women to her house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98588,\n            \"\\u2018 I wish, with all my heart,\\u2019says poor Fanny in her affectionate way, \\u2018 that we had asked your sisters instead of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98656,\n            \"While she with the truest affection had been planning a most eligible connection for him, was it to be supposed that he could be all the time secretly engaged to another person!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98749,\n            \"We consulted together, however, as to what should be done, and at last she determined to send for Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98784,\n            \"All that Mrs. Ferrars could say to make him put an end to the engagement, assisted too as you may well suppose by my arguments, and Fanny\\u2019s entreaties, was of no avail.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98843,\n            \"His mother explained to him her liberal designs, in case of his marrying Miss Morton;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100036,\n            \"and with repeated assurances to his sisters that he really believed there was no material danger in Fanny\\u2019s indisposition, and that they need not therefore be very uneasy about it, he went away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112946,\n            \"\\u2014 and a faint invitation from Fanny, to come to Norland whenever it should happen to be in their way, which of all things was the most unlikely to occur, with a more warm, though less public, assurance, from John to Elinor, of the promptitude with which he should come to see her at Delaford, was all that foretold any meeting in the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131131,\n            \"To John, to Fanny, yes, even to them, little as they deserve, I had given less than their due.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140791,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars was the most unfortunate of women \\u2014 poor Fanny had suffered agonies of sensibility \\u2014 and he considered the existence of each, under such a blow, with grateful wonder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141015,\n            \"Perhaps, however, he is kept silent by his fear of offending, and I shall, therefore, give him a hint, by a line to Oxford, that his sister and I both think a letter of proper submission from him, addressed perhaps to Fanny, and by her shown to her mother, might not be taken amiss;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141350,\n            \"and therefore, to make it easier to him, as he declared a much greater willingness to make mean concessions by word of mouth than on paper, it was resolved that, instead of writing to Fanny, he should go to London, and personally intreat her good offices in his favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141406,\n            \"\\u201cAnd if they really _ do _ interest themselves,\\u201dsaid Marianne, in her new character of candour, \\u201cin bringing about a reconciliation, I shall think that even John and Fanny are not entirely without merit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143198,\n            \"Lucy became as necessary to Mrs. Ferrars, as either Robert or Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143291,\n            \"and setting aside the jealousies and ill-will continually subsisting between Fanny and Lucy, in which their husbands of course took a part, as well as the frequent domestic disagreements between Robert and Lucy themselves, nothing could exceed the harmony in which they all lived together.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 12]\": [\n        [\n            11806,\n            \"Luckily Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother had arrived at Barton within the last hour, and as she was a very cheerful agreeable woman, he hoped the young ladies would not find it so very dull as they might imagine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11848,\n            \"The young ladies, as well as their mother, were perfectly satisfied with having two entire strangers of the party, and wished for no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11913,\n            \"She was full of jokes and laughter, and before dinner was over had said many witty things on the subject of lovers and husbands;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12542,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings was a widow with an ample jointure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12803,\n            \"and she was always anxious to get a good husband for every pretty girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12885,\n            \"and when its object was understood, she hardly knew whether most to laugh at its absurdity, or censure its impertinence, for she considered it as an unfeeling reflection on the colonel\\u2019s advanced years, and on his forlorn condition as an old bachelor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12934,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, who could not think a man five years younger than herself, so exceedingly ancient as he appeared to the youthful fancy of her daughter, ventured to clear Mrs. Jennings from the probability of wishing to throw ridicule on his age.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18049,\n            \"Who would submit to the indignity of being approved by such a woman as Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, that could command the indifference of any body else?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19299,\n            \"although the latter was an everlasting talker, and from the first had regarded her with a kindness which ensured her a large share of her discourse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19341,\n            \"and had Elinor\\u2019s memory been equal to her means of improvement, she might have known very early in their acquaintance all the particulars of Mr. Jennings\\u2019 s last illness, and what he said to his wife a few minutes before he died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21608,\n            \"When Mrs. Jennings attacked her one evening at the park, to give the name of the young man who was Elinor\\u2019s particular favourite, which had been long a matter of great curiosity to her, Margaret answered by looking at her sister, and saying, \\u201cI must not tell, may I, Elinor?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21815,\n            \"pray, Miss Margaret, let us know all about it,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22629,\n            \"I hope it is not to say that your sister is worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22739,\n            \"\\u201d said Mrs. Jennings, without attending to her daughter\\u2019s reproof.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22778,\n            \"And I hope she is well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23033,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you would but let us know what your business is,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cwe might see whether it could be put off or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23620,\n            \"\\u201cCome Colonel,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cbefore you go, do let us know what you are going about.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24171,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not you know,\\u201dsaid Willoughby, \\u201cthat we had been out in my curricle?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24192,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, yes, Mr. Impudence, I know that very well, and I was determined to find out _ where _ you had been to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24243,\n            \"and when I come to see you, I hope you will have new-furnished it, for it wanted it very much when I was there six years ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24289,\n            \"and Elinor found that in her resolution to know where they had been, she had actually made her own woman enquire of Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s groom;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24677,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf the impertinent remarks of Mrs. Jennings are to be the proof of impropriety in conduct, we are all offending every moment of our lives.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25079,\n            \"she was a great wonderer, as every one must be who takes a very lively interest in all the comings and goings of all their acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35806,\n            \"\\u201cAnd who knows but you may raise a dance,\\u201dsaid she.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36717,\n            \"\\u201cI think, Edward,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, as they were at breakfast the last morning, \\u201cyou would be a happier man if you had any profession to engage your time and give an interest to your plans and actions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37143,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe consequence of which, I suppose, will be,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, \\u201csince leisure has not promoted your own happiness, that your sons will be brought up to as many pursuits, employments, professions, and trades as Columella\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37397,\n            \"\\u201d This desponding turn of mind, though it could not be communicated to Mrs. Dashwood, gave additional pain to them all in the parting, which shortly took place, and left an uncomfortable impression on Elinor\\u2019s feelings especially, which required some trouble and time to subdue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38212,\n            \"\\u201d They were now joined by Mrs. Jennings, who had not patience enough to wait till the door was opened before she told _ her _ story.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38289,\n            \"I have brought my other son and daughter to see you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38408,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and Margaret came down stairs at the same time, and they all sat down to look at one another, while Mrs. Jennings continued her story as she walked through the passage into the parlour, attended by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38850,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, in the meantime, talked on as loud as she could, and continued her account of their surprise, the evening before, on seeing their friends, without ceasing till every thing was told.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38923,\n            \"\\u201cYou may believe how glad we all were to see them,\\u201dadded Mrs. Jennings, leaning forward towards Elinor, and speaking in a low voice as if she meant to be heard by no one else, though they were seated on different sides of the room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38976,\n            \"\\u201cbut, however, I can\\u2019t help wishing they had not travelled quite so fast, nor made such a long journey of it, for they came all round by London upon account of some business, for you know (nodding significantly and pointing to her daughter) it was wrong in her situation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39036,\n            \"I wanted her to stay at home and rest this morning, but she would come with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39431,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, who did not chuse to dine with them oftener than they dined at the cottage, absolutely refused on her own account;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39554,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings and Mrs. Palmer joined their entreaties, all seemed equally anxious to avoid a family party;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39928,\n            \"\\u201d cried Mrs. Palmer, with a laugh, \\u201cI shall be quite disappointed if you do not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40898,\n            \"\\u201cOh, my dear Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Palmer soon afterwards, \\u201cI have got such a favour to ask of you and your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42894,\n            \"In a morning\\u2019s excursion to Exeter, they had met with two young ladies, whom Mrs. Jennings had the satisfaction of discovering to be her relations, and this was enough for Sir John to invite them directly to the park, as soon as their present engagements at Exeter were over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43048,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s attempts at consolation were therefore unfortunately founded, when she advised her daughter not to care about their being so fashionable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53693,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI can answer for it that Miss Dashwood\\u2019s is not,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, laughing heartily;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54062,\n            \"He is brother to Mrs. John Dashwood \\u2014 _ that _ must be recommendation enough to her husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55058,\n            \"Though Mrs. Jennings was in the habit of spending a large portion of the year at the houses of her children and friends, she was not without a settled habitation of her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55132,\n            \"Towards this home, she began on the approach of January to turn her thoughts, and thither she one day abruptly, and very unexpectedly by them, asked the elder Misses Dashwood to accompany her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55255,\n            \"I am sure your mother can spare you very well, and I _ do _ beg you will favour me with your company, for I\\u2019ve quite set my heart upon it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55530,\n            \"So I would advise you two, to set off for town, when you are tired of Barton, without saying a word to Miss Dashwood about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55560,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cI am sure I shall be monstrous glad of Miss Marianne\\u2019s company, whether Miss Dashwood will go or not, only the more the merrier say I, and I thought it would be more comfortable for them to be together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55688,\n            \"Come, Miss Marianne, let us strike hands upon the bargain, and if Miss Dashwood will change her mind by and bye, why so much the better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55835,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings repeated her assurance that Mrs. Dashwood could spare them perfectly well;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55943,\n            \"Whatever Marianne was desirous of, her mother would be eager to promote \\u2014 she could not expect to influence the latter to cautiousness of conduct in an affair respecting which she had never been able to inspire her with distrust;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56088,\n            \"On being informed of the invitation, Mrs. Dashwood, persuaded that such an excursion would be productive of much amusement to both her daughters, and perceiving through all her affectionate attention to herself, how much the heart of Marianne was in it, would not hear of their declining the offer upon _ her _ account;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56157,\n            \"and then began to foresee, with her usual cheerfulness, a variety of advantages that would accrue to them all, from this separation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56335,\n            \"And in all probability you will see your brother, and whatever may be his faults, or the faults of his wife, when I consider whose son he is, I cannot bear to have you so wholly estranged from each other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56435,\n            \"\\u201cAnd what,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, \\u201cis my dear prudent Elinor going to suggest?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56485,\n            \"though I think very well of Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s heart, she is not a woman whose society can afford us pleasure, or whose protection will give us consequence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56518,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is very true,\\u201dreplied her mother, \\u201cbut of her society, separately from that of other people, you will scarcely have any thing at all, and you will almost always appear in public with Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56761,\n            \"\\u201cI will have you _ both _ go,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57349,\n            \"Elinor could not find herself in the carriage with Mrs. Jennings, and beginning a journey to London under her protection, and as her guest, without wondering at her own situation, so short had their acquaintance with that lady been, so wholly unsuited were they in age and disposition, and so many had been her objections against such a measure only a few days before!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57695,\n            \"They were three days on their journey, and Marianne\\u2019s behaviour as they travelled was a happy specimen of what future complaisance and companionableness to Mrs. Jennings might be expected to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57823,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings on her side treated them both with all possible kindness, was solicitous on every occasion for their ease and enjoyment, and only disturbed that she could not make them choose their own dinners at the inn, nor extort a confession of their preferring salmon to cod, or boiled fowls to veal cutlets.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58959,\n            \"for it is a long while since I have been at home, and you know one has always a world of little odd things to do after one has been away for any time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58995,\n            \"and then I have had Cartwright to settle with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59038,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI had the pleasure of hearing it at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s, where I have been dining.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59096,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMrs. Palmer appeared quite well, and I am commissioned to tell you, that you will certainly see her to-morrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59136,\n            \"Well, Colonel, I have brought two young ladies with me, you see \\u2014 that is, you see but one of them now, but there is another somewhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59579,\n            \"\\u201d After an hour or two spent in what her mother called comfortable chat, or in other words, in every variety of inquiry concerning all their acquaintance on Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s side, and in laughter without cause on Mrs. Palmer\\u2019s, it was proposed by the latter that they should all accompany her to some shops where she had business that morning, to which Mrs. Jennings and Elinor readily consented, as having likewise some purchases to make themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60326,\n            \"\\u201cIf this open weather holds much longer,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, when they met at breakfast the following morning, \\u201cSir John will not like leaving Barton next week;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60628,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, my dear, I\\u2019ll warrant you we do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60761,\n            \"The morning was chiefly spent in leaving cards at the houses of Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s acquaintance to inform them of her being in town;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60927,\n            \"The Miss Dashwoods had no greater reason to be dissatisfied with Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s style of living, and set of acquaintance, than with her behaviour to themselves, which was invariably kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60964,\n            \"Every thing in her household arrangements was conducted on the most liberal plan, and excepting a few old city friends, whom, to Lady Middleton\\u2019s regret, she had never dropped, she visited no one to whom an introduction could at all discompose the feelings of her young companions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61697,\n            \"but when the hour of appointment drew near, necessary as it was in common civility to Mrs. Jennings, that they should both attend her on such a visit, Elinor had some difficulty in persuading her sister to go, for still she had seen nothing of Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61972,\n            \"He looked at them slightly, without seeming to know who they were, and merely nodded to Mrs. Jennings from the other side of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62176,\n            \"\\u201cAye, aye,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cwe know the reason of all that very well;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62822,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBy many \\u2014 by some of whom you know nothing, by others with whom you are most intimate, Mrs. Jennings, Mrs. Palmer, and the Middletons.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63389,\n            \"They were engaged about the end of that time to attend Lady Middleton to a party, from which Mrs. Jennings was kept away by the indisposition of her youngest daughter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64745,\n            \"She was soon undressed and in bed, and as she seemed desirous of being alone, her sister then left her, and while she waited the return of Mrs. Jennings, had leisure enough for thinking over the past.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65420,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s attention was then all employed, not in urging her, not in pitying her, nor in appearing to regard her, but in endeavouring to engage Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s notice entirely to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65462,\n            \"As this was a favourite meal with Mrs. Jennings, it lasted a considerable time, and they were just setting themselves, after it, round the common working table, when a letter was delivered to Marianne, which she eagerly caught from the servant, and, turning of a death-like paleness, instantly ran out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65528,\n            \"Elinor, who saw as plainly by this, as if she had seen the direction, that it must come from Willoughby, felt immediately such a sickness at heart as made her hardly able to hold up her head, and sat in such a general tremour as made her fear it impossible to escape Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65592,\n            \"That good lady, however, saw only that Marianne had received a letter from Willoughby, which appeared to her a very good joke, and which she treated accordingly, by hoping, with a laugh, that she would find it to her liking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65667,\n            \"and calmly continuing her talk, as soon as Marianne disappeared, she said, \\u201cUpon my word, I never saw a young woman so desperately in love in my life!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65701,\n            \"_ My _ girls were nothing to her, and yet they used to be foolish enough;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65732,\n            \"I hope, from the bottom of my heart, he won\\u2019t keep her waiting much longer, for it is quite grievous to see her look so ill and forlorn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65775,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, though never less disposed to speak than at that moment, obliged herself to answer such an attack as this, and, therefore, trying to smile, replied, \\u201cAnd have you really, Ma\\u2019am, talked yourself into a persuasion of my sister\\u2019s being engaged to Mr. Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65855,\n            \"and I must beg, therefore, that you will not deceive yourself any longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65871,\n            \"I do assure you that nothing would surprise me more than to hear of their being going to be married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65941,\n            \"Did not I see them together in Devonshire every day, and all day long;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66060,\n            \"Indeed, you are doing a very unkind thing in spreading the report, and you will find that you have though you will not believe me now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66847,\n            \"In her earnest meditations on the contents of the letter, on the depravity of that mind which could dictate it, and probably, on the very different mind of a very different person, who had no other connection whatever with the affair than what her heart gave him with every thing that passed, Elinor forgot the immediate distress of her sister, forgot that she had three letters on her lap yet unread, and so entirely forgot how long she had been in the room, that when on hearing a carriage drive up to the door, she went to the window to see who could be coming so unreasonably early, she was all astonishment to perceive Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s chariot, which she knew had not been ordered till one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66988,\n            \"Determined not to quit Marianne, though hopeless of contributing, at present, to her ease, she hurried away to excuse herself from attending Mrs. Jennings, on account of her sister being indisposed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67026,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, with a thoroughly good-humoured concern for its cause, admitted the excuse most readily, and Elinor, after seeing her safe off, returned to Marianne, whom she found attempting to rise from the bed, and whom she reached just in time to prevent her from falling on the floor, faint and giddy from a long want of proper rest and food;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67897,\n            \"An opportunity of coming hither, though with Mrs. Jennings, was a temptation we could not resist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69530,\n            \"We owe Mrs. Jennings much more than civility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69738,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings came immediately to their room on her return, and without waiting to have her request of admittance answered, opened the door and walked in with a look of real concern.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70160,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, pleased to have her governed for a moment by such a motive, though believing it hardly possible that she could sit out the dinner, said no more;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70251,\n            \"Had she tried to speak, or had she been conscious of half Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s well-meant but ill-judged attentions to her, this calmness could not have been maintained;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70315,\n            \"Elinor, who did justice to Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s kindness, though its effusions were often distressing, and sometimes almost ridiculous, made her those acknowledgments, and returned her those civilities, which her sister could not make or return for herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70362,\n            \"Their good friend saw that Marianne was unhappy, and felt that every thing was due to her which might make her at all less so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70453,\n            \"Had not Elinor, in the sad countenance of her sister, seen a check to all mirth, she could have been entertained by Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s endeavours to cure a disappointment in love, by a variety of sweetmeats and olives, and a good fire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70562,\n            \"\\u201d cried Mrs. Jennings, as soon as she was gone, \\u201chow it grieves me to see her!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70584,\n            \"And I declare if she is not gone away without finishing her wine!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70614,\n            \"I am sure if I knew of any thing she would like, I would send all over the town for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70637,\n            \"Well, it is the oddest thing to me, that a man should use such a pretty girl so ill!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70690,\n            \"\\u2014\\u201d\\u201cThe lady then \\u2014 Miss Grey I think you called her \\u2014 is very rich?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70736,\n            \"I remember her aunt very well, Biddy Henshawe;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72424,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear,\\u201dsaid she, entering, \\u201cI have just recollected that I have some of the finest old Constantia wine in the house that ever was tasted, so I have brought a glass of it for your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72560,\n            \"and as I think nothing will be of so much service to her as rest, if you will give me leave, I will drink the wine myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73471,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, who had watched them with pleasure while they were talking, and who expected to see the effect of Miss Dashwood\\u2019s communication, in such an instantaneous gaiety on Colonel Brandon\\u2019s side, as might have become a man in the bloom of youth, of hope and happiness, saw him, with amazement, remain the whole evening more serious and thoughtful than usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73802,\n            \"All that she wants is gossip, and she only likes me now because I supply it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73944,\n            \"Thus a circumstance occurred, while the sisters were together in their own room after breakfast, which sunk the heart of Mrs. Jennings still lower in her estimation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73975,\n            \"because, through her own weakness, it chanced to prove a source of fresh pain to herself, though Mrs. Jennings was governed in it by an impulse of the utmost goodwill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74182,\n            \"The cruelty of Mrs. Jennings no language, within her reach in her moments of happiest eloquence, could have expressed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74449,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings left them earlier than usual;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74558,\n            \"while Marianne, who came into the drawing-room on Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s going away, remained fixed at the table where Elinor wrote, watching the advancement of her pen, grieving over her for the hardship of such a task, and grieving still more fondly over its effect on her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79963,\n            \"but Mrs. Jennings, who knew nothing of all this, who knew only that the Colonel continued as grave as ever, and that she could neither prevail on him to make the offer himself, nor commission her to make it for him, began, at the end of two days, to think that, instead of Midsummer, they would not be married till Michaelmas, and by the end of a week that it would not be a match at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80576,\n            \"\\u201cWell, my dear,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cand how did you travel?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80595,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNot in the stage, I assure you,\\u201dreplied Miss Steele, with quick exultation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80767,\n            \"here comes your beau, Nancy,\\u2019my cousin said t\\u2019other day, when she saw him crossing the street to the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80799,\n            \"said I \\u2014 I cannot think who you mean.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80851,\n            \"\\u201d replied her cousin, with affected earnestness, \\u201cand I beg you will contradict it, if you ever hear it talked of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80877,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings directly gave her the gratifying assurance that she certainly would _ not _, and Miss Steele was made completely happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81356,\n            \"When they stopped at the door, Mrs. Jennings recollected that there was a lady at the other end of the street on whom she ought to call;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82067,\n            \"I understand she is a woman of very good fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82285,\n            \"and was not sorry to be spared the necessity of answering him, by the arrival of Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s servant, who came to tell her that his mistress waited for them at the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82324,\n            \"Mr. Dashwood attended them down stairs, was introduced to Mrs. Jennings at the door of her carriage, and repeating his hope of being able to call on them the next day, took leave.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82412,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings, however, assured him directly, that she should not stand upon ceremony, for they were all cousins, or something like it, and she should certainly wait on Mrs. John Dashwood very soon, and bring her sisters to see her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83940,\n            \"Having now said enough to make his poverty clear, and to do away the necessity of buying a pair of ear-rings for each of his sisters, in his next visit at Gray\\u2019s, his thoughts took a cheerfuller turn, and he began to congratulate Elinor on having such a friend as Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84677,\n            \"and an offer from Colonel Brandon, or a legacy from Mrs. Jennings, was the easiest means of atoning for his own neglect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84863,\n            \"Your sister need not have any scruple even of visiting _ her _, which, to say the truth, has been a little the case, and very naturally;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84895,\n            \"for we only knew that Mrs. Jennings was the widow of a man who had got all his money in a low way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84920,\n            \"and Fanny and Mrs. Ferrars were both strongly prepossessed, that neither she nor her daughters were such kind of women as Fanny would like to associate with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84967,\n            \"Mrs. John Dashwood had so much confidence in her husband\\u2019s judgment, that she waited the very next day both on Mrs. Jennings and her daughter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84998,\n            \"and her confidence was rewarded by finding even the former, even the woman with whom her sisters were staying, by no means unworthy her notice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85092,\n            \"The same manners, however, which recommended Mrs. John Dashwood to the good opinion of Lady Middleton did not suit the fancy of Mrs. Jennings, and to _ her _ she appeared nothing more than a little proud-looking woman of uncordial address, who met her husband\\u2019s sisters without any affection, and almost without having anything to say to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91657,\n            \"All these jealousies and discontents, however, were so totally unsuspected by Mrs. Jennings, that she thought it a delightful thing for the girls to be together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91710,\n            \"She joined them sometimes at Sir John\\u2019s, sometimes at her own house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91726,\n            \"but wherever it was, she always came in excellent spirits, full of delight and importance, attributing Charlotte\\u2019s well doing to her own care, and ready to give so exact, so minute a detail of her situation, as only Miss Steele had curiosity enough to desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91914,\n            \"It so happened that while her two sisters with Mrs. Jennings were first calling on her in Harley Street, another of her acquaintance had dropt in \\u2014 a circumstance in itself not apparently likely to produce evil to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93814,\n            \"The consideration of Mrs. Dennison\\u2019s mistake, in supposing his sisters their guests, had suggested the propriety of their being really invited to become such, while Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s engagements kept her from home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96201,\n            \"that Mrs. Jennings (as she had of late often hoped might be the case) had ceased to imagine her at all attached to Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98166,\n            \"\\u2014 She attended to all that Mrs. Jennings had to say upon the subject, with an unchanging complexion, dissented from her in nothing, and was heard three times to say, \\u201cYes, ma\\u2019am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 She listened to her praise of Lucy with only moving from one chair to another, and when Mrs. Jennings talked of Edward\\u2019s affection, it cost her only a spasm in her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings with blunt sincerity, no longer able to be silent, \\u201che has acted like an honest man!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99253,\n            \"He therefore replied, without any resentment, \\u201cI would by no means speak disrespectfully of any relation of yours, madam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99489,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry to say, ma\\u2019am, in a most unhappy rupture: \\u2014 Edward is dismissed for ever from his mother\\u2019s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99920,\n            \"\\u201d said Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cthat is _ her _ revenge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99942,\n            \"But I don\\u2019t think mine would be, to make one son independent, because another had plagued me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100124,\n            \"and as her vehemence made reserve impossible in Elinor, and unnecessary in Mrs. Jennings, they all joined in a very spirited critique upon the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100476,\n            \"But though so much of the matter was known to them already, that Mrs. Jennings might have had enough to do in spreading that knowledge farther, without seeking after more, she had resolved from the first to pay a visit of comfort and inquiry to her cousins as soon as she could;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100533,\n            \"and nothing but the hindrance of more visitors than usual, had prevented her going to them within that time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100637,\n            \"An intimate acquaintance of Mrs. Jennings joined them soon after they entered the Gardens, and Elinor was not sorry that by her continuing with them, and engaging all Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s conversation, she was herself left to quiet reflection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100716,\n            \"But at last she found herself with some surprise, accosted by Miss Steele, who, though looking rather shy, expressed great satisfaction in meeting them, and on receiving encouragement from the particular kindness of Mrs. Jennings, left her own party for a short time, to join their\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100773,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings immediately whispered to Elinor, \\u201cGet it all out of her, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100802,\n            \"You see I cannot leave Mrs. Clarke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100886,\n            \"\\u201d And then lowering her voice, \\u201cI suppose Mrs. Jennings has heard all about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102763,\n            \"I have not time to speak to Mrs. Jennings about it myself, but pray tell her I am quite happy to hear she is not in anger against us, and Lady Middleton the same;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102801,\n            \"and if anything should happen to take you and your sister away, and Mrs. Jennings should want company, I am sure we should be very glad to come and stay with her for as long a time as she likes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102909,\n            \"for after this, she had time only to pay her farewell compliments to Mrs. Jennings, before her company was claimed by Mrs. Richardson;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103036,\n            \"As soon as they returned to the carriage, Mrs. Jennings was eager for information;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103474,\n            \"I am sure you will be glad to hear, as likewise dear Mrs. Jennings, I spent two happy hours with him yesterday afternoon, he would not hear of our parting, though earnestly did I, as I thought my duty required, urge him to it for prudence sake, and would have parted for ever on the spot, would he consent to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103598,\n            \"and should it ever be in your power to recommend him to any body that has a living to bestow, am very sure you will not forget us, and dear Mrs. Jennings too, trust she will speak a good word for us to Sir John, or Mr. Palmer, or any friend that may be able to assist us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103689,\n            \"hope Mrs. Jennings won\\u2019t think it too much trouble to give us a call, should she come this way any morning,\\u2019twould be a great kindness, and my cousins would be proud to know her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103786,\n            \"\\u201d As soon as Elinor had finished it, she performed what she concluded to be its writer\\u2019s real design, by placing it in the hands of Mrs. Jennings, who read it aloud with many comments of satisfaction and praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103884,\n            \"She calls me dear Mrs. Jennings, you see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104171,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings, with both her friends, received a very warm invitation from Charlotte to go with them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104387,\n            \"\\u2014 represented it, therefore, as a measure which would fix the time of her returning to that dear mother, whom she so much wished to see, in a more eligible, more comfortable manner, than any other plan could do, and perhaps without any greater delay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104542,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings was so far from being weary of her guests, that she pressed them very earnestly to return with her again from Cleveland.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105016,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings commended her in her heart for being so honest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105211,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings was delighted with her gratitude, and only wondered that after hearing such a sentence, the Colonel should be able to take leave of them, as he immediately did, with the utmost _ sang-froid _, and go away without making her any reply!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105722,\n            \"Her emotion was such as Mrs. Jennings had attributed to a very different cause;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106018,\n            \"an evil which Elinor, as Mrs. Jennings had supposed her to do, made very light of, at least as far as regarded its size.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106378,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, sagaciously smiling, as soon as the gentleman had withdrawn, \\u201cI do not ask you what the Colonel has been saying to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106444,\n            \"And I assure you I never was better pleased in my life, and I wish you joy of it with all my heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou judged from your knowledge of the Colonel\\u2019s general benevolence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107567,\n            \"and she, after apologising for not returning herself, had obliged him to enter, by saying that Miss Dashwood was above, and wanted to speak with him on very particular business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107796,\n            \"\\u201cMrs. Jennings told me,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cthat you wished to speak with me, at least I understood her so \\u2014 or I certainly should not have intruded on you in such a manner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109024,\n            \"\\u201cWell, my dear,\\u201dshe cried, \\u201cI sent you up the young man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109049,\n            \"\\u2014 And I suppose you had no great difficulty \\u2014 You did not find him very unwilling to accept your proposal?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109211,\n            \"\\u2014 And though one would be very glad to do a kindness by poor Mr. Ferrars, I do think it is not worth while to wait two or three months for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109312,\n            \"Sure you do not mean to persuade me that the Colonel only marries you for the sake of giving ten guineas to Mr. Ferrars!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109347,\n            \"and an explanation immediately took place, by which both gained considerable amusement for the moment, without any material loss of happiness to either, for Mrs. Jennings only exchanged one form of delight for another, and still without forfeiting her expectation of the first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109436,\n            \"but to hear a man apologising, as I thought, for a house that to my knowledge has five sitting rooms on the ground-floor, and I think the housekeeper told me could make up fifteen beds!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109735,\n            \"and she joined Mrs. Jennings most heartily in her expectation of their being all comfortably together in Delaford Parsonage before Michaelmas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110033,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings, though her carriage was always at Elinor\\u2019s service, so very much disliked Mrs. John Dashwood, that not even her curiosity to see how she looked after the late discovery, nor her strong desire to affront her by taking Edward\\u2019s part, could overcome her unwillingness to be in her company again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114029,\n            \"Mrs. Palmer had her child, and Mrs. Jennings her carpet-work;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114335,\n            \"she found him very capable of being a pleasant companion, and only prevented from being so always, by too great an aptitude to fancy himself as much superior to people in general, as he must feel himself to be to Mrs. Jennings and Charlotte.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114610,\n            \"\\u2014 His behaviour to her in this, as well as in every other particular, his open pleasure in meeting her after an absence of only ten days, his readiness to converse with her, and his deference for her opinion, might very well justify Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s persuasion of his attachment, and would have been enough, perhaps, had not Elinor still, as from the first, believed Marianne his real favourite, to make her suspect it herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114699,\n            \"But as it was, such a notion had scarcely ever entered her head, except by Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s suggestion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114737,\n            \"\\u2014 she watched his eyes, while Mrs. Jennings thought only of his behaviour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114753,\n            \"\\u2014 and while his looks of anxious solicitude on Marianne\\u2019s feeling, in her head and throat, the beginning of a heavy cold, because unexpressed by words, entirely escaped the latter lady\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115186,\n            \"and when Marianne, after persisting in rising, confessed herself unable to sit up, and returned voluntarily to her bed, Elinor was very ready to adopt Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s advice, of sending for the Palmers\\u2019 apothecary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115295,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, who had been inclined from the first to think Marianne\\u2019s complaint more serious than Elinor, now looked very grave on Mr. Harris\\u2019 s report, and confirming Charlotte\\u2019s fears and caution, urged the necessity of her immediate removal with her infant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115349,\n            \"and Mr. Palmer, though treating their apprehensions as idle, found the anxiety and importunity of his wife too great to be withstood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115453,\n            \"and whither she was almost equally urgent with her mother to accompany her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115467,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, however, with a kindness of heart which made Elinor really love her, declared her resolution of not stirring from Cleveland as long as Marianne remained ill, and of endeavouring, by her own attentive care, to supply to her the place of the mother she had taken her from;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115525,\n            \"and Elinor found her on every occasion a most willing and active helpmate, desirous to share in all her fatigues, and often by her better experience in nursing, of material use.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115737,\n            \"for Mr. Palmer, though very unwilling to go as well from real humanity and good-nature, as from a dislike of appearing to be frightened away by his wife, was persuaded at last by Colonel Brandon to perform his promise of following her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115826,\n            \"for to send the Colonel away while his love was in so much uneasiness on her sister\\u2019s account, would be to deprive them both, she thought, of every comfort;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115861,\n            \"and therefore telling him at once that his stay at Cleveland was necessary to herself, that she should want him to play at piquet of an evening, while Miss Dashwood was above with her sister, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115902,\n            \"she urged him so strongly to remain, that he, who was gratifying the first wish of his own heart by a compliance, could not long even affect to demur;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116115,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings had determined very early in the seizure that Marianne would never get over it, and Colonel Brandon, who was chiefly of use in listening to Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s forebodings, was not in a state of mind to resist their influence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116472,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, knowing nothing of any change in the patient, went unusually early to bed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116491,\n            \"her maid, who was one of the principal nurses, was recreating herself in the housekeeper\\u2019s room, and Elinor remained alone with Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117240,\n            \"and the servant who sat up with her, for she would not allow Mrs. Jennings to be called, only tortured her more, by hints of what her mistress had always thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117510,\n            \"With strong concern, and with many reproaches for not being called to their aid, did Mrs. Jennings hear in the morning of what had passed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117557,\n            \"and though trying to speak comfort to Elinor, her conviction of her sister\\u2019s danger would not allow her to offer the comfort of hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117660,\n            \"The distress of her sister too, particularly a favourite, was before her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117675,\n            \"\\u2014 and as for their mother, when Mrs. Jennings considered that Marianne might probably be to _ her _ what Charlotte was to herself, her sympathy in _ her _ sufferings was very sincere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117860,\n            \"and in this state she continued till noon, scarcely stirring from her sister\\u2019s bed, her thoughts wandering from one image of grief, one suffering friend to another, and her spirits oppressed to the utmost by the conversation of Mrs. Jennings, who scrupled not to attribute the severity and danger of this attack to the many weeks of previous indisposition which Marianne\\u2019s disappointment had brought on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118043,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, though forced, on examination, to acknowledge a temporary revival, tried to keep her young friend from indulging a thought of its continuance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118253,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, perhaps satisfied with the partial justification of her forebodings which had been found in their late alarm, allowed herself to trust in his judgment, and admitted, with unfeigned joy, and soon with unequivocal cheerfulness, the probability of an entire recovery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118583,\n            \"At seven o\\u2019clock, leaving Marianne still sweetly asleep, she joined Mrs. Jennings in the drawing-room to tea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118653,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings would have persuaded her, at its conclusion, to take some rest before her mother\\u2019s arrival, and allow _ her _ to take her place by Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118721,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings therefore attending her up stairs into the sick chamber, to satisfy herself that all continued right, left her there again to her charge and her thoughts, and retired to her own room to write letters and sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127702,\n            \"To Mrs. Jennings, to the Middletons, he has been long and intimately known;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128548,\n            \"and with youth, natural strength, and her mother\\u2019s presence in aid, it proceeded so smoothly as to enable her to remove, within four days after the arrival of the latter, into Mrs. Palmer\\u2019s dressing-room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128881,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings could not quit Cleveland during the Dashwoods\\u2019 stay;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128921,\n            \"At his and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s united request in return, Mrs. Dashwood was prevailed on to accept the use of his carriage on her journey back, for the better accommodation of her sick child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128961,\n            \"and the Colonel, at the joint invitation of Mrs. Dashwood and Mrs. Jennings, whose active good-nature made her friendly and hospitable for other people as well as herself, engaged with pleasure to redeem it by a visit at the cottage, in the course of a few weeks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129025,\n            \"and Marianne, after taking so particular and lengthened a leave of Mrs. Jennings, one so earnestly grateful, so full of respect and kind wishes as seemed due to her own heart from a secret acknowledgment of past inattention, and bidding Colonel Brandon farewell with a cordiality of a friend, was carefully assisted by him into the carriage, of which he seemed anxious that she should engross at least half.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129102,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and Elinor then followed, and the others were left by themselves, to talk of the travellers, and feel their own dullness, till Mrs. Jennings was summoned to her chaise to take comfort in the gossip of her maid for the loss of her two young companions;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 14]\": [\n        [\n            38584,\n            \"He entered the room with a look of self-consequence, slightly bowed to the ladies, without speaking a word, and, after briefly surveying them and their apartments, took up a newspaper from the table, and continued to read it as long as he staid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38786,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Palmer does not hear me,\\u201dsaid she, laughing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38891,\n            \"Mrs. Palmer laughed heartily at the recollection of their astonishment, and every body agreed, two or three times over, that it had been quite an agreeable surprise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39148,\n            \"\\u201cNow, Palmer, you shall see a monstrous pretty girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39327,\n            \"When Lady Middleton rose to go away, Mr. Palmer rose also, laid down the newspaper, stretched himself and looked at them all around.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39466,\n            \"But they had no curiosity to see how Mr. and Mrs. Palmer ate their dinner, and no expectation of pleasure from them in any other way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39554,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings and Mrs. Palmer joined their entreaties, all seemed equally anxious to avoid a family party;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39710,\n            \"As the Miss Dashwoods entered the drawing-room of the park the next day, at one door, Mrs. Palmer came running in at the other, looking as good humoured and merry as before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39749,\n            \"She took them all most affectionately by the hand, and expressed great delight in seeing them again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39768,\n            \"\\u201cI am so glad to see you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39777,\n            \"\\u201d said she, seating herself between Elinor and Marianne, \\u201cfor it is so bad a day I was afraid you might not come, which would be a shocking thing, as we go away again tomorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39833,\n            \"It was quite a sudden thing our coming at all, and I knew nothing of it till the carriage was coming to the door, and then Mr. Palmer asked me if I would go with him to Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39887,\n            \"I am so sorry we cannot stay longer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39896,\n            \"however we shall meet again in town very soon, I hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39928,\n            \"\\u201d cried Mrs. Palmer, with a laugh, \\u201cI shall be quite disappointed if you do not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39949,\n            \"I could get the nicest house in the world for you, next door to ours, in Hanover-square.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39977,\n            \"I am sure I shall be very happy to chaperon you at any time till I am confined, if Mrs. Dashwood should not like to go into public.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40008,\n            \"\\u201d They thanked her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40022,\n            \"\\u201cOh, my love,\\u201dcried Mrs. Palmer to her husband, who just then entered the room \\u2014 \\u201cyou must help me to persuade the Miss Dashwoods to go to town this winter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40208,\n            \"\\u201cOh, don\\u2019t be so sly before us,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Palmer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40226,\n            \"\\u201cfor we know all about it, I assure you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40404,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear,\\u201dsaid he to his lady, \\u201cit is very provoking that we should be so few.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40427,\n            \"Why did not you ask the Gilberts to come to us today?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40757,\n            \"His temper might perhaps be a little soured by finding, like many others of his sex, that through some unaccountable bias in favour of beauty, he was the husband of a very silly woman \\u2014 but she knew that this kind of blunder was too common for any sensible man to be lastingly hurt by it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41018,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere now,\\u201d\\u2014 said his lady, \\u201cyou see Mr. Palmer expects you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41099,\n            \"and we are so gay now, for Mr. Palmer is always going about the country canvassing against the election;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41182,\n            \"\\u201cHow charming it will be,\\u201dsaid Charlotte, \\u201cwhen he is in Parliament!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41230,\n            \"\\u2014 But do you know, he says, he will never frank for me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41262,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Palmer took no notice of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41272,\n            \"\\u201cHe cannot bear writing, you know,\\u201dshe continued \\u2014 \\u201che says it is quite shocking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41342,\n            \"Sometimes he won\\u2019t speak to me for half a day together, and then he comes out with something so droll \\u2014 all about any thing in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41374,\n            \"\\u201d She surprised Elinor very much as they returned into the drawing-room, by asking her whether she did not like Mr. Palmer excessively.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41426,\n            \"I thought you would, he is so pleasant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41436,\n            \"and Mr. Palmer is excessively pleased with you and your sisters I can tell you, and you can\\u2019t think how disappointed he will be if you don\\u2019t come to Cleveland.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41723,\n            \"but if he were ever so much there, I do not think Mr. Palmer would visit him, for he is in the opposition, you know, and besides it is such a way off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42413,\n            \"for I think you both excessively pretty, and so does Mr. Palmer too I am sure, though we could not get him to own it last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94742,\n            \"About the third or fourth morning after their being thus resettled in Berkeley Street, Mrs. Jennings, on returning from her ordinary visit to Mrs. Palmer, entered the drawing-room, where Elinor was sitting by herself, with an air of such hurrying importance as prepared her to hear something wonderful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115786,\n            \"and while he was preparing to go, Colonel Brandon himself, with a much greater exertion, began to talk of going likewise.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 15]\": [\n        [\n            15426,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou know him then,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15573,\n            \"But he is a pleasant, good humoured fellow, and has got the nicest little black bitch of a pointer I ever saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15673,\n            \"and he told them that Mr. Willoughby had no property of his own in the country;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15721,\n            \"adding, \\u201cYes, yes, he is very well worth catching I can tell you, Miss Dashwood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15755,\n            \"and if I were you, I would not give him up to my younger sister, in spite of all this tumbling down hills.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15806,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not believe,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, with a good humoured smile, \\u201cthat Mr. Willoughby will be incommoded by the attempts of either of _ my _ daughters towards what you call _ catching him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15879,\n            \"I am glad to find, however, from what you say, that he is a respectable young man, and one whose acquaintance will not be ineligible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16281,\n            \"He was received by Mrs. Dashwood with more than politeness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16293,\n            \"with a kindness which Sir John\\u2019s account of him and her own gratitude prompted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16345,\n            \"Of their personal charms he had not required a second interview to be convinced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16791,\n            \"and long before his visit concluded, they conversed with the familiarity of a long-established acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16858,\n            \"You know what he thinks of Cowper and Scott;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16868,\n            \"you are certain of his estimating their beauties as he ought, and you have received every assurance of his admiring Pope no more than is proper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17082,\n            \"I should scold her myself, if she were capable of wishing to check the delight of your conversation with our new friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17114,\n            \"Willoughby, on his side, gave every proof of his pleasure in their acquaintance, which an evident wish of improving it could offer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17140,\n            \"He came to them every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17232,\n            \"He was exactly formed to engage Marianne\\u2019s heart, for with all this, he joined not only a captivating person, but a natural ardour of mind which was now roused and increased by the example of her own, and which recommended him to her affection beyond every thing else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17327,\n            \"In Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s estimation he was as faultless as in Marianne\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17344,\n            \"and Elinor saw nothing to censure in him but a propensity, in which he strongly resembled and peculiarly delighted her sister, of saying too much what he thought on every occasion, without attention to persons or circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17385,\n            \"In hastily forming and giving his opinion of other people, in sacrificing general politeness to the enjoyment of undivided attention where his heart was engaged, and in slighting too easily the forms of worldly propriety, he displayed a want of caution which Elinor could not approve, in spite of all that he and Marianne could say in its support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17530,\n            \"Her mother too, in whose mind not one speculative thought of their marriage had been raised, by his prospect of riches, was led before the end of a week to hope and expect it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17568,\n            \"and secretly to congratulate herself on having gained two such sons-in-law as Edward and Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17622,\n            \"Their attention and wit were drawn off to his more fortunate rival;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17666,\n            \"Elinor was obliged, though unwillingly, to believe that the sentiments which Mrs. Jennings had assigned him for her own satisfaction, were now actually excited by her sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17830,\n            \"Sir John had dropped hints of past injuries and disappointments, which justified her belief of his being an unfortunate man, and she regarded him with respect and compassion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17897,\n            \"\\u201cBrandon is just the kind of man,\\u201dsaid Willoughby one day, when they were talking of him together, \\u201cwhom every body speaks well of, and nobody cares about;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17985,\n            \"He is highly esteemed by all the family at the park, and I never see him myself without taking pains to converse with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18080,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut perhaps the abuse of such people as yourself and Marianne will make amends for the regard of Lady Middleton and her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18147,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy _ prot\\u00e9g\\u00e9 _, as you call him, is a sensible man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18373,\n            \"I consider him, on the contrary, as a very respectable man, who has every body\\u2019s good word, and nobody\\u2019s notice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18514,\n            \"I can only pronounce him to be a sensible man, well-bred, well-informed, of gentle address, and, I believe, possessing an amiable heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18833,\n            \"and the ease and familiarity which naturally attended these parties were exactly calculated to give increasing intimacy to his acquaintance with the Dashwoods, to afford him opportunity of witnessing the excellencies of Marianne, of marking his animated admiration of her, and of receiving, in her behaviour to himself, the most pointed assurance of her affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19001,\n            \"When he was present she had no eyes for any one else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19030,\n            \"If their evenings at the park were concluded with cards, he cheated himself and all the rest of the party to get her a good hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19617,\n            \"Her admiration and regard, even her sisterly regard, was all his own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19632,\n            \"but he was a lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19638,\n            \"his attentions were wholly Marianne\\u2019s, and a far less agreeable man might have been more generally pleasing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20413,\n            \"Marianne told her, with the greatest delight, that Willoughby had given her a horse, one that he had bred himself on his estate in Somersetshire, and which was exactly calculated to carry a woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20527,\n            \"\\u201cHe intends to send his groom into Somersetshire immediately for it,\\u201dshe added, \\u201cand when it arrives we will ride every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20726,\n            \"I have not known him long indeed, but I am much better acquainted with him, than I am with any other creature in the world, except yourself and mama.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20929,\n            \"and she promised not to tempt her mother to such imprudent kindness by mentioning the offer, and to tell Willoughby when she saw him next, that it must be declined.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21114,\n            \"and in the whole of the sentence, in his manner of pronouncing it, and in his addressing her sister by her Christian name alone, she instantly saw an intimacy so decided, a meaning so direct, as marked a perfect agreement between them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21342,\n            \"and they had not known each other a week, I believe, before you were certain that Marianne wore his picture round her neck;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21392,\n            \"I am sure they will be married very soon, for he has got a lock of her hair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21448,\n            \"I am almost sure it is, for I saw him cut it off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21463,\n            \"Last night after tea, when you and mama went out of the room, they were whispering and talking together as fast as could be, and he seemed to be begging something of her, and presently he took up her scissors and cut off a long lock of her hair, for it was all tumbled down her back;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23066,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou would not be six hours later,\\u201dsaid Willoughby, \\u201cif you were to defer your journey till our return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23104,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor then heard Willoughby say, in a low voice to Marianne, \\u201cThere are some people who cannot bear a party of pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23228,\n            \"Consider, here are the two Miss Careys come over from Newton, the three Miss Dashwoods walked up from the cottage, and Mr. Willoughby got up two hours before his usual time, on purpose to go to Whitwell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23959,\n            \"He drove through the park very fast, and they were soon out of sight;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24171,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not you know,\\u201dsaid Willoughby, \\u201cthat we had been out in my curricle?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24192,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, yes, Mr. Impudence, I know that very well, and I was determined to find out _ where _ you had been to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25504,\n            \"It was engrossed by the extraordinary silence of her sister and Willoughby on the subject, which they must know to be peculiarly interesting to them all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25801,\n            \"and if no general engagement collected them at the park, the exercise which called him out in the morning was almost certain of ending there, where the rest of the day was spent by himself at the side of Marianne, and by his favourite pointer at her feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26408,\n            \"I never passed within view of it without admiring its situation, and grieving that no one should live in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26639,\n            \"\\u201cYou are a good woman,\\u201dhe warmly replied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26698,\n            \"and that you will always consider me with the kindness which has made everything belonging to you so dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26746,\n            \"\\u201cShall we see you tomorrow to dinner?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26755,\n            \"\\u201d said Mrs. Dashwood, when he was leaving them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26767,\n            \"\\u201cI do not ask you to come in the morning, for we must walk to the park, to call on Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26793,\n            \"\\u201d He engaged to be with them by four o\\u2019clock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26850,\n            \"and her mother, who concluded that a promise had been made by Willoughby the night before of calling on her while they were absent, was perfectly satisfied with her remaining at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26885,\n            \"On their return from the park they found Willoughby\\u2019s curricle and servant in waiting at the cottage, and Mrs. Dashwood was convinced that her conjecture had been just.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26979,\n            \"Surprised and alarmed they proceeded directly into the room she had just quitted, where they found only Willoughby, who was leaning against the mantel-piece with his back towards them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27013,\n            \"He turned round on their coming in, and his countenance showed that he strongly partook of the emotion which over-powered Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27110,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, for I am unable to keep my engagement with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27125,\n            \"Mrs. Smith has this morning exercised the privilege of riches upon a poor dependent cousin, by sending me on business to London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27164,\n            \"and by way of exhilaration I am now come to take my farewell of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27214,\n            \"\\u2014 and her business will not detain you from us long I hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27519,\n            \"\\u201d He then hastily took leave of them all and left the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27533,\n            \"They saw him step into his carriage, and in a minute it was out of sight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27607,\n            \"Willoughby\\u2019s behaviour in taking leave of them, his embarrassment, and affectation of cheerfulness, and, above all, his unwillingness to accept her mother\\u2019s invitation, a backwardness so unlike a lover, so unlike himself, greatly disturbed her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27671,\n            \"and the next that some unfortunate quarrel had taken place between him and her sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27802,\n            \"\\u201cOur dear Willoughby is now some miles from Barton, Elinor,\\u201dsaid she, as she sat down to work, \\u201cand with how heavy a heart does he travel?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27860,\n            \"And last night he was with us so happy, so cheerful, so affectionate?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27892,\n            \"\\u2014 Something more than what he owned to us must have happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27940,\n            \"Why else should he have shown such unwillingness to accept your invitation here?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28328,\n            \"You are resolved to think him blameable, because he took leave of us with less affection than his usual behaviour has shown.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28447,\n            \"But suspicion of something unpleasant is the inevitable consequence of such an alteration as we just witnessed in him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28467,\n            \"There is great truth, however, in what you have now urged of the allowances which ought to be made for him, and it is my wish to be candid in my judgment of every body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28506,\n            \"Willoughby may undoubtedly have very sufficient reasons for his conduct, and I will hope that he has.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28544,\n            \"but still I cannot help wondering at its being practiced by him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28578,\n            \"But you really do admit the justice of what I have said in his defence?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28609,\n            \"It may be proper to conceal their engagement (if they _ are _ engaged) from Mrs. Smith \\u2014 and if that is the case, it must be highly expedient for Willoughby to be but little in Devonshire at present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28672,\n            \"my dear child, do you accuse Willoughby and Marianne of concealment?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28767,\n            \"Has not his behaviour to Marianne and to all of us, for at least the last fortnight, declared that he loved and considered her as his future wife, and that he felt for us the attachment of the nearest relation?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28819,\n            \"Has not my consent been daily asked by his looks, his manner, his attentive and affectionate respect?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28859,\n            \"How is it to be supposed that Willoughby, persuaded as he must be of your sister\\u2019s love, should leave her, and leave her perhaps for months, without telling her of his affection;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28965,\n            \"You must think wretchedly indeed of Willoughby, if, after all that has openly passed between them, you can doubt the nature of the terms on which they are together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28998,\n            \"Has he been acting a part in his behaviour to your sister all this time?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29014,\n            \"Do you suppose him really indifferent to her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29042,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut with a strange kind of tenderness, if he can leave her with such indifference, such carelessness of the future, as you attribute to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29259,\n            \"\\u201cI love Willoughby, sincerely love him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29268,\n            \"and suspicion of his integrity cannot be more painful to yourself than to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29295,\n            \"I was startled, I confess, by the alteration in his manners this morning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29311,\n            \"\\u2014 he did not speak like himself, and did not return your kindness with any cordiality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29329,\n            \"But all this may be explained by such a situation of his affairs as you have supposed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29347,\n            \"He had just parted from my sister, had seen her leave him in the greatest affliction;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29365,\n            \"and if he felt obliged, from a fear of offending Mrs. Smith, to resist the temptation of returning here soon, and yet aware that by declining your invitation, by saying that he was going away for some time, he should seem to act an ungenerous, a suspicious part by our family, he might well be embarrassed and disturbed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29432,\n            \"In such a case, a plain and open avowal of his difficulties would have been more to his honour I think, as well as more consistent with his general character;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29520,\n            \"Though _ we _ have not known him long, he is no stranger in this part of the world;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29550,\n            \"Had he been in a situation to act independently and marry immediately, it might have been odd that he should leave us without acknowledging everything to me at once: but this is not the case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29806,\n            \"and though her family were most anxiously attentive to her comfort, it was impossible for them, if they spoke at all, to keep clear of every subject which her feelings connected with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30032,\n            \"She played over every favourite song that she had been used to play to Willoughby, every air in which their voices had been oftenest joined, and sat at the instrument gazing on every line of music that he had written out for her, till her heart was so heavy that no farther sadness could be gained;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30386,\n            \"\\u201cWhy do you not ask Marianne at once,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwhether she is or she is not engaged to Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30644,\n            \"It was several days before Willoughby\\u2019s name was mentioned before Marianne by any of her family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30715,\n            \"our dear Willoughby went away before we could get through it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30727,\n            \"We will put it by, that when he comes again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30811,\n            \"One morning, about a week after his leaving the country, Marianne was prevailed on to join her sisters in their usual walk, instead of wandering away by herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31132,\n            \"It is not Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31197,\n            \"and Elinor, to screen Marianne from particularity, as she felt almost certain of its not being Willoughby, quickened her pace and kept up with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35886,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI wish with all my soul,\\u201dcried Sir John, \\u201cthat Willoughby were among us again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41509,\n            \"She thought it probable that as they lived in the same county, Mrs. Palmer might be able to give some more particular account of Willoughby\\u2019s general character, than could be gathered from the Middletons\\u2019 partial acquaintance with him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41554,\n            \"and she was eager to gain from any one, such a confirmation of his merits as might remove the possibility of fear from Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41580,\n            \"She began by inquiring if they saw much of Mr. Willoughby at Cleveland, and whether they were intimately acquainted with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41610,\n            \"I know him extremely well,\\u201dreplied Mrs. Palmer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41622,\n            \"\\u2014 \\u201cNot that I ever spoke to him, indeed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41634,\n            \"but I have seen him for ever in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41644,\n            \"Somehow or other I never happened to be staying at Barton while he was at Allenham.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41661,\n            \"Mama saw him here once before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41678,\n            \"However, I dare say we should have seen a great deal of him in Somersetshire, if it had not happened very unluckily that we should never have been in the country together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41713,\n            \"He is very little at Combe, I believe;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41723,\n            \"but if he were ever so much there, I do not think Mr. Palmer would visit him, for he is in the opposition, you know, and besides it is such a way off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41762,\n            \"I know why you inquire about him, very well;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42213,\n            \"He is such a charming man, that it is quite a pity he should be so grave and so dull.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42235,\n            \"Mama says _ he _ was in love with your sister too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42248,\n            \"I assure you it was a great compliment if he was, for he hardly ever falls in love with any body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42297,\n            \"that is, I do not believe many people are acquainted with him, because Combe Magna is so far off;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42319,\n            \"but they all think him extremely agreeable I assure you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42330,\n            \"Nobody is more liked than Mr. Willoughby wherever he goes, and so you may tell your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42444,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Palmer\\u2019s information respecting Willoughby was not very material;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42458,\n            \"but any testimony in his favour, however small, was pleasing to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45820,\n            \"and since Edward\\u2019s visit, they had never dined together without his drinking to her best affections with so much significancy and so many nods and winks, as to excite general attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45892,\n            \"The Miss Steeles, as she expected, had now all the benefit of these jokes, and in the eldest of them they raised a curiosity to know the name of the gentleman alluded to, which, though often impertinently expressed, was perfectly of a piece with her general inquisitiveness into the concerns of their family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46030,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Ferrars is the happy man, is he?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46066,\n            \"I know him very well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46099,\n            \"\\u201cThough we have seen him once or twice at my uncle\\u2019s, it is rather too much to pretend to know him very well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46214,\n            \"The manner in which Miss Steele had spoken of Edward, increased her curiosity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46229,\n            \"for it struck her as being rather ill-natured, and suggested the suspicion of that lady\\u2019s knowing, or fancying herself to know something to his disadvantage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46261,\n            \"\\u2014 But her curiosity was unavailing, for no farther notice was taken of Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s name by Miss Steele when alluded to, or even openly mentioned by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61170,\n            \"About a week after their arrival, it became certain that Willoughby was also arrived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61186,\n            \"His card was on the table when they came in from the morning\\u2019s drive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61207,\n            \"\\u201d cried Marianne, \\u201che has been here while we were out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61364,\n            \"but a moment\\u2019s glance at her sister when they returned was enough to inform her, that Willoughby had paid no second visit there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61697,\n            \"but when the hour of appointment drew near, necessary as it was in common civility to Mrs. Jennings, that they should both attend her on such a visit, Elinor had some difficulty in persuading her sister to go, for still she had seen nothing of Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62251,\n            \"\\u201cSo my daughter Middleton told me, for it seems Sir John met him somewhere in the street this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62336,\n            \"and she was still more eagerly bent on this measure by perceiving after breakfast on the morrow, that Marianne was again writing to Willoughby, for she could not suppose it to be to any other person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62430,\n            \"Elinor was very earnest in her application to her mother, relating all that had passed, her suspicions of Willoughby\\u2019s inconstancy, urging her by every plea of duty and affection to demand from Marianne an account of her real situation with respect to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62717,\n            \"He tried to smile as he replied, \\u201cyour sister\\u2019s engagement to Mr. Willoughby is very generally known.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62856,\n            \"But still I might not have believed it, for where the mind is perhaps rather unwilling to be convinced, it will always find something to support its doubts, if I had not, when the servant let me in today, accidentally seen a letter in his hand, directed to Mr. Willoughby in your sister\\u2019s writing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63027,\n            \"\\u201d These words, which conveyed to Elinor a direct avowal of his love for her sister, affected her very much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63085,\n            \"The real state of things between Willoughby and her sister was so little known to herself, that in endeavouring to explain it, she might be as liable to say too much as too little.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63122,\n            \"Yet as she was convinced that Marianne\\u2019s affection for Willoughby, could leave no hope of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s success, whatever the event of that affection might be, and at the same time wished to shield her conduct from censure, she thought it most prudent and kind, after some consideration, to say more than she really knew or believed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63692,\n            \"They had not remained in this manner long, before Elinor perceived Willoughby, standing within a few yards of them, in earnest conversation with a very fashionable looking young woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63725,\n            \"She soon caught his eye, and he immediately bowed, but without attempting to speak to her, or to approach Marianne, though he could not but see her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63757,\n            \"and then continued his discourse with the same lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63783,\n            \"At that moment she first perceived him, and her whole countenance glowing with sudden delight, she would have moved towards him instantly, had not her sister caught hold of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63930,\n            \"At last he turned round again, and regarded them both;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64265,\n            \"but as if, on catching the eye of the young lady with whom he had been previously talking, he felt the necessity of instant exertion, he recovered himself again, and after saying, \\u201cYes, I had the pleasure of receiving the information of your arrival in town, which you were so good as to send me,\\u201dturned hastily away with a slight bow and joined his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64492,\n            \"\\u201d With difficulty however could she prevent her from following him herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64505,\n            \"and to persuade her to check her agitation, to wait, at least, with the appearance of composure, till she might speak to him with more privacy and more effect, was impossible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64565,\n            \"In a short time Elinor saw Willoughby quit the room by the door towards the staircase, and telling Marianne that he was gone, urged the impossibility of speaking to him again that evening, as a fresh argument for her to be calm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64854,\n            \"Her indignation would have been still stronger than it was, had she not witnessed that embarrassment which seemed to speak a consciousness of his own misconduct, and prevented her from believing him so unprincipled as to have been sporting with the affections of her sister from the first, without any design that would bear investigation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64913,\n            \"Absence might have weakened his regard, and convenience might have determined him to overcome it, but that such a regard had formerly existed she could not bring herself to doubt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65232,\n            \"It was some minutes before she could go on with her letter, and the frequent bursts of grief which still obliged her, at intervals, to withhold her pen, were proofs enough of her feeling how more than probable it was that she was writing for the last time to Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65528,\n            \"Elinor, who saw as plainly by this, as if she had seen the direction, that it must come from Willoughby, felt immediately such a sickness at heart as made her hardly able to hold up her head, and sat in such a general tremour as made her fear it impossible to escape Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65592,\n            \"That good lady, however, saw only that Marianne had received a letter from Willoughby, which appeared to her a very good joke, and which she treated accordingly, by hoping, with a laugh, that she would find it to her liking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65732,\n            \"I hope, from the bottom of my heart, he won\\u2019t keep her waiting much longer, for it is quite grievous to see her look so ill and forlorn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65775,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, though never less disposed to speak than at that moment, obliged herself to answer such an attack as this, and, therefore, trying to smile, replied, \\u201cAnd have you really, Ma\\u2019am, talked yourself into a persuasion of my sister\\u2019s being engaged to Mr. Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66089,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings laughed again, but Elinor had not spirits to say more, and eager at all events to know what Willoughby had written, hurried away to their room, where, on opening the door, she saw Marianne stretched on the bed, almost choked by grief, one letter in her hand, and two or three others lying by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66340,\n            \"I am much concerned to find there was anything in my behaviour last night that did not meet your approbation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66361,\n            \"and though I am quite at a loss to discover in what point I could be so unfortunate as to offend you, I entreat your forgiveness of what I can assure you to have been perfectly unintentional.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66400,\n            \"I shall never reflect on my former acquaintance with your family in Devonshire without the most grateful pleasure, and flatter myself it will not be broken by any mistake or misapprehension of my actions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66436,\n            \"My esteem for your whole family is very sincere;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66446,\n            \"but if I have been so unfortunate as to give rise to a belief of more than I felt, or meant to express, I shall reproach myself for not having been more guarded in my professions of that esteem.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66607,\n            \"Though aware, before she began it, that it must bring a confession of his inconstancy, and confirm their separation for ever, she was not aware that such language could be suffered to announce it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66646,\n            \"nor could she have supposed Willoughby capable of departing so far from the appearance of every honourable and delicate feeling \\u2014 so far from the common decorum of a gentleman, as to send a letter so impudently cruel: a letter which, instead of bringing with his desire of a release any professions of regret, acknowledged no breach of faith, denied all peculiar affection whatever \\u2014 a letter of which every line was an insult, and which proclaimed its writer to be deep in hardened villainy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66756,\n            \"but every perusal only served to increase her abhorrence of the man, and so bitter were her feelings against him, that she dared not trust herself to speak, lest she might wound Marianne still deeper by treating their disengagement, not as a loss to her of any possible good but as an escape from the worst and most irremediable of all evils, a connection, for life, with an unprincipled man, as a deliverance the most real, a blessing the most important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67497,\n            \"Edward loves you \\u2014 what, oh what, can do away such happiness as that?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67620,\n            \"Much as you suffer now, think of what you would have suffered if the discovery of his character had been delayed to a later period \\u2014 if your engagement had been carried on for months and months, as it might have been, before he chose to put an end to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67714,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, he is not so unworthy as you believe him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67728,\n            \"He has broken no faith with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67736,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut he told you that he loved you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67779,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYet you wrote to him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67837,\n            \"The first, which was what her sister had sent him on their arrival in town, was to this effect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67877,\n            \"and I think you will feel something more than surprise, when you know that I am in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67917,\n            \"I wish you may receive this in time to come here to-night, but I will not depend on it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67940,\n            \"At any rate I shall expect you to-morrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67962,\n            \"\\u201d Her second note, which had been written on the morning after the dance at the Middletons \\u2019, was in these words: \\u2014 \\u201cI cannot express my disappointment in having missed you the day before yesterday, nor my astonishment at not having received any answer to a note which I sent you above a week ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68024,\n            \"I have been expecting to hear from you, and still more to see you, every hour of the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68066,\n            \"You had better come earlier another time, because we are generally out by one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68098,\n            \"I have been told that you were asked to be of the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68118,\n            \"You must be very much altered indeed since we parted, if that could be the case, and you not there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68141,\n            \"But I will not suppose this possible, and I hope very soon to receive your personal assurance of its being otherwise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68169,\n            \"\\u201d The contents of her last note to him were these: \\u2014 \\u201cWhat am I to imagine, Willoughby, by your behaviour last night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68205,\n            \"I was prepared to meet you with the pleasure which our separation naturally produced, with the familiarity which our intimacy at Barton appeared to me to justify.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68260,\n            \"but though I have not yet been able to form any reasonable apology for your behaviour, I am perfectly ready to hear your justification of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68288,\n            \"You have perhaps been misinformed, or purposely deceived, in something concerning me, which may have lowered me in your opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68312,\n            \"Tell me what it is, explain the grounds on which you acted, and I shall be satisfied, in being able to satisfy you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68339,\n            \"It would grieve me indeed to be obliged to think ill of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68353,\n            \"but if I am to do it, if I am to learn that you are not what we have hitherto believed you, that your regard for us all was insincere, that your behaviour to me was intended only to deceive, let it be told as soon as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68438,\n            \"If your sentiments are no longer what they were, you will return my notes, and the lock of my hair which is in your possession.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68585,\n            \"\\u201cI felt myself,\\u201dshe added, \\u201cto be as solemnly engaged to him, as if the strictest legal covenant had bound us to each other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68761,\n            \"When he told me that it might be many weeks before we met again \\u2014 his distress \\u2014 can I ever forget his distress?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68859,\n            \"I could rather believe every creature of my acquaintance leagued together to ruin me in his opinion, than believe his nature capable of such cruelty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68886,\n            \"This woman of whom he writes \\u2014 whoever she be \\u2014 or any one, in short, but your own dear self, mama, and Edward, may have been so barbarous to bely me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69263,\n            \"Whatever he might have heard against me \\u2014 ought he not to have suspended his belief?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69280,\n            \"ought he not to have told me of it, to have given me the power of clearing myself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69300,\n            \"\\u2018 The lock of hair, (repeating it from the letter,) which you so obligingly bestowed on me\\u2019\\u2014 That is unpardonable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69406,\n            \"\\u2014 Whom did I ever hear him talk of as young and attractive among his female acquaintance?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69427,\n            \"no one, no one \\u2014 he talked to me only of myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69498,\n            \"I came only for Willoughby\\u2019s sake \\u2014 and now who cares for me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71669,\n            \"I must do _ this _ justice to Mr. Willoughby \\u2014 he has broken no positive engagement with my sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71732,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, for her sister\\u2019s sake, could not press the subject farther, and she hoped it was not required of her for Willoughby\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71806,\n            \"\\u201cWell, my dear,\\u2019tis a true saying about an ill-wind, for it will be all the better for Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71834,\n            \"He will have her at last;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71874,\n            \"I hope he will come tonight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72162,\n            \"Well, I shall spirit up the Colonel as soon as I can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72188,\n            \"If we _ can _ but put Willoughby out of her head!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72201,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, if we can do _ that _, Ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cwe shall do very well with or without Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72664,\n            \"Colonel Brandon came in while the party were at tea, and by his manner of looking round the room for Marianne, Elinor immediately fancied that he neither expected nor wished to see her there, and, in short, that he was already aware of what occasioned her absence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72768,\n            \"do tell him, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72775,\n            \"\\u201d He shortly afterwards drew a chair close to hers, and, with a look which perfectly assured her of his good information, inquired after her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72833,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, then,\\u201dhe hesitatingly replied, \\u201cwhat I heard this morning may be \\u2014 there may be more truth in it than I could believe possible at first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72927,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou mean,\\u201danswered Elinor, with forced calmness, \\u201cMr. Willoughby\\u2019s marriage with Miss Grey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73053,\n            \"The name of Willoughby, John Willoughby, frequently repeated, first caught my attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73069,\n            \"and what followed was a positive assertion that every thing was now finally settled respecting his marriage with Miss Grey \\u2014 it was no longer to be a secret \\u2014 it would take place even within a few weeks, with many particulars of preparations and other matters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73118,\n            \"One thing, especially, I remember, because it served to identify the man still more: \\u2014 as soon as the ceremony was over, they were to go to Combe Magna, his seat in Somersetshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73258,\n            \"but Willoughby is capable \\u2014 at least I think\\u201d\\u2014 he stopped a moment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73326,\n            \"Till yesterday, I believe, she never doubted his regard;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73338,\n            \"and even now, perhaps \\u2014 but _ I _ am almost convinced that he never was really attached to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73417,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou know her disposition, and may believe how eagerly she would still justify him if she could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74061,\n            \"In one moment her imagination placed before her a letter from Willoughby, full of tenderness and contrition, explanatory of all that had passed, satisfactory, convincing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74091,\n            \"and instantly followed by Willoughby himself, rushing eagerly into the room to inforce, at her feet, by the eloquence of his eyes, the assurances of his letter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74277,\n            \"Her mother, still confident of their engagement, and relying as warmly as ever on his constancy, had only been roused by Elinor\\u2019s application, to intreat from Marianne greater openness towards them both;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74316,\n            \"and this, with such tenderness towards her, such affection for Willoughby, and such a conviction of their future happiness in each other, that she wept with agony through the whole of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74373,\n            \"dearer through the very excess of her mistaken confidence in Willoughby, and she was wildly urgent to be gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75038,\n            \"\\u201cYou have something to tell me of Mr. Willoughby, that will open his character farther.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75451,\n            \"Hers, for me, was, I believe, fervent as the attachment of your sister to Mr. Willoughby and it was, though from a different cause, no less unfortunate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77245,\n            \"Would he have been less gay or less happy in the smiles of your sister?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77319,\n            \"He had left her, promising to return;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77328,\n            \"he neither returned, nor wrote, nor relieved her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77351,\n            \"\\u201cHis character is now before you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77368,\n            \"Knowing all this, as I have now known it many weeks, guess what I must have felt on seeing your sister as fond of him as ever, and on being assured that she was to marry him: guess what I must have felt for all your sakes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77498,\n            \"and sometimes I thought your sister\\u2019s influence might yet reclaim him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77512,\n            \"But now, after such dishonorable usage, who can tell what were his designs on her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77530,\n            \"Whatever they may have been, however, she may now, and hereafter doubtless _ will _ turn with gratitude towards her own condition, when she compares it with that of my poor Eliza, when she considers the wretched and hopeless situation of this poor girl, and pictures her to herself, with an affection for him so strong, still as strong as her own, and with a mind tormented by self-reproach, which must attend her through life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77802,\n            \"\\u201cI have been more pained,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cby her endeavors to acquit him than by all the rest;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77826,\n            \"for it irritates her mind more than the most perfect conviction of his unworthiness can do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77924,\n            \"have you met him to \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cI could meet him no other way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77940,\n            \"Eliza had confessed to me, though most reluctantly, the name of her lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77956,\n            \"and when he returned to town, which was within a fortnight after myself, we met by appointment, he to defend, I to punish his conduct.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78189,\n            \"Not that Marianne appeared to distrust the truth of any part of it, for she listened to it all with the most steady and submissive attention, made neither objection nor remark, attempted no vindication of Willoughby, and seemed to show by her tears that she felt it to be impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78338,\n            \"She felt the loss of Willoughby\\u2019s character yet more heavily than she had felt the loss of his heart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78360,\n            \"his seduction and desertion of Miss Williams, the misery of that poor girl, and the doubt of what his designs might _ once _ have been on herself, preyed altogether so much on her spirits, that she could not bring herself to speak of what she felt even to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78585,\n            \"Against the interest of her own individual comfort, Mrs. Dashwood had determined that it would be better for Marianne to be any where, at that time, than at Barton, where every thing within her view would be bringing back the past in the strongest and most afflicting manner, by constantly placing Willoughby before her, such as she had always seen him there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78764,\n            \"From all danger of seeing Willoughby again, her mother considered her to be at least equally safe in town as in the country, since his acquaintance must now be dropped by all who called themselves her friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78826,\n            \"and chance had less in its favour in the crowd of London than even in the retirement of Barton, where it might force him before her while paying that visit at Allenham on his marriage, which Mrs. Dashwood, from foreseeing at first as a probable event, had brought herself to expect as a certain one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78902,\n            \"a letter from her son-in-law had told her that he and his wife were to be in town before the middle of February, and she judged it right that they should sometimes see their brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79064,\n            \"and Elinor, on the other hand, suspecting that it would not be in her power to avoid Edward entirely, comforted herself by thinking, that though their longer stay would therefore militate against her own happiness, it would be better for Marianne than an immediate return into Devonshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79117,\n            \"Her carefulness in guarding her sister from ever hearing Willoughby\\u2019s name mentioned, was not thrown away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79150,\n            \"for neither Mrs. Jennings, nor Sir John, nor even Mrs. Palmer herself, ever spoke of him before her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79257,\n            \"He wished him at the devil with all his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79268,\n            \"He would not speak another word to him, meet him where he might, for all the world!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79366,\n            \"\\u201cShe was determined to drop his acquaintance immediately, and she was very thankful that she had never been acquainted with him at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79424,\n            \"she hated him so much that she was resolved never to mention his name again, and she should tell everybody she saw, how good-for-nothing he was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79488,\n            \"She could soon tell at what coachmaker\\u2019s the new carriage was building, by what painter Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s portrait was drawn, and at what warehouse Miss Grey\\u2019s clothes might be seen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80111,\n            \"Early in February, within a fortnight from the receipt of Willoughby\\u2019s letter, Elinor had the painful office of informing her sister that he was married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91476,\n            \"Would either of them only have given her a full and minute account of the whole affair between Marianne and Mr. Willoughby, she would have thought herself amply rewarded for the sacrifice of the best place by the fire after dinner, which their arrival occasioned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119111,\n            \"Elinor, starting back with a look of horror at the sight of him, obeyed the first impulse of her heart in turning instantly to quit the room, and her hand was already on the lock, when its action was suspended by his hastily advancing, and saying, in a voice rather of command than supplication, \\u201cMiss Dashwood, for half an hour \\u2014 for ten minutes \\u2014 I entreat you to stay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119191,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, sir,\\u201dshe replied with firmness, \\u201cI shall _ not _ stay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119220,\n            \"The servants, I suppose, forgot to tell you that Mr. Palmer was not in the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119240,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHad they told me,\\u201dhe cried with vehemence, \\u201cthat Mr. Palmer and all his relations were at the devil, it would not have turned me from the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119277,\n            \"My business is with you, and only you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119451,\n            \"\\u201d He was sitting in an attitude of deep meditation, and seemed not to hear her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119469,\n            \"\\u201cYour sister,\\u201dsaid he, with abruptness, a moment afterwards \\u2014 \\u201cis out of danger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119490,\n            \"I heard it from the servant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119527,\n            \"\\u201cFor God\\u2019s sake tell me, is she out of danger, or is she not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119635,\n            \"Tell me honestly\\u201da deeper glow overspreading his cheeks, \\u201cdo you think me most a knave or a fool?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119669,\n            \"She began to think that he must be in liquor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119698,\n            \"and with this impression she immediately rose, saying, \\u201cMr. Willoughby, I advise you at present to return to Combe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119723,\n            \"I am not at leisure to remain with you longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119734,\n            \"Whatever your business may be with me, it will be better recollected and explained to-morrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119753,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI understand you,\\u201dhe replied, with an expressive smile, and a voice perfectly calm;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119805,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 cried Elinor, more and more at a loss to understand what he would be at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119861,\n            \"\\u201d The steadiness of his manner, and the intelligence of his eye as he spoke, convincing Elinor, that whatever other unpardonable folly might bring him to Cleveland, he was not brought there by intoxication, she said, after a moment\\u2019s recollection, \\u201cMr. Willoughby, you _ ought _ to feel, and I certainly _ do _, that after what has passed, your coming here in this manner, and forcing yourself upon my notice, requires a very particular excuse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119965,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI mean,\\u201dsaid he, with serious energy, \\u201cif I can, to make you hate me one degree less than you do _ now _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120016,\n            \"to open my whole heart to you, and by convincing you, that though I have been always a blockhead, I have not been always a rascal, to obtain something like forgiveness from Ma \\u2014 from your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120069,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cUpon my soul it is,\\u201d\\u2014 was his answer, with a warmth which brought all the former Willoughby to her remembrance, and in spite of herself made her think him sincere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120175,\n            \"_ Now _ will you listen to me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120190,\n            \"\\u201cI do not know,\\u201dsaid he, after a pause of expectation on her side, and thoughtfulness on his own, \\u201chow _ you _ may have accounted for my behaviour to your sister, or what diabolical motive you may have imputed to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120241,\n            \"Perhaps you will hardly think the better of me, \\u2014 it is worth the trial however, and you shall hear every thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120266,\n            \"When I first became intimate in your family, I had no other intention, no other view in the acquaintance than to pass my time pleasantly while I was obliged to remain in Devonshire, more pleasantly than I had ever done before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120311,\n            \"Your sister\\u2019s lovely person and interesting manners could not but please me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120326,\n            \"and her behaviour to me almost from the first, was of a kind \\u2014 it is astonishing, when I reflect on what it was, and what _ she _ was, that my heart should have been so insensible!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120384,\n            \"Careless of her happiness, thinking only of my own amusement, giving way to feelings which I had always been too much in the habit of indulging, I endeavoured, by every means in my power, to make myself pleasing to her, without any design of returning her affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120438,\n            \"\\u201d Miss Dashwood, at this point, turning her eyes on him with the most angry contempt, stopped him, by saying, \\u201cIt is hardly worth while, Mr. Willoughby, for you to relate, or for me to listen any longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120514,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI insist on you hearing the whole of it,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cMy fortune was never large, and I had always been expensive, always in the habit of associating with people of better income than myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120598,\n            \"yet that event being uncertain, and possibly far distant, it had been for some time my intention to re-establish my circumstances by marrying a woman of fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120630,\n            \"To attach myself to your sister, therefore, was not a thing to be thought of;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120648,\n            \"and with a meanness, selfishness, cruelty, which no indignant, no contemptuous look, even of yours, Miss Dashwood, can ever reprobate too much, \\u2014 I was acting in this manner, trying to engage her regard, without a thought of returning it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120775,\n            \"or, what is more, could I have sacrificed hers?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120793,\n            \"To avoid a comparative poverty, which her affection and her society would have deprived of all its horrors, I have, by raising myself to affluence, lost every thing that could make it a blessing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120832,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou did then,\\u201dsaid Elinor, a little softened, \\u201cbelieve yourself at one time attached to her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120882,\n            \"Yes, I found myself, by insensible degrees, sincerely fond of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120897,\n            \"and the happiest hours of my life were what I spent with her when I felt my intentions were strictly honourable, and my feelings blameless.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120924,\n            \"Even _ then _, however, when fully determined on paying my addresses to her, I allowed myself most improperly to put off, from day to day, the moment of doing it, from an unwillingness to enter into an engagement while my circumstances were so greatly embarrassed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121045,\n            \"At last, however, my resolution was taken, and I had determined, as soon as I could engage her alone, to justify the attentions I had so invariably paid her, and openly assure her of an affection which I had already taken such pains to display.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121097,\n            \"But in the interim \\u2014 in the interim of the very few hours that were to pass, before I could have an opportunity of speaking with her in private \\u2014 a circumstance occurred \\u2014 an unlucky circumstance, to ruin all my resolution, and with it all my comfort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121163,\n            \"\\u201cMrs. Smith had somehow or other been informed, I imagine by some distant relation, whose interest it was to deprive me of her favour, of an affair, a connection \\u2014 but I need not explain myself farther,\\u201dhe added, looking at her with an heightened colour and an enquiring eye, \\u2014 \\u201cyour particular intimacy \\u2014 you have probably heard the whole story long ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121239,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have,\\u201dreturned Elinor, colouring likewise, and hardening her heart anew against any compassion for him, \\u201cI have heard it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121269,\n            \"And how you will explain away any part of your guilt in that dreadful business, I confess is beyond my comprehension.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121292,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cRemember,\\u201dcried Willoughby, \\u201cfrom whom you received the account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121315,\n            \"I acknowledge that her situation and her character ought to have been respected by me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121331,\n            \"I do not mean to justify myself, but at the same time cannot leave you to suppose that I have nothing to urge \\u2014 that because she was injured she was irreproachable, and because _ I _ was a libertine, _ she _ must be a saint.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121382,\n            \"If the violence of her passions, the weakness of her understanding \\u2014 I do not mean, however, to defend myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121406,\n            \"Her affection for me deserved better treatment, and I often, with great self-reproach, recall the tenderness which, for a very short time, had the power of creating any return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121454,\n            \"But I have injured more than herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121496,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYour indifference, however, towards that unfortunate girl \\u2014 I must say it, unpleasant to me as the discussion of such a subject may well be \\u2014 your indifference is no apology for your cruel neglect of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121539,\n            \"Do not think yourself excused by any weakness, any natural defect of understanding on her side, in the wanton cruelty so evident on yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121566,\n            \"You must have known, that while you were enjoying yourself in Devonshire pursuing fresh schemes, always gay, always happy, she was reduced to the extremest indigence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121646,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, sir, and what said Mrs. Smith?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121659,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe taxed me with the offence at once, and my confusion may be guessed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121677,\n            \"The purity of her life, the formality of her notions, her ignorance of the world \\u2014 every thing was against me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121718,\n            \"She was previously disposed, I believe, to doubt the morality of my conduct in general, and was moreover discontented with the very little attention, the very little portion of my time that I had bestowed on her, in my present visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121794,\n            \"she offered to forgive the past, if I would marry Eliza.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121807,\n            \"That could not be \\u2014 and I was formally dismissed from her favour and her house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121863,\n            \"My affection for Marianne, my thorough conviction of her attachment to me \\u2014 it was all insufficient to outweigh that dread of poverty, or get the better of those false ideas of the necessity of riches, which I was naturally inclined to feel, and expensive society had increased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121916,\n            \"I had reason to believe myself secure of my present wife, if I chose to address her, and I persuaded myself to think that nothing else in common prudence remained for me to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121966,\n            \"\\u2014 I was engaged to dine with you on that very day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122011,\n            \"To see Marianne, I felt, would be dreadful, and I even doubted whether I could see her again, and keep to my resolution.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122056,\n            \"for I went, I saw her, and saw her miserable, and left her miserable \\u2014 and left her hoping never to see her again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122127,\n            \"I could not bear to leave the country in a manner that might lead you, or the rest of the neighbourhood, to suspect any part of what had really passed between Mrs. Smith and myself \\u2014 and I resolved therefore on calling at the cottage, in my way to Honiton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122195,\n            \"and, to heighten the matter, I found her alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122207,\n            \"You were all gone I do not know where.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122217,\n            \"I had left her only the evening before, so fully, so firmly resolved within my self on doing right!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122239,\n            \"A few hours were to have engaged her to me for ever;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122282,\n            \"But in this, our last interview of friendship, I approached her with a sense of guilt that almost took from me the power of dissembling.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122310,\n            \"Her sorrow, her disappointment, her deep regret, when I told her that I was obliged to leave Devonshire so immediately \\u2014 I never shall forget it \\u2014 united too with such reliance, such confidence in me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122380,\n            \"\\u201cDid you tell her that you should soon return?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122391,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not know what I told her,\\u201dhe replied, impatiently;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122447,\n            \"\\u2014 Then came your dear mother to torture me farther, with all her kindness and confidence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122479,\n            \"Miss Dashwood, you cannot have an idea of the comfort it gives me to look back on my own misery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122750,\n            \"\\u2014 Every line, every word was \\u2014 in the hackneyed metaphor which their dear writer, were she here, would forbid \\u2014 a dagger to my heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122812,\n            \"\\u2014 her taste, her opinions \\u2014 I believe they are better known to me than my own, \\u2014 and I am sure they are dearer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122864,\n            \"\\u2014 yet she felt it her duty to check such ideas in her companion as the last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122899,\n            \"Relate only what in your conscience you think necessary for me to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122913,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMarianne\\u2019s note, by assuring me that I was still as dear to her as in former days, \\u2014 that in spite of the many, many weeks we had been separated, she was as constant in her own feelings, and as full of faith in the constancy of mine as ever, \\u2014 awakened all my remorse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122979,\n            \"I say awakened, because time and London, business and dissipation, had in some measure quieted it, and I had been growing a fine hardened villain, fancying myself indifferent to her, and chusing to fancy that she too must have become indifferent to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123029,\n            \"talking to myself of our past attachment as a mere idle, trifling business, shrugging up my shoulders in proof of its being so, and silencing every reproach, overcoming every scruple, by secretly saying now and then, \\u2018 I shall be heartily glad to hear she is well married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123094,\n            \"I felt that she was infinitely dearer to me than any other woman in the world, and that I was using her infamously.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123119,\n            \"But every thing was then just settled between Miss Grey and me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123150,\n            \"I sent no answer to Marianne, intending by that to preserve myself from her farther notice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123236,\n            \"You would be surprised to hear how often I watched you, how often I was on the point of falling in with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123261,\n            \"I have entered many a shop to avoid your sight, as the carriage drove by.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123278,\n            \"Lodging as I did in Bond Street, there was hardly a day in which I did not catch a glimpse of one or other of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123306,\n            \"and nothing but the most constant watchfulness on my side, a most invariably prevailing desire to keep out of your sight, could have separated us so long.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123336,\n            \"I avoided the Middletons as much as possible, as well as everybody else who was likely to prove an acquaintance in common.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123360,\n            \"Not aware of their being in town, however, I blundered on Sir John, I believe, the first day of his coming, and the day after I had called at Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123400,\n            \"He asked me to a party, a dance at his house in the evening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123416,\n            \"Had he _ not _ told me as an inducement that you and your sister were to be there, I should have felt it too certain a thing, to trust myself near him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123513,\n            \"If you _ can _ pity me, Miss Dashwood, pity my situation as it was _ then _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123534,\n            \"With my head and heart full of your sister, I was forced to play the happy lover to another woman!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123566,\n            \"Well, at last, as I need not tell you, you were forced on me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123898,\n            \"Your sister wrote to me again, you know, the very next morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123919,\n            \"I was breakfasting at the Ellisons, \\u2014 and her letter, with some others, was brought to me there from my lodgings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123944,\n            \"It happened to catch Sophia\\u2019s eye before it caught mine \\u2014 and its size, the elegance of the paper, the hand-writing altogether, immediately gave her a suspicion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123979,\n            \"Some vague report had reached her before of my attachment to some young lady in Devonshire, and what had passed within her observation the preceding evening had marked who the young lady was, and made her more jealous than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124065,\n            \"Her wretchedness I could have borne, but her passion \\u2014 her malice \\u2014 At all events it must be appeased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124087,\n            \"And, in short \\u2014 what do you think of my wife\\u2019s style of letter-writing?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124181,\n            \"\\u2014 we were engaged, every thing in preparation, the day almost fixed \\u2014 But I am talking like a fool.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124208,\n            \"In honest words, her money was necessary to me, and in a situation like mine, any thing was to be done to prevent a rupture.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124237,\n            \"And after all, what did it signify to my character in the opinion of Marianne and her friends, in what language my answer was couched?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124274,\n            \"My business was to declare myself a scoundrel, and whether I did it with a bow or a bluster was of little importance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124299,\n            \"\\u2018 I am ruined for ever in their opinion,\\u2019said I to myself: \\u2018 I am shut out for ever from their society, they already think me an unprincipled fellow, this letter will only make them think me a blackguard one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124346,\n            \"\\u2019 Such were my reasonings, as, in a sort of desperate carelessness, I copied my wife\\u2019s words, and parted with the last relics of Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124378,\n            \"Her three notes, \\u2014 unluckily they were all in my pocketbook, or I should have denied their existence, and hoarded them for ever, \\u2014 I was forced to put them up, and could not even kiss them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124469,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are very wrong, Mr. Willoughby, very blamable,\\u201dsaid Elinor, while her voice, in spite of herself, betrayed her compassionate emotion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124501,\n            \"\\u201cyou ought not to speak in this way, either of Mrs. Willoughby or my sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124534,\n            \"Your wife has a claim to your politeness, to your respect, at least.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124550,\n            \"She must be attached to you, or she would not have married you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124565,\n            \"To treat her with unkindness, to speak of her slightingly is no atonement to Marianne \\u2014 nor can I suppose it a relief to your own conscience.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124594,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo not talk to me of my wife,\\u201dsaid he with a heavy sigh;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124621,\n            \"She knew I had no regard for her when we married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124658,\n            \"And now do you pity me, Miss Dashwood?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124678,\n            \"Am I, \\u2014 be it only one degree, \\u2014 am I less guilty in your opinion than I was before?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124731,\n            \"You have proved yourself, on the whole, less faulty than I had believed you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124760,\n            \"But I hardly know \\u2014 the misery that you have inflicted \\u2014 I hardly know what could have made it worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124782,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWill you repeat to your sister when she is recovered, what I have been telling you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124802,\n            \"\\u2014 Let me be a little lightened too in her opinion as well as in yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124819,\n            \"You tell me that she has forgiven me already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124829,\n            \"Let me be able to fancy that a better knowledge of my heart, and of my present feelings, will draw from her a more spontaneous, more natural, more gentle, less dignified, forgiveness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124868,\n            \"Tell her of my misery and my penitence \\u2014 tell her that my heart was never inconstant to her, and if you will, that at this moment she is dearer to me than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125451,\n            \"and the connection, for the sake of which he had, with little scruple, left her sister to misery, was likely to prove a source of unhappiness to himself of a far more incurable nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125868,\n            \"And if that some one should be the very he whom, of all others, I could least bear \\u2014 but I will not stay to rob myself of all your compassionate goodwill, by showing that where I have most injured I can least forgive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125941,\n            \"Elinor, for some time after he left her, for some time even after the sound of his carriage had died away, remained too much oppressed by a crowd of ideas, widely differing in themselves, but of which sadness was the general result, to think even of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125996,\n            \"Willoughby, he, whom only half an hour ago she had abhorred as the most worthless of men, Willoughby, in spite of all his faults, excited a degree of commiseration for the sufferings produced by them, which made her think of him as now separated for ever from her family, with a tenderness, a regret, rather in proportion, as she soon acknowledged within herself \\u2014 to his wishes than to his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126197,\n            \"The past, the present, the future, Willoughby\\u2019s visit, Marianne\\u2019s safety, and her mother\\u2019s expected arrival, threw her altogether into an agitation of spirits which kept off every indication of fatigue, and made her only fearful of betraying herself to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126437,\n            \"and there, shedding tears of joy, though still unable to speak, embraced Elinor again and again, turning from her at intervals to press Colonel Brandon\\u2019s hand, with a look which spoke at once her gratitude, and her conviction of his sharing with herself in the bliss of the moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126495,\n            \"He shared it, however, in a silence even greater than her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126700,\n            \"Willoughby, \\u201cpoor Willoughby,\\u201das she now allowed herself to call him, was constantly in her thoughts;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126722,\n            \"she would not but have heard his vindication for the world, and now blamed, now acquitted herself for having judged him so harshly before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126792,\n            \"and for a moment wished Willoughby a widower.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126801,\n            \"Then, remembering Colonel Brandon, reproved herself, felt that to _ his _ sufferings and _ his _ constancy far more than to his rival\\u2019s, the reward of her sister was due, and wished any thing rather than Mrs. Willoughby\\u2019s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126852,\n            \"The shock of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s errand at Barton had been much softened to Mrs. Dashwood by her own previous alarm;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126876,\n            \"for so great was her uneasiness about Marianne, that she had already determined to set out for Cleveland on that very day, without waiting for any further intelligence, and had so far settled her journey before his arrival, that the Careys were then expected every moment to fetch Margaret away, as her mother was unwilling to take her where there might be infection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126985,\n            \"Elinor could not hear the declaration, nor witness its proofs without sometimes wondering whether her mother ever recollected Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127044,\n            \"Marianne was restored to her from a danger in which, as she now began to feel, her own mistaken judgment in encouraging the unfortunate attachment to Willoughby, had contributed to place her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127140,\n            \"He has told me so himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127188,\n            \"Had I sat down to wish for any possible good to my family, I should have fixed on Colonel Brandon\\u2019s marrying one of you as the object most desirable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127221,\n            \"And I believe Marianne will be the most happy with him of the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127303,\n            \"\\u201cHe opened his whole heart to me yesterday as we travelled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127348,\n            \"I saw that it equalled my own, and he perhaps, thinking that mere friendship, as the world now goes, would not justify so warm a sympathy \\u2014 or rather, not thinking at all, I suppose \\u2014 giving way to irresistible feelings, made me acquainted with his earnest, tender, constant, affection for Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127428,\n            \"\\u201d Here, however, Elinor perceived, \\u2014 not the language, not the professions of Colonel Brandon, but the natural embellishments of her mother\\u2019s active fancy, which fashioned every thing delightful to her as it chose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127471,\n            \"\\u201cHis regard for her, infinitely surpassing anything that Willoughby ever felt or feigned, as much more warm, as more sincere or constant \\u2014 which ever we are to call it \\u2014 has subsisted through all the knowledge of dear Marianne\\u2019s unhappy prepossession for that worthless young man!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127535,\n            \"\\u2014 could he have seen her happy with another \\u2014 Such a noble mind!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127557,\n            \"\\u2014 no one can be deceived in _ him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127568,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cColonel Brandon\\u2019s character,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cas an excellent man, is well established.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127631,\n            \"But his coming for me as he did, with such active, such ready friendship, is enough to prove him one of the worthiest of men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127702,\n            \"To Mrs. Jennings, to the Middletons, he has been long and intimately known;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127719,\n            \"they equally love and respect him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127726,\n            \"and even my own knowledge of him, though lately acquired, is very considerable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127742,\n            \"and so highly do _ I _ value and esteem him, that if Marianne can be happy with him, I shall be as ready as yourself to think our connection the greatest blessing to us in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127783,\n            \"What answer did you give him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127790,\n            \"\\u2014 Did you allow him to hope?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127802,\n            \"my love, I could not then talk of hope to him or to myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127836,\n            \"His was an involuntary confidence, an irrepressible effusion to a soothing friend, not an application to a parent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127896,\n            \"and since our arrival, since our delightful security, I have repeated it to him more fully, have given him every encouragement in my power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127924,\n            \"Time, a very little time, I tell him, will do everything;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127965,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTo judge from the Colonel\\u2019s spirits, however, you have not yet made him equally sanguine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127991,\n            \"He thinks Marianne\\u2019s affection too deeply rooted for any change in it under a great length of time, and even supposing her heart again free, is too diffident of himself to believe, that with such a difference of age and disposition he could ever attach her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128052,\n            \"His age is only so much beyond hers as to be an advantage, as to make his character and principles fixed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128075,\n            \"and his disposition, I am well convinced, is exactly the very one to make your sister happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128141,\n            \"There was always a something, if you remember, in Willoughby\\u2019s eyes at times, which I did not like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128174,\n            \"but her mother, without waiting for her assent, continued, \\u201cAnd his manners, the Colonel\\u2019s manners are not only more pleasing to me than Willoughby\\u2019s ever were, but they are of a kind I well know to be more solidly attaching to Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128267,\n            \"I am very sure myself, that had Willoughby turned out as really amiable, as he has proved himself the contrary, Marianne would yet never have been so happy with _ him _ as she will be with Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128479,\n            \"\\u201d Here they were interrupted by the entrance of a third person, and Elinor withdrew to think it all over in private, to wish success to her friend, and yet in wishing it, to feel a pang for Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128595,\n            \"When there, at her own particular request, for she was impatient to pour forth her thanks to him for fetching her mother, Colonel Brandon was invited to visit her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128628,\n            \"His emotion on entering the room, in seeing her altered looks, and in receiving the pale hand which she immediately held out to him, was such, as, in Elinor\\u2019s conjecture, must arise from something more than his affection for Marianne, or the consciousness of its being known to others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128687,\n            \"and she soon discovered in his melancholy eye and varying complexion as he looked at her sister, the probable recurrence of many past scenes of misery to his mind, brought back by that resemblance between Marianne and Eliza already acknowledged, and now strengthened by the hollow eye, the sickly skin, the posture of reclining weakness, and the warm acknowledgment of peculiar obligation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128756,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, not less watchful of what passed than her daughter, but with a mind very differently influenced, and therefore watching to very different effect, saw nothing in the Colonel\\u2019s behaviour but what arose from the most simple and self-evident sensations, while in the actions and words of Marianne she persuaded herself to think that something more than gratitude already dawned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128894,\n            \"and Colonel Brandon was soon brought, by their united request, to consider his own abode there as equally determinate, if not equally indispensable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128921,\n            \"At his and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s united request in return, Mrs. Dashwood was prevailed on to accept the use of his carriage on her journey back, for the better accommodation of her sick child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128961,\n            \"and the Colonel, at the joint invitation of Mrs. Dashwood and Mrs. Jennings, whose active good-nature made her friendly and hospitable for other people as well as herself, engaged with pleasure to redeem it by a visit at the cottage, in the course of a few weeks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129025,\n            \"and Marianne, after taking so particular and lengthened a leave of Mrs. Jennings, one so earnestly grateful, so full of respect and kind wishes as seemed due to her own heart from a secret acknowledgment of past inattention, and bidding Colonel Brandon farewell with a cordiality of a friend, was carefully assisted by him into the carriage, of which he seemed anxious that she should engross at least half.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129441,\n            \"for no sooner had they entered their common sitting-room, than Marianne turned her eyes around it with a look of resolute firmness, as if determined at once to accustom herself to the sight of every object with which the remembrance of Willoughby could be connected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129537,\n            \"but the music on which her eye first rested was an opera, procured for her by Willoughby, containing some of their favourite duets, and bearing on its outward leaf her own name in his hand-writing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130004,\n            \"Her smile however changed to a sigh when she remembered that promise to Willoughby was yet unfulfilled, and feared she had that to communicate which might again unsettle the mind of Marianne, and ruin at least for a time this fair prospect of busy tranquillity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130256,\n            \"and there I first saw Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130345,\n            \"\\u201cAs for regret,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cI have done with that, as far as _ he _ is concerned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130370,\n            \"I do not mean to talk to you of what my feelings have been for him, but what they are _ now _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130395,\n            \"At present, if I could be satisfied on one point, if I could be allowed to think that he was not _ always _ acting a part, not _ always _ deceiving me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130432,\n            \"but above all, if I could be assured that he never was so _ very _ wicked as my fears have sometimes fancied him, since the story of that unfortunate girl \\u2014\\u201dShe stopt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130509,\n            \"for not only is it horrible to suspect a person, who has been what _ he _ has been to _ me _, of such designs, but what must it make me appear to myself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130548,\n            \"What in a situation like mine, but a most shamefully unguarded affection could expose me to \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cHow then,\\u201dasked her sister, \\u201cwould you account for his behaviour?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130584,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI would suppose him, \\u2014 Oh, how gladly would I suppose him, only fickle, very, very fickle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130651,\n            \"\\u201cI am not wishing him too much good,\\u201dsaid Marianne at last with a sigh, \\u201cwhen I wish his secret reflections may be no more unpleasant than my own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130693,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo you compare your conduct with his?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130718,\n            \"I compare it with yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130796,\n            \"I considered the past: I saw in my own behaviour, since the beginning of our acquaintance with him last autumn, nothing but a series of imprudence towards myself, and want of kindness to others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131808,\n            \"and till they reached the door of the cottage, easily conjecturing what her curiosity must be though no question was suffered to speak it, talked of nothing but Willoughby, and their conversation together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131960,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood did not hear unmoved the vindication of her former favourite.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131974,\n            \"She rejoiced in his being cleared from some part of his imputed guilt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131988,\n            \"\\u2014 she was sorry for him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131995,\n            \"\\u2014 she wished him happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132029,\n            \"Nothing could do away the knowledge of what the latter had suffered through his means, nor remove the guilt of his conduct towards Eliza.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132055,\n            \"Nothing could replace him, therefore, in her former esteem, nor injure the interests of Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132075,\n            \"Had Mrs. Dashwood, like her daughter, heard Willoughby\\u2019s story from himself \\u2014 had she witnessed his distress, and been under the influence of his countenance and his manner, it is probable that her compassion would have been greater.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132214,\n            \"In the evening, when they were all three together, Marianne began voluntarily to speak of him again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132411,\n            \"I never could have been happy with him, after knowing, as sooner or later I must have known, all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132581,\n            \"and I dare say you perceive, as well as myself, not only in this, but in many other circumstances, reason enough to be convinced that your marriage must have involved you in many certain troubles and disappointments, in which you would have been poorly supported by an affection, on his side, much less certain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132679,\n            \"His demands and your inexperience together, on a small, very small income, must have brought on distresses which would not be the _ less _ grievous to you, from having been entirely unknown and unthought of before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132806,\n            \"Beyond _ that _, had you endeavoured, however reasonably, to abridge _ his _ enjoyments, is it not to be feared, that instead of prevailing on feelings so selfish to consent to it, you would have lessened your own influence on his heart, and made him regret the connection which had involved him in such difficulties?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132885,\n            \"\\u201d in a tone that implied \\u2014 \\u201cdo you really think him selfish?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132929,\n            \"It was selfishness which first made him sport with your affections;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133058,\n            \"and he thinks only that he has married a woman of a less amiable temper than yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133076,\n            \"But does it follow that had he married you, he would have been happy?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133122,\n            \"He would have had a wife of whose temper he could make no complaint, but he would have been always necessitous \\u2014 always poor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133277,\n            \"she, therefore, pursuing the first subject, immediately continued, \\u201c_ One _ observation may, I think, be fairly drawn from the whole of the story \\u2014 that all Willoughby\\u2019s difficulties have arisen from the first offence against virtue, in his behaviour to Eliza Williams.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133331,\n            \"That crime has been the origin of every lesser one, and of all his present discontents.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133358,\n            \"and her mother was led by it to an enumeration of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s injuries and merits, warm as friendship and design could unitedly dictate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133671,\n            \"and when, as he waited at table, he had satisfied the inquiries of his mistress as to the event of his errand, this was his voluntary communication, \\u2014 \\u201cI suppose you know, ma\\u2019am, that Mr. Ferrars is married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133938,\n            \"\\u201cWho told you that Mr. Ferrars was married, Thomas?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133951,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI see Mr. Ferrars myself, ma\\u2019am, this morning in Exeter, and his lady too, Miss Steele as was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134043,\n            \"so I took off my hat, and she knew me and called to me, and inquired after you, ma\\u2019am, and the young ladies, especially Miss Marianne, and bid me I should give her compliments and Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s, their best compliments and service, and how sorry they was they had not time to come on and see you, but they was in a great hurry to go forwards, for they was going further down for a little while, but howsever, when they come back, they\\u2019d make sure to come and see you.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 16]\": [\n        [\n            60,\n            \"The late owner of this estate was a single man, who lived to a very advanced age, and who for many years of his life, had a constant companion and housekeeper in his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98,\n            \"But her death, which happened ten years before his own, produced a great alteration in his home;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118,\n            \"for to supply her loss, he invited and received into his house the family of his nephew Mr. Henry Dashwood, the legal inheritor of the Norland estate, and the person to whom he intended to bequeath it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1826,\n            \"but as she had already imbibed a good deal of Marianne\\u2019s romance, without having much of her sense, she did not, at thirteen, bid fair to equal her sisters at a more advanced period of life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4557,\n            \"The contempt which she had, very early in their acquaintance, felt for her daughter-in-law, was very much increased by the farther knowledge of her character, which half a year\\u2019s residence in her family afforded;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4602,\n            \"and perhaps in spite of every consideration of politeness or maternal affection on the side of the former, the two ladies might have found it impossible to have lived together so long, had not a particular circumstance occurred to give still greater eligibility, according to the opinions of Mrs. Dashwood, to her daughters\\u2019 continuance at Norland.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4665,\n            \"This circumstance was a growing attachment between her eldest girl and the brother of Mrs. John Dashwood, a gentleman-like and pleasing young man, who was introduced to their acquaintance soon after his sister\\u2019s establishment at Norland, and who had since spent the greatest part of his time there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4792,\n            \"It was enough for her that he appeared to be amiable, that he loved her daughter, and that Elinor returned the partiality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5168,\n            \"She was first called to observe and approve him farther, by a reflection which Elinor chanced one day to make on the difference between him and his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5438,\n            \"\\u201cIn a few months, my dear Marianne,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cElinor will, in all probability be settled for life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5522,\n            \"You will gain a brother, a real, affectionate brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6057,\n            \"In one circumstance only, my Marianne, may your destiny be different from hers!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6918,\n            \"She knew that what Marianne and her mother conjectured one moment, they believed the next \\u2014 that with them, to wish was to hope, and to hope was to expect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7591,\n            \"She was far from depending on that result of his preference of her, which her mother and sister still considered as certain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7773,\n            \"She gave her an answer which marked her contempt, and instantly left the room, resolving that, whatever might be the inconvenience or expense of so sudden a removal, her beloved Elinor should not be exposed another week to such insinuations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8002,\n            \"He seemed really anxious to accommodate them and the whole of his letter was written in so friendly a style as could not fail of giving pleasure to his cousin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8620,\n            \"Though her late conversation with her daughter-in-law had made her resolve on remaining at Norland no longer than was unavoidable, it had not produced the smallest effect on her in that point to which it principally tended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9050,\n            \"The man and one of the maids were sent off immediately into Devonshire, to prepare the house for their mistress\\u2019 s arrival;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9134,\n            \"Her eagerness to be gone from Norland was preserved from diminution by the evident satisfaction of her daughter-in-law in the prospect of her removal;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9407,\n            \"\\u201d said Marianne, as she wandered alone before the house, on the last evening of their being there;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9449,\n            \"happy house, could you know what I suffer in now viewing you from this spot, from whence perhaps I may view you no more!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10286,\n            \"\\u201d In the mean time, till all these alterations could be made from the savings of an income of five hundred a-year by a woman who never saved in her life, they were wise enough to be contented with the house as it was;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12063,\n            \"His appearance however was not unpleasing, in spite of his being in the opinion of Marianne and Margaret an absolute old bachelor, for he was on the wrong side of five and thirty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12240,\n            \"The instrument was unlocked, every body prepared to be charmed, and Marianne, who sang very well, at their request went through the chief of the songs which Lady Middleton had brought into the family on her marriage, and which perhaps had lain ever since in the same position on the pianoforte, for her ladyship had celebrated that event by giving up music, although by her mother\\u2019s account, she had played extremely well, and by her own was very fond of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12432,\n            \"and she felt a respect for him on the occasion, which the others had reasonably forfeited by their shameless want of taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12456,\n            \"His pleasure in music, though it amounted not to that ecstatic delight which alone could sympathize with her own, was estimable when contrasted against the horrible insensibility of the others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12489,\n            \"and she was reasonable enough to allow that a man of five and thirty might well have outlived all acuteness of feeling and every exquisite power of enjoyment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12622,\n            \"She was remarkably quick in the discovery of attachments, and had enjoyed the advantage of raising the blushes and the vanity of many a young lady by insinuations of her power over such a young man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12660,\n            \"and this kind of discernment enabled her soon after her arrival at Barton decisively to pronounce that Colonel Brandon was very much in love with Marianne Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12688,\n            \"She rather suspected it to be so, on the very first evening of their being together, from his listening so attentively while she sang to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13323,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cA woman of seven and twenty,\\u201dsaid Marianne, after pausing a moment, \\u201ccan never hope to feel or inspire affection again, and if her home be uncomfortable, or her fortune small, I can suppose that she might bring herself to submit to the offices of a nurse, for the sake of the provision and security of a wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13820,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI rather think you are mistaken, for when I was talking to her yesterday of getting a new grate for the spare bedchamber, she observed that there was no immediate hurry for it, as it was not likely that the room would be wanted for some time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14392,\n            \"and towards one of these hills did Marianne and Margaret one memorable morning direct their steps, attracted by the partial sunshine of a showery sky, and unable longer to bear the confinement which the settled rain of the two preceding days had occasioned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14438,\n            \"The weather was not tempting enough to draw the two others from their pencil and their book, in spite of Marianne\\u2019s declaration that the day would be lastingly fair, and that every threatening cloud would be drawn off from their hills;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15158,\n            \"Marianne herself had seen less of his person than the rest, for the confusion which crimsoned over her face, on his lifting her up, had robbed her of the power of regarding him after their entering the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15200,\n            \"But she had seen enough of him to join in all the admiration of the others, and with an energy which always adorned her praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15284,\n            \"His name was good, his residence was in their favourite village, and she soon found out that of all manly dresses a shooting-jacket was the most becoming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15781,\n            \"Miss Marianne must not expect to have all the men to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16381,\n            \"Her form, though not so correct as her sister\\u2019s, in having the advantage of height, was more striking;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16405,\n            \"and her face was so lovely, that when in the common cant of praise, she was called a beautiful girl, truth was less violently outraged than usually happens.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16610,\n            \"She could not be silent when such points were introduced, and she had neither shyness nor reserve in their discussion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16858,\n            \"You know what he thinks of Cowper and Scott;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16868,\n            \"you are certain of his estimating their beauties as he ought, and you have received every assurance of his admiring Pope no more than is proper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17057,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy love,\\u201dsaid her mother, \\u201cyou must not be offended with Elinor \\u2014 she was only in jest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17082,\n            \"I should scold her myself, if she were capable of wishing to check the delight of your conversation with our new friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17232,\n            \"He was exactly formed to engage Marianne\\u2019s heart, for with all this, he joined not only a captivating person, but a natural ardour of mind which was now roused and increased by the example of her own, and which recommended him to her affection beyond every thing else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17327,\n            \"In Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s estimation he was as faultless as in Marianne\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17385,\n            \"In hastily forming and giving his opinion of other people, in sacrificing general politeness to the enjoyment of undivided attention where his heart was engaged, and in slighting too easily the forms of worldly propriety, he displayed a want of caution which Elinor could not approve, in spite of all that he and Marianne could say in its support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17449,\n            \"Marianne began now to perceive that the desperation which had seized her at sixteen and a half, of ever seeing a man who could satisfy her ideas of perfection, had been rash and unjustifiable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18080,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut perhaps the abuse of such people as yourself and Marianne will make amends for the regard of Lady Middleton and her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18147,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy _ prot\\u00e9g\\u00e9 _, as you call him, is a sensible man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18173,\n            \"Yes, Marianne, even in a man between thirty and forty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18833,\n            \"and the ease and familiarity which naturally attended these parties were exactly calculated to give increasing intimacy to his acquaintance with the Dashwoods, to afford him opportunity of witnessing the excellencies of Marianne, of marking his animated admiration of her, and of receiving, in her behaviour to himself, the most pointed assurance of her affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19001,\n            \"When he was present she had no eyes for any one else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19030,\n            \"If their evenings at the park were concluded with cards, he cheated himself and all the rest of the party to get her a good hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19638,\n            \"his attentions were wholly Marianne\\u2019s, and a far less agreeable man might have been more generally pleasing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19659,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, unfortunately for himself, had no such encouragement to think only of Marianne, and in conversing with Elinor he found the greatest consolation for the indifference of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20014,\n            \"\\u201d After a short pause he resumed the conversation by saying, \\u2014 \\u201cDoes your sister make no distinction in her objections against a second attachment?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20413,\n            \"Marianne told her, with the greatest delight, that Willoughby had given her a horse, one that he had bred himself on his estate in Somersetshire, and which was exactly calculated to carry a woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20452,\n            \"Without considering that it was not in her mother\\u2019s plan to keep any horse, that if she were to alter her resolution in favour of this gift, she must buy another for the servant, and keep a servant to ride it, and after all, build a stable to receive them, she had accepted the present without hesitation, and told her sister of it in raptures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20527,\n            \"\\u201cHe intends to send his groom into Somersetshire immediately for it,\\u201dshe added, \\u201cand when it arrives we will ride every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20726,\n            \"I have not known him long indeed, but I am much better acquainted with him, than I am with any other creature in the world, except yourself and mama.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20821,\n            \"Of John I know very little, though we have lived together for years;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20883,\n            \"But by an appeal to her affection for her mother, by representing the inconveniences which that indulgent mother must draw on herself, if (as would probably be the case) she consented to this increase of establishment, Marianne was shortly subdued;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20929,\n            \"and she promised not to tempt her mother to such imprudent kindness by mentioning the offer, and to tell Willoughby when she saw him next, that it must be declined.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21084,\n            \"When you leave Barton to form your own establishment in a more lasting home, Queen Mab shall receive you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21114,\n            \"and in the whole of the sentence, in his manner of pronouncing it, and in his addressing her sister by her Christian name alone, she instantly saw an intimacy so decided, a meaning so direct, as marked a perfect agreement between them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21342,\n            \"and they had not known each other a week, I believe, before you were certain that Marianne wore his picture round her neck;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21392,\n            \"I am sure they will be married very soon, for he has got a lock of her hair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21463,\n            \"Last night after tea, when you and mama went out of the room, they were whispering and talking together as fast as could be, and he seemed to be begging something of her, and presently he took up her scissors and cut off a long lock of her hair, for it was all tumbled down her back;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22934,\n            \"\\u201cBut if you write a note to the housekeeper, Mr. Brandon,\\u201dsaid Marianne, eagerly, \\u201cwill it not be sufficient?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23104,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor then heard Willoughby say, in a low voice to Marianne, \\u201cThere are some people who cannot bear a party of pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24397,\n            \"As soon as they left the dining-room, Elinor enquired of her about it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24800,\n            \"and after a ten minutes\\u2019 interval of earnest thought, she came to her sister again, and said with great good humour, \\u201cPerhaps, Elinor, it _ was _ rather ill-judged in me to go to Allenham;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25011,\n            \"\\u201d Could Elinor have listened to her without interruption from the others, she would have described every room in the house with equal delight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25682,\n            \"and it was so wholly contradictory to their general opinions and practice, that a doubt sometimes entered her mind of their being really engaged, and this doubt was enough to prevent her making any inquiry of Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25739,\n            \"To Marianne it had all the distinguishing tenderness which a lover\\u2019s heart could give, and to the rest of the family it was the affectionate attention of a son and a brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25801,\n            \"and if no general engagement collected them at the park, the exercise which called him out in the morning was almost certain of ending there, where the rest of the day was spent by himself at the side of Marianne, and by his favourite pointer at her feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26548,\n            \"and this dear parlour in which our acquaintance first began, and in which so many happy hours have been since spent by us together, you would degrade to the condition of a common entrance, and every body would be eager to pass through the room which has hitherto contained within itself more real accommodation and comfort than any other apartment of the handsomest dimensions in the world could possibly afford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26639,\n            \"\\u201cYou are a good woman,\\u201dhe warmly replied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26698,\n            \"and that you will always consider me with the kindness which has made everything belonging to you so dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26850,\n            \"and her mother, who concluded that a promise had been made by Willoughby the night before of calling on her while they were absent, was perfectly satisfied with her remaining at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26944,\n            \"They were no sooner in the passage than Marianne came hastily out of the parlour apparently in violent affliction, with her handkerchief at her eyes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26979,\n            \"Surprised and alarmed they proceeded directly into the room she had just quitted, where they found only Willoughby, who was leaning against the mantel-piece with his back towards them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27013,\n            \"He turned round on their coming in, and his countenance showed that he strongly partook of the emotion which over-powered Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27607,\n            \"Willoughby\\u2019s behaviour in taking leave of them, his embarrassment, and affectation of cheerfulness, and, above all, his unwillingness to accept her mother\\u2019s invitation, a backwardness so unlike a lover, so unlike himself, greatly disturbed her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27802,\n            \"\\u201cOur dear Willoughby is now some miles from Barton, Elinor,\\u201dsaid she, as she sat down to work, \\u201cand with how heavy a heart does he travel?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27917,\n            \"_ You _ must have seen the difference as well as I.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28077,\n            \"I am persuaded that Mrs. Smith suspects his regard for Marianne, disapproves of it, (perhaps because she has other views for him,) and on that account is eager to get him away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28672,\n            \"my dear child, do you accuse Willoughby and Marianne of concealment?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28767,\n            \"Has not his behaviour to Marianne and to all of us, for at least the last fortnight, declared that he loved and considered her as his future wife, and that he felt for us the attachment of the nearest relation?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29668,\n            \"They saw nothing of Marianne till dinner time, when she entered the room and took her place at the table without saying a word.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29715,\n            \"She avoided the looks of them all, could neither eat nor speak, and after some time, on her mother\\u2019s silently pressing her hand with tender compassion, her small degree of fortitude was quite overcome, she burst into tears and left the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29806,\n            \"and though her family were most anxiously attentive to her comfort, it was impossible for them, if they spoke at all, to keep clear of every subject which her feelings connected with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29869,\n            \"She would have been ashamed to look her family in the face the next morning, had she not risen from her bed in more need of repose than when she lay down in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30032,\n            \"She played over every favourite song that she had been used to play to Willoughby, every air in which their voices had been oftenest joined, and sat at the instrument gazing on every line of music that he had written out for her, till her heart was so heavy that no farther sadness could be gained;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30150,\n            \"She read nothing but what they had been used to read together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30386,\n            \"\\u201cWhy do you not ask Marianne at once,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwhether she is or she is not engaged to Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30499,\n            \"I should never deserve her confidence again, after forcing from her a confession of what is meant at present to be unacknowledged to any one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30526,\n            \"I know Marianne\\u2019s heart: I know that she dearly loves me, and that I shall not be the last to whom the affair is made known, when circumstances make the revealment of it eligible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30644,\n            \"It was several days before Willoughby\\u2019s name was mentioned before Marianne by any of her family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30687,\n            \"\\u2014 but one evening, Mrs. Dashwood, accidentally taking up a volume of Shakespeare, exclaimed, \\u201cWe have never finished Hamlet, Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30811,\n            \"One morning, about a week after his leaving the country, Marianne was prevailed on to join her sisters in their usual walk, instead of wandering away by herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30854,\n            \"If her sisters intended to walk on the downs, she directly stole away towards the lanes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30872,\n            \"if they talked of the valley, she was as speedy in climbing the hills, and could never be found when the others set off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30918,\n            \"They walked along the road through the valley, and chiefly in silence, for Marianne\\u2019s _ mind _ could not be controlled, and Elinor, satisfied with gaining one point, would not then attempt more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31083,\n            \"and in a moment afterwards Marianne rapturously exclaimed, \\u201cIt is he;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31101,\n            \"\\u2014 I know it is!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31197,\n            \"and Elinor, to screen Marianne from particularity, as she felt almost certain of its not being Willoughby, quickened her pace and kept up with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31246,\n            \"and abruptly turning round, she was hurrying back, when the voices of both her sisters were raised to detain her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31334,\n            \"but she dispersed her tears to smile on _ him _, and in her sister\\u2019s happiness forgot for a time her own disappointment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31388,\n            \"He was welcomed by them all with great cordiality, but especially by Marianne, who showed more warmth of regard in her reception of him than even Elinor herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31419,\n            \"To Marianne, indeed, the meeting between Edward and her sister was but a continuation of that unaccountable coldness which she had often observed at Norland in their mutual behaviour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32070,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMarianne,\\u201dcried her sister, \\u201chow can you say so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32114,\n            \"Have you forgot, Marianne, how many pleasant days we have owed to them?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32480,\n            \"\\u201d said she, when dinner was over and they had drawn round the fire;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32981,\n            \"\\u201d repeated Edward \\u2014 \\u201cbut why must you have hunters?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32999,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne coloured as she replied, \\u201cBut most people do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33225,\n            \"You, Miss Dashwood, would give a general commission for every new print of merit to be sent you \\u2014 and as for Marianne, I know her greatness of soul, there would not be music enough in London to content her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33340,\n            \"But I was willing to show you that I had not forgot our old disputes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33356,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI love to be reminded of the past, Edward \\u2014 whether it be melancholy or gay, I love to recall it \\u2014 and you will never offend me by talking of former times.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33588,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay, Edward,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201c_ you _ need not reproach me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33643,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNor do I think it a part of Marianne\\u2019s,\\u201dsaid Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33661,\n            \"\\u201cI should hardly call her a lively girl \\u2014 she is very earnest, very eager in all she does \\u2014 sometimes talks a great deal and always with animation \\u2014 but she is not often really merry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33701,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe you are right,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cand yet I have always set her down as a lively girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33819,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut I thought it was right, Elinor,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cto be guided wholly by the opinion of other people.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33905,\n            \"You must not confound my meaning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33912,\n            \"I am guilty, I confess, of having often wished you to treat our acquaintance in general with greater attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33934,\n            \"but when have I advised you to adopt their sentiments or to conform to their judgment in serious matters?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34431,\n            \"He joined her and Marianne in the breakfast-room the next morning before the others were down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34450,\n            \"and Marianne, who was always eager to promote their happiness as far as she could, soon left them to themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34593,\n            \"This was a subject which ensured Marianne\\u2019s attention, and she was beginning to describe her own admiration of these scenes, and to question him more minutely on the objects that had particularly struck him, when Edward interrupted her by saying, \\u201cYou must not enquire too far, Marianne \\u2014 remember I have no knowledge in the picturesque, and I shall offend you by my ignorance and want of taste if we come to particulars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34845,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am afraid it is but too true,\\u201dsaid Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35174,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne looked with amazement at Edward, with compassion at her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35214,\n            \"She was sitting by Edward, and in taking his tea from Mrs. Dashwood, his hand passed so directly before her, as to make a ring, with a plait of hair in the centre, very conspicuous on one of his fingers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35261,\n            \"\\u201cI never saw you wear a ring before, Edward,\\u201dshe cried.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35407,\n            \"the only difference in their conclusions was, that what Marianne considered as a free gift from her sister, Elinor was conscious must have been procured by some theft or contrivance unknown to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35545,\n            \"but her own forgiveness might have been more speedy, had she known how little offence it had given her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35870,\n            \"you thought nobody could dance because a certain person that shall be nameless is gone!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35963,\n            \"Edward saw enough to comprehend, not only the meaning of others, but such of Marianne\\u2019s expressions as had puzzled him before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35989,\n            \"and when their visitors left them, he went immediately round her, and said, in a whisper, \\u201cI have been guessing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37451,\n            \"But as it was her determination to subdue it, and to prevent herself from appearing to suffer more than what all her family suffered on his going away, she did not adopt the method so judiciously employed by Marianne, on a similar occasion, to augment and fix her sorrow, by seeking silence, solitude and idleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38187,\n            \"Has she run away because we are come?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38196,\n            \"I see her instrument is open.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38203,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShe is walking, I believe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39148,\n            \"\\u201cNow, Palmer, you shall see a monstrous pretty girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39591,\n            \"\\u201d said Marianne, as soon as they were gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39777,\n            \"\\u201d said she, seating herself between Elinor and Marianne, \\u201cfor it is so bad a day I was afraid you might not come, which would be a shocking thing, as we go away again tomorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40621,\n            \"and exultingly said, she did not care how cross he was to her, as they must live together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41374,\n            \"\\u201d She surprised Elinor very much as they returned into the drawing-room, by asking her whether she did not like Mr. Palmer excessively.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41554,\n            \"and she was eager to gain from any one, such a confirmation of his merits as might remove the possibility of fear from Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46299,\n            \"Marianne, who had never much toleration for any thing like impertinence, vulgarity, inferiority of parts, or even difference of taste from herself, was at this time particularly ill-disposed, from the state of her spirits, to be pleased with the Miss Steeles, or to encourage their advances;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46356,\n            \"and to the invariable coldness of her behaviour towards them, which checked every endeavour at intimacy on their side, Elinor principally attributed that preference of herself which soon became evident in the manners of both, but especially of Lucy, who missed no opportunity of engaging her in conversation, or of striving to improve their acquaintance by an easy and frank communication of her sentiments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50567,\n            \"And so well was she able to answer her own expectations, that when she joined them at dinner only two hours after she had first suffered the extinction of all her dearest hopes, no one would have supposed from the appearance of the sisters, that Elinor was mourning in secret over obstacles which must divide her for ever from the object of her love, and that Marianne was internally dwelling on the perfections of a man, of whose whole heart she felt thoroughly possessed, and whom she expected to see in every carriage which drove near their house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50672,\n            \"The necessity of concealing from her mother and Marianne, what had been entrusted in confidence to herself, though it obliged her to unceasing exertion, was no aggravation of Elinor\\u2019s distress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51553,\n            \"Margaret, with her mother\\u2019s permission, was equally compliant, and Marianne, though always unwilling to join any of their parties, was persuaded by her mother, who could not bear to have her seclude herself from any chance of amusement, to go likewise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52026,\n            \"No one made any objection but Marianne, who with her usual inattention to the forms of general civility, exclaimed, \\u201cYour Ladyship will have the goodness to excuse _ me _ \\u2014 you know I detest cards.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52469,\n            \"The pianoforte at which Marianne, wrapped up in her own music and her own thoughts, had by this time forgotten that any body was in the room besides herself, was luckily so near them that Miss Dashwood now judged she might safely, under the shelter of its noise, introduce the interesting subject, without any risk of being heard at the card-table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53632,\n            \"\\u201d repeated Miss Steele, whose ear had caught those words by a sudden pause in Marianne\\u2019s music.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53823,\n            \"Lucy first put an end to it by saying in a lower tone, though Marianne was then giving them the powerful protection of a very magnificent concerto, \\u2014 \\u201cI will honestly tell you of one scheme which has lately come into my head, for bringing matters to bear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55170,\n            \"Elinor, without observing the varying complexion of her sister, and the animated look which spoke no indifference to the plan, immediately gave a grateful but absolute denial for both, in which she believed herself to be speaking their united inclinations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55475,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have a notion,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cthat Miss Marianne would not object to such a scheme, if her elder sister would come into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55560,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cI am sure I shall be monstrous glad of Miss Marianne\\u2019s company, whether Miss Dashwood will go or not, only the more the merrier say I, and I thought it would be more comfortable for them to be together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55688,\n            \"Come, Miss Marianne, let us strike hands upon the bargain, and if Miss Dashwood will change her mind by and bye, why so much the better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55852,\n            \"and Elinor, who now understood her sister, and saw to what indifference to almost every thing else she was carried by her eagerness to be with Willoughby again, made no farther direct opposition to the plan, and merely referred it to her mother\\u2019s decision, from whom however she scarcely expected to receive any support in her endeavour to prevent a visit, which she could not approve of for Marianne, and which on her own account she had particular reasons to avoid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55943,\n            \"Whatever Marianne was desirous of, her mother would be eager to promote \\u2014 she could not expect to influence the latter to cautiousness of conduct in an affair respecting which she had never been able to inspire her with distrust;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56088,\n            \"On being informed of the invitation, Mrs. Dashwood, persuaded that such an excursion would be productive of much amusement to both her daughters, and perceiving through all her affectionate attention to herself, how much the heart of Marianne was in it, would not hear of their declining the offer upon _ her _ account;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56380,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThough with your usual anxiety for our happiness,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cyou have been obviating every impediment to the present scheme which occurred to you, there is still one objection which, in my opinion, cannot be so easily removed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57135,\n            \"With regard to herself, it was now a matter of unconcern whether she went to town or not, and when she saw her mother so thoroughly pleased with the plan, and her sister exhilarated by it in look, voice, and manner, restored to all her usual animation, and elevated to more than her usual gaiety, she could not be dissatisfied with the cause, and would hardly allow herself to distrust the consequence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57243,\n            \"Her unwillingness to quit her mother was her only restorative to calmness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57421,\n            \"But these objections had all, with that happy ardour of youth which Marianne and her mother equally shared, been overcome or overlooked;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57695,\n            \"They were three days on their journey, and Marianne\\u2019s behaviour as they travelled was a happy specimen of what future complaisance and companionableness to Mrs. Jennings might be expected to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57731,\n            \"She sat in silence almost all the way, wrapt in her own meditations, and scarcely ever voluntarily speaking, except when any object of picturesque beauty within their view drew from her an exclamation of delight exclusively addressed to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58063,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am _ not _ going to write to my mother,\\u201dreplied Marianne, hastily, and as if wishing to avoid any farther inquiry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58280,\n            \"She could scarcely eat any dinner, and when they afterwards returned to the drawing room, seemed anxiously listening to the sound of every carriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59549,\n            \"\\u201cWhat do you think he said when he heard of your coming with Mama?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59683,\n            \"Wherever they went, she was evidently always on the watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59695,\n            \"In Bond Street especially, where much of their business lay, her eyes were in constant inquiry;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59714,\n            \"and in whatever shop the party were engaged, her mind was equally abstracted from every thing actually before them, from all that interested and occupied the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59744,\n            \"Restless and dissatisfied every where, her sister could never obtain her opinion of any article of purchase, however it might equally concern them both: she received no pleasure from anything;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59778,\n            \"was only impatient to be at home again, and could with difficulty govern her vexation at the tediousness of Mrs. Palmer, whose eye was caught by every thing pretty, expensive, or new;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59849,\n            \"and no sooner had they entered the house than Marianne flew eagerly up stairs, and when Elinor followed, she found her turning from the table with a sorrowful countenance, which declared that no Willoughby had been there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59890,\n            \"\\u201cHas no letter been left here for me since we went out?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60462,\n            \"\\u201cIt is charming weather for _ them _ indeed,\\u201dshe continued, as she sat down to the breakfast table with a happy countenance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61093,\n            \"he came to look at Marianne and talk to Elinor, who often derived more satisfaction from conversing with him than from any other daily occurrence, but who saw at the same time with much concern his continued regard for her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61145,\n            \"It grieved her to see the earnestness with which he often watched Marianne, and his spirits were certainly worse than when at Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61207,\n            \"\\u201d cried Marianne, \\u201che has been here while we were out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61274,\n            \"This event, while it raised the spirits of Elinor, restored to those of her sister all, and more than all, their former agitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61540,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNor I,\\u201danswered Marianne with energy, \\u201cour situations then are alike.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62165,\n            \"She complained of it as they returned to Berkeley Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62251,\n            \"\\u201cSo my daughter Middleton told me, for it seems Sir John met him somewhere in the street this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62284,\n            \"Impatient in this situation to be doing something that might lead to her sister\\u2019s relief, Elinor resolved to write the next morning to her mother, and hoped by awakening her fears for the health of Marianne, to procure those inquiries which had been so long delayed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62336,\n            \"and she was still more eagerly bent on this measure by perceiving after breakfast on the morrow, that Marianne was again writing to Willoughby, for she could not suppose it to be to any other person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62430,\n            \"Elinor was very earnest in her application to her mother, relating all that had passed, her suspicions of Willoughby\\u2019s inconstancy, urging her by every plea of duty and affection to demand from Marianne an account of her real situation with respect to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62498,\n            \"Marianne, who had seen him from the window, and who hated company of any kind, left the room before he entered it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63122,\n            \"Yet as she was convinced that Marianne\\u2019s affection for Willoughby, could leave no hope of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s success, whatever the event of that affection might be, and at the same time wished to shield her conduct from censure, she thought it most prudent and kind, after some consideration, to say more than she really knew or believed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63508,\n            \"and when at last they were told that Lady Middleton waited for them at the door, she started as if she had forgotten that any one was expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63645,\n            \"After some time spent in saying little or doing less, Lady Middleton sat down to Cassino, and as Marianne was not in spirits for moving about, she and Elinor luckily succeeding to chairs, placed themselves at no great distance from the table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63725,\n            \"She soon caught his eye, and he immediately bowed, but without attempting to speak to her, or to approach Marianne, though he could not but see her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64342,\n            \"Marianne, now looking dreadfully white, and unable to stand, sunk into her chair, and Elinor, expecting every moment to see her faint, tried to screen her from the observation of others, while reviving her with lavender water.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64469,\n            \"No, my dearest Marianne, you must wait.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64542,\n            \"for Marianne continued incessantly to give way in a low voice to the misery of her feelings, by exclamations of wretchedness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64565,\n            \"In a short time Elinor saw Willoughby quit the room by the door towards the staircase, and telling Marianne that he was gone, urged the impossibility of speaking to him again that evening, as a fresh argument for her to be calm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64636,\n            \"Lady Middleton, though in the middle of a rubber, on being informed that Marianne was unwell, was too polite to object for a moment to her wish of going away, and making over her cards to a friend, they departed as soon as the carriage could be found.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64816,\n            \"for however Marianne might still feed her own wishes, _ she _ could not attribute such behaviour to mistake or misapprehension of any kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64946,\n            \"As for Marianne, on the pangs which so unhappy a meeting must already have given her, and on those still more severe which might await her in its probable consequence, she could not reflect without the deepest concern.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65060,\n            \"Before the housemaid had lit their fire the next day, or the sun gained any power over a cold, gloomy morning in January, Marianne, only half dressed, was kneeling against one of the window-seats for the sake of all the little light she could command from it, and writing as fast as a continual flow of tears would permit her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65148,\n            \"and after observing her for a few moments with silent anxiety, said, in a tone of the most considerate gentleness, \\u201cMarianne, may I ask \\u2014?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65299,\n            \"and she would have tried to sooth and tranquilize her still more, had not Marianne entreated her, with all the eagerness of the most nervous irritability, not to speak to her for the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65462,\n            \"As this was a favourite meal with Mrs. Jennings, it lasted a considerable time, and they were just setting themselves, after it, round the common working table, when a letter was delivered to Marianne, which she eagerly caught from the servant, and, turning of a death-like paleness, instantly ran out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65592,\n            \"That good lady, however, saw only that Marianne had received a letter from Willoughby, which appeared to her a very good joke, and which she treated accordingly, by hoping, with a laugh, that she would find it to her liking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65667,\n            \"and calmly continuing her talk, as soon as Marianne disappeared, she said, \\u201cUpon my word, I never saw a young woman so desperately in love in my life!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66089,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings laughed again, but Elinor had not spirits to say more, and eager at all events to know what Willoughby had written, hurried away to their room, where, on opening the door, she saw Marianne stretched on the bed, almost choked by grief, one letter in her hand, and two or three others lying by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66168,\n            \"and seating herself on the bed, took her hand, kissed her affectionately several times, and then gave way to a burst of tears, which at first was scarcely less violent than Marianne\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66756,\n            \"but every perusal only served to increase her abhorrence of the man, and so bitter were her feelings against him, that she dared not trust herself to speak, lest she might wound Marianne still deeper by treating their disengagement, not as a loss to her of any possible good but as an escape from the worst and most irremediable of all evils, a connection, for life, with an unprincipled man, as a deliverance the most real, a blessing the most important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66847,\n            \"In her earnest meditations on the contents of the letter, on the depravity of that mind which could dictate it, and probably, on the very different mind of a very different person, who had no other connection whatever with the affair than what her heart gave him with every thing that passed, Elinor forgot the immediate distress of her sister, forgot that she had three letters on her lap yet unread, and so entirely forgot how long she had been in the room, that when on hearing a carriage drive up to the door, she went to the window to see who could be coming so unreasonably early, she was all astonishment to perceive Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s chariot, which she knew had not been ordered till one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66988,\n            \"Determined not to quit Marianne, though hopeless of contributing, at present, to her ease, she hurried away to excuse herself from attending Mrs. Jennings, on account of her sister being indisposed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67026,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, with a thoroughly good-humoured concern for its cause, admitted the excuse most readily, and Elinor, after seeing her safe off, returned to Marianne, whom she found attempting to rise from the bed, and whom she reached just in time to prevent her from falling on the floor, faint and giddy from a long want of proper rest and food;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67201,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI only wish,\\u201dreplied her sister, \\u201cthere were any thing I _ could _ do, which might be of comfort to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67231,\n            \"\\u201d This, as every thing else would have been, was too much for Marianne, who could only exclaim, in the anguish of her heart, \\u201cOh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67341,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI cannot, I cannot,\\u201dcried Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67417,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo you call _ me _ happy, Marianne?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67556,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI can have no pleasure while I see you in this state.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67591,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou must not talk so, Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68438,\n            \"If your sentiments are no longer what they were, you will return my notes, and the lock of my hair which is in your possession.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68585,\n            \"\\u201cI felt myself,\\u201dshe added, \\u201cto be as solemnly engaged to him, as if the strictest legal covenant had bound us to each other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68761,\n            \"When he told me that it might be many weeks before we met again \\u2014 his distress \\u2014 can I ever forget his distress?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68859,\n            \"I could rather believe every creature of my acquaintance leagued together to ruin me in his opinion, than believe his nature capable of such cruelty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68953,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor would not contend, and only replied, \\u201cWhoever may have been so detestably your enemy, let them be cheated of their malignant triumph, my dear sister, by seeing how nobly the consciousness of your own innocence and good intentions supports your spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69058,\n            \"Elinor, Elinor, they who suffer little may be proud and independent as they like \\u2014 may resist insult, or return mortification \\u2014 but I cannot.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69087,\n            \"I must feel \\u2014 I must be wretched \\u2014 and they are welcome to enjoy the consciousness of it that can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69109,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut for my mother\\u2019s sake and mine \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cI would do more than for my own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69774,\n            \"\\u201cHow do you do my dear?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69782,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 said she in a voice of great compassion to Marianne, who turned away her face without attempting to answer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69903,\n            \"Well, said I, all I can say is, that if this be true, he has used a young lady of my acquaintance abominably ill, and I wish with all my soul his wife may plague his heart out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69947,\n            \"And so I shall always say, my dear, you may depend on it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70026,\n            \"and with your pretty face you will never want admirers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70042,\n            \"I won\\u2019t disturb her any longer, for she had better have her cry out at once and have done with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70066,\n            \"The Parrys and Sandersons luckily are coming tonight you know, and that will amuse her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70083,\n            \"\\u201d She then went away, walking on tiptoe out of the room, as if she supposed her young friend\\u2019s affliction could be increased by noise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70113,\n            \"Marianne, to the surprise of her sister, determined on dining with them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70193,\n            \"and adjusting her dress for her as well as she could, while Marianne still remained on the bed, was ready to assist her into the dining room as soon as they were summoned to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70362,\n            \"Their good friend saw that Marianne was unhappy, and felt that every thing was due to her which might make her at all less so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70504,\n            \"As soon, however, as the consciousness of all this was forced by continual repetition on Marianne, she could stay no longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70892,\n            \"I warrant you, Miss Marianne would have been ready to wait till matters came round.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71172,\n            \"Marianne, I dare say, will not leave her room again this evening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72286,\n            \"\\u201cYou had better leave me,\\u201dwas all the notice that her sister received from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72305,\n            \"\\u201cI will leave you,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cif you will go to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72543,\n            \"But I have just left Marianne in bed, and, I hope, almost asleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72664,\n            \"Colonel Brandon came in while the party were at tea, and by his manner of looking round the room for Marianne, Elinor immediately fancied that he neither expected nor wished to see her there, and, in short, that he was already aware of what occasioned her absence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72805,\n            \"\\u201cMarianne is not well,\\u201dsaid she.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73802,\n            \"All that she wants is gossip, and she only likes me now because I supply it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73914,\n            \"She expected from other people the same opinions and feelings as her own, and she judged of their motives by the immediate effect of their actions on herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74010,\n            \"With a letter in her outstretched hand, and countenance gaily smiling, from the persuasion of bringing comfort, she entered their room, saying, \\u201cNow, my dear, I bring you something that I am sure will do you good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74061,\n            \"In one moment her imagination placed before her a letter from Willoughby, full of tenderness and contrition, explanatory of all that had passed, satisfactory, convincing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74277,\n            \"Her mother, still confident of their engagement, and relying as warmly as ever on his constancy, had only been roused by Elinor\\u2019s application, to intreat from Marianne greater openness towards them both;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74394,\n            \"Elinor, unable herself to determine whether it were better for Marianne to be in London or at Barton, offered no counsel of her own except of patience till their mother\\u2019s wishes could be known;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74497,\n            \"Elinor, with a very heavy heart, aware of the pain she was going to communicate, and perceiving, by Marianne\\u2019s letter, how ill she had succeeded in laying any foundation for it, then sat down to write her mother an account of what had passed, and entreat her directions for the future;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74558,\n            \"while Marianne, who came into the drawing-room on Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s going away, remained fixed at the table where Elinor wrote, watching the advancement of her pen, grieving over her for the hardship of such a task, and grieving still more fondly over its effect on her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75221,\n            \"\\u201cYou have probably entirely forgotten a conversation \\u2014 (it is not to be supposed that it could make any impression on you) \\u2014 a conversation between us one evening at Barton Park \\u2014 it was the evening of a dance \\u2014 in which I alluded to a lady I had once known, as resembling, in some measure, your sister Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75362,\n            \"This lady was one of my nearest relations, an orphan from her infancy, and under the guardianship of my father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75415,\n            \"and my affection for her, as we grew up, was such, as perhaps, judging from my present forlorn and cheerless gravity, you might think me incapable of having ever felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75451,\n            \"Hers, for me, was, I believe, fervent as the attachment of your sister to Mr. Willoughby and it was, though from a different cause, no less unfortunate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75496,\n            \"She was married \\u2014 married against her inclination to my brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75508,\n            \"Her fortune was large, and our family estate much encumbered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75547,\n            \"My brother did not deserve her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75554,\n            \"he did not even love her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75657,\n            \"I was banished to the house of a relation far distant, and she was allowed no liberty, no society, no amusement, till my father\\u2019s point was gained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75751,\n            \"My brother had no regard for her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75759,\n            \"his pleasures were not what they ought to have been, and from the first he treated her unkindly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76335,\n            \"What I endured in so beholding her \\u2014 but I have no right to wound your feelings by attempting to describe it \\u2014 I have pained you too much already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76481,\n            \"\\u201cYour sister, I hope, cannot be offended,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cby the resemblance I have fancied between her and my poor disgraced relation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76522,\n            \"and had the natural sweet disposition of the one been guarded by a firmer mind, or a happier marriage, she might have been all that you will live to see the other be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76612,\n            \"She left to my care her only child, a little girl, the offspring of her first guilty connection, who was then about three years old.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76665,\n            \"and gladly would I have discharged it in the strictest sense, by watching over her education myself, had the nature of our situations allowed it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76712,\n            \"I saw her there whenever I could, and after the death of my brother, (which happened about five years ago, and which left to me the possession of the family property,) she visited me at Delaford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76755,\n            \"I called her a distant relation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77781,\n            \"attended too with the assurance of her expecting material advantage to Marianne, from the communication of what had passed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77940,\n            \"Eliza had confessed to me, though most reluctantly, the name of her lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78189,\n            \"Not that Marianne appeared to distrust the truth of any part of it, for she listened to it all with the most steady and submissive attention, made neither objection nor remark, attempted no vindication of Willoughby, and seemed to show by her tears that she felt it to be impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78523,\n            \"to express her anxious solicitude for Marianne, and entreat she would bear up with fortitude under this misfortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78543,\n            \"Bad indeed must the nature of Marianne\\u2019s affliction be, when her mother could talk of fortitude!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78585,\n            \"Against the interest of her own individual comfort, Mrs. Dashwood had determined that it would be better for Marianne to be any where, at that time, than at Barton, where every thing within her view would be bringing back the past in the strongest and most afflicting manner, by constantly placing Willoughby before her, such as she had always seen him there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78701,\n            \"A variety of occupations, of objects, and of company, which could not be procured at Barton, would be inevitable there, and might yet, she hoped, cheat Marianne, at times, into some interest beyond herself, and even into some amusement, much as the ideas of both might now be spurned by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78764,\n            \"From all danger of seeing Willoughby again, her mother considered her to be at least equally safe in town as in the country, since his acquaintance must now be dropped by all who called themselves her friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78943,\n            \"Marianne had promised to be guided by her mother\\u2019s opinion, and she submitted to it therefore without opposition, though it proved perfectly different from what she wished and expected, though she felt it to be entirely wrong, formed on mistaken grounds, and that by requiring her longer continuance in London it deprived her of the only possible alleviation of her wretchedness, the personal sympathy of her mother, and doomed her to such society and such scenes as must prevent her ever knowing a moment\\u2019s rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79064,\n            \"and Elinor, on the other hand, suspecting that it would not be in her power to avoid Edward entirely, comforted herself by thinking, that though their longer stay would therefore militate against her own happiness, it would be better for Marianne than an immediate return into Devonshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79137,\n            \"Marianne, though without knowing it herself, reaped all its advantage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79488,\n            \"She could soon tell at what coachmaker\\u2019s the new carriage was building, by what painter Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s portrait was drawn, and at what warehouse Miss Grey\\u2019s clothes might be seen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79743,\n            \"and having thus supported the dignity of her own sex, and spoken her decided censure of what was wrong in the other, she thought herself at liberty to attend to the interest of her own assemblies, and therefore determined (though rather against the opinion of Sir John) that as Mrs. Willoughby would at once be a woman of elegance and fortune, to leave her card with her as soon as she married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80141,\n            \"She had taken care to have the intelligence conveyed to herself, as soon as it was known that the ceremony was over, as she was desirous that Marianne should not receive the first notice of it from the public papers, which she saw her eagerly examining every morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81044,\n            \"\\u201cI am sorry she is not well \\u2014\\u201dfor Marianne had left the room on their arrival.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81648,\n            \"Marianne was spared from the troublesome feelings of contempt and resentment, on this impertinent examination of their features, and on the puppyism of his manner in deciding on all the different horrors of the different toothpick-cases presented to his inspection, by remaining unconscious of it all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81700,\n            \"for she was as well able to collect her thoughts within herself, and be as ignorant of what was passing around her, in Mr. Gray\\u2019s shop, as in her own bedroom.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84424,\n            \"She was as handsome a girl last September, as I ever saw;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84504,\n            \"I question whether Marianne _ now _, will marry a man worth more than five or six hundred a-year, at the utmost, and I am very much deceived if _ you _ do not do better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87597,\n            \"\\u201d And so saying, she took the screens out of her sister-in-law\\u2019s hands, to admire them herself as they ought to be admired.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87703,\n            \"but Colonel Brandon\\u2019s eyes, as they were fixed on Marianne, declared that he noticed only what was amiable in it, the affectionate heart which could not bear to see a sister slighted in the smallest point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87754,\n            \"The cold insolence of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s general behaviour to her sister, seemed, to her, to foretell such difficulties and distresses to Elinor, as her own wounded heart taught her to think of with horror;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87796,\n            \"and urged by a strong impulse of affectionate sensibility, she moved after a moment, to her sister\\u2019s chair, and putting one arm round her neck, and one cheek close to hers, said in a low, but eager, voice, \\u201cDear, dear Elinor, don\\u2019t mind them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88037,\n            \"\\u201d said her brother to Colonel Brandon, in a low voice, as soon as he could secure his attention: \\u201cShe has not such good health as her sister, \\u2014 she is very nervous, \\u2014 she has not Elinor\\u2019s constitution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88115,\n            \"You would not think it perhaps, but Marianne _ was _ remarkably handsome a few months ago;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89771,\n            \"for she soon afterwards felt herself so heroically disposed as to determine, under pretence of fetching Marianne, to leave the others by themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89858,\n            \"for Marianne\\u2019s joy hurried her into the drawing-room immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89983,\n            \"while Marianne was looking with the most speaking tenderness, sometimes at Edward and sometimes at Elinor, regretting only that their delight in each other should be checked by Lucy\\u2019s unwelcome presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90019,\n            \"Edward was the first to speak, and it was to notice Marianne\\u2019s altered looks, and express his fear of her not finding London agree with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90286,\n            \"But Marianne, who saw his agitation, and could easily trace it to whatever cause best pleased herself, was perfectly satisfied, and soon talked of something else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90836,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne looked at her steadily, and said, \\u201cYou know, Elinor, that this is a kind of talking which I cannot bear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90923,\n            \"and Elinor dared not follow her to say more, for bound as she was by her promise of secrecy to Lucy, she could give no information that would convince Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91301,\n            \"Though nothing could be more polite than Lady Middleton\\u2019s behaviour to Elinor and Marianne, she did not really like them at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91476,\n            \"Would either of them only have given her a full and minute account of the whole affair between Marianne and Mr. Willoughby, she would have thought herself amply rewarded for the sacrifice of the best place by the fire after dinner, which their arrival occasioned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91532,\n            \"for though she often threw out expressions of pity for her sister to Elinor, and more than once dropt a reflection on the inconstancy of beaux before Marianne, no effect was produced, but a look of indifference from the former, or of disgust in the latter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92211,\n            \"Marianne had now been brought by degrees, so much into the habit of going out every day, that it was become a matter of indifference to her, whether she went or not: and she prepared quietly and mechanically for every evening\\u2019s engagement, though without expecting the smallest amusement from any, and very often without knowing, till the last moment, where it was to take her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92358,\n            \"was never easy till she knew the price of every part of Marianne\\u2019s dress;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92375,\n            \"could have guessed the number of her gowns altogether with better judgment than Marianne herself, and was not without hopes of finding out before they parted, how much her washing cost per week, and how much she had every year to spend upon herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94216,\n            \"at the same time, however, slyly suspecting that another year would make the invitation needless, by bringing Elinor to town as Colonel Brandon\\u2019s wife, and Marianne as _ their _ visitor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96201,\n            \"that Mrs. Jennings (as she had of late often hoped might be the case) had ceased to imagine her at all attached to Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96417,\n            \"No time was to be lost in undeceiving her, in making her acquainted with the real truth, and in endeavouring to bring her to hear it talked of by others, without betraying that she felt any uneasiness for her sister, or any resentment against Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96476,\n            \"\\u2014 She was going to remove what she really believed to be her sister\\u2019s chief consolation, \\u2014 to give such particulars of Edward as she feared would ruin him for ever in her good opinion,-and to make Marianne, by a resemblance in their situations, which to _ her _ fancy would seem strong, feel all her own disappointment over again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96652,\n            \"_ That _ belonged rather to the hearer, for Marianne listened with horror, and cried excessively.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96671,\n            \"Elinor was to be the comforter of others in her own distresses, no less than in theirs;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96742,\n            \"and acknowledging as Elinor did, that she _ had _ loved him most sincerely, could she feel less than herself!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96821,\n            \"and Elinor left her to be convinced that it was so, by that which only could convince her, a better knowledge of mankind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96916,\n            \"The first question on her side, which led to farther particulars, was, \\u2014 \\u201cHow long has this been known to you, Elinor?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96979,\n            \"\\u201d At these words, Marianne\\u2019s eyes expressed the astonishment which her lips could not utter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97170,\n            \"\\u201cI have very often wished to undeceive yourself and my mother,\\u201dadded Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97391,\n            \"And after all, Marianne, after all that is bewitching in the idea of a single and constant attachment, and all that can be said of one\\u2019s happiness depending entirely on any particular person, it is not meant \\u2014 it is not fit \\u2014 it is not possible that it should be so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97490,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf such is your way of thinking,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cif the loss of what is most valued is so easily to be made up by something else, your resolution, your self-command, are, perhaps, a little less to be wondered at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97559,\n            \"You do not suppose that I have ever felt much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97570,\n            \"For four months, Marianne, I have had all this hanging on my mind, without being at liberty to speak of it to a single creature;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97949,\n            \"Elinor,\\u201dshe cried, \\u201cyou have made me hate myself for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98047,\n            \"In such a frame of mind as she was now in, Elinor had no difficulty in obtaining from her whatever promise she required;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98072,\n            \"and at her request, Marianne engaged never to speak of the affair to any one with the least appearance of bitterness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98135,\n            \"but where Marianne felt that she had injured, no reparation could be too much for her to make.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98552,\n            \"for otherwise we both wished very much to have invited you and Marianne to be with us, while your kind friend there, was attending her daughter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99018,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell may you wonder, Marianne,\\u201dreplied her brother, \\u201cat the obstinacy which could resist such arguments as these.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100124,\n            \"and as her vehemence made reserve impossible in Elinor, and unnecessary in Mrs. Jennings, they all joined in a very spirited critique upon the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100389,\n            \"she felt it with all the pain of continual self-reproach, regretted most bitterly that she had never exerted herself before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100600,\n            \"but Marianne, who knew that the Willoughbys were again in town, and had a constant dread of meeting them, chose rather to stay at home, than venture into so public a place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103053,\n            \"but as Elinor wished to spread as little as possible intelligence that had in the first place been so unfairly obtained, she confined herself to the brief repetition of such simple particulars, as she felt assured that Lucy, for the sake of her own consequence, would choose to have known.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103786,\n            \"\\u201d As soon as Elinor had finished it, she performed what she concluded to be its writer\\u2019s real design, by placing it in the hands of Mrs. Jennings, who read it aloud with many comments of satisfaction and praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103982,\n            \"The Miss Dashwoods had now been rather more than two months in town, and Marianne\\u2019s impatience to be gone increased every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104039,\n            \"Elinor was hardly less anxious than herself for their removal, and only so much less bent on its being effected immediately, as that she was conscious of the difficulties of so long a journey, which Marianne could not be brought to acknowledge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104085,\n            \"She began, however, seriously to turn her thoughts towards its accomplishment, and had already mentioned their wishes to their kind hostess, who resisted them with all the eloquence of her good-will, when a plan was suggested, which, though detaining them from home yet a few weeks longer, appeared to Elinor altogether much more eligible than any other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104257,\n            \"When she told Marianne what she had done, however, her first reply was not very auspicious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104350,\n            \"No, Elinor, you cannot expect me to go there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104516,\n            \"As Marianne\\u2019s affection for her mother was sincere, it must triumph with little difficulty, over the imaginary evils she had started.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104569,\n            \"Elinor was grateful for the attention, but it could not alter her design;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104609,\n            \"\\u2014 and Marianne found some relief in drawing up a statement of the hours that were yet to divide her from Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104822,\n            \"The effect of his discourse on the lady too, could not escape her observation, for though she was too honorable to listen, and had even changed her seat, on purpose that she might _ not _ hear, to one close by the piano forte on which Marianne was playing, she could not keep herself from seeing that Elinor changed colour, attended with agitation, and was too intent on what he said to pursue her employment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104906,\n            \"Still farther in confirmation of her hopes, in the interval of Marianne\\u2019s turning from one lesson to another, some words of the Colonel\\u2019s inevitably reached her ear, in which he seemed to be apologising for the badness of his house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104985,\n            \"What Elinor said in reply she could not distinguish, but judged from the motion of her lips, that she did not think _ that _ any material objection;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105030,\n            \"They then talked on for a few minutes longer without her catching a syllable, when another lucky stop in Marianne\\u2019s performance brought her these words in the Colonel\\u2019s calm voice, \\u2014 \\u201cI am afraid it cannot take place very soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105738,\n            \"but whatever minor feelings less pure, less pleasing, might have a share in that emotion, her esteem for the general benevolence, and her gratitude for the particular friendship, which together prompted Colonel Brandon to this act, were strongly felt, and warmly expressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106018,\n            \"an evil which Elinor, as Mrs. Jennings had supposed her to do, made very light of, at least as far as regarded its size.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106318,\n            \"but after this narration of what really passed between Colonel Brandon and Elinor, while they stood at the window, the gratitude expressed by the latter on their parting, may perhaps appear in general, not less reasonably excited, nor less properly worded than if it had arisen from an offer of marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106378,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, sagaciously smiling, as soon as the gentleman had withdrawn, \\u201cI do not ask you what the Colonel has been saying to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106689,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou mean to go to Delaford after them I suppose,\\u201dsaid Elinor, with a faint smile.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106892,\n            \"and besides, you must long to tell your sister all about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106917,\n            \"\\u201cCertainly, ma\\u2019am, I shall tell Marianne of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107341,\n            \"but returning again in a moment, \\u201cI have just been thinking of Betty\\u2019s sister, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113297,\n            \"She had no such object for her lingering thoughts to fix on, she left no creature behind, from whom it would give her a moment\\u2019s regret to be divided for ever, she was pleased to be free herself from the persecution of Lucy\\u2019s friendship, she was grateful for bringing her sister away unseen by Willoughby since his marriage, and she looked forward with hope to what a few months of tranquility at Barton might do towards restoring Marianne\\u2019s peace of mind, and confirming her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113401,\n            \"The second day brought them into the cherished, or the prohibited, county of Somerset, for as such was it dwelt on by turns in Marianne\\u2019s imagination;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113911,\n            \"The morning was fine and dry, and Marianne, in her plan of employment abroad, had not calculated for any change of weather during their stay at Cleveland.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114092,\n            \"and Marianne, who had the knack of finding her way in every house to the library, however it might be avoided by the family in general, soon procured herself a book.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114610,\n            \"\\u2014 His behaviour to her in this, as well as in every other particular, his open pleasure in meeting her after an absence of only ten days, his readiness to converse with her, and his deference for her opinion, might very well justify Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s persuasion of his attachment, and would have been enough, perhaps, had not Elinor still, as from the first, believed Marianne his real favourite, to make her suspect it herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114753,\n            \"\\u2014 and while his looks of anxious solicitude on Marianne\\u2019s feeling, in her head and throat, the beginning of a heavy cold, because unexpressed by words, entirely escaped the latter lady\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114813,\n            \"Two delightful twilight walks on the third and fourth evenings of her being there, not merely on the dry gravel of the shrubbery, but all over the grounds, and especially in the most distant parts of them, where there was something more of wildness than in the rest, where the trees were the oldest, and the grass was the longest and wettest, had \\u2014 assisted by the still greater imprudence of sitting in her wet shoes and stockings \\u2014 given Marianne a cold so violent as, though for a day or two trifled with or denied, would force itself by increasing ailments on the concern of every body, and the notice of herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115017,\n            \"Marianne got up the next morning at her usual time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115097,\n            \"and when, at last, she went early to bed, more and more indisposed, Colonel Brandon was only astonished at her sister\\u2019s composure, who, though attending and nursing her the whole day, against Marianne\\u2019s inclination, and forcing proper medicines on her at night, trusted, like Marianne, to the certainty and efficacy of sleep, and felt no real alarm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115186,\n            \"and when Marianne, after persisting in rising, confessed herself unable to sit up, and returned voluntarily to her bed, Elinor was very ready to adopt Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s advice, of sending for the Palmers\\u2019 apothecary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115295,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, who had been inclined from the first to think Marianne\\u2019s complaint more serious than Elinor, now looked very grave on Mr. Harris\\u2019 s report, and confirming Charlotte\\u2019s fears and caution, urged the necessity of her immediate removal with her infant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115467,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, however, with a kindness of heart which made Elinor really love her, declared her resolution of not stirring from Cleveland as long as Marianne remained ill, and of endeavouring, by her own attentive care, to supply to her the place of the mother she had taken her from;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115560,\n            \"Poor Marianne, languid and low from the nature of her malady, and feeling herself universally ill, could no longer hope that tomorrow would find her recovered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115993,\n            \"She knew not that she had been the means of sending the owners of Cleveland away, in about seven days from the time of their arrival.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116035,\n            \"and as it gave her likewise no concern, she never mentioned her name.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116115,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings had determined very early in the seizure that Marianne would never get over it, and Colonel Brandon, who was chiefly of use in listening to Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s forebodings, was not in a state of mind to resist their influence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116185,\n            \"but the many hours of each day in which he was left entirely alone, were but too favourable for the admission of every melancholy idea, and he could not expel from his mind the persuasion that he should see Marianne no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116491,\n            \"her maid, who was one of the principal nurses, was recreating herself in the housekeeper\\u2019s room, and Elinor remained alone with Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116530,\n            \"and her sister, who watched, with unremitting attention her continual change of posture, and heard the frequent but inarticulate sounds of complaint which passed her lips, was almost wishing to rouse her from so painful a slumber, when Marianne, suddenly awakened by some accidental noise in the house, started hastily up, and, with feverish wildness, cried out, \\u2014 \\u201cIs mama coming?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116655,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut she must not go round by London,\\u201dcried Marianne, in the same hurried manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116722,\n            \"and Marianne, still talking wildly of mama, her alarm increased so rapidly, as to determine her on sending instantly for Mr. Harris, and despatching a messenger to Barton for her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117276,\n            \"Marianne\\u2019s ideas were still, at intervals, fixed incoherently on her mother, and whenever she mentioned her name, it gave a pang to the heart of poor Elinor, who, reproaching herself for having trifled with so many days of illness, and wretched for some immediate relief, fancied that all relief might soon be in vain, that every thing had been delayed too long, and pictured to herself her suffering mother arriving too late to see this darling child, or to see her rational.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117675,\n            \"\\u2014 and as for their mother, when Mrs. Jennings considered that Marianne might probably be to _ her _ what Charlotte was to herself, her sympathy in _ her _ sufferings was very sincere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117860,\n            \"and in this state she continued till noon, scarcely stirring from her sister\\u2019s bed, her thoughts wandering from one image of grief, one suffering friend to another, and her spirits oppressed to the utmost by the conversation of Mrs. Jennings, who scrupled not to attribute the severity and danger of this attack to the many weeks of previous indisposition which Marianne\\u2019s disappointment had brought on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118236,\n            \"Marianne was in every respect materially better, and he declared her entirely out of danger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118327,\n            \"Marianne restored to life, health, friends, and to her doting mother, was an idea to fill her heart with sensations of exquisite comfort, and expand it in fervent gratitude;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118433,\n            \"The possibility of a relapse would of course, in some moments, occur to remind her of what anxiety was \\u2014 but when she saw, on her frequent and minute examination, that every symptom of recovery continued, and saw Marianne at six o\\u2019clock sink into a quiet, steady, and to all appearance comfortable, sleep, she silenced every doubt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118583,\n            \"At seven o\\u2019clock, leaving Marianne still sweetly asleep, she joined Mrs. Jennings in the drawing-room to tea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118653,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings would have persuaded her, at its conclusion, to take some rest before her mother\\u2019s arrival, and allow _ her _ to take her place by Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120016,\n            \"to open my whole heart to you, and by convincing you, that though I have been always a blockhead, I have not been always a rascal, to obtain something like forgiveness from Ma \\u2014 from your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121863,\n            \"My affection for Marianne, my thorough conviction of her attachment to me \\u2014 it was all insufficient to outweigh that dread of poverty, or get the better of those false ideas of the necessity of riches, which I was naturally inclined to feel, and expensive society had increased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122011,\n            \"To see Marianne, I felt, would be dreadful, and I even doubted whether I could see her again, and keep to my resolution.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122913,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMarianne\\u2019s note, by assuring me that I was still as dear to her as in former days, \\u2014 that in spite of the many, many weeks we had been separated, she was as constant in her own feelings, and as full of faith in the constancy of mine as ever, \\u2014 awakened all my remorse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123150,\n            \"I sent no answer to Marianne, intending by that to preserve myself from her farther notice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124237,\n            \"And after all, what did it signify to my character in the opinion of Marianne and her friends, in what language my answer was couched?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124346,\n            \"\\u2019 Such were my reasonings, as, in a sort of desperate carelessness, I copied my wife\\u2019s words, and parted with the last relics of Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124565,\n            \"To treat her with unkindness, to speak of her slightingly is no atonement to Marianne \\u2014 nor can I suppose it a relief to your own conscience.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125059,\n            \"As bluntly as he could speak it, therefore, he told me that Marianne Dashwood was dying of a putrid fever at Cleveland \\u2014 a letter that morning received from Mrs. Jennings declared her danger most imminent \\u2014 the Palmers are all gone off in a fright, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126197,\n            \"The past, the present, the future, Willoughby\\u2019s visit, Marianne\\u2019s safety, and her mother\\u2019s expected arrival, threw her altogether into an agitation of spirits which kept off every indication of fatigue, and made her only fearful of betraying herself to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126333,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, whose terror as they drew near the house had produced almost the conviction of Marianne\\u2019s being no more, had no voice to inquire after her, no voice even for Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126510,\n            \"As soon as Mrs. Dashwood had recovered herself, to see Marianne was her first desire;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126553,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s delight, as she saw what each felt in the meeting, was only checked by an apprehension of its robbing Marianne of farther sleep: but Mrs. Dashwood could be calm, could be even prudent, when the life of a child was at stake, and Marianne, satisfied in knowing her mother was near her, and conscious of being too weak for conversation, submitted readily to the silence and quiet prescribed by every nurse around her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126762,\n            \"She dreaded the performance of it, dreaded what its effect on Marianne might be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126801,\n            \"Then, remembering Colonel Brandon, reproved herself, felt that to _ his _ sufferings and _ his _ constancy far more than to his rival\\u2019s, the reward of her sister was due, and wished any thing rather than Mrs. Willoughby\\u2019s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126876,\n            \"for so great was her uneasiness about Marianne, that she had already determined to set out for Cleveland on that very day, without waiting for any further intelligence, and had so far settled her journey before his arrival, that the Careys were then expected every moment to fetch Margaret away, as her mother was unwilling to take her where there might be infection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126945,\n            \"Marianne continued to mend every day, and the brilliant cheerfulness of Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s looks and spirits proved her to be, as she repeatedly declared herself, one of the happiest women in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127044,\n            \"Marianne was restored to her from a danger in which, as she now began to feel, her own mistaken judgment in encouraging the unfortunate attachment to Willoughby, had contributed to place her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127221,\n            \"And I believe Marianne will be the most happy with him of the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127348,\n            \"I saw that it equalled my own, and he perhaps, thinking that mere friendship, as the world now goes, would not justify so warm a sympathy \\u2014 or rather, not thinking at all, I suppose \\u2014 giving way to irresistible feelings, made me acquainted with his earnest, tender, constant, affection for Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127471,\n            \"\\u201cHis regard for her, infinitely surpassing anything that Willoughby ever felt or feigned, as much more warm, as more sincere or constant \\u2014 which ever we are to call it \\u2014 has subsisted through all the knowledge of dear Marianne\\u2019s unhappy prepossession for that worthless young man!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127742,\n            \"and so highly do _ I _ value and esteem him, that if Marianne can be happy with him, I shall be as ready as yourself to think our connection the greatest blessing to us in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127991,\n            \"He thinks Marianne\\u2019s affection too deeply rooted for any change in it under a great length of time, and even supposing her heart again free, is too diffident of himself to believe, that with such a difference of age and disposition he could ever attach her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128174,\n            \"but her mother, without waiting for her assent, continued, \\u201cAnd his manners, the Colonel\\u2019s manners are not only more pleasing to me than Willoughby\\u2019s ever were, but they are of a kind I well know to be more solidly attaching to Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128267,\n            \"I am very sure myself, that had Willoughby turned out as really amiable, as he has proved himself the contrary, Marianne would yet never have been so happy with _ him _ as she will be with Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128526,\n            \"Marianne\\u2019s illness, though weakening in its kind, had not been long enough to make her recovery slow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128628,\n            \"His emotion on entering the room, in seeing her altered looks, and in receiving the pale hand which she immediately held out to him, was such, as, in Elinor\\u2019s conjecture, must arise from something more than his affection for Marianne, or the consciousness of its being known to others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128687,\n            \"and she soon discovered in his melancholy eye and varying complexion as he looked at her sister, the probable recurrence of many past scenes of misery to his mind, brought back by that resemblance between Marianne and Eliza already acknowledged, and now strengthened by the hollow eye, the sickly skin, the posture of reclining weakness, and the warm acknowledgment of peculiar obligation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128756,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, not less watchful of what passed than her daughter, but with a mind very differently influenced, and therefore watching to very different effect, saw nothing in the Colonel\\u2019s behaviour but what arose from the most simple and self-evident sensations, while in the actions and words of Marianne she persuaded herself to think that something more than gratitude already dawned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128828,\n            \"At the end of another day or two, Marianne growing visibly stronger every twelve hours, Mrs. Dashwood, urged equally by her own and her daughter\\u2019s wishes, began to talk of removing to Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129025,\n            \"and Marianne, after taking so particular and lengthened a leave of Mrs. Jennings, one so earnestly grateful, so full of respect and kind wishes as seemed due to her own heart from a secret acknowledgment of past inattention, and bidding Colonel Brandon farewell with a cordiality of a friend, was carefully assisted by him into the carriage, of which he seemed anxious that she should engross at least half.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129169,\n            \"The Dashwoods were two days on the road, and Marianne bore her journey on both, without essential fatigue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129190,\n            \"Every thing that the most zealous affection, the most solicitous care could do to render her comfortable, was the office of each watchful companion, and each found their reward in her bodily ease, and her calmness of spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129376,\n            \"and when she saw, as she assisted Marianne from the carriage, that she had been crying, she saw only an emotion too natural in itself to raise any thing less tender than pity, and in its unobtrusiveness entitled to praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129441,\n            \"for no sooner had they entered their common sitting-room, than Marianne turned her eyes around it with a look of resolute firmness, as if determined at once to accustom herself to the sight of every object with which the remembrance of Willoughby could be connected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130004,\n            \"Her smile however changed to a sigh when she remembered that promise to Willoughby was yet unfulfilled, and feared she had that to communicate which might again unsettle the mind of Marianne, and ruin at least for a time this fair prospect of busy tranquillity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130140,\n            \"and Marianne, leaning on Elinor\\u2019s arm, was authorised to walk as long as she could without fatigue, in the lane before the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130169,\n            \"The sisters set out at a pace, slow as the feebleness of Marianne in an exercise hitherto untried since her illness required;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130193,\n            \"and they had advanced only so far beyond the house as to admit a full view of the hill, the important hill behind, when pausing with her eyes turned towards it, Marianne calmly said, \\u2014 \\u201cThere, exactly there,\\u201d\\u2014 pointing with one hand, \\u201con that projecting mound, \\u2014 there I fell;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130345,\n            \"\\u201cAs for regret,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cI have done with that, as far as _ he _ is concerned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130615,\n            \"She was debating within herself on the eligibility of beginning her story directly, or postponing it till Marianne were in stronger health;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130651,\n            \"\\u201cI am not wishing him too much good,\\u201dsaid Marianne at last with a sigh, \\u201cwhen I wish his secret reflections may be no more unpleasant than my own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131401,\n            \"I have laid down my plan, and if I am capable of adhering to it \\u2014 my feelings shall be governed and my temper improved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131776,\n            \"her hand, unknowingly to herself, closely pressed her sister\\u2019s, and tears covered her cheeks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131864,\n            \"As soon as they entered the house, Marianne with a kiss of gratitude and these two words just articulate through her tears, \\u201cTell mama,\\u201dwithdrew from her sister and walked slowly up stairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132214,\n            \"In the evening, when they were all three together, Marianne began voluntarily to speak of him again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132342,\n            \"Marianne slowly continued, \\u2014 \\u201cIt is a great relief to me \\u2014 what Elinor told me this morning \\u2014 I have now heard exactly what I wished to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132542,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne sighed, and repeated, \\u201cI wish for no change.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132870,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne\\u2019s lips quivered, and she repeated the word \\u201cSelfish?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133185,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have not a doubt of it,\\u201dsaid Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133240,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne would not let her proceed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133404,\n            \"Elinor, according to her expectation, saw on the two or three following days, that Marianne did not continue to gain strength as she had done;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133720,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne gave a violent start, fixed her eyes upon Elinor, saw her turning pale, and fell back in her chair in hysterics.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133747,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, whose eyes, as she answered the servant\\u2019s inquiry, had intuitively taken the same direction, was shocked to perceive by Elinor\\u2019s countenance how much she really suffered, and a moment afterwards, alike distressed by Marianne\\u2019s situation, knew not on which child to bestow her principal attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133809,\n            \"The servant, who saw only that Miss Marianne was taken ill, had sense enough to call one of the maids, who, with Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s assistance, supported her into the other room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133849,\n            \"By that time, Marianne was rather better, and her mother leaving her to the care of Margaret and the maid, returned to Elinor, who, though still much disordered, had so far recovered the use of her reason and voice as to be just beginning an inquiry of Thomas, as to the source of his intelligence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134043,\n            \"so I took off my hat, and she knew me and called to me, and inquired after you, ma\\u2019am, and the young ladies, especially Miss Marianne, and bid me I should give her compliments and Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s, their best compliments and service, and how sorry they was they had not time to come on and see you, but they was in a great hurry to go forwards, for they was going further down for a little while, but howsever, when they come back, they\\u2019d make sure to come and see you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134723,\n            \"and justly concluded that every thing had been expressly softened at the time, to spare her from an increase of unhappiness, suffering as she then had suffered for Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134830,\n            \"\\u2014 that Marianne\\u2019s affliction, because more acknowledged, more immediately before her, had too much engrossed her tenderness, and led her away to forget that in Elinor she might have a daughter suffering almost as much, certainly with less self-provocation, and greater fortitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135603,\n            \"She saw her mother and Marianne change colour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136096,\n            \"\\u2014 but her mother and Marianne both turned their eyes on him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136154,\n            \"\\u201d was repeated by Marianne and her mother in an accent of the utmost amazement;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137446,\n            \"and her joy, though sincere as her love for her sister, was of a kind to give her neither spirits nor language.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140190,\n            \"A three weeks\\u2019 residence at Delaford, where, in his evening hours at least, he had little to do but to calculate the disproportion between thirty-six and seventeen, brought him to Barton in a temper of mind which needed all the improvement in Marianne\\u2019s looks, all the kindness of her welcome, and all the encouragement of her mother\\u2019s language, to make it cheerful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140753,\n            \"I cannot get him out of my head, but you must send for him to Barton, and Miss Marianne must try to comfort him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141406,\n            \"\\u201cAnd if they really _ do _ interest themselves,\\u201dsaid Marianne, in her new character of candour, \\u201cin bringing about a reconciliation, I shall think that even John and Fanny are not entirely without merit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142269,\n            \"They had in fact nothing to wish for, but the marriage of Colonel Brandon and Marianne, and rather better pasturage for their cows.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142469,\n            \"And though, perhaps, Marianne may not seem exactly the person to attract him, yet I think it would altogether be advisable for you to have them now frequently staying with you, for as Colonel Brandon seems a great deal at home, nobody can tell what may happen;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142522,\n            \"for, when people are much thrown together, and see little of anybody else, \\u2014 and it will always be in your power to set her off to advantage, and so forth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142558,\n            \"In short, you may as well give her a chance: you understand me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143561,\n            \"for her wish of bringing Marianne and Colonel Brandon together was hardly less earnest, though rather more liberal than what John had expressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143640,\n            \"They each felt his sorrows, and their own obligations, and Marianne, by general consent, was to be the reward of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143986,\n            \"and that Marianne found her own happiness in forming his, was equally the persuasion and delight of each observing friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144050,\n            \"and his punishment was soon afterwards complete in the voluntary forgiveness of Mrs. Smith, who, by stating his marriage with a woman of character, as the source of her clemency, gave him reason for believing that had he behaved with honour towards Marianne, he might at once have been happy and rich.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144239,\n            \"For Marianne, however, in spite of his incivility in surviving her loss, he always retained that decided regard which interested him in every thing that befell her, and made her his secret standard of perfection in woman;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144323,\n            \"and fortunately for Sir John and Mrs. Jennings, when Marianne was taken from them, Margaret had reached an age highly suitable for dancing, and not very ineligible for being supposed to have a lover.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144380,\n            \"and among the merits and the happiness of Elinor and Marianne, let it not be ranked as the least considerable, that though sisters, and living almost within sight of each other, they could live without disagreement between themselves, or producing coolness between their husbands.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 17]\": [\n        [\n            47028,\n            \"But really I never understood that you were at all connected with that family, and therefore I am a little surprised, I confess, at so serious an inquiry into her character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47100,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars is certainly nothing to me at present \\u2014 but the time _ may _ come \\u2014 how soon it will come must depend upon herself \\u2014 when we may be very intimately connected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51798,\n            \"And we will make the dear little love some amends for her disappointment to-morrow, and then I hope she will not much mind it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52911,\n            \"Mr. Ferrars, I believe, is entirely dependent on his mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53506,\n            \"But Mrs. Ferrars is a very headstrong proud woman, and in her first fit of anger upon hearing it, would very likely secure every thing to Robert, and the idea of that, for Edward\\u2019s sake, frightens away all my inclination for hasty measures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83719,\n            \"You may guess, after all these expenses, how very far we must be from being rich, and how acceptable Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s kindness is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85571,\n            \"for though she could now meet Edward\\u2019s mother without that strong anxiety which had once promised to attend such an introduction, though she could now see her with perfect indifference as to her opinion of herself, her desire of being in company with Mrs. Ferrars, her curiosity to know what she was like, was as lively as ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87043,\n            \"Elinor, having once delivered her opinion on William\\u2019s side, by which she offended Mrs. Ferrars and Fanny still more, did not see the necessity of enforcing it by any farther assertion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87629,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars looked exceedingly angry, and drawing herself up more stiffly than ever, pronounced in retort this bitter philippic, \\u201cMiss Morton is Lord Morton\\u2019s daughter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89165,\n            \"\\u201cI am sure I should have seen it in a moment, if Mrs. Ferrars had took a dislike to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89277,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was prevented from making any reply to this civil triumph, by the door\\u2019s being thrown open, the servant\\u2019s announcing Mr. Ferrars, and Edward\\u2019s immediately walking in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93560,\n            \"\\u2018 my dear Ferrars, do tell me how it is to be managed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95898,\n            \"and the best of all is, that he is gone back again to Harley Street, that he may be within call when Mrs. Ferrars is told of it, for she was sent for as soon as ever my cousins left the house, for your sister was sure _ she _ would be in hysterics too;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96013,\n            \"for I am sure Mrs. Ferrars may afford to do very well by her son, and though Lucy has next to nothing herself, she knows better than any body how to make the most of every thing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96054,\n            \"I dare say, if Mrs. Ferrars would only allow him five hundred a-year, she would make as good an appearance with it as any body else would with eight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98784,\n            \"All that Mrs. Ferrars could say to make him put an end to the engagement, assisted too as you may well suppose by my arguments, and Fanny\\u2019s entreaties, was of no avail.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99375,\n            \"We all wish her extremely happy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99382,\n            \"and Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s conduct throughout the whole, has been such as every conscientious, good mother, in like circumstances, would adopt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99442,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s heart wrung for the feelings of Edward, while braving his mother\\u2019s threats, for a woman who could not reward him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99489,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry to say, ma\\u2019am, in a most unhappy rupture: \\u2014 Edward is dismissed for ever from his mother\\u2019s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99520,\n            \"He left her house yesterday, but where he is gone, or whether he is still in town, I do not know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100074,\n            \"leaving the three ladies unanimous in their sentiments on the present occasion, as far at least as it regarded Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s conduct, the Dashwoods \\u2019, and Edward\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101979,\n            \"And just then I could not hear any more, for my cousin called from below to tell me Mrs. Richardson was come in her coach, and would take one of us to Kensington Gardens;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105291,\n            \"\\u201cI have heard,\\u201dsaid he, with great compassion, \\u201cof the injustice your friend Mr. Ferrars has suffered from his family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105319,\n            \"for if I understand the matter right, he has been entirely cast off by them for persevering in his engagement with a very deserving young woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105403,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars does not know what she may be doing \\u2014 what she may drive her son to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105444,\n            \"He is not a young man with whom one can be intimately acquainted in a short time, but I have seen enough of him to wish him well for his own sake, and as a friend of yours, I wish it still more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105500,\n            \"Will you be so good as to tell him that the living of Delaford, now just vacant, as I am informed by this day\\u2019s post, is his, if he think it worth his acceptance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107010,\n            \"and till I have written to Mr. Ferrars, I think it ought not to be mentioned to any body else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107079,\n            \"Why Mr. Ferrars was to have been written to about it in such a hurry, she could not immediately comprehend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107131,\n            \"Mr. Ferrars is to be the man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107238,\n            \"\\u201cColonel Brandon is so delicate a man, that he rather wished any one to announce his intentions to Mr. Ferrars than himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109312,\n            \"Sure you do not mean to persuade me that the Colonel only marries you for the sake of giving ten guineas to Mr. Ferrars!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109929,\n            \"It was now above a week since John Dashwood had called in Berkeley Street, and as since that time no notice had been taken by them of his wife\\u2019s indisposition, beyond one verbal enquiry, Elinor began to feel it necessary to pay her a visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110098,\n            \"The consequence was, that Elinor set out by herself to pay a visit, for which no one could really have less inclination, and to run the risk of a t\\u00eate-\\u00e0-t\\u00eate with a woman, whom neither of the others had so much reason to dislike.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110830,\n            \"\\u201cMrs. Ferrars,\\u201dadded he, lowering his voice to the tone becoming so important a subject, \\u201cknows nothing about it at present, and I believe it will be best to keep it entirely concealed from her as long as may be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110960,\n            \"She has done with her son, \\u2014 she cast him off for ever, and has made all those over whom she had any influence, cast him off likewise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111026,\n            \"She would not be so weak as to throw away the comfort of a child, and yet retain the anxiety of a parent!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111126,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars can never forget that Edward is her son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111144,\n            \"I should think it must nearly have escaped her memory by _ this _ time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111414,\n            \"I have good reason to think \\u2014 indeed I have it from the best authority, or I should not repeat it, for otherwise it would be very wrong to say any thing about it, \\u2014 but I have it from the very best authority, \\u2014 not that I ever precisely heard Mrs. Ferrars say it herself \\u2014 but her daughter _ did _, and I have it from her, \\u2014 that in short, whatever objections there might be against a certain \\u2014 a certain connection, you understand me, \\u2014 it would have been far preferable to her, \\u2014 it would not have given her half the vexation that _ this _ does.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111538,\n            \"I was exceedingly pleased to hear that Mrs. Ferrars considered it in that light;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134222,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWas Mr. Ferrars in the carriage with her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134325,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThey come straight from town, as Miss Lucy \\u2014 Mrs. Ferrars told me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140318,\n            \"Every thing was explained to him by Mrs. Dashwood, and he found fresh reason to rejoice in what he had done for Mr. Ferrars, since eventually it promoted the interest of Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140610,\n            \"came crying to me the day after, in a great fright for fear of Mrs. Ferrars, as well as not knowing how to get to Plymouth;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140791,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars was the most unfortunate of women \\u2014 poor Fanny had suffered agonies of sensibility \\u2014 and he considered the existence of each, under such a blow, with grateful wonder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140841,\n            \"Neither of them were ever again to be mentioned to Mrs. Ferrars;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140855,\n            \"and even, if she might hereafter be induced to forgive her son, his wife should never be acknowledged as her daughter, nor be permitted to appear in her presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140972,\n            \"He thus continued: \\u2014 \\u201cMrs. Ferrars has never yet mentioned Edward\\u2019s name, which does not surprise us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141080,\n            \"for we all know the tenderness of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s heart, and that she wishes for nothing so much as to be on good terms with her children.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141534,\n            \"After a proper resistance on the part of Mrs. Ferrars, just so violent and so steady as to preserve her from that reproach which she always seemed fearful of incurring, the reproach of being too amiable, Edward was admitted to her presence, and pronounced to be again her son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141733,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars at first reasonably endeavoured to dissuade him from marrying Miss Dashwood, by every argument in her power;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141815,\n            \"_ but when she found that, though perfectly admitting the truth of her representation, he was by no means inclined to be guided by it, she judged it wisest, from the experience of the past, to submit \\u2014 and therefore, after such an ungracious delay as she owed to her own dignity, and as served to prevent every suspicion of good-will, she issued her decree of consent to the marriage of Edward and Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141900,\n            \"What she would engage to do towards augmenting their income was next to be considered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141916,\n            \"and here it plainly appeared, that though Edward was now her only son, he was by no means her eldest;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142574,\n            \"\\u201d But though Mrs. Ferrars _ did _ come to see them, and always treated them with the make-believe of decent affection, they were never insulted by her real favour and preference.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 18]\": [\n        [\n            244,\n            \"By a former marriage, Mr. Henry Dashwood had one son: by his present lady, three daughters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            265,\n            \"The son, a steady respectable young man, was amply provided for by the fortune of his mother, which had been large, and half of which devolved on him on his coming of age.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            321,\n            \"To him therefore the succession to the Norland estate was not so really important as to his sisters;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            382,\n            \"for the remaining moiety of his first wife\\u2019s fortune was also secured to her child, and he had only a life-interest in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            565,\n            \"The whole was tied up for the benefit of this child, who, in occasional visits with his father and mother at Norland, had so far gained on the affections of his uncle, by such attractions as are by no means unusual in children of two or three years old;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            619,\n            \"an imperfect articulation, an earnest desire of having his own way, many cunning tricks, and a great deal of noise, as to outweigh all the value of all the attention which, for years, he had received from his niece and her daughters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            846,\n            \"Mr. John Dashwood had not the strong feelings of the rest of the family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            862,\n            \"but he was affected by a recommendation of such a nature at such a time, and he promised to do every thing in his power to make them comfortable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            893,\n            \"His father was rendered easy by such an assurance, and Mr. John Dashwood had then leisure to consider how much there might prudently be in his power to do for them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            927,\n            \"He was not an ill-disposed young man, unless to be rather cold hearted and rather selfish is to be ill-disposed: but he was, in general, well respected;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            977,\n            \"Had he married a more amiable woman, he might have been made still more respectable than he was: \\u2014 he might even have been made amiable himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1007,\n            \"for he was very young when he married, and very fond of his wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1023,\n            \"But Mrs. John Dashwood was a strong caricature of himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1043,\n            \"When he gave his promise to his father, he meditated within himself to increase the fortunes of his sisters by the present of a thousand pounds a-piece.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1083,\n            \"The prospect of four thousand a-year, in addition to his present income, besides the remaining half of his own mother\\u2019s fortune, warmed his heart, and made him feel capable of generosity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1123,\n            \"\\u201cYes, he would give them three thousand pounds: it would be liberal and handsome!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4665,\n            \"This circumstance was a growing attachment between her eldest girl and the brother of Mrs. John Dashwood, a gentleman-like and pleasing young man, who was introduced to their acquaintance soon after his sister\\u2019s establishment at Norland, and who had since spent the greatest part of his time there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4722,\n            \"Some mothers might have encouraged the intimacy from motives of interest, for Edward Ferrars was the eldest son of a man who had died very rich;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4750,\n            \"and some might have repressed it from motives of prudence, for, except a trifling sum, the whole of his fortune depended on the will of his mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4792,\n            \"It was enough for her that he appeared to be amiable, that he loved her daughter, and that Elinor returned the partiality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4865,\n            \"Edward Ferrars was not recommended to their good opinion by any peculiar graces of person or address.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4883,\n            \"He was not handsome, and his manners required intimacy to make them pleasing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4942,\n            \"But he was neither fitted by abilities nor disposition to answer the wishes of his mother and sister, who longed to see him distinguished \\u2014 as \\u2014 they hardly knew what.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4975,\n            \"They wanted him to make a fine figure in the world in some manner or other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4992,\n            \"His mother wished to interest him in political concerns, to get him into parliament, or to see him connected with some of the great men of the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5031,\n            \"but in the mean while, till one of these superior blessings could be attained, it would have quieted her ambition to see him driving a barouche.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5085,\n            \"Fortunately he had a younger brother who was more promising.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5096,\n            \"Edward had been staying several weeks in the house before he engaged much of Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5136,\n            \"She saw only that he was quiet and unobtrusive, and she liked him for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5153,\n            \"He did not disturb the wretchedness of her mind by ill-timed conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5168,\n            \"She was first called to observe and approve him farther, by a reflection which Elinor chanced one day to make on the difference between him and his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5198,\n            \"It was a contrast which recommended him most forcibly to her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5236,\n            \"I love him already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5241,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI think you will like him,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cwhen you know more of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5286,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou may esteem him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5309,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Dashwood now took pains to get acquainted with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5322,\n            \"Her manners were attaching, and soon banished his reserve.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5333,\n            \"She speedily comprehended all his merits;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5340,\n            \"the persuasion of his regard for Elinor perhaps assisted her penetration;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5352,\n            \"but she really felt assured of his worth: and even that quietness of manner, which militated against all her established ideas of what a young man\\u2019s address ought to be, was no longer uninteresting when she knew his heart to be warm and his temper affectionate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5404,\n            \"No sooner did she perceive any symptom of love in his behaviour to Elinor, than she considered their serious attachment as certain, and looked forward to their marriage as rapidly approaching.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5534,\n            \"I have the highest opinion in the world of Edward\\u2019s heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5653,\n            \"And besides all this, I am afraid, Mama, he has no real taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5728,\n            \"He admires as a lover, not as a connoisseur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5791,\n            \"mama, how spiritless, how tame was Edward\\u2019s manner in reading to us last night!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5886,\n            \"but you _ would _ give him Cowper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5895,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay, Mama, if he is not to be animated by Cowper!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5997,\n            \"He must have all Edward\\u2019s virtues, and his person and manners must ornament his goodness with every possible charm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6118,\n            \"He does not draw himself, indeed, but he has great pleasure in seeing the performances of other people, and I assure you he is by no means deficient in natural taste, though he has not had opportunities of improving it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6240,\n            \"but the kind of approbation which Elinor described as excited in him by the drawings of other people, was very far from that rapturous delight, which, in her opinion, could alone be called taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6533,\n            \"\\u201cOf his sense and his goodness,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cno one can, I think, be in doubt, who has seen him often enough to engage him in unreserved conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6592,\n            \"You know enough of him to do justice to his solid worth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6605,\n            \"But of his minuter propensities, as you call them you have from peculiar circumstances been kept more ignorant than myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6627,\n            \"He and I have been at times thrown a good deal together, while you have been wholly engrossed on the most affectionate principle by my mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6826,\n            \"When you tell me to love him as a brother, I shall no more see imperfection in his face, than I now do in his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7161,\n            \"and till his sentiments are fully known, you cannot wonder at my wishing to avoid any encouragement of my own partiality, by believing or calling it more than it is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7261,\n            \"and I am very much mistaken if Edward is not himself aware that there would be many difficulties in his way, if he were to wish to marry a woman who had not either a great fortune or high rank.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7528,\n            \"She knew that his mother neither behaved to him so as to make his home comfortable at present, nor to give him any assurance that he might form a home for himself, without strictly attending to her views for his aggrandizement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7591,\n            \"She was far from depending on that result of his preference of her, which her mother and sister still considered as certain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7615,\n            \"Nay, the longer they were together the more doubtful seemed the nature of his regard;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7938,\n            \"He earnestly pressed her, after giving the particulars of the house and garden, to come with her daughters to Barton Park, the place of his own residence, from whence she might judge, herself, whether Barton Cottage, for the houses were in the same parish, could, by any alteration, be made comfortable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8002,\n            \"He seemed really anxious to accommodate them and the whole of his letter was written in so friendly a style as could not fail of giving pleasure to his cousin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8184,\n            \"She instantly wrote Sir John Middleton her acknowledgment of his kindness, and her acceptance of his proposal;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8460,\n            \"\\u2014 Edward turned hastily towards her, on hearing this, and, in a voice of surprise and concern, which required no explanation to her, repeated, \\u201cDevonshire!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8663,\n            \"To separate Edward and Elinor was as far from being her object as ever;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8706,\n            \"Mr. John Dashwood told his mother again and again how exceedingly sorry he was that she had taken a house at such a distance from Norland as to prevent his being of any service to her in removing her furniture.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8757,\n            \"for the very exertion to which he had limited the performance of his promise to his father was by this arrangement rendered impracticable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10850,\n            \"Conversation however was not wanted, for Sir John was very chatty, and Lady Middleton had taken the wise precaution of bringing with her their eldest child, a fine little boy about six years old, by which means there was one subject always to be recurred to by the ladies in case of extremity, for they had to enquire his name and age, admire his beauty, and ask him questions which his mother answered for him, while he hung about her and held down his head, to the great surprise of her ladyship, who wondered at his being so shy before company, as he could make noise enough at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10991,\n            \"In the present case it took up ten minutes to determine whether the boy were most like his father or mother, and in what particular he resembled either, for of course every body differed, and every body was astonished at the opinion of the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12688,\n            \"She rather suspected it to be so, on the very first evening of their being together, from his listening so attentively while she sang to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12885,\n            \"and when its object was understood, she hardly knew whether most to laugh at its absurdity, or censure its impertinence, for she considered it as an unfeeling reflection on the colonel\\u2019s advanced years, and on his forlorn condition as an old bachelor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12934,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, who could not think a man five years younger than herself, so exceedingly ancient as he appeared to the youthful fancy of her daughter, ventured to clear Mrs. Jennings from the probability of wishing to throw ridicule on his age.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13212,\n            \"I know very well that Colonel Brandon is not old enough to make his friends yet apprehensive of losing him in the course of nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13282,\n            \"But if there should by any chance happen to be a woman who is single at seven and twenty, I should not think Colonel Brandon\\u2019s being thirty-five any objection to his marrying _ her _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13393,\n            \"In his marrying such a woman therefore there would be nothing unsuitable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13462,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt would be impossible, I know,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cto convince you that a woman of seven and twenty could feel for a man of thirty-five anything near enough to love, to make him a desirable companion to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13511,\n            \"But I must object to your dooming Colonel Brandon and his wife to the constant confinement of a sick chamber, merely because he chanced to complain yesterday (a very cold damp day) of a slight rheumatic feel in one of his shoulders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13694,\n            \"We have now been here almost a fortnight, and yet he does not come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13753,\n            \"On the contrary, if I have felt any anxiety at all on the subject, it has been in recollecting that he sometimes showed a want of pleasure and readiness in accepting my invitation, when I talked of his coming to Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13923,\n            \"In Edward\\u2019s farewell there was no distinction between Elinor and me: it was the good wishes of an affectionate brother to both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13949,\n            \"Twice did I leave them purposely together in the course of the last morning, and each time did he most unaccountably follow me out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13978,\n            \"And Elinor, in quitting Norland and Edward, cried not as I did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17568,\n            \"and secretly to congratulate herself on having gained two such sons-in-law as Edward and Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21870,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, yes, we can guess where he is;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21893,\n            \"He is the curate of the parish I dare say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28077,\n            \"I am persuaded that Mrs. Smith suspects his regard for Marianne, disapproves of it, (perhaps because she has other views for him,) and on that account is eager to get him away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31070,\n            \"In a few minutes they could distinguish him to be a gentleman;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31226,\n            \"They were soon within thirty yards of the gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31334,\n            \"but she dispersed her tears to smile on _ him _, and in her sister\\u2019s happiness forgot for a time her own disappointment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31361,\n            \"He dismounted, and giving his horse to his servant, walked back with them to Barton, whither he was purposely coming to visit them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31388,\n            \"He was welcomed by them all with great cordiality, but especially by Marianne, who showed more warmth of regard in her reception of him than even Elinor herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31419,\n            \"To Marianne, indeed, the meeting between Edward and her sister was but a continuation of that unaccountable coldness which she had often observed at Norland in their mutual behaviour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31451,\n            \"On Edward\\u2019s side, more particularly, there was a deficiency of all that a lover ought to look and say on such an occasion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31479,\n            \"He was confused, seemed scarcely sensible of pleasure in seeing them, looked neither rapturous nor gay, said little but what was forced from him by questions, and distinguished Elinor by no mark of affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32093,\n            \"They are a very respectable family, Mr. Ferrars;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32158,\n            \"and directing her attention to their visitor, endeavoured to support something like discourse with him, by talking of their present residence, its conveniences, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32319,\n            \"They had begun to fail him before he entered the house, and they were quite overcome by the captivating manners of Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32382,\n            \"His affections seemed to reanimate towards them all, and his interest in their welfare again became perceptible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32409,\n            \"he praised their house, admired its prospect, was attentive, and kind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32496,\n            \"\\u201care you still to be a great orator in spite of yourself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32514,\n            \"I hope my mother is now convinced that I have no more talents than inclination for a public life!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32545,\n            \"for famous you must be to satisfy all your family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32556,\n            \"and with no inclination for expense, no affection for strangers, no profession, and no assurance, you may find it a difficult matter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32667,\n            \"but, like every body else it must be in my own way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32981,\n            \"\\u201d repeated Edward \\u2014 \\u201cbut why must you have hunters?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33186,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhat magnificent orders would travel from this family to London,\\u201dsaid Edward, \\u201cin such an event!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33225,\n            \"You, Miss Dashwood, would give a general commission for every new print of merit to be sent you \\u2014 and as for Marianne, I know her greatness of soul, there would not be music enough in London to content her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33340,\n            \"But I was willing to show you that I had not forgot our old disputes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33356,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI love to be reminded of the past, Edward \\u2014 whether it be melancholy or gay, I love to recall it \\u2014 and you will never offend me by talking of former times.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33394,\n            \"You are very right in supposing how my money would be spent \\u2014 some of it, at least \\u2014 my loose cash would certainly be employed in improving my collection of music and books.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33430,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd the bulk of your fortune would be laid out in annuities on the authors or their heirs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33451,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, Edward, I should have something else to do with it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33467,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, then, you would bestow it as a reward on that person who wrote the ablest defence of your favourite maxim, that no one can ever be in love more than once in their life \\u2014 your opinion on that point is unchanged, I presume?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33588,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay, Edward,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201c_ you _ need not reproach me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33701,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe you are right,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cand yet I have always set her down as a lively girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33954,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou have not been able to bring your sister over to your plan of general civility,\\u201dsaid Edward to Elinor, \\u201cDo you gain no ground?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34019,\n            \"but I am afraid my practice is much more on your sister\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34064,\n            \"I have frequently thought that I must have been intended by nature to be fond of low company, I am so little at my ease among strangers of gentility!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34247,\n            \"but trying to laugh off the subject, she said to him, \\u201cDo not you know my sister well enough to understand what she means?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34275,\n            \"Do not you know she calls every one reserved who does not talk as fast, and admire what she admires as rapturously as herself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34431,\n            \"He joined her and Marianne in the breakfast-room the next morning before the others were down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34501,\n            \"\\u201cI am going into the village to see my horses,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cas you are not yet ready for breakfast;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34534,\n            \"\\u201d Edward returned to them with fresh admiration of the surrounding country;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34593,\n            \"This was a subject which ensured Marianne\\u2019s attention, and she was beginning to describe her own admiration of these scenes, and to question him more minutely on the objects that had particularly struck him, when Edward interrupted her by saying, \\u201cYou must not enquire too far, Marianne \\u2014 remember I have no knowledge in the picturesque, and I shall offend you by my ignorance and want of taste if we come to particulars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34869,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI suspect,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cthat to avoid one kind of affectation, Edward here falls into another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34893,\n            \"Because he believes many people pretend to more admiration of the beauties of nature than they really feel, and is disgusted with such pretensions, he affects greater indifference and less discrimination in viewing them himself than he possesses.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35061,\n            \"But, in return, your sister must allow me to feel no more than I profess.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35102,\n            \"I admire them much more if they are tall, straight, and flourishing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35139,\n            \"I have more pleasure in a snug farm-house than a watch-tower \\u2014 and a troop of tidy, happy villagers please me better than the finest banditti in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35174,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne looked with amazement at Edward, with compassion at her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35214,\n            \"She was sitting by Edward, and in taking his tea from Mrs. Dashwood, his hand passed so directly before her, as to make a ring, with a plait of hair in the centre, very conspicuous on one of his fingers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35261,\n            \"\\u201cI never saw you wear a ring before, Edward,\\u201dshe cried.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35285,\n            \"I remember her promising to give you some.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35567,\n            \"Before the middle of the day, they were visited by Sir John and Mrs. Jennings, who, having heard of the arrival of a gentleman at the cottage, came to take a survey of the guest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35636,\n            \"and this prepared a future mine of raillery against the devoted Elinor, which nothing but the newness of their acquaintance with Edward could have prevented from being immediately sprung.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35726,\n            \"On the present occasion, for the better entertainment of their visitor, towards whose amusement he felt himself bound to contribute, he wished to engage them for both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35963,\n            \"Edward saw enough to comprehend, not only the meaning of others, but such of Marianne\\u2019s expressions as had puzzled him before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35989,\n            \"and when their visitors left them, he went immediately round her, and said, in a whisper, \\u201cI have been guessing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36198,\n            \"but, as if he were bent only on self-mortification, he seemed resolved to be gone when his enjoyment among his friends was at the height.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36364,\n            \"He valued their kindness beyond any thing, and his greatest happiness was in being with them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36382,\n            \"Yet, he must leave them at the end of a week, in spite of their wishes and his own, and without any restraint on his time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36717,\n            \"\\u201cI think, Edward,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, as they were at breakfast the last morning, \\u201cyou would be a happier man if you had any profession to engage your time and give an interest to your plans and actions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36764,\n            \"Some inconvenience to your friends, indeed, might result from it \\u2014 you would not be able to give them so much of your time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36791,\n            \"But (with a smile) you would be materially benefited in one particular at least \\u2014 you would know where to go when you left them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36889,\n            \"But unfortunately my own nicety, and the nicety of my friends, have made me what I am, an idle, helpless being.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37001,\n            \"But I had no inclination for the law, even in this less abstruse study of it, which my family approved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37024,\n            \"As for the navy, it had fashion on its side, but I was too old when the subject was first started to enter it \\u2014 and, at length, as there was no necessity for my having any profession at all, as I might be as dashing and expensive without a red coat on my back as with one, idleness was pronounced on the whole to be most advantageous and honourable, and a young man of eighteen is not in general so earnestly bent on being busy as to resist the solicitations of his friends to do nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37143,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe consequence of which, I suppose, will be,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, \\u201csince leisure has not promoted your own happiness, that your sons will be brought up to as many pursuits, employments, professions, and trades as Columella\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37195,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThey will be brought up,\\u201dsaid he, in a serious accent, \\u201cto be as unlike myself as is possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37320,\n            \"Your mother will secure to you, in time, that independence you are so anxious for;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37338,\n            \"it is her duty, and it will, it must ere long become her happiness to prevent your whole youth from being wasted in discontent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37451,\n            \"But as it was her determination to subdue it, and to prevent herself from appearing to suffer more than what all her family suffered on his going away, she did not adopt the method so judiciously employed by Marianne, on a similar occasion, to augment and fix her sorrow, by seeking silence, solitude and idleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37531,\n            \"Elinor sat down to her drawing-table as soon as he was out of the house, busily employed herself the whole day, neither sought nor avoided the mention of his name, appeared to interest herself almost as much as ever in the general concerns of the family, and if, by this conduct, she did not lessen her own grief, it was at least prevented from unnecessary increase, and her mother and sisters were spared much solicitude on her account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37730,\n            \"Without shutting herself up from her family, or leaving the house in determined solitude to avoid them, or lying awake the whole night to indulge meditation, Elinor found every day afforded her leisure enough to think of Edward, and of Edward\\u2019s behaviour, in every possible variety which the different state of her spirits at different times could produce, \\u2014 with tenderness, pity, approbation, censure, and doubt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37901,\n            \"From a reverie of this kind, as she sat at her drawing-table, she was roused one morning, soon after Edward\\u2019s leaving them, by the arrival of company.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47355,\n            \"for I dare say he never dropped the smallest hint of it to you or any of your family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47466,\n            \"And I do not think Mr. Ferrars can be displeased, when he knows I have trusted you, because I know he has the highest opinion in the world of all your family, and looks upon yourself and the other Miss Dashwoods quite as his own sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47653,\n            \"He was under my uncle\\u2019s care, you know, a considerable while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47718,\n            \"\\u201cHe was four years with my uncle, who lives at Longstaple, near Plymouth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47735,\n            \"It was there our acquaintance begun, for my sister and me was often staying with my uncle, and it was there our engagement was formed, though not till a year after he had quitted as a pupil;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47776,\n            \"but he was almost always with us afterwards.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47831,\n            \"Though you do not know him so well as me, Miss Dashwood, you must have seen enough of him to be sensible he is very capable of making a woman sincerely attached to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47952,\n            \"We cannot mean the same Mr. Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48121,\n            \"and, as he was always particularly afraid of his sister\\u2019s suspecting any thing, _ that _ was reason enough for his not mentioning it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48777,\n            \"She does not know how to hold her tongue, as you must perceive, and I am sure I was in the greatest fright in the world t\\u2019other day, when Edward\\u2019s name was mentioned by Sir John, lest she should out with it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48876,\n            \"and seeing him so seldom \\u2014 we can hardly meet above twice a-year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49083,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTo be sure,\\u201dcontinued Lucy, after a few minutes silence on both sides, \\u201chis mother must provide for him sometime or other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49138,\n            \"He was so miserable when he left us at Longstaple, to go to you, that I was afraid you would think him quite ill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49165,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid he come from your uncle\\u2019s, then, when he visited us?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49189,\n            \"he had been staying a fortnight with us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49230,\n            \"\\u201cI remember he told us, that he had been staying a fortnight with some friends near Plymouth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49250,\n            \"\\u201d She remembered too, her own surprise at the time, at his mentioning nothing farther of those friends, at his total silence with respect even to their names.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49297,\n            \"\\u201cWe did, indeed, particularly so when he first arrived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49310,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI begged him to exert himself for fear you should suspect what was the matter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49328,\n            \"but it made him so melancholy, not being able to stay more than a fortnight with us, and seeing me so much affected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49401,\n            \"\\u201cYou know his hand, I dare say, \\u2014 a charming one it is;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49894,\n            \"and Edward\\u2019s visit near Plymouth, his melancholy state of mind, his dissatisfaction at his own prospects, his uncertain behaviour towards herself, the intimate knowledge of the Miss Steeles as to Norland and their family connections, which had often surprised her, the picture, the letter, the ring, formed altogether such a body of evidence, as overcame every fear of condemning him unfairly, and established as a fact, which no partiality could set aside, his ill-treatment of herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50088,\n            \"Her mother, sisters, Fanny, all had been conscious of his regard for her at Norland;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50250,\n            \"Could he ever be tolerably happy with Lucy Steele;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50389,\n            \"If in the supposition of his seeking to marry herself, his difficulties from his mother had seemed great, how much greater were they now likely to be, when the object of his engagement was undoubtedly inferior in connections, and probably inferior in fortune to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50506,\n            \"Supported by the conviction of having done nothing to merit her present unhappiness, and consoled by the belief that Edward had done nothing to forfeit her esteem, she thought she could even now, under the first smart of the heavy blow, command herself enough to guard every suspicion of the truth from her mother and sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50567,\n            \"And so well was she able to answer her own expectations, that when she joined them at dinner only two hours after she had first suffered the extinction of all her dearest hopes, no one would have supposed from the appearance of the sisters, that Elinor was mourning in secret over obstacles which must divide her for ever from the object of her love, and that Marianne was internally dwelling on the perfections of a man, of whose whole heart she felt thoroughly possessed, and whom she expected to see in every carriage which drove near their house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50708,\n            \"On the contrary it was a relief to her, to be spared the communication of what would give such affliction to them, and to be saved likewise from hearing that condemnation of Edward, which would probably flow from the excess of their partial affection for herself, and which was more than she felt equal to support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50891,\n            \"She wanted to hear many particulars of their engagement repeated again, she wanted more clearly to understand what Lucy really felt for Edward, whether there were any sincerity in her declaration of tender regard for him, and she particularly wanted to convince Lucy, by her readiness to enter on the matter again, and her calmness in conversing on it, that she was no otherwise interested in it than as a friend, which she very much feared her involuntary agitation, in their morning discourse, must have left at least doubtful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53147,\n            \"\\u201cEdward\\u2019s love for me,\\u201dsaid Lucy, \\u201chas been pretty well put to the test, by our long, very long absence since we were first engaged, and it has stood the trial so well, that I should be unpardonable to doubt it now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53240,\n            \"\\u201cI am rather of a jealous temper too by nature, and from our different situations in life, from his being so much more in the world than me, and our continual separation, I was enough inclined for suspicion, to have found out the truth in an instant, if there had been the slightest alteration in his behaviour to me when we met, or any lowness of spirits that I could not account for, or if he had talked more of one lady than another, or seemed in any respect less happy at Longstaple than he used to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53506,\n            \"But Mrs. Ferrars is a very headstrong proud woman, and in her first fit of anger upon hearing it, would very likely secure every thing to Robert, and the idea of that, for Edward\\u2019s sake, frightens away all my inclination for hasty measures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53916,\n            \"now my plan is that he should take orders as soon as he can, and then through your interest, which I am sure you would be kind enough to use out of friendship for him, and I hope out of some regard to me, your brother might be persuaded to give him Norland living;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54062,\n            \"He is brother to Mrs. John Dashwood \\u2014 _ that _ must be recommendation enough to her husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54282,\n            \"and I do really believe, that if you was to say to me, \\u2018 I advise you by all means to put an end to your engagement with Edward Ferrars, it will be more for the happiness of both of you,\\u2019I should resolve upon doing it immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54793,\n            \"but that he had not even the chance of being tolerably happy in marriage, which sincere affection on _ her _ side would have given, for self-interest alone could induce a woman to keep a man to an engagement, of which she seemed so thoroughly aware that he was weary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55852,\n            \"and Elinor, who now understood her sister, and saw to what indifference to almost every thing else she was carried by her eagerness to be with Willoughby again, made no farther direct opposition to the plan, and merely referred it to her mother\\u2019s decision, from whom however she scarcely expected to receive any support in her endeavour to prevent a visit, which she could not approve of for Marianne, and which on her own account she had particular reasons to avoid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56842,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor had often wished for an opportunity of attempting to weaken her mother\\u2019s dependence on the attachment of Edward and herself, that the shock might be less when the whole truth were revealed, and now on this attack, though almost hopeless of success, she forced herself to begin her design by saying, as calmly as she could, \\u201cI like Edward Ferrars very much, and shall always be glad to see him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57573,\n            \"and Elinor was resolved not only upon gaining every new light as to his character which her own observation or the intelligence of others could give her, but likewise upon watching his behaviour to her sister with such zealous attention, as to ascertain what he was and what he meant, before many meetings had taken place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85208,\n            \"but nothing would have induced Fanny voluntarily to mention his name before her, till able to tell her that his marriage with Miss Morton was resolved on, or till her husband\\u2019s expectations on Colonel Brandon were answered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85328,\n            \"He dared not come to Bartlett\\u2019s Buildings for fear of detection, and though their mutual impatience to meet, was not to be told, they could do nothing at present but write.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85365,\n            \"Edward assured them himself of his being in town, within a very short time, by twice calling in Berkeley Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85388,\n            \"Twice was his card found on the table, when they returned from their morning\\u2019s engagements.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85415,\n            \"and still more pleased that she had missed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85968,\n            \"They were relieved however, not by her own recollection, but by the good will of Lucy, who believed herself to be inflicting a severe disappointment when she told her that Edward certainly would not be in Harley Street on Tuesday, and even hoped to be carrying the pain still farther by persuading her that he was kept away by the extreme affection for herself, which he could not conceal when they were together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88037,\n            \"\\u201d said her brother to Colonel Brandon, in a low voice, as soon as he could secure his attention: \\u201cShe has not such good health as her sister, \\u2014 she is very nervous, \\u2014 she has not Elinor\\u2019s constitution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88184,\n            \"She had seen enough of her pride, her meanness, and her determined prejudice against herself, to comprehend all the difficulties that must have perplexed the engagement, and retarded the marriage, of Edward and herself, had he been otherwise free;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88282,\n            \"Or at least, if she did not bring herself quite to rejoice in Edward\\u2019s being fettered to Lucy, she determined, that had Lucy been more amiable, she _ ought _ to have rejoiced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88976,\n            \"But it seemed to satisfy Lucy, for she directly replied, \\u201cIndeed I am perfectly convinced of your regard for me, and next to Edward\\u2019s love, it is the greatest comfort I have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89019,\n            \"But now there is one good thing, we shall be able to meet, and meet pretty often, for Lady Middleton\\u2019s delighted with Mrs. Dashwood, so we shall be a good deal in Harley Street, I dare say, and Edward spends half his time with his sister \\u2014 besides, Lady Middleton and Mrs. Ferrars will visit now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89277,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was prevented from making any reply to this civil triumph, by the door\\u2019s being thrown open, the servant\\u2019s announcing Mr. Ferrars, and Edward\\u2019s immediately walking in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89465,\n            \"and so anxious was she, for his sake and her own, to do it well, that she forced herself, after a moment\\u2019s recollection, to welcome him, with a look and manner that were almost easy, and almost open;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89523,\n            \"She would not allow the presence of Lucy, nor the consciousness of some injustice towards herself, to deter her from saying that she was happy to see him, and that she had very much regretted being from home, when he called before in Berkeley Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89573,\n            \"She would not be frightened from paying him those attentions which, as a friend and almost a relation, were his due, by the observant eyes of Lucy, though she soon perceived them to be narrowly watching her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89615,\n            \"Her manners gave some re-assurance to Edward, and he had courage enough to sit down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89634,\n            \"but his embarrassment still exceeded that of the ladies in a proportion, which the case rendered reasonable, though his sex might make it rare;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89872,\n            \"Her pleasure in seeing him was like every other of her feelings, strong in itself, and strongly spoken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89893,\n            \"She met him with a hand that would be taken, and a voice that expressed the affection of a sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89942,\n            \"\\u201d Edward tried to return her kindness as it deserved, but before such witnesses he dared not say half what he really felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89983,\n            \"while Marianne was looking with the most speaking tenderness, sometimes at Edward and sometimes at Elinor, regretting only that their delight in each other should be checked by Lucy\\u2019s unwelcome presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90019,\n            \"Edward was the first to speak, and it was to notice Marianne\\u2019s altered looks, and express his fear of her not finding London agree with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90211,\n            \"\\u201cI think, Elinor,\\u201dshe presently added, \\u201cwe must employ Edward to take care of us in our return to Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90252,\n            \"and, I trust, Edward will not be very unwilling to accept the charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90268,\n            \"\\u201d Poor Edward muttered something, but what it was, nobody knew, not even himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90286,\n            \"But Marianne, who saw his agitation, and could easily trace it to whatever cause best pleased herself, was perfectly satisfied, and soon talked of something else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90317,\n            \"\\u201cWe spent such a day, Edward, in Harley Street yesterday!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90338,\n            \"\\u2014 But I have much to say to you on that head, which cannot be said now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90507,\n            \"for, seriously speaking, I am very sure that conscience only kept Edward from Harley Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90525,\n            \"And I really believe he _ has _ the most delicate conscience in the world;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90563,\n            \"He is the most fearful of giving pain, of wounding expectation, and the most incapable of being selfish, of any body I ever saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90591,\n            \"Edward, it is so, and I will say it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90613,\n            \"\\u2014 Then you must be no friend of mine;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90641,\n            \"\\u201d The nature of her commendation, in the present case, however, happened to be particularly ill-suited to the feelings of two thirds of her auditors, and was so very unexhilarating to Edward, that he very soon got up to go away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90709,\n            \"\\u201d And drawing him a little aside, she whispered her persuasion that Lucy could not stay much longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90801,\n            \"\\u2014 we were all his friends, and Lucy has been the longest known to him of any.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90820,\n            \"It is but natural that he should like to see her as well as ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91606,\n            \"But so little were they, any more than the others, inclined to oblige her, that if Sir John dined from home, she might spend a whole day without hearing any other raillery on the subject, than what she was kind enough to bestow on herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91710,\n            \"She joined them sometimes at Sir John\\u2019s, sometimes at her own house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91817,\n            \"and though she could plainly perceive, at different times, the most striking resemblance between this baby and every one of his relations on both sides, there was no convincing his father of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91873,\n            \"nor could he even be brought to acknowledge the simple proposition of its being the finest child in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92771,\n            \"and had just determined to find out his name from the latter, when they both came towards her, and Mr. Dashwood introduced him to her as Mr. Robert Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92846,\n            \"Happy had it been for her, if her regard for Edward had depended less on his own merit, than on the merit of his nearest relations!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92875,\n            \"For then his brother\\u2019s bow must have given the finishing stroke to what the ill-humour of his mother and sister would have begun.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93122,\n            \"Why would you be persuaded by my uncle, Sir Robert, against your own judgment, to place Edward under private tuition, at the most critical time of his life?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93209,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor would not oppose his opinion, because, whatever might be her general estimation of the advantage of a public school, she could not think of Edward\\u2019s abode in Mr. Pratt\\u2019s family, with any satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94101,\n            \"and I think the attention is due to them, as their uncle did so very well by Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94339,\n            \"Such an opportunity of being with Edward and his family was, above all things, the most material to her interest, and such an invitation the most gratifying to her feelings!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95435,\n            \"\\u2019 and so, away she went to your sister, who was sitting all alone at her carpet-work, little suspecting what was to come \\u2014 for she had just been saying to your brother, only five minutes before, that she thought to make a match between Edward and some Lord\\u2019s daughter or other, I forget who.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95846,\n            \"for they say he is monstrous fond of her, as well he may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95861,\n            \"I should not wonder, if he was to be in the greatest passion!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96013,\n            \"for I am sure Mrs. Ferrars may afford to do very well by her son, and though Lucy has next to nothing herself, she knows better than any body how to make the most of every thing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96054,\n            \"I dare say, if Mrs. Ferrars would only allow him five hundred a-year, she would make as good an appearance with it as any body else would with eight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96201,\n            \"that Mrs. Jennings (as she had of late often hoped might be the case) had ceased to imagine her at all attached to Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96417,\n            \"No time was to be lost in undeceiving her, in making her acquainted with the real truth, and in endeavouring to bring her to hear it talked of by others, without betraying that she felt any uneasiness for her sister, or any resentment against Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96476,\n            \"\\u2014 She was going to remove what she really believed to be her sister\\u2019s chief consolation, \\u2014 to give such particulars of Edward as she feared would ruin him for ever in her good opinion,-and to make Marianne, by a resemblance in their situations, which to _ her _ fancy would seem strong, feel all her own disappointment over again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96736,\n            \"Edward seemed a second Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96742,\n            \"and acknowledging as Elinor did, that she _ had _ loved him most sincerely, could she feel less than herself!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96765,\n            \"As for Lucy Steele, she considered her so totally unamiable, so absolutely incapable of attaching a sensible man, that she could not be persuaded at first to believe, and afterwards to pardon, any former affection of Edward for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97216,\n            \"and yet you loved him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97226,\n            \"But I did not love only him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97329,\n            \"I acquit Edward of essential misconduct.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97336,\n            \"I wish him very happy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97342,\n            \"and I am so sure of his always doing his duty, that though now he may harbour some regret, in the end he must become so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97455,\n            \"he will marry a woman superior in person and understanding to half her sex;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97470,\n            \"and time and habit will teach him to forget that he ever thought another superior to _ her _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97716,\n            \"I have known myself to be divided from Edward for ever, without hearing one circumstance that could make me less desire the connection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97747,\n            \"nor has anything declared him indifferent to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 She listened to her praise of Lucy with only moving from one chair to another, and when Mrs. Jennings talked of Edward\\u2019s affection, it cost her only a spasm in her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98749,\n            \"We consulted together, however, as to what should be done, and at last she determined to send for Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98784,\n            \"All that Mrs. Ferrars could say to make him put an end to the engagement, assisted too as you may well suppose by my arguments, and Fanny\\u2019s entreaties, was of no avail.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98832,\n            \"I never thought Edward so stubborn, so unfeeling before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98843,\n            \"His mother explained to him her liberal designs, in case of his marrying Miss Morton;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings with blunt sincerity, no longer able to be silent, \\u201che has acted like an honest man!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99417,\n            \"Edward has drawn his own lot, and I fear it will be a bad one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99442,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s heart wrung for the feelings of Edward, while braving his mother\\u2019s threats, for a woman who could not reward him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99489,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry to say, ma\\u2019am, in a most unhappy rupture: \\u2014 Edward is dismissed for ever from his mother\\u2019s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99520,\n            \"He left her house yesterday, but where he is gone, or whether he is still in town, I do not know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99618,\n            \"\\u2014 and when to that is added the recollection, that he might, but for his own folly, within three months have been in the receipt of two thousand, five hundred a-year (for Miss Morton has thirty thousand pounds,) I cannot picture to myself a more wretched condition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99675,\n            \"We must all feel for him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99682,\n            \"and the more so, because it is totally out of our power to assist him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99705,\n            \"\\u201d cried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cI am sure he should be very welcome to bed and board at my house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99728,\n            \"and so I would tell him if I could see him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99761,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s heart thanked her for such kindness towards Edward, though she could not forbear smiling at the form of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99786,\n            \"\\u201cIf he would only have done as well by himself,\\u201dsaid John Dashwood, \\u201cas all his friends were disposed to do by him, he might now have been in his proper situation, and would have wanted for nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99832,\n            \"But as it is, it must be out of anybody\\u2019s power to assist him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99974,\n            \"\\u201cCan anything be more galling to the spirit of a man,\\u201dcontinued John, \\u201cthan to see his younger brother in possession of an estate which might have been his own?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100074,\n            \"leaving the three ladies unanimous in their sentiments on the present occasion, as far at least as it regarded Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s conduct, the Dashwoods \\u2019, and Edward\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100181,\n            \"_ They _ only knew how little he had had to tempt him to be disobedient, and how small was the consolation, beyond the consciousness of doing right, that could remain to him in the loss of friends and fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100683,\n            \"She saw nothing of the Willoughbys, nothing of Edward, and for some time nothing of anybody who could by any chance whether grave or gay, be interesting to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101072,\n            \"I do not care if it _ is _ the Doctor\\u2019s favourite colour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101088,\n            \"I am sure, for my part, I should never have known he _ did _ like it better than any other colour, if he had not happened to say so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101176,\n            \"\\u201cWell, but Miss Dashwood,\\u201dspeaking triumphantly, \\u201cpeople may say what they chuse about Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s declaring he would not have Lucy, for it is no such thing I can tell you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101308,\n            \"for Miss Godby told Miss Sparks, that nobody in their senses could expect Mr. Ferrars to give up a woman like Miss Morton, with thirty thousand pounds to her fortune, for Lucy Steele that had nothing at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101360,\n            \"And besides that, my cousin Richard said himself, that when it came to the point he was afraid Mr. Ferrars would be off;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101387,\n            \"and when Edward did not come near us for three days, I could not tell what to think myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101422,\n            \"for we came away from your brother\\u2019s Wednesday, and we saw nothing of him not all Thursday, Friday, and Saturday, and did not know what was become of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101458,\n            \"Once Lucy thought to write to him, but then her spirits rose against that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101474,\n            \"However this morning he came just as we came home from church;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101487,\n            \"and then it all came out, how he had been sent for Wednesday to Harley Street, and been talked to by his mother and all of them, and how he had declared before them all that he loved nobody but Lucy, and nobody but Lucy would he have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101540,\n            \"And how he had been so worried by what passed, that as soon as he had went away from his mother\\u2019s house, he had got upon his horse, and rid into the country, some where or other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101607,\n            \"And after thinking it all over and over again, he said, it seemed to him as if, now he had no fortune, and no nothing at all, it would be quite unkind to keep her on to the engagement, because it must be for her loss, for he had nothing but two thousand pounds, and no hope of any thing else;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101677,\n            \"and if he was to go into orders, as he had some thoughts, he could get nothing but a curacy, and how was they to live upon that?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101709,\n            \"\\u2014 He could not bear to think of her doing no better, and so he begged, if she had the least mind for it, to put an end to the matter directly, and leave him shift for himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101752,\n            \"I heard him say all this as plain as could possibly be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101765,\n            \"And it was entirely for _ her _ sake, and upon _ her _ account, that he said a word about being off, and not upon his own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101797,\n            \"I will take my oath he never dropt a syllable of being tired of her, or of wishing to marry Miss Morton, or any thing like it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101844,\n            \"so she told him directly (with a great deal about sweet and love, you know, and all that \\u2014 Oh, la!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101870,\n            \"one can\\u2019t repeat such kind of things you know) \\u2014 she told him directly, she had not the least mind in the world to be off, for she could live with him upon a trifle, and how little so ever he might have, she should be very glad to have it all, you know, or something of the kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101939,\n            \"So then he was monstrous happy, and talked on some time about what they should do, and they agreed he should take orders directly, and they must wait to be married till he got a living.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102017,\n            \"so I was forced to go into the room and interrupt them, to ask Lucy if she would like to go, but she did not care to leave Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102213,\n            \"for I certainly would not have suffered you to give me particulars of a conversation which you ought not to have known yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102237,\n            \"How could you behave so unfairly by your sister?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102523,\n            \"and after _ that _, as soon as he can light upon a Bishop, he will be ordained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102544,\n            \"I wonder what curacy he will get!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102581,\n            \"They will tell me I should write to the Doctor, to get Edward the curacy of his new living.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103153,\n            \"\\u2014 ay, we all know how _ that _ will end: \\u2014 they will wait a twelvemonth, and finding no good comes of it, will set down upon a curacy of fifty pounds a-year, with the interest of his two thousand pounds, and what little matter Mr. Steele and Mr. Pratt can give her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103345,\n            \"but I know your friendship for me will make you pleased to hear such a good account of myself and my dear Edward, after all the troubles we have went through lately, therefore will make no more apologies, but proceed to say that, thank God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103423,\n            \"We have had great trials, and great persecutions, but however, at the same time, gratefully acknowledge many friends, yourself not the least among them, whose great kindness I shall always thankfully remember, as will Edward too, who I have told of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103474,\n            \"I am sure you will be glad to hear, as likewise dear Mrs. Jennings, I spent two happy hours with him yesterday afternoon, he would not hear of our parting, though earnestly did I, as I thought my duty required, urge him to it for prudence sake, and would have parted for ever on the spot, would he consent to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103545,\n            \"but he said it should never be, he did not regard his mother\\u2019s anger, while he could have my affections;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103598,\n            \"and should it ever be in your power to recommend him to any body that has a living to bestow, am very sure you will not forget us, and dear Mrs. Jennings too, trust she will speak a good word for us to Sir John, or Mr. Palmer, or any friend that may be able to assist us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105651,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s astonishment at this commission could hardly have been greater, had the Colonel been really making her an offer of his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105678,\n            \"The preferment, which only two days before she had considered as hopeless for Edward, was already provided to enable him to marry;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105788,\n            \"She thanked him for it with all her heart, spoke of Edward\\u2019s principles and disposition with that praise which she knew them to deserve;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105841,\n            \"But at the same time, she could not help thinking that no one could so well perform it as himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105863,\n            \"It was an office in short, from which, unwilling to give Edward the pain of receiving an obligation from _ her _, she would have been very glad to be spared herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105936,\n            \"Edward, she believed, was still in town, and fortunately she had heard his address from Miss Steele.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105957,\n            \"She could undertake therefore to inform him of it, in the course of the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106142,\n            \"\\u201cThis little rectory _ can _ do no more than make Mr. Ferrars comfortable as a bachelor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107458,\n            \"How she should begin \\u2014 how she should express herself in her note to Edward, was now all her concern.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107505,\n            \"but she equally feared to say too much or too little, and sat deliberating over her paper, with the pen in her hand, till broken in on by the entrance of Edward himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107567,\n            \"and she, after apologising for not returning herself, had obliged him to enter, by saying that Miss Dashwood was above, and wanted to speak with him on very particular business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107602,\n            \"Elinor had just been congratulating herself, in the midst of her perplexity, that however difficult it might be to express herself properly by letter, it was at least preferable to giving the information by word of mouth, when her visitor entered, to force her upon this greatest exertion of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107658,\n            \"Her astonishment and confusion were very great on his so sudden appearance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107671,\n            \"She had not seen him before since his engagement became public, and therefore not since his knowing her to be acquainted with it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107696,\n            \"which, with the consciousness of what she had been thinking of, and what she had to tell him, made her feel particularly uncomfortable for some minutes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107745,\n            \"\\u2014 Whether he had asked her pardon for his intrusion on first coming into the room, he could not recollect;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107796,\n            \"\\u201cMrs. Jennings told me,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cthat you wished to speak with me, at least I understood her so \\u2014 or I certainly should not have intruded on you in such a manner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107837,\n            \"though at the same time, I should have been extremely sorry to leave London without seeing you and your sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108041,\n            \"Allow me to congratulate you on having so respectable and well-judging a friend, and to join in his wish that the living \\u2014 it is about two hundred a-year \\u2014 were much more considerable, and such as might better enable you to \\u2014 as might be more than a temporary accommodation to yourself \\u2014 such, in short, as might establish all your views of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108115,\n            \"\\u201d What Edward felt, as he could not say it himself, it cannot be expected that any one else should say for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108176,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, gathering more resolution, as some of the worst was over, \\u201cColonel Brandon means it as a testimony of his concern for what has lately passed \\u2014 for the cruel situation in which the unjustifiable conduct of your family has placed you \\u2014 a concern which I am sure Marianne, myself, and all your friends, must share;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108290,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe unkindness of your own relations has made you astonished to find friendship any where.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108348,\n            \"\\u2014 I feel it \\u2014 I would express it if I could \\u2014 but, as you well know, I am no orator.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108485,\n            \"but, upon my word, you owe nothing to my solicitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108568,\n            \"\\u2014 at last, and as if it were rather an effort, he said, \\u201cColonel Brandon seems a man of great worth and respectability.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108596,\n            \"I have always heard him spoken of as such, and your brother I know esteems him highly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108630,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cI believe that you will find him, on farther acquaintance, all that you have heard him to be, and as you will be such very near neighbours (for I understand the parsonage is almost close to the mansion-house,) it is particularly important that he _ should _ be all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109650,\n            \"Edward, having carried his thanks to Colonel Brandon, proceeded with his happiness to Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109758,\n            \"So far was she, at the same time, from any backwardness to give Elinor that credit which Edward _ would _ give her, that she spoke of her friendship for them both with the most grateful warmth, was ready to own all their obligation to her, and openly declared that no exertion for their good on Miss Dashwood\\u2019s part, either present or future, would ever surprise her, for she believed her capable of doing any thing in the world for those she really valued.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109929,\n            \"It was now above a week since John Dashwood had called in Berkeley Street, and as since that time no notice had been taken by them of his wife\\u2019s indisposition, beyond one verbal enquiry, Elinor began to feel it necessary to pay her a visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110355,\n            \"\\u2014 has he really given it to Edward?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110392,\n            \"\\u2014 Colonel Brandon has given the living of Delaford to Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110452,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cVery well \\u2014 and for the next presentation to a living of that value \\u2014 supposing the late incumbent to have been old and sickly, and likely to vacate it soon \\u2014 he might have got I dare say \\u2014 fourteen hundred pounds.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110540,\n            \"I wonder he should be so improvident in a point of such common, such natural, concern!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110596,\n            \"Edward is only to hold the living till the person to whom the Colonel has really sold the presentation, is old enough to take it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110646,\n            \"and by relating that she had herself been employed in conveying the offer from Colonel Brandon to Edward, and, therefore, must understand the terms on which it was given, obliged him to submit to her authority.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110693,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 he cried, after hearing what she said \\u2014 \\u201cwhat could be the Colonel\\u2019s motive?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110736,\n            \"whatever Colonel Brandon may be, Edward is a very lucky man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110830,\n            \"\\u201cMrs. Ferrars,\\u201dadded he, lowering his voice to the tone becoming so important a subject, \\u201cknows nothing about it at present, and I believe it will be best to keep it entirely concealed from her as long as may be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110879,\n            \"When the marriage takes place, I fear she must hear of it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110960,\n            \"She has done with her son, \\u2014 she cast him off for ever, and has made all those over whom she had any influence, cast him off likewise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111126,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars can never forget that Edward is her son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111138,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou surprise me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111186,\n            \"\\u201cWe think _ now _,\\u201d\\u2014 said Mr. Dashwood, after a short pause, \\u201cof _ Robert\\u2019s _ marrying Miss Morton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111261,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI only mean that I suppose, from your manner of speaking, it must be the same to Miss Morton whether she marry Edward or Robert.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111301,\n            \"for Robert will now to all intents and purposes be considered as the eldest son;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111317,\n            \"\\u2014 and as to any thing else, they are both very agreeable young men: I do not know that one is superior to the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111963,\n            \"The idea of Edward\\u2019s being a clergyman, and living in a small parsonage-house, diverted him beyond measure;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111987,\n            \"\\u2014 and when to that was added the fanciful imagery of Edward reading prayers in a white surplice, and publishing the banns of marriage between John Smith and Mary Brown, he could conceive nothing more ridiculous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112173,\n            \"for I know him to be a very good-hearted creature;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112200,\n            \"You must not judge of him, Miss Dashwood, from _ your _ slight acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112270,\n            \"but upon my soul, I believe he has as good a heart as any in the kingdom;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112330,\n            \"and I, feeling myself called on to act with resolution, immediately said to her, \\u2018 My dear madam, I do not know what you may intend to do on the occasion, but as for myself, I must say, that if Edward does marry this young woman, _ I _ never will see him again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112532,\n            \"Just the kind of girl I should suppose likely to captivate poor Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112546,\n            \"I offered immediately, as soon as my mother related the affair to me, to talk to him myself, and dissuade him from the match;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112655,\n            \"I certainly should have represented it to Edward in a very strong light.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112669,\n            \"\\u2018 My dear fellow,\\u2019I should have said, \\u2018 consider what you are doing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112687,\n            \"You are making a most disgraceful connection, and such a one as your family are unanimous in disapproving.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112731,\n            \"He must be starved, you know, that is certain;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113178,\n            \"Marianne, few as had been her hours of comfort in London, and eager as she had long been to quit it, could not, when it came to the point, bid adieu to the house in which she had for the last time enjoyed those hopes, and that confidence, in Willoughby, which were now extinguished for ever, without great pain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113247,\n            \"Nor could she leave the place in which Willoughby remained, busy in new engagements, and new schemes, in which _ she _ could have no share, without shedding many tears.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113297,\n            \"She had no such object for her lingering thoughts to fix on, she left no creature behind, from whom it would give her a moment\\u2019s regret to be divided for ever, she was pleased to be free herself from the persecution of Lucy\\u2019s friendship, she was grateful for bringing her sister away unseen by Willoughby since his marriage, and she looked forward with hope to what a few months of tranquility at Barton might do towards restoring Marianne\\u2019s peace of mind, and confirming her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114490,\n            \"\\u2014 not sorry to be driven by the observation of his Epicurism, his selfishness, and his conceit, to rest with complacency on the remembrance of Edward\\u2019s generous temper, simple taste, and diffident feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114531,\n            \"Of Edward, or at least of some of his concerns, she now received intelligence from Colonel Brandon, who had been into Dorsetshire lately;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114558,\n            \"and who, treating her at once as the disinterested friend of Mr. Ferrars, and the kind confidante of himself, talked to her a great deal of the parsonage at Delaford, described its deficiencies, and told her what he meant to do himself towards removing them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114610,\n            \"\\u2014 His behaviour to her in this, as well as in every other particular, his open pleasure in meeting her after an absence of only ten days, his readiness to converse with her, and his deference for her opinion, might very well justify Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s persuasion of his attachment, and would have been enough, perhaps, had not Elinor still, as from the first, believed Marianne his real favourite, to make her suspect it herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114737,\n            \"\\u2014 she watched his eyes, while Mrs. Jennings thought only of his behaviour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114753,\n            \"\\u2014 and while his looks of anxious solicitude on Marianne\\u2019s feeling, in her head and throat, the beginning of a heavy cold, because unexpressed by words, entirely escaped the latter lady\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115097,\n            \"and when, at last, she went early to bed, more and more indisposed, Colonel Brandon was only astonished at her sister\\u2019s composure, who, though attending and nursing her the whole day, against Marianne\\u2019s inclination, and forcing proper medicines on her at night, trusted, like Marianne, to the certainty and efficacy of sleep, and felt no real alarm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115349,\n            \"and Mr. Palmer, though treating their apprehensions as idle, found the anxiety and importunity of his wife too great to be withstood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115384,\n            \"and within an hour after Mr. Harris\\u2019 s arrival, she set off, with her little boy and his nurse, for the house of a near relation of Mr. Palmer\\u2019s, who lived a few miles on the other side of Bath;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115434,\n            \"whither her husband promised, at her earnest entreaty, to join her in a day or two;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115826,\n            \"for to send the Colonel away while his love was in so much uneasiness on her sister\\u2019s account, would be to deprive them both, she thought, of every comfort;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133568,\n            \"and in the first of John\\u2019s, there had been this sentence: \\u2014 \\u201cWe know nothing of our unfortunate Edward, and can make no enquiries on so prohibited a subject, but conclude him to be still at Oxford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133613,\n            \"\\u201d which was all the intelligence of Edward afforded her by the correspondence, for his name was not even mentioned in any of the succeeding letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133641,\n            \"She was not doomed, however, to be long in ignorance of his measures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134403,\n            \"She recognised the whole of Lucy in the message, and was very confident that Edward would never come near them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134914,\n            \"She now found, that in spite of herself, she had always admitted a hope, while Edward remained single, that something would occur to prevent his marrying Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134946,\n            \"that some resolution of his own, some mediation of friends, or some more eligible opportunity of establishment for the lady, would arise to assist the happiness of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135004,\n            \"That he should be married soon, before (as she imagined) he could be in orders, and consequently before he could be in possession of the living, surprised her a little at first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135042,\n            \"But she soon saw how likely it was that Lucy, in her self-provident care, in her haste to secure him, should overlook every thing but the risk of delay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135095,\n            \"What had Edward felt on being within four miles from Barton, on seeing her mother\\u2019s servant, on hearing Lucy\\u2019s message!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135238,\n            \"In Edward \\u2014 she knew not what she saw, nor what she wished to see;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135265,\n            \"she turned away her head from every sketch of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135516,\n            \"Were it possible, she must say it must be Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135532,\n            \"He had just dismounted: she could not be mistaken, \\u2014 it _ was _ Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135557,\n            \"\\u201cHe comes from Mr. Pratt\\u2019s purposely to see us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135627,\n            \"She would have given the world to be able to speak \\u2014 and to make them understand that she hoped no coolness, no slight, would appear in their behaviour to him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135706,\n            \"in a moment he was in the passage, and in another he was before them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135741,\n            \"His complexion was white with agitation, and he looked as if fearful of his reception, and conscious that he merited no kind one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135767,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, however, conforming, as she trusted, to the wishes of that daughter, by whom she then meant in the warmth of her heart to be guided in every thing, met him with a look of forced complacency, gave him her hand, and wished him joy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135833,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s lips had moved with her mother\\u2019s, and, when the moment of action was over, she wished that she had shaken hands with him too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135971,\n            \"It was put an end to by Mrs. Dashwood, who felt obliged to hope that he had left Mrs. Ferrars very well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136096,\n            \"\\u2014 but her mother and Marianne both turned their eyes on him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136109,\n            \"He coloured, seemed perplexed, looked doubtingly, and, after some hesitation, said, \\u2014 \\u201cPerhaps you mean \\u2014 my brother \\u2014 you mean Mrs. \\u2014 Mrs. _ Robert _ Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136212,\n            \"took up a pair of scissors that lay there, and while spoiling both them and their sheath by cutting the latter to pieces as he spoke, said, in a hurried voice, \\u2014 \\u201cPerhaps you do not know: you may not have heard that my brother is lately married to \\u2014 to the youngest \\u2014 to Miss Lucy Steele.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136277,\n            \"\\u201d His words were echoed with unspeakable astonishment by all but Elinor, who sat with her head leaning over her work, in a state of such agitation as made her hardly know where she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136315,\n            \"\\u201cYes,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cthey were married last week, and are now at Dawlish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136406,\n            \"for immediately afterwards he fell into a reverie, which no remarks, no inquiries, no affectionate address of Mrs. Dashwood could penetrate, and at last, without saying a word, quitted the room, and walked out towards the village \\u2014 leaving the others in the greatest astonishment and perplexity on a change in his situation, so wonderful and so sudden;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136493,\n            \"Unaccountable, however, as the circumstances of his release might appear to the whole family, it was certain that Edward was free;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136535,\n            \"\\u2014 for after experiencing the blessings of _ one _ imprudent engagement, contracted without his mother\\u2019s consent, as he had already done for more than four years, nothing less could be expected of him in the failure of _ that _, than the immediate contraction of another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136702,\n            \"\\u2014 that when they all sat down to table at four o\\u2019clock, about three hours after his arrival, he had secured his lady, engaged her mother\\u2019s consent, and was not only in the rapturous profession of the lover, but, in the reality of reason and truth, one of the happiest of men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136874,\n            \"\\u2014 and the change was openly spoken in such a genuine, flowing, grateful cheerfulness, as his friends had never witnessed in him before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136966,\n            \"Had my mother given me some active profession when I was removed at eighteen from the care of Mr. Pratt, I think, nay, I am sure, it would never have happened;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137079,\n            \"But instead of having any thing to do, instead of having any profession chosen for me, or being allowed to chuse any myself, I returned home to be completely idle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137166,\n            \"and as my mother did not make my home in every respect comfortable, as I had no friend, no companion in my brother, and disliked new acquaintance, it was not unnatural for me to be very often at Longstaple, where I always felt myself at home, and was always sure of a welcome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137364,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, too happy to be comfortable, knew not how to love Edward, nor praise Elinor enough, how to be enough thankful for his release without wounding his delicacy, nor how at once to give them leisure for unrestrained conversation together, and yet enjoy, as she wished, the sight and society of both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137484,\n            \"From the moment of learning that Lucy was married to another, that Edward was free, to the moment of his justifying the hopes which had so instantly followed, she was every thing by turns but tranquil.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137524,\n            \"But when the second moment had passed, when she found every doubt, every solicitude removed, compared her situation with what so lately it had been, \\u2014 saw him honourably released from his former engagement, \\u2014 saw him instantly profiting by the release, to address herself and declare an affection as tender, as constant as she had ever supposed it to be, \\u2014 she was oppressed, she was overcome by her own felicity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137834,\n            \"How they could be thrown together, and by what attraction Robert could be drawn on to marry a girl, of whose beauty she had herself heard him speak without any admiration, \\u2014 a girl too already engaged to his brother, and on whose account that brother had been thrown off by his family \\u2014 it was beyond her comprehension to make out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137935,\n            \"Edward could only attempt an explanation by supposing, that, perhaps, at first accidentally meeting, the vanity of the one had been so worked on by the flattery of the other, as to lead by degrees to all the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137980,\n            \"Elinor remembered what Robert had told her in Harley Street, of his opinion of what his own mediation in his brother\\u2019s affairs might have done, if applied to in time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138015,\n            \"She repeated it to Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138036,\n            \"\\u201cAnd _ that _,\\u201dhe presently added, \\u201cmight perhaps be in _ his _ head when the acquaintance between them first began.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138087,\n            \"\\u201d How long it had been carrying on between them, however, he was equally at a loss with herself to make out;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138112,\n            \"for at Oxford, where he had remained for choice ever since his quitting London, he had had no means of hearing of her but from herself, and her letters to the very last were neither less frequent, nor less affectionate than usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138229,\n            \"\\u201cDEAR SIR, \\u201cBeing very sure I have long lost your affections, I have thought myself at liberty to bestow my own on another, and have no doubt of being as happy with him as I once used to think I might be with you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138481,\n            \"\\u201cI will not ask your opinion of it as a composition,\\u201dsaid Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138627,\n            \"The independence she settled on Robert, through resentment against you, has put it in his power to make his own choice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138681,\n            \"She will hardly be less hurt, I suppose, by Robert\\u2019s marrying Lucy, than she would have been by your marrying her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138745,\n            \"\\u201d In what state the affair stood at present between them, Edward knew not, for no communication with any of his family had yet been attempted by him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138936,\n            \"What he might say on the subject a twelvemonth after, must be referred to the imagination of husbands and wives.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138958,\n            \"That Lucy had certainly meant to deceive, to go off with a flourish of malice against him in her message by Thomas, was perfectly clear to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139061,\n            \"and till her last letter reached him, he had always believed her to be a well-disposed, good-hearted girl, and thoroughly attached to himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139092,\n            \"Nothing but such a persuasion could have prevented his putting an end to an engagement, which, long before the discovery of it laid him open to his mother\\u2019s anger, had been a continual source of disquiet and regret to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139138,\n            \"\\u201cI thought it my duty,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cindependent of my feelings, to give her the option of continuing the engagement or not, when I was renounced by my mother, and stood to all appearance without a friend in the world to assist me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139435,\n            \"Elinor scolded him, harshly as ladies always scold the imprudence which compliments themselves, for having spent so much time with them at Norland, when he must have felt his own inconstancy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139929,\n            \"Edward had two thousand pounds, and Elinor one, which, with Delaford living, was all that they could call their own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139996,\n            \"Edward was not entirely without hopes of some favourable change in his mother towards him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140089,\n            \"About four days after Edward\\u2019s arrival Colonel Brandon appeared, to complete Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s satisfaction, and to give her the dignity of having, for the first time since her living at Barton, more company with her than her house would hold.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140753,\n            \"I cannot get him out of my head, but you must send for him to Barton, and Miss Marianne must try to comfort him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140932,\n            \"and he called on Elinor to join with him in regretting that Lucy\\u2019s engagement with Edward had not rather been fulfilled, than that she should thus be the means of spreading misery farther in the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140972,\n            \"He thus continued: \\u2014 \\u201cMrs. Ferrars has never yet mentioned Edward\\u2019s name, which does not surprise us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140996,\n            \"but, to our great astonishment, not a line has been received from him on the occasion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141015,\n            \"Perhaps, however, he is kept silent by his fear of offending, and I shall, therefore, give him a hint, by a line to Oxford, that his sister and I both think a letter of proper submission from him, addressed perhaps to Fanny, and by her shown to her mother, might not be taken amiss;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141160,\n            \"\\u201cwould they have me beg my mother\\u2019s pardon for Robert\\u2019s ingratitude to _ her _, and breach of honour to _ me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141255,\n            \"\\u2014 and I should think you might _ now _ venture so far as to profess some concern for having ever formed the engagement which drew on you your mother\\u2019s anger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141296,\n            \"\\u201cAnd when she has forgiven you, perhaps a little humility may be convenient while acknowledging a second engagement, almost as imprudent in _ her _ eyes as the first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141350,\n            \"and therefore, to make it easier to him, as he declared a much greater willingness to make mean concessions by word of mouth than on paper, it was resolved that, instead of writing to Fanny, he should go to London, and personally intreat her good offices in his favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141473,\n            \"They were to go immediately to Delaford, that Edward might have some personal knowledge of his future home, and assist his patron and friend in deciding on what improvements were needed to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141534,\n            \"After a proper resistance on the part of Mrs. Ferrars, just so violent and so steady as to preserve her from that reproach which she always seemed fearful of incurring, the reproach of being too amiable, Edward was admitted to her presence, and pronounced to be again her son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141733,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars at first reasonably endeavoured to dissuade him from marrying Miss Dashwood, by every argument in her power;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141755,\n            \"\\u2014 told him, that in Miss Morton he would have a woman of higher rank and larger fortune;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141815,\n            \"_ but when she found that, though perfectly admitting the truth of her representation, he was by no means inclined to be guided by it, she judged it wisest, from the experience of the past, to submit \\u2014 and therefore, after such an ungracious delay as she owed to her own dignity, and as served to prevent every suspicion of good-will, she issued her decree of consent to the marriage of Edward and Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141916,\n            \"and here it plainly appeared, that though Edward was now her only son, he was by no means her eldest;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142046,\n            \"With an income quite sufficient to their wants thus secured to them, they had nothing to wait for after Edward was in possession of the living, but the readiness of the house, to which Colonel Brandon, with an eager desire for the accommodation of Elinor, was making considerable improvements;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142230,\n            \"for she was able to visit Edward and his wife in their Parsonage by Michaelmas, and she found in Elinor and her husband, as she really believed, one of the happiest couples in the world.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 19]\": [\n        [\n            1380,\n            \"So acutely did Mrs. Dashwood feel this ungracious behaviour, and so earnestly did she despise her daughter-in-law for it, that, on the arrival of the latter, she would have quitted the house for ever, had not the entreaty of her eldest girl induced her first to reflect on the propriety of going, and her own tender love for all her three children determined her afterwards to stay, and for their sakes avoid a breach with their brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1470,\n            \"Elinor, this eldest daughter, whose advice was so effectual, possessed a strength of understanding, and coolness of judgment, which qualified her, though only nineteen, to be the counsellor of her mother, and enabled her frequently to counteract, to the advantage of them all, that eagerness of mind in Mrs. Dashwood which must generally have led to imprudence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1557,\n            \"but she knew how to govern them: it was a knowledge which her mother had yet to learn;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1643,\n            \"The resemblance between her and her mother was strikingly great.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4792,\n            \"It was enough for her that he appeared to be amiable, that he loved her daughter, and that Elinor returned the partiality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4842,\n            \"and that Elinor\\u2019s merit should not be acknowledged by every one who knew her, was to her comprehension impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5168,\n            \"She was first called to observe and approve him farther, by a reflection which Elinor chanced one day to make on the difference between him and his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5241,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI think you will like him,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cwhen you know more of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5340,\n            \"the persuasion of his regard for Elinor perhaps assisted her penetration;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5404,\n            \"No sooner did she perceive any symptom of love in his behaviour to Elinor, than she considered their serious attachment as certain, and looked forward to their marriage as rapidly approaching.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5438,\n            \"\\u201cIn a few months, my dear Marianne,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cElinor will, in all probability be settled for life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5464,\n            \"We shall miss her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5481,\n            \"Mama, how shall we do without her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5964,\n            \"Mama, the more I know of the world, the more am I convinced that I shall never see a man whom I can really love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6057,\n            \"In one circumstance only, my Marianne, may your destiny be different from hers!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6118,\n            \"He does not draw himself, indeed, but he has great pleasure in seeing the performances of other people, and I assure you he is by no means deficient in natural taste, though he has not had opportunities of improving it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6240,\n            \"but the kind of approbation which Elinor described as excited in him by the drawings of other people, was very far from that rapturous delight, which, in her opinion, could alone be called taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6480,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sure,\\u201dreplied Elinor, with a smile, \\u201cthat his dearest friends could not be dissatisfied with such commendation as that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6533,\n            \"\\u201cOf his sense and his goodness,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cno one can, I think, be in doubt, who has seen him often enough to engage him in unreserved conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6826,\n            \"When you tell me to love him as a brother, I shall no more see imperfection in his face, than I now do in his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6898,\n            \"but she required greater certainty of it to make Marianne\\u2019s conviction of their attachment agreeable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6918,\n            \"She knew that what Marianne and her mother conjectured one moment, they believed the next \\u2014 that with them, to wish was to hope, and to hope was to expect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7059,\n            \"\\u201cand be assured that I meant no offence to you, by speaking, in so quiet a way, of my own feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7303,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne was astonished to find how much the imagination of her mother and herself had outstripped the truth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7528,\n            \"She knew that his mother neither behaved to him so as to make his home comfortable at present, nor to give him any assurance that he might form a home for himself, without strictly attending to her views for his aggrandizement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7591,\n            \"She was far from depending on that result of his preference of her, which her mother and sister still considered as certain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7773,\n            \"She gave her an answer which marked her contempt, and instantly left the room, resolving that, whatever might be the inconvenience or expense of so sudden a removal, her beloved Elinor should not be exposed another week to such insinuations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7938,\n            \"He earnestly pressed her, after giving the particulars of the house and garden, to come with her daughters to Barton Park, the place of his own residence, from whence she might judge, herself, whether Barton Cottage, for the houses were in the same parish, could, by any alteration, be made comfortable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8228,\n            \"Elinor had always thought it would be more prudent for them to settle at some distance from Norland, than immediately amongst their present acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8254,\n            \"On _ that _ head, therefore, it was not for her to oppose her mother\\u2019s intention of removing into Devonshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8316,\n            \"and, therefore, though it was not a plan which brought any charm to her fancy, though it was a removal from the vicinity of Norland beyond her wishes, she made no attempt to dissuade her mother from sending a letter of acquiescence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8663,\n            \"To separate Edward and Elinor was as far from being her object as ever;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10376,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s drawings were affixed to the walls of their sitting room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13212,\n            \"I know very well that Colonel Brandon is not old enough to make his friends yet apprehensive of losing him in the course of nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13282,\n            \"But if there should by any chance happen to be a woman who is single at seven and twenty, I should not think Colonel Brandon\\u2019s being thirty-five any objection to his marrying _ her _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13462,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt would be impossible, I know,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cto convince you that a woman of seven and twenty could feel for a man of thirty-five anything near enough to love, to make him a desirable companion to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13511,\n            \"But I must object to your dooming Colonel Brandon and his wife to the constant confinement of a sick chamber, merely because he chanced to complain yesterday (a very cold damp day) of a slight rheumatic feel in one of his shoulders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13804,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have never mentioned it to her, but of course she must.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13820,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI rather think you are mistaken, for when I was talking to her yesterday of getting a new grate for the spare bedchamber, she observed that there was no immediate hurry for it, as it was not likely that the room would be wanted for some time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13923,\n            \"In Edward\\u2019s farewell there was no distinction between Elinor and me: it was the good wishes of an affectionate brother to both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13978,\n            \"And Elinor, in quitting Norland and Edward, cried not as I did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14510,\n            \"and when they caught in their faces the animating gales of a high south-westerly wind, they pitied the fears which had prevented their mother and Elinor from sharing such delightful sensations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14884,\n            \"Elinor and her mother rose up in amazement at their entrance, and while the eyes of both were fixed on him with an evident wonder and a secret admiration which equally sprung from his appearance, he apologized for his intrusion by relating its cause, in a manner so frank and so graceful that his person, which was uncommonly handsome, received additional charms from his voice and expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17057,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy love,\\u201dsaid her mother, \\u201cyou must not be offended with Elinor \\u2014 she was only in jest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17082,\n            \"I should scold her myself, if she were capable of wishing to check the delight of your conversation with our new friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17344,\n            \"and Elinor saw nothing to censure in him but a propensity, in which he strongly resembled and peculiarly delighted her sister, of saying too much what he thought on every occasion, without attention to persons or circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17385,\n            \"In hastily forming and giving his opinion of other people, in sacrificing general politeness to the enjoyment of undivided attention where his heart was engaged, and in slighting too easily the forms of worldly propriety, he displayed a want of caution which Elinor could not approve, in spite of all that he and Marianne could say in its support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17666,\n            \"Elinor was obliged, though unwillingly, to believe that the sentiments which Mrs. Jennings had assigned him for her own satisfaction, were now actually excited by her sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17830,\n            \"Sir John had dropped hints of past injuries and disappointments, which justified her belief of his being an unfortunate man, and she regarded him with respect and compassion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17985,\n            \"He is highly esteemed by all the family at the park, and I never see him myself without taking pains to converse with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18147,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy _ prot\\u00e9g\\u00e9 _, as you call him, is a sensible man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18373,\n            \"I consider him, on the contrary, as a very respectable man, who has every body\\u2019s good word, and nobody\\u2019s notice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18514,\n            \"I can only pronounce him to be a sensible man, well-bred, well-informed, of gentle address, and, I believe, possessing an amiable heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18894,\n            \"Elinor could not be surprised at their attachment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18903,\n            \"She only wished that it were less openly shown;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19234,\n            \"Her heart was not so much at ease, nor her satisfaction in their amusements so pure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19252,\n            \"They afforded her no companion that could make amends for what she had left behind, nor that could teach her to think of Norland with less regret than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19299,\n            \"although the latter was an everlasting talker, and from the first had regarded her with a kindness which ensured her a large share of her discourse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19341,\n            \"and had Elinor\\u2019s memory been equal to her means of improvement, she might have known very early in their acquaintance all the particulars of Mr. Jennings\\u2019 s last illness, and what he said to his wife a few minutes before he died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19427,\n            \"Towards her husband and mother she was the same as to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19482,\n            \"and though she did not oppose the parties arranged by her husband, provided every thing were conducted in style and her two eldest children attended her, she never appeared to receive more enjoyment from them than she might have experienced in sitting at home;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19529,\n            \"\\u2014 and so little did her presence add to the pleasure of the others, by any share in their conversation, that they were sometimes only reminded of her being amongst them by her solicitude about her troublesome boys.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19617,\n            \"Her admiration and regard, even her sisterly regard, was all his own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19659,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, unfortunately for himself, had no such encouragement to think only of Marianne, and in conversing with Elinor he found the greatest consolation for the indifference of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19873,\n            \"and then they may be more easy to define and to justify than they now are, by any body but herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20413,\n            \"Marianne told her, with the greatest delight, that Willoughby had given her a horse, one that he had bred himself on his estate in Somersetshire, and which was exactly calculated to carry a woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20452,\n            \"Without considering that it was not in her mother\\u2019s plan to keep any horse, that if she were to alter her resolution in favour of this gift, she must buy another for the servant, and keep a servant to ride it, and after all, build a stable to receive them, she had accepted the present without hesitation, and told her sister of it in raptures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20726,\n            \"I have not known him long indeed, but I am much better acquainted with him, than I am with any other creature in the world, except yourself and mama.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21317,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou have said so,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201calmost every day since they first met on High-church Down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21608,\n            \"When Mrs. Jennings attacked her one evening at the park, to give the name of the young man who was Elinor\\u2019s particular favourite, which had been long a matter of great curiosity to her, Margaret answered by looking at her sister, and saying, \\u201cI must not tell, may I, Elinor?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21989,\n            \"\\u201d Most grateful did Elinor feel to Lady Middleton for observing, at this moment, \\u201cthat it rained very hard,\\u201dthough she believed the interruption to proceed less from any attention to her, than from her ladyship\\u2019s great dislike of all such inelegant subjects of raillery as delighted her husband and mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22340,\n            \"\\u2014 and Mrs. Dashwood, who had already a cold, was persuaded by Elinor to stay at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22364,\n            \"Their intended excursion to Whitwell turned out very different from what Elinor had expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23104,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor then heard Willoughby say, in a low voice to Marianne, \\u201cThere are some people who cannot bear a party of pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24243,\n            \"and when I come to see you, I hope you will have new-furnished it, for it wanted it very much when I was there six years ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24289,\n            \"and Elinor found that in her resolution to know where they had been, she had actually made her own woman enquire of Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s groom;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24319,\n            \"and that she had by that method been informed that they had gone to Allenham, and spent a considerable time there in walking about the garden and going all over the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24397,\n            \"As soon as they left the dining-room, Elinor enquired of her about it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24444,\n            \"\\u201cWhy should you imagine, Elinor, that we did not go there, or that we did not see the house?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24800,\n            \"and after a ten minutes\\u2019 interval of earnest thought, she came to her sister again, and said with great good humour, \\u201cPerhaps, Elinor, it _ was _ rather ill-judged in me to go to Allenham;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25011,\n            \"\\u201d Could Elinor have listened to her without interruption from the others, she would have described every room in the house with equal delight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25504,\n            \"It was engrossed by the extraordinary silence of her sister and Willoughby on the subject, which they must know to be peculiarly interesting to them all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25553,\n            \"Why they should not openly acknowledge to her mother and herself, what their constant behaviour to each other declared to have taken place, Elinor could not imagine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25583,\n            \"She could easily conceive that marriage might not be immediately in their power;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25654,\n            \"But for this strange kind of secrecy maintained by them relative to their engagement, which in fact concealed nothing at all, she could not account;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25682,\n            \"and it was so wholly contradictory to their general opinions and practice, that a doubt sometimes entered her mind of their being really engaged, and this doubt was enough to prevent her making any inquiry of Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26767,\n            \"\\u201cI do not ask you to come in the morning, for we must walk to the park, to call on Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26809,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s visit to Lady Middleton took place the next day, and two of her daughters went with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27581,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s uneasiness was at least equal to her mother\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27983,\n            \"I have thought it all over I assure you, and I can perfectly account for every thing that at first seemed strange to me as well as to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28037,\n            \"\\u2014 but you, Elinor, who love to doubt where you can \\u2014 it will not satisfy _ you _, I know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28062,\n            \"but you shall not talk _ me _ out of my trust in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28201,\n            \"You will tell me, I know, that this may or may _ not _ have happened;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28220,\n            \"but I will listen to no cavil, unless you can point out any other method of understanding the affair as satisfactory at this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28267,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen you would have told me, that it might or might not have happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28328,\n            \"You are resolved to think him blameable, because he took leave of us with less affection than his usual behaviour has shown.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28439,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI can hardly tell myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28578,\n            \"But you really do admit the justice of what I have said in his defence?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28672,\n            \"my dear child, do you accuse Willoughby and Marianne of concealment?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28685,\n            \"This is strange indeed, when your eyes have been reproaching them every day for incautiousness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28702,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI want no proof of their affection,\\u201dsaid Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28733,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYet not a syllable has been said to you on the subject, by either of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28910,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI confess,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cthat every circumstance except _ one _ is in favour of their engagement;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28934,\n            \"but that _ one _ is the total silence of both on the subject, and with me it almost outweighs every other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28965,\n            \"You must think wretchedly indeed of Willoughby, if, after all that has openly passed between them, you can doubt the nature of the terms on which they are together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29014,\n            \"Do you suppose him really indifferent to her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29042,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut with a strange kind of tenderness, if he can leave her with such indifference, such carelessness of the future, as you attribute to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29140,\n            \"If you were to see them at the altar, you would suppose they were going to be married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29197,\n            \"You cannot doubt your sister\\u2019s wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29245,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI hope not, I believe not,\\u201dcried Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29268,\n            \"and suspicion of his integrity cannot be more painful to yourself than to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29638,\n            \"and Elinor was then at liberty to think over the representations of her mother, to acknowledge the probability of many, and hope for the justice of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30227,\n            \"Her mother was surprised, and Elinor again became uneasy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30256,\n            \"\\u201cRemember, Elinor,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201chow very often Sir John fetches our letters himself from the post, and carries them to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30318,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor could not deny the truth of this, and she tried to find in it a motive sufficient for their silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30342,\n            \"But there was one method so direct, so simple, and in her opinion so eligible of knowing the real state of the affair, and of instantly removing all mystery, that she could not help suggesting it to her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30386,\n            \"\\u201cWhy do you not ask Marianne at once,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwhether she is or she is not engaged to Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30918,\n            \"They walked along the road through the valley, and chiefly in silence, for Marianne\\u2019s _ mind _ could not be controlled, and Elinor, satisfied with gaining one point, would not then attempt more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31197,\n            \"and Elinor, to screen Marianne from particularity, as she felt almost certain of its not being Willoughby, quickened her pace and kept up with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31388,\n            \"He was welcomed by them all with great cordiality, but especially by Marianne, who showed more warmth of regard in her reception of him than even Elinor herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31479,\n            \"He was confused, seemed scarcely sensible of pleasure in seeing them, looked neither rapturous nor gay, said little but what was forced from him by questions, and distinguished Elinor by no mark of affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32158,\n            \"and directing her attention to their visitor, endeavoured to support something like discourse with him, by talking of their present residence, its conveniences, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32776,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps,\\u201dsaid Elinor, smiling, \\u201cwe may come to the same point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32959,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor smiled again, to hear her sister describing so accurately their future expenses at Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33068,\n            \"\\u201cWe are all unanimous in that wish, I suppose,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cin spite of the insufficiency of wealth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33163,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou must begin your improvements on this house,\\u201dobserved Elinor, \\u201cand your difficulties will soon vanish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33467,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, then, you would bestow it as a reward on that person who wrote the ablest defence of your favourite maxim, that no one can ever be in love more than once in their life \\u2014 your opinion on that point is unchanged, I presume?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33643,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNor do I think it a part of Marianne\\u2019s,\\u201dsaid Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33701,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe you are right,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cand yet I have always set her down as a lively girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33727,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have frequently detected myself in such kind of mistakes,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cin a total misapprehension of character in some point or other: fancying people so much more gay or grave, or ingenious or stupid than they really are, and I can hardly tell why or in what the deception originated.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33819,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut I thought it was right, Elinor,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cto be guided wholly by the opinion of other people.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33862,\n            \"This has always been your doctrine, I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33954,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou have not been able to bring your sister over to your plan of general civility,\\u201dsaid Edward to Elinor, \\u201cDo you gain no ground?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34247,\n            \"but trying to laugh off the subject, she said to him, \\u201cDo not you know my sister well enough to understand what she means?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34431,\n            \"He joined her and Marianne in the breakfast-room the next morning before the others were down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34869,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI suspect,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cthat to avoid one kind of affectation, Edward here falls into another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35407,\n            \"the only difference in their conclusions was, that what Marianne considered as a free gift from her sister, Elinor was conscious must have been procured by some theft or contrivance unknown to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35636,\n            \"and this prepared a future mine of raillery against the devoted Elinor, which nothing but the newness of their acquaintance with Edward could have prevented from being immediately sprung.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35667,\n            \"But, as it was, she only learned, from some very significant looks, how far their penetration, founded on Margaret\\u2019s instructions, extended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37397,\n            \"\\u201d This desponding turn of mind, though it could not be communicated to Mrs. Dashwood, gave additional pain to them all in the parting, which shortly took place, and left an uncomfortable impression on Elinor\\u2019s feelings especially, which required some trouble and time to subdue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37451,\n            \"But as it was her determination to subdue it, and to prevent herself from appearing to suffer more than what all her family suffered on his going away, she did not adopt the method so judiciously employed by Marianne, on a similar occasion, to augment and fix her sorrow, by seeking silence, solitude and idleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37531,\n            \"Elinor sat down to her drawing-table as soon as he was out of the house, busily employed herself the whole day, neither sought nor avoided the mention of his name, appeared to interest herself almost as much as ever in the general concerns of the family, and if, by this conduct, she did not lessen her own grief, it was at least prevented from unnecessary increase, and her mother and sisters were spared much solicitude on her account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37730,\n            \"Without shutting herself up from her family, or leaving the house in determined solitude to avoid them, or lying awake the whole night to indulge meditation, Elinor found every day afforded her leisure enough to think of Edward, and of Edward\\u2019s behaviour, in every possible variety which the different state of her spirits at different times could produce, \\u2014 with tenderness, pity, approbation, censure, and doubt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37901,\n            \"From a reverie of this kind, as she sat at her drawing-table, she was roused one morning, soon after Edward\\u2019s leaving them, by the arrival of company.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38014,\n            \"She was sitting near the window, and as soon as Sir John perceived her, he left the rest of the party to the ceremony of knocking at the door, and stepping across the turf, obliged her to open the casement to speak to him, though the space was so short between the door and the window, as to make it hardly possible to speak at one without being heard at the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38093,\n            \"\\u201cWell,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cwe have brought you some strangers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38108,\n            \"How do you like them?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38137,\n            \"Charlotte is very pretty, I can tell you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38147,\n            \"You may see her if you look this way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38157,\n            \"\\u201d As Elinor was certain of seeing her in a couple of minutes, without taking that liberty, she begged to be excused.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38289,\n            \"I have brought my other son and daughter to see you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38923,\n            \"\\u201cYou may believe how glad we all were to see them,\\u201dadded Mrs. Jennings, leaning forward towards Elinor, and speaking in a low voice as if she meant to be heard by no one else, though they were seated on different sides of the room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38976,\n            \"\\u201cbut, however, I can\\u2019t help wishing they had not travelled quite so fast, nor made such a long journey of it, for they came all round by London upon account of some business, for you know (nodding significantly and pointing to her daughter) it was wrong in her situation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39036,\n            \"I wanted her to stay at home and rest this morning, but she would come with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39644,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThey mean no less to be civil and kind to us now,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cby these frequent invitations, than by those which we received from them a few weeks ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39777,\n            \"\\u201d said she, seating herself between Elinor and Marianne, \\u201cfor it is so bad a day I was afraid you might not come, which would be a shocking thing, as we go away again tomorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40757,\n            \"His temper might perhaps be a little soured by finding, like many others of his sex, that through some unaccountable bias in favour of beauty, he was the husband of a very silly woman \\u2014 but she knew that this kind of blunder was too common for any sensible man to be lastingly hurt by it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40898,\n            \"\\u201cOh, my dear Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Palmer soon afterwards, \\u201cI have got such a favour to ask of you and your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40956,\n            \"You cannot think how happy I shall be!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41374,\n            \"\\u201d She surprised Elinor very much as they returned into the drawing-room, by asking her whether she did not like Mr. Palmer excessively.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41415,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell \\u2014 I am so glad you do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41426,\n            \"I thought you would, he is so pleasant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41436,\n            \"and Mr. Palmer is excessively pleased with you and your sisters I can tell you, and you can\\u2019t think how disappointed he will be if you don\\u2019t come to Cleveland.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41473,\n            \"\\u2014 I can\\u2019t imagine why you should object to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41486,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was again obliged to decline her invitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41509,\n            \"She thought it probable that as they lived in the same county, Mrs. Palmer might be able to give some more particular account of Willoughby\\u2019s general character, than could be gathered from the Middletons\\u2019 partial acquaintance with him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41554,\n            \"and she was eager to gain from any one, such a confirmation of his merits as might remove the possibility of fear from Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41580,\n            \"She began by inquiring if they saw much of Mr. Willoughby at Cleveland, and whether they were intimately acquainted with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41723,\n            \"but if he were ever so much there, I do not think Mr. Palmer would visit him, for he is in the opposition, you know, and besides it is such a way off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41762,\n            \"I know why you inquire about him, very well;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41799,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cUpon my word,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cyou know much more of the matter than I do, if you have any reason to expect such a match.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41853,\n            \"I assure you I heard of it in my way through town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41882,\n            \"\\u2014 I met Colonel Brandon Monday morning in Bond-street, just before we left town, and he told me of it directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41961,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut I do assure you it was so, for all that, and I will tell you how it happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42248,\n            \"I assure you it was a great compliment if he was, for he hardly ever falls in love with any body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42297,\n            \"that is, I do not believe many people are acquainted with him, because Combe Magna is so far off;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42319,\n            \"but they all think him extremely agreeable I assure you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42394,\n            \"However, I don\\u2019t think her hardly at all handsomer than you, I assure you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42413,\n            \"for I think you both excessively pretty, and so does Mr. Palmer too I am sure, though we could not get him to own it last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42473,\n            \"\\u201cI am so glad we are got acquainted at last,\\u201dcontinued Charlotte.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42489,\n            \"\\u2014 \\u201cAnd now I hope we shall always be great friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42502,\n            \"You can\\u2019t think how much I longed to see you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42551,\n            \"I hope you will be a great deal at Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42650,\n            \"But mama did not think the match good enough for me, otherwise Sir John would have mentioned it to the Colonel, and we should have been married immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42717,\n            \"but if mama had not objected to it, I dare say he would have liked it of all things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43710,\n            \"Their manners were particularly civil, and Elinor soon allowed them credit for some kind of sense, when she saw with what constant and judicious attention they were making themselves agreeable to Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44547,\n            \"She did her best when thus called on, by speaking of Lady Middleton with more warmth than she felt, though with far less than Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44694,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have a notion,\\u201dsaid Lucy, \\u201cyou think the little Middletons rather too much indulged;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44750,\n            \"I cannot bear them if they are tame and quiet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44833,\n            \"I suppose you were very sorry to leave Sussex.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45135,\n            \"For my part, I think they are vastly agreeable, provided they dress smart and behave civil.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45216,\n            \"I suppose your brother was quite a beau, Miss Dashwood, before he married, as he was so rich?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45238,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cUpon my word,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cI cannot tell you, for I do not perfectly comprehend the meaning of the word.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45266,\n            \"But this I can say, that if he ever was a beau before he married, he is one still for there is not the smallest alteration in him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45341,\n            \"\\u2014 you will make Miss Dashwood believe you think of nothing else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45380,\n            \"The vulgar freedom and folly of the eldest left her no recommendation, and as Elinor was not blinded by the beauty, or the shrewd look of the youngest, to her want of real elegance and artlessness, she left the house without any wish of knowing them better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45509,\n            \"And to be better acquainted therefore, Elinor soon found was their inevitable lot, for as Sir John was entirely on the side of the Miss Steeles, their party would be too strong for opposition, and that kind of intimacy must be submitted to, which consists of sitting an hour or two together in the same room almost every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45667,\n            \"and Elinor had not seen them more than twice, before the eldest of them wished her joy on her sister\\u2019s having been so lucky as to make a conquest of a very smart beau since she came to Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45745,\n            \"And I hope you may have as good luck yourself soon, \\u2014 but perhaps you may have a friend in the corner already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45820,\n            \"and since Edward\\u2019s visit, they had never dined together without his drinking to her best affections with so much significancy and so many nods and winks, as to excite general attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45892,\n            \"The Miss Steeles, as she expected, had now all the benefit of these jokes, and in the eldest of them they raised a curiosity to know the name of the gentleman alluded to, which, though often impertinently expressed, was perfectly of a piece with her general inquisitiveness into the concerns of their family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46176,\n            \"but nothing more of it was said, and for the first time in her life, she thought Mrs. Jennings deficient either in curiosity after petty information, or in a disposition to communicate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46214,\n            \"The manner in which Miss Steele had spoken of Edward, increased her curiosity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46229,\n            \"for it struck her as being rather ill-natured, and suggested the suspicion of that lady\\u2019s knowing, or fancying herself to know something to his disadvantage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46261,\n            \"\\u2014 But her curiosity was unavailing, for no farther notice was taken of Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s name by Miss Steele when alluded to, or even openly mentioned by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46356,\n            \"and to the invariable coldness of her behaviour towards them, which checked every endeavour at intimacy on their side, Elinor principally attributed that preference of herself which soon became evident in the manners of both, but especially of Lucy, who missed no opportunity of engaging her in conversation, or of striving to improve their acquaintance by an easy and frank communication of her sentiments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46614,\n            \"\\u201cYou will think my question an odd one, I dare say,\\u201dsaid Lucy to her one day, as they were walking together from the park to the cottage \\u2014 \\u201cbut pray, are you personally acquainted with your sister-in-law\\u2019s mother, Mrs. Ferrars?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46847,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor made her a civil reply, and they walked on for a few minutes in silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47191,\n            \"\\u201d And she did not feel much delighted with the idea of such a sister-in-law.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47355,\n            \"for I dare say he never dropped the smallest hint of it to you or any of your family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47401,\n            \"Not a soul of all my relations know of it but Anne, and I never should have mentioned it to you, if I had not felt the greatest dependence in the world upon your secrecy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47466,\n            \"And I do not think Mr. Ferrars can be displeased, when he knows I have trusted you, because I know he has the highest opinion in the world of all your family, and looks upon yourself and the other Miss Dashwoods quite as his own sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47544,\n            \"but at length forcing herself to speak, and to speak cautiously, she said, with calmness of manner, which tolerably well concealed her surprise and solicitude \\u2014 \\u201cMay I ask if your engagement is of long standing?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47619,\n            \"\\u201cI did not know,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cthat you were even acquainted till the other day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47831,\n            \"Though you do not know him so well as me, Miss Dashwood, you must have seen enough of him to be sensible he is very capable of making a woman sincerely attached to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48092,\n            \"You knew nothing of me, or my family, and, therefore, there could be no _ occasion _ for ever mentioning my name to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48428,\n            \"\\u201cI am sure,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cI have no doubt in the world of your faithfully keeping this secret, because you must know of what importance it is to us, not to have it reach his mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48615,\n            \"\\u201cI was afraid you would think I was taking a great liberty with you,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cin telling you all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48642,\n            \"I have not known you long to be sure, personally at least, but I have known you and all your family by description a great while;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48671,\n            \"and as soon as I saw you, I felt almost as if you was an old acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48690,\n            \"Besides in the present case, I really thought some explanation was due to you after my making such particular inquiries about Edward\\u2019s mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49138,\n            \"He was so miserable when he left us at Longstaple, to go to you, that I was afraid you would think him quite ill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49230,\n            \"\\u201cI remember he told us, that he had been staying a fortnight with some friends near Plymouth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49250,\n            \"\\u201d She remembered too, her own surprise at the time, at his mentioning nothing farther of those friends, at his total silence with respect even to their names.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49723,\n            \"Fortunately for her, they had now reached the cottage, and the conversation could be continued no farther.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49743,\n            \"After sitting with them a few minutes, the Miss Steeles returned to the Park, and Elinor was then at liberty to think and be wretched.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49894,\n            \"and Edward\\u2019s visit near Plymouth, his melancholy state of mind, his dissatisfaction at his own prospects, his uncertain behaviour towards herself, the intimate knowledge of the Miss Steeles as to Norland and their family connections, which had often surprised her, the picture, the letter, the ring, formed altogether such a body of evidence, as overcame every fear of condemning him unfairly, and established as a fact, which no partiality could set aside, his ill-treatment of herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50088,\n            \"Her mother, sisters, Fanny, all had been conscious of his regard for her at Norland;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50506,\n            \"Supported by the conviction of having done nothing to merit her present unhappiness, and consoled by the belief that Edward had done nothing to forfeit her esteem, she thought she could even now, under the first smart of the heavy blow, command herself enough to guard every suspicion of the truth from her mother and sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50567,\n            \"And so well was she able to answer her own expectations, that when she joined them at dinner only two hours after she had first suffered the extinction of all her dearest hopes, no one would have supposed from the appearance of the sisters, that Elinor was mourning in secret over obstacles which must divide her for ever from the object of her love, and that Marianne was internally dwelling on the perfections of a man, of whose whole heart she felt thoroughly possessed, and whom she expected to see in every carriage which drove near their house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50672,\n            \"The necessity of concealing from her mother and Marianne, what had been entrusted in confidence to herself, though it obliged her to unceasing exertion, was no aggravation of Elinor\\u2019s distress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50708,\n            \"On the contrary it was a relief to her, to be spared the communication of what would give such affliction to them, and to be saved likewise from hearing that condemnation of Edward, which would probably flow from the excess of their partial affection for herself, and which was more than she felt equal to support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50769,\n            \"From their counsel, or their conversation, she knew she could receive no assistance, their tenderness and sorrow must add to her distress, while her self-command would neither receive encouragement from their example nor from their praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50891,\n            \"She wanted to hear many particulars of their engagement repeated again, she wanted more clearly to understand what Lucy really felt for Edward, whether there were any sincerity in her declaration of tender regard for him, and she particularly wanted to convince Lucy, by her readiness to enter on the matter again, and her calmness in conversing on it, that she was no otherwise interested in it than as a friend, which she very much feared her involuntary agitation, in their morning discourse, must have left at least doubtful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51494,\n            \"Elinor, who foresaw a fairer opening for the point she had in view, in such a party as this was likely to be, more at liberty among themselves under the tranquil and well-bred direction of Lady Middleton than when her husband united them together in one noisy purpose, immediately accepted the invitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51637,\n            \"it produced not one novelty of thought or expression, and nothing could be less interesting than the whole of their discourse both in the dining parlour and drawing room: to the latter, the children accompanied them, and while they remained there, she was too well convinced of the impossibility of engaging Lucy\\u2019s attention to attempt it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52183,\n            \"\\u201cPerhaps,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cif I should happen to cut out, I may be of some use to Miss Lucy Steele, in rolling her papers for her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52430,\n            \"Lucy made room for her with ready attention, and the two fair rivals were thus seated side by side at the same table, and, with the utmost harmony, engaged in forwarding the same work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52554,\n            \"\\u201cI should be undeserving of the confidence you have honoured me with, if I felt no desire for its continuance, or no farther curiosity on its subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53916,\n            \"now my plan is that he should take orders as soon as he can, and then through your interest, which I am sure you would be kind enough to use out of friendship for him, and I hope out of some regard to me, your brother might be persuaded to give him Norland living;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54282,\n            \"and I do really believe, that if you was to say to me, \\u2018 I advise you by all means to put an end to your engagement with Edward Ferrars, it will be more for the happiness of both of you,\\u2019I should resolve upon doing it immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54336,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor blushed for the insincerity of Edward\\u2019s future wife, and replied, \\u201cThis compliment would effectually frighten me from giving any opinion on the subject had I formed one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54396,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201c\\u2019Tis because you are an indifferent person,\\u201dsaid Lucy, with some pique, and laying a particular stress on those words, \\u201cthat your judgment might justly have such weight with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54460,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor thought it wisest to make no answer to this, lest they might provoke each other to an unsuitable increase of ease and unreserve;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54592,\n            \"To be sure, your brother and sister will ask you to come to them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54608,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt will not be in my power to accept their invitation if they do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54701,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was soon called to the card-table by the conclusion of the first rubber, and the confidential discourse of the two ladies was therefore at an end, to which both of them submitted without any reluctance, for nothing had been said on either side to make them dislike each other less than they had done before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54793,\n            \"but that he had not even the chance of being tolerably happy in marriage, which sincere affection on _ her _ side would have given, for self-interest alone could induce a woman to keep a man to an engagement, of which she seemed so thoroughly aware that he was weary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55170,\n            \"Elinor, without observing the varying complexion of her sister, and the animated look which spoke no indifference to the plan, immediately gave a grateful but absolute denial for both, in which she believed herself to be speaking their united inclinations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55776,\n            \"But my mother, my dearest, kindest mother, \\u2014 I feel the justice of what Elinor has urged, and if she were to be made less happy, less comfortable by our absence \\u2014 Oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55852,\n            \"and Elinor, who now understood her sister, and saw to what indifference to almost every thing else she was carried by her eagerness to be with Willoughby again, made no farther direct opposition to the plan, and merely referred it to her mother\\u2019s decision, from whom however she scarcely expected to receive any support in her endeavour to prevent a visit, which she could not approve of for Marianne, and which on her own account she had particular reasons to avoid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55943,\n            \"Whatever Marianne was desirous of, her mother would be eager to promote \\u2014 she could not expect to influence the latter to cautiousness of conduct in an affair respecting which she had never been able to inspire her with distrust;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56380,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThough with your usual anxiety for our happiness,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cyou have been obviating every impediment to the present scheme which occurred to you, there is still one objection which, in my opinion, cannot be so easily removed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56485,\n            \"though I think very well of Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s heart, she is not a woman whose society can afford us pleasure, or whose protection will give us consequence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56820,\n            \"she would, perhaps, expect some from improving her acquaintance with her sister-in-law\\u2019s family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56842,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor had often wished for an opportunity of attempting to weaken her mother\\u2019s dependence on the attachment of Edward and herself, that the shock might be less when the whole truth were revealed, and now on this attack, though almost hopeless of success, she forced herself to begin her design by saying, as calmly as she could, \\u201cI like Edward Ferrars very much, and shall always be glad to see him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56925,\n            \"but as to the rest of the family, it is a matter of perfect indifference to me, whether I am ever known to them or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57135,\n            \"With regard to herself, it was now a matter of unconcern whether she went to town or not, and when she saw her mother so thoroughly pleased with the plan, and her sister exhilarated by it in look, voice, and manner, restored to all her usual animation, and elevated to more than her usual gaiety, she could not be dissatisfied with the cause, and would hardly allow herself to distrust the consequence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57270,\n            \"Her mother\\u2019s affliction was hardly less, and Elinor was the only one of the three, who seemed to consider the separation as any thing short of eternal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57349,\n            \"Elinor could not find herself in the carriage with Mrs. Jennings, and beginning a journey to London under her protection, and as her guest, without wondering at her own situation, so short had their acquaintance with that lady been, so wholly unsuited were they in age and disposition, and so many had been her objections against such a measure only a few days before!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57573,\n            \"and Elinor was resolved not only upon gaining every new light as to his character which her own observation or the intelligence of others could give her, but likewise upon watching his behaviour to her sister with such zealous attention, as to ascertain what he was and what he meant, before many meetings had taken place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57633,\n            \"Should the result of her observations be unfavourable, she was determined at all events to open the eyes of her sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57731,\n            \"She sat in silence almost all the way, wrapt in her own meditations, and scarcely ever voluntarily speaking, except when any object of picturesque beauty within their view drew from her an exclamation of delight exclusively addressed to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57991,\n            \"As dinner was not to be ready in less than two hours from their arrival, Elinor determined to employ the interval in writing to her mother, and sat down for that purpose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58253,\n            \"but there was a flutter in them which prevented their giving much pleasure to her sister, and this agitation increased as the evening drew on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58538,\n            \"and she felt particularly hurt that a man so partial to her sister should perceive that she experienced nothing but grief and disappointment in seeing him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58616,\n            \"Elinor answered in some distress that she was, and then talked of head-aches, low spirits, and over fatigues;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58640,\n            \"and of every thing to which she could decently attribute her sister\\u2019s behaviour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58656,\n            \"He heard her with the most earnest attention, but seeming to recollect himself, said no more on the subject, and began directly to speak of his pleasure at seeing them in London, making the usual inquiries about their journey, and the friends they had left behind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59235,\n            \"However, I got a very good husband, and I don\\u2019t know what the greatest beauty can do more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59422,\n            \"They had not long finished their breakfast before Mrs. Palmer\\u2019s barouche stopped at the door, and in a few minutes she came laughing into the room: so delighted to see them all, that it was hard to say whether she received most pleasure from meeting her mother or the Miss Dashwoods again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59481,\n            \"So surprised at their coming to town, though it was what she had rather expected all along;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59500,\n            \"so angry at their accepting her mother\\u2019s invitation after having declined her own, though at the same time she would never have forgiven them if they had not come!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59579,\n            \"\\u201d After an hour or two spent in what her mother called comfortable chat, or in other words, in every variety of inquiry concerning all their acquaintance on Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s side, and in laughter without cause on Mrs. Palmer\\u2019s, it was proposed by the latter that they should all accompany her to some shops where she had business that morning, to which Mrs. Jennings and Elinor readily consented, as having likewise some purchases to make themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59849,\n            \"and no sooner had they entered the house than Marianne flew eagerly up stairs, and when Elinor followed, she found her turning from the table with a sorrowful countenance, which declared that no Willoughby had been there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60107,\n            \"\\u201d She determined, after some consideration, that if appearances continued many days longer as unpleasant as they now were, she would represent in the strongest manner to her mother the necessity of some serious enquiry into the affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60192,\n            \"and Elinor was obliged to assist in making a whist table for the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60628,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, my dear, I\\u2019ll warrant you we do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61019,\n            \"Pleased to find herself more comfortably situated in that particular than she had expected, Elinor was very willing to compound for the want of much real enjoyment from any of their evening parties, which, whether at home or abroad, formed only for cards, could have little to amuse her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61093,\n            \"he came to look at Marianne and talk to Elinor, who often derived more satisfaction from conversing with him than from any other daily occurrence, but who saw at the same time with much concern his continued regard for her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61145,\n            \"It grieved her to see the earnestness with which he often watched Marianne, and his spirits were certainly worse than when at Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61274,\n            \"This event, while it raised the spirits of Elinor, restored to those of her sister all, and more than all, their former agitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61346,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s thoughts were full of what might be passing in Berkeley Street during their absence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61364,\n            \"but a moment\\u2019s glance at her sister when they returned was enough to inform her, that Willoughby had paid no second visit there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61697,\n            \"but when the hour of appointment drew near, necessary as it was in common civility to Mrs. Jennings, that they should both attend her on such a visit, Elinor had some difficulty in persuading her sister to go, for still she had seen nothing of Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61773,\n            \"Elinor found, when the evening was over, that disposition is not materially altered by a change of abode, for although scarcely settled in town, Sir John had contrived to collect around him, nearly twenty young people, and to amuse them with a ball.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62284,\n            \"Impatient in this situation to be doing something that might lead to her sister\\u2019s relief, Elinor resolved to write the next morning to her mother, and hoped by awakening her fears for the health of Marianne, to procure those inquiries which had been so long delayed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62336,\n            \"and she was still more eagerly bent on this measure by perceiving after breakfast on the morrow, that Marianne was again writing to Willoughby, for she could not suppose it to be to any other person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62430,\n            \"Elinor was very earnest in her application to her mother, relating all that had passed, her suspicions of Willoughby\\u2019s inconstancy, urging her by every plea of duty and affection to demand from Marianne an account of her real situation with respect to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62479,\n            \"Her letter was scarcely finished, when a rap foretold a visitor, and Colonel Brandon was announced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62561,\n            \"Elinor, persuaded that he had some communication to make in which her sister was concerned, impatiently expected its opening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62650,\n            \"After a pause of several minutes, their silence was broken, by his asking her in a voice of some agitation, when he was to congratulate her on the acquisition of a brother?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62686,\n            \"Elinor was not prepared for such a question, and having no answer ready, was obliged to adopt the simple and common expedient, of asking what he meant?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62740,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt cannot be generally known,\\u201dreturned Elinor, \\u201cfor her own family do not know it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62762,\n            \"\\u201d He looked surprised and said, \\u201cI beg your pardon, I am afraid my inquiry has been impertinent;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62822,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBy many \\u2014 by some of whom you know nothing, by others with whom you are most intimate, Mrs. Jennings, Mrs. Palmer, and the Middletons.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62856,\n            \"But still I might not have believed it, for where the mind is perhaps rather unwilling to be convinced, it will always find something to support its doubts, if I had not, when the servant let me in today, accidentally seen a letter in his hand, directed to Mr. Willoughby in your sister\\u2019s writing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62963,\n            \"Excuse me, Miss Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62969,\n            \"I believe I have been wrong in saying so much, but I hardly know what to do, and on your prudence I have the strongest dependence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63027,\n            \"\\u201d These words, which conveyed to Elinor a direct avowal of his love for her sister, affected her very much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63085,\n            \"The real state of things between Willoughby and her sister was so little known to herself, that in endeavouring to explain it, she might be as liable to say too much as too little.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63122,\n            \"Yet as she was convinced that Marianne\\u2019s affection for Willoughby, could leave no hope of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s success, whatever the event of that affection might be, and at the same time wished to shield her conduct from censure, she thought it most prudent and kind, after some consideration, to say more than she really knew or believed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63190,\n            \"She acknowledged, therefore, that though she had never been informed by themselves of the terms on which they stood with each other, of their mutual affection she had no doubt, and of their correspondence she was not astonished to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63235,\n            \"He listened to her with silent attention, and on her ceasing to speak, rose directly from his seat, and after saying in a voice of emotion, \\u201cto your sister I wish all imaginable happiness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63314,\n            \"she was left, on the contrary, with a melancholy impression of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s unhappiness, and was prevented even from wishing it removed, by her anxiety for the very event that must confirm it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63357,\n            \"Nothing occurred during the next three or four days, to make Elinor regret what she had done, in applying to her mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63645,\n            \"After some time spent in saying little or doing less, Lady Middleton sat down to Cassino, and as Marianne was not in spirits for moving about, she and Elinor luckily succeeding to chairs, placed themselves at no great distance from the table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63692,\n            \"They had not remained in this manner long, before Elinor perceived Willoughby, standing within a few yards of them, in earnest conversation with a very fashionable looking young woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63783,\n            \"At that moment she first perceived him, and her whole countenance glowing with sudden delight, she would have moved towards him instantly, had not her sister caught hold of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64492,\n            \"\\u201d With difficulty however could she prevent her from following him herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64565,\n            \"In a short time Elinor saw Willoughby quit the room by the door towards the staircase, and telling Marianne that he was gone, urged the impossibility of speaking to him again that evening, as a fresh argument for her to be calm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64611,\n            \"She instantly begged her sister would entreat Lady Middleton to take them home, as she was too miserable to stay a minute longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64745,\n            \"She was soon undressed and in bed, and as she seemed desirous of being alone, her sister then left her, and while she waited the return of Mrs. Jennings, had leisure enough for thinking over the past.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64854,\n            \"Her indignation would have been still stronger than it was, had she not witnessed that embarrassment which seemed to speak a consciousness of his own misconduct, and prevented her from believing him so unprincipled as to have been sporting with the affections of her sister from the first, without any design that would bear investigation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65129,\n            \"In this situation, Elinor, roused from sleep by her agitation and sobs, first perceived her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65148,\n            \"and after observing her for a few moments with silent anxiety, said, in a tone of the most considerate gentleness, \\u201cMarianne, may I ask \\u2014?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65179,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, Elinor,\\u201dshe replied, \\u201cask nothing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65287,\n            \"Elinor paid her every quiet and unobtrusive attention in her power;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65299,\n            \"and she would have tried to sooth and tranquilize her still more, had not Marianne entreated her, with all the eagerness of the most nervous irritability, not to speak to her for the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65420,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s attention was then all employed, not in urging her, not in pitying her, nor in appearing to regard her, but in endeavouring to engage Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s notice entirely to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65528,\n            \"Elinor, who saw as plainly by this, as if she had seen the direction, that it must come from Willoughby, felt immediately such a sickness at heart as made her hardly able to hold up her head, and sat in such a general tremour as made her fear it impossible to escape Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65640,\n            \"Of Elinor\\u2019s distress, she was too busily employed in measuring lengths of worsted for her rug, to see any thing at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65775,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, though never less disposed to speak than at that moment, obliged herself to answer such an attack as this, and, therefore, trying to smile, replied, \\u201cAnd have you really, Ma\\u2019am, talked yourself into a persuasion of my sister\\u2019s being engaged to Mr. Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66040,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed, Ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Elinor, very seriously, \\u201cyou are mistaken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66089,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings laughed again, but Elinor had not spirits to say more, and eager at all events to know what Willoughby had written, hurried away to their room, where, on opening the door, she saw Marianne stretched on the bed, almost choked by grief, one letter in her hand, and two or three others lying by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66847,\n            \"In her earnest meditations on the contents of the letter, on the depravity of that mind which could dictate it, and probably, on the very different mind of a very different person, who had no other connection whatever with the affair than what her heart gave him with every thing that passed, Elinor forgot the immediate distress of her sister, forgot that she had three letters on her lap yet unread, and so entirely forgot how long she had been in the room, that when on hearing a carriage drive up to the door, she went to the window to see who could be coming so unreasonably early, she was all astonishment to perceive Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s chariot, which she knew had not been ordered till one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67026,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, with a thoroughly good-humoured concern for its cause, admitted the excuse most readily, and Elinor, after seeing her safe off, returned to Marianne, whom she found attempting to rise from the bed, and whom she reached just in time to prevent her from falling on the floor, faint and giddy from a long want of proper rest and food;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67263,\n            \"Elinor, I am miserable, indeed,\\u201dbefore her voice was entirely lost in sobs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67400,\n            \"Happy, happy Elinor, _ you _ cannot have an idea of what I suffer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68741,\n            \"Have you forgot the last evening of our being together at Barton?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68886,\n            \"This woman of whom he writes \\u2014 whoever she be \\u2014 or any one, in short, but your own dear self, mama, and Edward, may have been so barbarous to bely me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68953,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor would not contend, and only replied, \\u201cWhoever may have been so detestably your enemy, let them be cheated of their malignant triumph, my dear sister, by seeing how nobly the consciousness of your own innocence and good intentions supports your spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69058,\n            \"Elinor, Elinor, they who suffer little may be proud and independent as they like \\u2014 may resist insult, or return mortification \\u2014 but I cannot.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69156,\n            \"Elinor was employed in walking thoughtfully from the fire to the window, from the window to the fire, without knowing that she received warmth from one, or discerning objects through the other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70113,\n            \"Marianne, to the surprise of her sister, determined on dining with them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70160,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, pleased to have her governed for a moment by such a motive, though believing it hardly possible that she could sit out the dinner, said no more;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70193,\n            \"and adjusting her dress for her as well as she could, while Marianne still remained on the bed, was ready to assist her into the dining room as soon as they were summoned to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70315,\n            \"Elinor, who did justice to Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s kindness, though its effusions were often distressing, and sometimes almost ridiculous, made her those acknowledgments, and returned her those civilities, which her sister could not make or return for herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70453,\n            \"Had not Elinor, in the sad countenance of her sister, seen a check to all mirth, she could have been entertained by Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s endeavours to cure a disappointment in love, by a variety of sweetmeats and olives, and a good fire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70690,\n            \"\\u2014\\u201d\\u201cThe lady then \\u2014 Miss Grey I think you called her \\u2014 is very rich?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71669,\n            \"I must do _ this _ justice to Mr. Willoughby \\u2014 he has broken no positive engagement with my sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71691,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cLaw, my dear!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71732,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, for her sister\\u2019s sake, could not press the subject farther, and she hoped it was not required of her for Willoughby\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72201,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, if we can do _ that _, Ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cwe shall do very well with or without Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72286,\n            \"\\u201cYou had better leave me,\\u201dwas all the notice that her sister received from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72305,\n            \"\\u201cI will leave you,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cif you will go to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72342,\n            \"Her sister\\u2019s earnest, though gentle persuasion, however, soon softened her to compliance, and Elinor saw her lay her aching head on the pillow, and as she hoped, in a way to get some quiet rest before she left her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72424,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear,\\u201dsaid she, entering, \\u201cI have just recollected that I have some of the finest old Constantia wine in the house that ever was tasted, so I have brought a glass of it for your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72543,\n            \"But I have just left Marianne in bed, and, I hope, almost asleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72612,\n            \"and Elinor, as she swallowed the chief of it, reflected, that though its effects on a colicky gout were, at present, of little importance to her, its healing powers, on a disappointed heart might be as reasonably tried on herself as on her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72664,\n            \"Colonel Brandon came in while the party were at tea, and by his manner of looking round the room for Marianne, Elinor immediately fancied that he neither expected nor wished to see her there, and, in short, that he was already aware of what occasioned her absence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72911,\n            \"If you know it already, as surely you must, I may be spared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72927,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou mean,\\u201danswered Elinor, with forced calmness, \\u201cMr. Willoughby\\u2019s marriage with Miss Grey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73820,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor had not needed this to be assured of the injustice to which her sister was often led in her opinion of others, by the irritable refinement of her own mind, and the too great importance placed by her on the delicacies of a strong sensibility, and the graces of a polished manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74277,\n            \"Her mother, still confident of their engagement, and relying as warmly as ever on his constancy, had only been roused by Elinor\\u2019s application, to intreat from Marianne greater openness towards them both;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74788,\n            \"and Elinor, who was convinced that solicitude for Marianne brought him thither, and who saw _ that _ solicitude in his disturbed and melancholy look, and in his anxious though brief inquiry after her, could not forgive her sister for esteeming him so lightly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75029,\n            \"\\u201cI understand you,\\u201dsaid Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76461,\n            \"and Elinor spoke her feelings in an exclamation of tender concern, at the fate of his unfortunate friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77711,\n            \"but had I not seriously, and from my heart believed it might be of service, might lessen her regrets, I would not have suffered myself to trouble you with this account of my family afflictions, with a recital which may seem to have been intended to raise myself at the expense of others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77802,\n            \"\\u201cI have been more pained,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cby her endeavors to acquit him than by all the rest;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77843,\n            \"Now, though at first she will suffer much, I am sure she will soon become easier.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78010,\n            \"but to a man and a soldier she presumed not to censure it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78244,\n            \"But though this behaviour assured Elinor that the conviction of this guilt _ was _ carried home to her mind, though she saw with satisfaction the effect of it, in her no longer avoiding Colonel Brandon when he called, in her speaking to him, even voluntarily speaking, with a kind of compassionate respect, and though she saw her spirits less violently irritated than before, she did not see her less wretched.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78360,\n            \"his seduction and desertion of Miss Williams, the misery of that poor girl, and the doubt of what his designs might _ once _ have been on herself, preyed altogether so much on her spirits, that she could not bring herself to speak of what she felt even to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78415,\n            \"and, brooding over her sorrows in silence, gave more pain to her sister than could have been communicated by the most open and most frequent confession of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78446,\n            \"To give the feelings or the language of Mrs. Dashwood on receiving and answering Elinor\\u2019s letter would be only to give a repetition of what her daughters had already felt and said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79064,\n            \"and Elinor, on the other hand, suspecting that it would not be in her power to avoid Edward entirely, comforted herself by thinking, that though their longer stay would therefore militate against her own happiness, it would be better for Marianne than an immediate return into Devonshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79174,\n            \"Elinor wished that the same forbearance could have extended towards herself, but that was impossible, and she was obliged to listen day after day to the indignation of them all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79457,\n            \"\\u201d The rest of Mrs. Palmer\\u2019s sympathy was shown in procuring all the particulars in her power of the approaching marriage, and communicating them to Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79838,\n            \"He had abundantly earned the privilege of intimate discussion of her sister\\u2019s disappointment, by the friendly zeal with which he had endeavoured to soften it, and they always conversed with confidence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80111,\n            \"Early in February, within a fortnight from the receipt of Willoughby\\u2019s letter, Elinor had the painful office of informing her sister that he was married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80261,\n            \"and Elinor now hoped, as there could be no danger of her seeing either of them, to prevail on her sister, who had never yet left the house since the blow first fell, to go out again by degrees as she had done before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80358,\n            \"Elinor only was sorry to see them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80549,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor perfectly understood her, and was forced to use all her self-command to make it appear that she did _ not _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80903,\n            \"\\u201cI suppose you will go and stay with your brother and sister, Miss Dashwood, when they come to town,\\u201dsaid Lucy, returning, after a cessation of hostile hints, to the charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80943,\n            \"\\u201cNo, I do not think we shall.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80965,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor would not humour her by farther opposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81026,\n            \"\\u201cI am sorry we cannot see your sister, Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Miss Steele.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81044,\n            \"\\u201cI am sorry she is not well \\u2014\\u201dfor Marianne had left the room on their arrival.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81212,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor began to find this impertinence too much for her temper;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81308,\n            \"She expressly conditioned, however, for paying no visits, and would do no more than accompany them to Gray\\u2019s in Sackville Street, where Elinor was carrying on a negotiation for the exchange of a few old-fashioned jewels of her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81484,\n            \"one gentleman only was standing there, and it is probable that Elinor was not without hope of exciting his politeness to a quicker despatch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81827,\n            \"Elinor lost no time in bringing her business forward, was on the point of concluding it, when another gentleman presented himself at her side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82529,\n            \"After staying with them half an hour, he asked Elinor to walk with him to Conduit Street, and introduce him to Sir John and Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82623,\n            \"and I think, Elinor, I may congratulate you on the prospect of a very respectable establishment in life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82644,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMe, brother!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82698,\n            \"\\u201d and then working himself up to a pitch of enthusiastic generosity, he added, \\u201cElinor, I wish with all my heart it were _ twice _ as much, for your sake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82735,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed I believe you,\\u201dreplied Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82914,\n            \"and no civility shall be wanting on my part to make him pleased with you and your family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83251,\n            \"To give you another instance of her liberality: \\u2014 The other day, as soon as we came to town, aware that money could not be very plenty with us just now, she put bank-notes into Fanny\\u2019s hands to the amount of two hundred pounds.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83323,\n            \"\\u201d He paused for her assent and compassion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83332,\n            \"and she forced herself to say, \\u201cYour expenses both in town and country must certainly be considerable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83630,\n            \"Our respected father, as you well know, bequeathed all the Stanhill effects that remained at Norland (and very valuable they were) to your mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83757,\n            \"\\u201cand assisted by her liberality, I hope you may yet live to be in easy circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83914,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor kept her concern and her censure to herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83940,\n            \"Having now said enough to make his poverty clear, and to do away the necessity of buying a pair of ear-rings for each of his sisters, in his next visit at Gray\\u2019s, his thoughts took a cheerfuller turn, and he began to congratulate Elinor on having such a friend as Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84052,\n            \"Her inviting you to town is certainly a vast thing in your favour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84066,\n            \"and indeed, it speaks altogether so great a regard for you, that in all probability when she dies you will not be forgotten.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84212,\n            \"Whereas, in my opinion, by her taking so much notice of you, and treating you in this kind of way, she has given you a sort of claim on her future consideration, which a conscientious woman would not disregard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84460,\n            \"I remember Fanny used to say that she would marry sooner and better than you did;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84555,\n            \"but, my dear Elinor, I shall be exceedingly glad to know more of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84572,\n            \"and I think I can answer for your having Fanny and myself among the earliest and best pleased of your visitors.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84594,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor tried very seriously to convince him that there was no likelihood of her marrying Colonel Brandon;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84794,\n            \"\\u201cI shall have a charming account to carry to Fanny,\\u201dsaid he, as he walked back with his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84967,\n            \"Mrs. John Dashwood had so much confidence in her husband\\u2019s judgment, that she waited the very next day both on Mrs. Jennings and her daughter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84998,\n            \"and her confidence was rewarded by finding even the former, even the woman with whom her sisters were staying, by no means unworthy her notice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85092,\n            \"The same manners, however, which recommended Mrs. John Dashwood to the good opinion of Lady Middleton did not suit the fancy of Mrs. Jennings, and to _ her _ she appeared nothing more than a little proud-looking woman of uncordial address, who met her husband\\u2019s sisters without any affection, and almost without having anything to say to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85208,\n            \"but nothing would have induced Fanny voluntarily to mention his name before her, till able to tell her that his marriage with Miss Morton was resolved on, or till her husband\\u2019s expectations on Colonel Brandon were answered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85536,\n            \"but Elinor could not learn whether her sons were to be of the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85551,\n            \"The expectation of seeing _ her _, however, was enough to make her interested in the engagement;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85888,\n            \"She began immediately to determine, that Edward who lived with his mother, must be asked as his mother was, to a party given by his sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85968,\n            \"They were relieved however, not by her own recollection, but by the good will of Lucy, who believed herself to be inflicting a severe disappointment when she told her that Edward certainly would not be in Harley Street on Tuesday, and even hoped to be carrying the pain still farther by persuading her that he was kept away by the extreme affection for herself, which he could not conceal when they were together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86076,\n            \"\\u201d said Lucy, as they walked up the stairs together \\u2014 for the Middletons arrived so directly after Mrs. Jennings, that they all followed the servant at the same time: \\u2014 \\u201cthere is nobody here but you, that can feel for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86157,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor could have given her immediate relief by suggesting the possibility of its being Miss Morton\\u2019s mother, rather than her own, whom they were about to behold;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86190,\n            \"but instead of doing that, she assured her, and with great sincerity, that she did pity her \\u2014 to the utter amazement of Lucy, who, though really uncomfortable herself, hoped at least to be an object of irrepressible envy to Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86491,\n            \"while she herself, who had comparatively no power to wound them, sat pointedly slighted by both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87043,\n            \"Elinor, having once delivered her opinion on William\\u2019s side, by which she offended Mrs. Ferrars and Fanny still more, did not see the necessity of enforcing it by any farther assertion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87112,\n            \"Before her removing from Norland, Elinor had painted a very pretty pair of screens for her sister-in-law, which being now just mounted and brought home, ornamented her present drawing room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87182,\n            \"\\u201cThese are done by my eldest sister,\\u201dsaid he;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87216,\n            \"I do not know whether you have ever happened to see any of her performances before, but she is in general reckoned to draw extremely well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87584,\n            \"\\u2014 it is Elinor of whom _ we _ think and speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87754,\n            \"The cold insolence of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s general behaviour to her sister, seemed, to her, to foretell such difficulties and distresses to Elinor, as her own wounded heart taught her to think of with horror;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87796,\n            \"and urged by a strong impulse of affectionate sensibility, she moved after a moment, to her sister\\u2019s chair, and putting one arm round her neck, and one cheek close to hers, said in a low, but eager, voice, \\u201cDear, dear Elinor, don\\u2019t mind them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87856,\n            \"Don\\u2019t let them make _ you _ unhappy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87937,\n            \"poor dear,\\u201dimmediately gave her her salts;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87947,\n            \"and Sir John felt so desperately enraged against the author of this nervous distress, that he instantly changed his seat to one close by Lucy Steele, and gave her, in a whisper, a brief account of the whole shocking affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88037,\n            \"\\u201d said her brother to Colonel Brandon, in a low voice, as soon as he could secure his attention: \\u201cShe has not such good health as her sister, \\u2014 she is very nervous, \\u2014 she has not Elinor\\u2019s constitution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88343,\n            \"\\u2014 that her interest and her vanity should so very much blind her as to make the attention which seemed only paid her because she was _ not Elinor _, appear a compliment to herself \\u2014 or to allow her to derive encouragement from a preference only given her, because her real situation was unknown.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88487,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear friend,\\u201dcried Lucy, as soon as they were by themselves, \\u201cI come to talk to you of my happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88539,\n            \"You know how I dreaded the thoughts of seeing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88664,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor wished to talk of something else, but Lucy still pressed her to own that she had reason for her happiness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88696,\n            \"\\u201cUndoubtedly, if they had known your engagement,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cnothing could be more flattering than their treatment of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88722,\n            \"\\u2014 but as that was not the case \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cI guessed you would say so,\\u201d\\u2014 replied Lucy quickly \\u2014 \\u201cbut there was no reason in the world why Mrs. Ferrars should seem to like me, if she did not, and her liking me is every thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88836,\n            \"\\u2014 I wonder I should never hear you say how agreeable Mrs. Dashwood was!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88976,\n            \"But it seemed to satisfy Lucy, for she directly replied, \\u201cIndeed I am perfectly convinced of your regard for me, and next to Edward\\u2019s love, it is the greatest comfort I have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89120,\n            \"\\u2014 I am sure if ever you tell your sister what I think of her, you cannot speak too high.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89142,\n            \"\\u201d But Elinor would not give her any encouragement to hope that she _ should _ tell her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89189,\n            \"If she had only made me a formal courtesy, for instance, without saying a word, and never after had took any notice of me, and never looked at me in a pleasant way \\u2014 you know what I mean \\u2014 if I had been treated in that forbidding sort of way, I should have gave it all up in despair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89277,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was prevented from making any reply to this civil triumph, by the door\\u2019s being thrown open, the servant\\u2019s announcing Mr. Ferrars, and Edward\\u2019s immediately walking in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89715,\n            \"and almost every thing that _ was _ said, proceeded from Elinor, who was obliged to volunteer all the information about her mother\\u2019s health, their coming to town, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89983,\n            \"while Marianne was looking with the most speaking tenderness, sometimes at Edward and sometimes at Elinor, regretting only that their delight in each other should be checked by Lucy\\u2019s unwelcome presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90211,\n            \"\\u201cI think, Elinor,\\u201dshe presently added, \\u201cwe must employ Edward to take care of us in our return to Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90836,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne looked at her steadily, and said, \\u201cYou know, Elinor, that this is a kind of talking which I cannot bear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90864,\n            \"If you only hope to have your assertion contradicted, as I must suppose to be the case, you ought to recollect that I am the last person in the world to do it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90923,\n            \"and Elinor dared not follow her to say more, for bound as she was by her promise of secrecy to Lucy, she could give no information that would convince Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91301,\n            \"Though nothing could be more polite than Lady Middleton\\u2019s behaviour to Elinor and Marianne, she did not really like them at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91532,\n            \"for though she often threw out expressions of pity for her sister to Elinor, and more than once dropt a reflection on the inconstancy of beaux before Marianne, no effect was produced, but a look of indifference from the former, or of disgust in the latter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92458,\n            \"for after undergoing an examination into the value and make of her gown, the colour of her shoes, and the arrangement of her hair, she was almost sure of being told that upon \\u201cher word she looked vastly smart, and she dared to say she would make a great many conquests.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92515,\n            \"\\u201d With such encouragement as this, was she dismissed on the present occasion, to her brother\\u2019s carriage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92665,\n            \"As Elinor was neither musical, nor affecting to be so, she made no scruple of turning her eyes from the grand pianoforte, whenever it suited her, and unrestrained even by the presence of a harp, and violoncello, would fix them at pleasure on any other object in the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92721,\n            \"In one of these excursive glances she perceived among a group of young men, the very he, who had given them a lecture on toothpick-cases at Gray\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92771,\n            \"and had just determined to find out his name from the latter, when they both came towards her, and Mr. Dashwood introduced him to her as Mr. Robert Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92846,\n            \"Happy had it been for her, if her regard for Edward had depended less on his own merit, than on the merit of his nearest relations!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92944,\n            \"Why they _ were _ different, Robert explained to her himself in the course of a quarter of an hour\\u2019s conversation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93209,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor would not oppose his opinion, because, whatever might be her general estimation of the advantage of a public school, she could not think of Edward\\u2019s abode in Mr. Pratt\\u2019s family, with any satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94216,\n            \"at the same time, however, slyly suspecting that another year would make the invitation needless, by bringing Elinor to town as Colonel Brandon\\u2019s wife, and Marianne as _ their _ visitor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94549,\n            \"The Miss Steeles removed to Harley Street, and all that reached Elinor of their influence there, strengthened her expectation of the event.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94742,\n            \"About the third or fourth morning after their being thus resettled in Berkeley Street, Mrs. Jennings, on returning from her ordinary visit to Mrs. Palmer, entered the drawing-room, where Elinor was sitting by herself, with an air of such hurrying importance as prepared her to hear something wonderful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97789,\n            \"And all this has been going on at a time, when, as you know too well, it has not been my only unhappiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97949,\n            \"Elinor,\\u201dshe cried, \\u201cyou have made me hate myself for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97965,\n            \"\\u2014 How barbarous have I been to you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97974,\n            \"\\u2014 you, who have been my only comfort, who have borne with me in all my misery, who have seemed to be only suffering for me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98010,\n            \"\\u2014 Is this the only return I can make you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98021,\n            \"\\u2014 Because your merit cries out upon myself, I have been trying to do it away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98047,\n            \"In such a frame of mind as she was now in, Elinor had no difficulty in obtaining from her whatever promise she required;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98248,\n            \"\\u2014 Such advances towards heroism in her sister, made Elinor feel equal to any thing herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99442,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s heart wrung for the feelings of Edward, while braving his mother\\u2019s threats, for a woman who could not reward him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99761,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s heart thanked her for such kindness towards Edward, though she could not forbear smiling at the form of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100124,\n            \"and as her vehemence made reserve impossible in Elinor, and unnecessary in Mrs. Jennings, they all joined in a very spirited critique upon the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100637,\n            \"An intimate acquaintance of Mrs. Jennings joined them soon after they entered the Gardens, and Elinor was not sorry that by her continuing with them, and engaging all Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s conversation, she was herself left to quiet reflection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100683,\n            \"She saw nothing of the Willoughbys, nothing of Edward, and for some time nothing of anybody who could by any chance whether grave or gay, be interesting to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100716,\n            \"But at last she found herself with some surprise, accosted by Miss Steele, who, though looking rather shy, expressed great satisfaction in meeting them, and on receiving encouragement from the particular kindness of Mrs. Jennings, left her own party for a short time, to join their\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100773,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings immediately whispered to Elinor, \\u201cGet it all out of her, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100792,\n            \"She will tell you any thing if you ask.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101144,\n            \"\\u201d She had wandered away to a subject on which Elinor had nothing to say, and therefore soon judged it expedient to find her way back again to the first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101176,\n            \"\\u201cWell, but Miss Dashwood,\\u201dspeaking triumphantly, \\u201cpeople may say what they chuse about Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s declaring he would not have Lucy, for it is no such thing I can tell you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101260,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI never heard any thing of the kind hinted at before, I assure you,\\u201dsaid Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102070,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not understand what you mean by interrupting them,\\u201dsaid Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102112,\n            \"Miss Dashwood, do you think people make love when any body else is by?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102203,\n            \"I am sorry I did not know it before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102414,\n            \"However, I shan\\u2019t say anything against them to _ you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102716,\n            \"I had a vast deal more to say to you, but I must not stay away from them not any longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102739,\n            \"I assure you they are very genteel people.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102801,\n            \"and if anything should happen to take you and your sister away, and Mrs. Jennings should want company, I am sure we should be very glad to come and stay with her for as long a time as she likes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102890,\n            \"\\u2014 I wonder you was not afraid of its being torn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103345,\n            \"but I know your friendship for me will make you pleased to hear such a good account of myself and my dear Edward, after all the troubles we have went through lately, therefore will make no more apologies, but proceed to say that, thank God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103423,\n            \"We have had great trials, and great persecutions, but however, at the same time, gratefully acknowledge many friends, yourself not the least among them, whose great kindness I shall always thankfully remember, as will Edward too, who I have told of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103474,\n            \"I am sure you will be glad to hear, as likewise dear Mrs. Jennings, I spent two happy hours with him yesterday afternoon, he would not hear of our parting, though earnestly did I, as I thought my duty required, urge him to it for prudence sake, and would have parted for ever on the spot, would he consent to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103944,\n            \"\\u2014 Thank you, my dear, for showing it me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104771,\n            \"for, on Elinor\\u2019s moving to the window to take more expeditiously the dimensions of a print, which she was going to copy for her friend, he followed her to it with a look of particular meaning, and conversed with her there for several minutes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104822,\n            \"The effect of his discourse on the lady too, could not escape her observation, for though she was too honorable to listen, and had even changed her seat, on purpose that she might _ not _ hear, to one close by the piano forte on which Marianne was playing, she could not keep herself from seeing that Elinor changed colour, attended with agitation, and was too intent on what he said to pursue her employment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105319,\n            \"for if I understand the matter right, he has been entirely cast off by them for persevering in his engagement with a very deserving young woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105651,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s astonishment at this commission could hardly have been greater, had the Colonel been really making her an offer of his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106541,\n            \"my dear, you are very modest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106650,\n            \"Well, my dear, I wish you joy of it again and again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106711,\n            \"\\u201cAye, my dear, that I do, indeed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106813,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings immediately preparing to go, said, \\u2014 \\u201cWell, my dear, I must be gone before I have had half my talk out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107126,\n            \"\\u2014 I understand you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107288,\n            \"However, I will not disturb you (seeing her preparing to write.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107341,\n            \"but returning again in a moment, \\u201cI have just been thinking of Betty\\u2019s sister, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107423,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cCertainly, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dreplied Elinor, not hearing much of what she said, and more anxious to be alone, than to be mistress of the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107458,\n            \"How she should begin \\u2014 how she should express herself in her note to Edward, was now all her concern.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107602,\n            \"Elinor had just been congratulating herself, in the midst of her perplexity, that however difficult it might be to express herself properly by letter, it was at least preferable to giving the information by word of mouth, when her visitor entered, to force her upon this greatest exertion of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108041,\n            \"Allow me to congratulate you on having so respectable and well-judging a friend, and to join in his wish that the living \\u2014 it is about two hundred a-year \\u2014 were much more considerable, and such as might better enable you to \\u2014 as might be more than a temporary accommodation to yourself \\u2014 such, in short, as might establish all your views of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108176,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, gathering more resolution, as some of the worst was over, \\u201cColonel Brandon means it as a testimony of his concern for what has lately passed \\u2014 for the cruel situation in which the unjustifiable conduct of your family has placed you \\u2014 a concern which I am sure Marianne, myself, and all your friends, must share;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108348,\n            \"\\u2014 I feel it \\u2014 I would express it if I could \\u2014 but, as you well know, I am no orator.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108630,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cI believe that you will find him, on farther acquaintance, all that you have heard him to be, and as you will be such very near neighbours (for I understand the parsonage is almost close to the mansion-house,) it is particularly important that he _ should _ be all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108824,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor did not offer to detain him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108833,\n            \"and they parted, with a very earnest assurance on _ her _ side of her unceasing good wishes for his happiness in every change of situation that might befall him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108888,\n            \"\\u201cWhen I see him again,\\u201dsaid Elinor to herself, as the door shut him out, \\u201cI shall see him the husband of Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108959,\n            \"When Mrs. Jennings came home, though she returned from seeing people whom she had never seen before, and of whom therefore she must have a great deal to say, her mind was so much more occupied by the important secret in her possession, than by anything else, that she reverted to it again as soon as Elinor appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109024,\n            \"\\u201cWell, my dear,\\u201dshe cried, \\u201cI sent you up the young man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109049,\n            \"\\u2014 And I suppose you had no great difficulty \\u2014 You did not find him very unwilling to accept your proposal?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109144,\n            \"but I suppose two or three months will complete his ordination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109312,\n            \"Sure you do not mean to persuade me that the Colonel only marries you for the sake of giving ten guineas to Mr. Ferrars!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109554,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe Colonel is a ninny, my dear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109626,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was quite of her opinion, as to the probability of their not waiting for any thing more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109758,\n            \"So far was she, at the same time, from any backwardness to give Elinor that credit which Edward _ would _ give her, that she spoke of her friendship for them both with the most grateful warmth, was ready to own all their obligation to her, and openly declared that no exertion for their good on Miss Dashwood\\u2019s part, either present or future, would ever surprise her, for she believed her capable of doing any thing in the world for those she really valued.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109929,\n            \"It was now above a week since John Dashwood had called in Berkeley Street, and as since that time no notice had been taken by them of his wife\\u2019s indisposition, beyond one verbal enquiry, Elinor began to feel it necessary to pay her a visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110033,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings, though her carriage was always at Elinor\\u2019s service, so very much disliked Mrs. John Dashwood, that not even her curiosity to see how she looked after the late discovery, nor her strong desire to affront her by taking Edward\\u2019s part, could overcome her unwillingness to be in her company again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110098,\n            \"The consequence was, that Elinor set out by herself to pay a visit, for which no one could really have less inclination, and to run the risk of a t\\u00eate-\\u00e0-t\\u00eate with a woman, whom neither of the others had so much reason to dislike.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110306,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor made what excuse she could for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110646,\n            \"and by relating that she had herself been employed in conveying the offer from Colonel Brandon to Edward, and, therefore, must understand the terms on which it was given, obliged him to submit to her authority.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110693,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 he cried, after hearing what she said \\u2014 \\u201cwhat could be the Colonel\\u2019s motive?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111216,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, smiling at the grave and decisive importance of her brother\\u2019s tone, calmly replied, \\u2014 \\u201cThe lady, I suppose, has no choice in the affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111261,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI only mean that I suppose, from your manner of speaking, it must be the same to Miss Morton whether she marry Edward or Robert.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111367,\n            \"\\u201cOf _ one _ thing, my dear sister,\\u201dkindly taking her hand, and speaking in an awful whisper, \\u201cI may assure you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111397,\n            \"\\u2014 and I _ will _ do it, because I know it must gratify you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111414,\n            \"I have good reason to think \\u2014 indeed I have it from the best authority, or I should not repeat it, for otherwise it would be very wrong to say any thing about it, \\u2014 but I have it from the very best authority, \\u2014 not that I ever precisely heard Mrs. Ferrars say it herself \\u2014 but her daughter _ did _, and I have it from her, \\u2014 that in short, whatever objections there might be against a certain \\u2014 a certain connection, you understand me, \\u2014 it would have been far preferable to her, \\u2014 it would not have given her half the vexation that _ this _ does.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111554,\n            \"a very gratifying circumstance you know to us all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111638,\n            \"But I thought I would just tell you of this, because I knew how much it must please you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111696,\n            \"Has Colonel Brandon been with you lately?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111733,\n            \"\\u2014 and she was therefore glad to be spared from the necessity of saying much in reply herself, and from the danger of hearing any thing more from her brother, by the entrance of Mr. Robert Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111806,\n            \"and Elinor was left to improve her acquaintance with Robert, who, by the gay unconcern, the happy self-complacency of his manner while enjoying so unfair a division of his mother\\u2019s love and liberality, to the prejudice of his banished brother, earned only by his own dissipated course of life, and that brother\\u2019s integrity, was confirming her most unfavourable opinion of his head and heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112200,\n            \"You must not judge of him, Miss Dashwood, from _ your _ slight acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112772,\n            \"But though _ she _ never spoke of it out of her own family, Elinor could see its influence on her mind, in the something like confusion of countenance with which she entered, and an attempt at cordiality in her behaviour to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112819,\n            \"She even proceeded so far as to be concerned to find that Elinor and her sister were so soon to leave town, as she had hoped to see more of them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112889,\n            \"One other short call in Harley Street, in which Elinor received her brother\\u2019s congratulations on their travelling so far towards Barton without any expense, and on Colonel Brandon\\u2019s being to follow them to Cleveland in a day or two, completed the intercourse of the brother and sisters in town;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112946,\n            \"\\u2014 and a faint invitation from Fanny, to come to Norland whenever it should happen to be in their way, which of all things was the most unlikely to occur, with a more warm, though less public, assurance, from John to Elinor, of the promptitude with which he should come to see her at Delaford, was all that foretold any meeting in the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113019,\n            \"It amused her to observe that all her friends seemed determined to send her to Delaford;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113060,\n            \"for not only was it considered as her future home by her brother and Mrs. Jennings, but even Lucy, when they parted, gave her a pressing invitation to visit her there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113297,\n            \"She had no such object for her lingering thoughts to fix on, she left no creature behind, from whom it would give her a moment\\u2019s regret to be divided for ever, she was pleased to be free herself from the persecution of Lucy\\u2019s friendship, she was grateful for bringing her sister away unseen by Willoughby since his marriage, and she looked forward with hope to what a few months of tranquility at Barton might do towards restoring Marianne\\u2019s peace of mind, and confirming her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114079,\n            \"Elinor, however little concerned in it, joined in their discourse;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114209,\n            \"and Elinor could have forgiven every thing but her laugh.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114264,\n            \"Elinor had seen so little of Mr. Palmer, and in that little had seen so much variety in his address to her sister and herself, that she knew not what to expect to find him in his own family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114384,\n            \"For the rest of his character and habits, they were marked, as far as Elinor could perceive, with no traits at all unusual in his sex and time of life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114610,\n            \"\\u2014 His behaviour to her in this, as well as in every other particular, his open pleasure in meeting her after an absence of only ten days, his readiness to converse with her, and his deference for her opinion, might very well justify Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s persuasion of his attachment, and would have been enough, perhaps, had not Elinor still, as from the first, believed Marianne his real favourite, to make her suspect it herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114985,\n            \"and it was with difficulty that Elinor prevailed on her, when she went to bed, to try one or two of the simplest of the remedies.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115097,\n            \"and when, at last, she went early to bed, more and more indisposed, Colonel Brandon was only astonished at her sister\\u2019s composure, who, though attending and nursing her the whole day, against Marianne\\u2019s inclination, and forcing proper medicines on her at night, trusted, like Marianne, to the certainty and efficacy of sleep, and felt no real alarm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115186,\n            \"and when Marianne, after persisting in rising, confessed herself unable to sit up, and returned voluntarily to her bed, Elinor was very ready to adopt Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s advice, of sending for the Palmers\\u2019 apothecary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115230,\n            \"He came, examined his patient, and though encouraging Miss Dashwood to expect that a very few days would restore her sister to health, yet, by pronouncing her disorder to have a putrid tendency, and allowing the word \\u201cinfection\\u201dto pass his lips, gave instant alarm to Mrs. Palmer, on her baby\\u2019s account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115295,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, who had been inclined from the first to think Marianne\\u2019s complaint more serious than Elinor, now looked very grave on Mr. Harris\\u2019 s report, and confirming Charlotte\\u2019s fears and caution, urged the necessity of her immediate removal with her infant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115467,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, however, with a kindness of heart which made Elinor really love her, declared her resolution of not stirring from Cleveland as long as Marianne remained ill, and of endeavouring, by her own attentive care, to supply to her the place of the mother she had taken her from;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115525,\n            \"and Elinor found her on every occasion a most willing and active helpmate, desirous to share in all her fatigues, and often by her better experience in nursing, of material use.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115664,\n            \"though Elinor tried to raise her spirits, and make her believe, as she _ then _ really believed herself, that it would be a very short one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116292,\n            \"rejoicing that in her letters to her mother, she had pursued her own judgment rather than her friend\\u2019s, in making very light of the indisposition which delayed them at Cleveland;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116431,\n            \"Her sleep, though not so quiet as Elinor wished to see it, lasted a considerable time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116450,\n            \"and anxious to observe the result of it herself, she resolved to sit with her during the whole of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116491,\n            \"her maid, who was one of the principal nurses, was recreating herself in the housekeeper\\u2019s room, and Elinor remained alone with Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116689,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor perceived with alarm that she was not quite herself, and, while attempting to soothe her, eagerly felt her pulse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116785,\n            \"and as soon she had rung up the maid to take her place by her sister, she hastened down to the drawing-room, where she knew he was generally to be found at a much later hour than the present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117276,\n            \"Marianne\\u2019s ideas were still, at intervals, fixed incoherently on her mother, and whenever she mentioned her name, it gave a pang to the heart of poor Elinor, who, reproaching herself for having trifled with so many days of illness, and wretched for some immediate relief, fancied that all relief might soon be in vain, that every thing had been delayed too long, and pictured to herself her suffering mother arriving too late to see this darling child, or to see her rational.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117414,\n            \"His opinion, however, made some little amends for his delay, for though acknowledging a very unexpected and unpleasant alteration in his patient, he would not allow the danger to be material, and talked of the relief which a fresh mode of treatment must procure, with a confidence which, in a lesser degree, was communicated to Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117479,\n            \"He promised to call again in the course of three or four hours, and left both the patient and her anxious attendant more composed than he had found them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117557,\n            \"and though trying to speak comfort to Elinor, her conviction of her sister\\u2019s danger would not allow her to offer the comfort of hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117936,\n            \"Elinor felt all the reasonableness of the idea, and it gave fresh misery to her reflections.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118688,\n            \"but Elinor had no sense of fatigue, no capability of sleep at that moment about her, and she was not to be kept away from her sister an unnecessary instant.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118826,\n            \"Had it been ten, Elinor would have been convinced that at that moment she heard a carriage driving up to the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118961,\n            \"Never in her life had Elinor found it so difficult to be calm, as at that moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119111,\n            \"Elinor, starting back with a look of horror at the sight of him, obeyed the first impulse of her heart in turning instantly to quit the room, and her hand was already on the lock, when its action was suspended by his hastily advancing, and saying, in a voice rather of command than supplication, \\u201cMiss Dashwood, for half an hour \\u2014 for ten minutes \\u2014 I entreat you to stay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119277,\n            \"My business is with you, and only you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120184,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor bowed her assent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120832,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou did then,\\u201dsaid Elinor, a little softened, \\u201cbelieve yourself at one time attached to her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121239,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have,\\u201dreturned Elinor, colouring likewise, and hardening her heart anew against any compassion for him, \\u201cI have heard it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122979,\n            \"I say awakened, because time and London, business and dissipation, had in some measure quieted it, and I had been growing a fine hardened villain, fancying myself indifferent to her, and chusing to fancy that she too must have become indifferent to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124469,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are very wrong, Mr. Willoughby, very blamable,\\u201dsaid Elinor, while her voice, in spite of herself, betrayed her compassionate emotion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124905,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI will tell her all that is necessary to what may comparatively be called, your justification.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125868,\n            \"And if that some one should be the very he whom, of all others, I could least bear \\u2014 but I will not stay to rob myself of all your compassionate goodwill, by showing that where I have most injured I can least forgive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125916,\n            \"Good bye, \\u2014 God bless you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125941,\n            \"Elinor, for some time after he left her, for some time even after the sound of his carriage had died away, remained too much oppressed by a crowd of ideas, widely differing in themselves, but of which sadness was the general result, to think even of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125996,\n            \"Willoughby, he, whom only half an hour ago she had abhorred as the most worthless of men, Willoughby, in spite of all his faults, excited a degree of commiseration for the sufferings produced by them, which made her think of him as now separated for ever from her family, with a tenderness, a regret, rather in proportion, as she soon acknowledged within herself \\u2014 to his wishes than to his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126197,\n            \"The past, the present, the future, Willoughby\\u2019s visit, Marianne\\u2019s safety, and her mother\\u2019s expected arrival, threw her altogether into an agitation of spirits which kept off every indication of fatigue, and made her only fearful of betraying herself to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126293,\n            \"\\u2014 Eager to save her mother from every unnecessary moment\\u2019s horrible suspense, she ran immediately into the hall, and reached the outward door just in time to receive and support her as she entered it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126333,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, whose terror as they drew near the house had produced almost the conviction of Marianne\\u2019s being no more, had no voice to inquire after her, no voice even for Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126422,\n            \"She was supported into the drawing-room between her daughter and her friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126437,\n            \"and there, shedding tears of joy, though still unable to speak, embraced Elinor again and again, turning from her at intervals to press Colonel Brandon\\u2019s hand, with a look which spoke at once her gratitude, and her conviction of his sharing with herself in the bliss of the moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126528,\n            \"and in two minutes she was with her beloved child, rendered dearer to her than ever by absence, unhappiness, and danger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126553,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s delight, as she saw what each felt in the meeting, was only checked by an apprehension of its robbing Marianne of farther sleep: but Mrs. Dashwood could be calm, could be even prudent, when the life of a child was at stake, and Marianne, satisfied in knowing her mother was near her, and conscious of being too weak for conversation, submitted readily to the silence and quiet prescribed by every nurse around her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126653,\n            \"and Elinor, in compliance with her mother\\u2019s entreaty, went to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126749,\n            \"But her promise of relating it to her sister was invariably painful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126801,\n            \"Then, remembering Colonel Brandon, reproved herself, felt that to _ his _ sufferings and _ his _ constancy far more than to his rival\\u2019s, the reward of her sister was due, and wished any thing rather than Mrs. Willoughby\\u2019s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126985,\n            \"Elinor could not hear the declaration, nor witness its proofs without sometimes wondering whether her mother ever recollected Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127006,\n            \"But Mrs. Dashwood, trusting to the temperate account of her own disappointment which Elinor had sent her, was led away by the exuberance of her joy to think only of what would increase it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127080,\n            \"\\u2014 and in her recovery she had yet another source of joy unthought of by Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127123,\n            \"My Elinor, you do not yet know all my happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127169,\n            \"\\u201cYou are never like me, dear Elinor, or I should wonder at your composure now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127188,\n            \"Had I sat down to wish for any possible good to my family, I should have fixed on Colonel Brandon\\u2019s marrying one of you as the object most desirable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127236,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was half inclined to ask her reason for thinking so, because satisfied that none founded on an impartial consideration of their age, characters, or feelings, could be given;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127271,\n            \"\\u2014 but her mother must always be carried away by her imagination on any interesting subject, and therefore instead of an inquiry, she passed it off with a smile.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127325,\n            \"I, you may well believe, could talk of nothing but my child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127428,\n            \"\\u201d Here, however, Elinor perceived, \\u2014 not the language, not the professions of Colonel Brandon, but the natural embellishments of her mother\\u2019s active fancy, which fashioned every thing delightful to her as it chose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127568,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cColonel Brandon\\u2019s character,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cas an excellent man, is well established.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128141,\n            \"There was always a something, if you remember, in Willoughby\\u2019s eyes at times, which I did not like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128174,\n            \"but her mother, without waiting for her assent, continued, \\u201cAnd his manners, the Colonel\\u2019s manners are not only more pleasing to me than Willoughby\\u2019s ever were, but they are of a kind I well know to be more solidly attaching to Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128314,\n            \"\\u2014 Her daughter could not quite agree with her, but her dissent was not heard, and therefore gave no offence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128479,\n            \"\\u201d Here they were interrupted by the entrance of a third person, and Elinor withdrew to think it all over in private, to wish success to her friend, and yet in wishing it, to feel a pang for Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128628,\n            \"His emotion on entering the room, in seeing her altered looks, and in receiving the pale hand which she immediately held out to him, was such, as, in Elinor\\u2019s conjecture, must arise from something more than his affection for Marianne, or the consciousness of its being known to others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129102,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and Elinor then followed, and the others were left by themselves, to talk of the travellers, and feel their own dullness, till Mrs. Jennings was summoned to her chaise to take comfort in the gossip of her maid for the loss of her two young companions;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129245,\n            \"She, who had seen her week after week so constantly suffering, oppressed by anguish of heart which she had neither courage to speak of, nor fortitude to conceal, now saw with a joy, which no other could equally share, an apparent composure of mind, which, in being the result as she trusted of serious reflection, must eventually lead her to contentment and cheerfulness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129948,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor honoured her for a plan which originated so nobly as this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130140,\n            \"and Marianne, leaning on Elinor\\u2019s arm, was authorised to walk as long as she could without fatigue, in the lane before the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130295,\n            \"shall we ever talk on that subject, Elinor?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130336,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor tenderly invited her to be open.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130470,\n            \"Elinor joyfully treasured her words as she answered, \\u201cIf you could be assured of that, you think you should be easy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130969,\n            \"Had I died, in what peculiar misery should I have left you, my nurse, my friend, my sister!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131016,\n            \"How should I have lived in _ your _ remembrance!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131031,\n            \"How could you have consoled her!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131156,\n            \"But you, you above all, above my mother, had been wronged by me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131173,\n            \"I, and only I, knew your heart and its sorrows;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131194,\n            \"\\u2014 not to any compassion that could benefit you or myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131206,\n            \"\\u2014 Your example was before me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131218,\n            \"Was I more considerate of you and your comfort?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131228,\n            \"Did I imitate your forbearance, or lessen your restraints, by taking any part in those offices of general complaisance or particular gratitude which you had hitherto been left to discharge alone?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131264,\n            \"not less when I knew you to be unhappy, than when I had believed you at ease, did I turn away from every exertion of duty or friendship;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131776,\n            \"her hand, unknowingly to herself, closely pressed her sister\\u2019s, and tears covered her cheeks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131808,\n            \"and till they reached the door of the cottage, easily conjecturing what her curiosity must be though no question was suffered to speak it, talked of nothing but Willoughby, and their conversation together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131864,\n            \"As soon as they entered the house, Marianne with a kiss of gratitude and these two words just articulate through her tears, \\u201cTell mama,\\u201dwithdrew from her sister and walked slowly up stairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132304,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Dashwood would have interrupted her instantly with soothing tenderness, had not Elinor, who really wished to hear her sister\\u2019s unbiased opinion, by an eager sign, engaged her silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132342,\n            \"Marianne slowly continued, \\u2014 \\u201cIt is a great relief to me \\u2014 what Elinor told me this morning \\u2014 I have now heard exactly what I wished to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132456,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI know it \\u2014 I know it,\\u201dcried her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132556,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou consider the matter,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cexactly as a good mind and a sound understanding must consider it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133213,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cRather say your mother\\u2019s imprudence, my child,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133248,\n            \"\\u2014 and Elinor, satisfied that each felt their own error, wished to avoid any survey of the past that might weaken her sister\\u2019s spirits;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133277,\n            \"she, therefore, pursuing the first subject, immediately continued, \\u201c_ One _ observation may, I think, be fairly drawn from the whole of the story \\u2014 that all Willoughby\\u2019s difficulties have arisen from the first offence against virtue, in his behaviour to Eliza Williams.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133386,\n            \"Her daughter did not look, however, as if much of it were heard by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133404,\n            \"Elinor, according to her expectation, saw on the two or three following days, that Marianne did not continue to gain strength as she had done;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133720,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne gave a violent start, fixed her eyes upon Elinor, saw her turning pale, and fell back in her chair in hysterics.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133747,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, whose eyes, as she answered the servant\\u2019s inquiry, had intuitively taken the same direction, was shocked to perceive by Elinor\\u2019s countenance how much she really suffered, and a moment afterwards, alike distressed by Marianne\\u2019s situation, knew not on which child to bestow her principal attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133849,\n            \"By that time, Marianne was rather better, and her mother leaving her to the care of Margaret and the maid, returned to Elinor, who, though still much disordered, had so far recovered the use of her reason and voice as to be just beginning an inquiry of Thomas, as to the source of his intelligence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134268,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s heart could easily account for his not putting himself forward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134394,\n            \"but Elinor knew better than to expect them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134595,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s and Elinor\\u2019s appetites were equally lost, and Margaret might think herself very well off, that with so much uneasiness as both her sisters had lately experienced, so much reason as they had often had to be careless of their meals, she had never been obliged to go without her dinner before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134658,\n            \"When the dessert and the wine were arranged, and Mrs. Dashwood and Elinor were left by themselves, they remained long together in a similarity of thoughtfulness and silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134706,\n            \"She now found that she had erred in relying on Elinor\\u2019s representation of herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134755,\n            \"She found that she had been misled by the careful, the considerate attention of her daughter, to think the attachment, which once she had so well understood, much slighter in reality, than she had been wont to believe, or than it was now proved to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134808,\n            \"She feared that under this persuasion she had been unjust, inattentive, nay, almost unkind, to her Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134830,\n            \"\\u2014 that Marianne\\u2019s affliction, because more acknowledged, more immediately before her, had too much engrossed her tenderness, and led her away to forget that in Elinor she might have a daughter suffering almost as much, certainly with less self-provocation, and greater fortitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135276,\n            \"Elinor flattered herself that some one of their connections in London would write to them to announce the event, and give farther particulars, \\u2014 but day after day passed off, and brought no letter, no tidings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135833,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s lips had moved with her mother\\u2019s, and, when the moment of action was over, she wished that she had shaken hands with him too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136011,\n            \"Elinor resolving to exert herself, though fearing the sound of her own voice, now said, \\u201cIs Mrs. Ferrars at Longstaple?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136061,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI meant,\\u201dsaid Elinor, taking up some work from the table, \\u201cto enquire for Mrs. _ Edward _ Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136277,\n            \"\\u201d His words were echoed with unspeakable astonishment by all but Elinor, who sat with her head leaning over her work, in a state of such agitation as made her hardly know where she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136375,\n            \"Edward, who had till then looked any where, rather than at her, saw her hurry away, and perhaps saw \\u2014 or even heard, her emotion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136518,\n            \"and to what purpose that freedom would be employed was easily pre-determined by all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136702,\n            \"\\u2014 that when they all sat down to table at four o\\u2019clock, about three hours after his arrival, he had secured his lady, engaged her mother\\u2019s consent, and was not only in the rapturous profession of the lover, but, in the reality of reason and truth, one of the happiest of men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137364,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, too happy to be comfortable, knew not how to love Edward, nor praise Elinor enough, how to be enough thankful for his release without wounding his delicacy, nor how at once to give them leisure for unrestrained conversation together, and yet enjoy, as she wished, the sight and society of both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137471,\n            \"But Elinor \\u2014 how are _ her _ feelings to be described?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137801,\n            \"\\u2014 and Elinor\\u2019s particular knowledge of each party made it appear to her in every view, as one of the most extraordinary and unaccountable circumstances she had ever heard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137935,\n            \"Edward could only attempt an explanation by supposing, that, perhaps, at first accidentally meeting, the vanity of the one had been so worked on by the flattery of the other, as to lead by degrees to all the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137980,\n            \"Elinor remembered what Robert had told her in Harley Street, of his opinion of what his own mediation in his brother\\u2019s affairs might have done, if applied to in time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138229,\n            \"\\u201cDEAR SIR, \\u201cBeing very sure I have long lost your affections, I have thought myself at liberty to bestow my own on another, and have no doubt of being as happy with him as I once used to think I might be with you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138294,\n            \"Sincerely wish you happy in your choice, and it shall not be my fault if we are not always good friends, as our near relationship now makes proper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138325,\n            \"I can safely say I owe you no ill-will, and am sure you will be too generous to do us any ill offices.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138352,\n            \"Your brother has gained my affections entirely, and as we could not live without one another, we are just returned from the altar, and are now on our way to Dawlish for a few weeks, which place your dear brother has great curiosity to see, but thought I would first trouble you with these few lines, and shall always remain, \\u201cYour sincere well-wisher, friend, and sister, \\u201cLUCY FERRARS.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138435,\n            \"\\u201cI have burnt all your letters, and will return your picture the first opportunity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138452,\n            \"Please to destroy my scrawls \\u2014 but the ring with my hair you are very welcome to keep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138481,\n            \"\\u201cI will not ask your opinion of it as a composition,\\u201dsaid Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138498,\n            \"\\u2014 \\u201cFor worlds would not I have had a letter of hers seen by _ you _ in former days.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138681,\n            \"She will hardly be less hurt, I suppose, by Robert\\u2019s marrying Lucy, than she would have been by your marrying her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138958,\n            \"That Lucy had certainly meant to deceive, to go off with a flourish of malice against him in her message by Thomas, was perfectly clear to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139061,\n            \"and till her last letter reached him, he had always believed her to be a well-disposed, good-hearted girl, and thoroughly attached to himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139435,\n            \"Elinor scolded him, harshly as ladies always scold the imprudence which compliments themselves, for having spent so much time with them at Norland, when he must have felt his own inconstancy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139470,\n            \"\\u201cYour behaviour was certainly very wrong,\\u201dsaid she;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139482,\n            \"\\u201cbecause \\u2014 to say nothing of my own conviction, our relations were all led away by it to fancy and expect _ what _, as you were _ then _ situated, could never be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139544,\n            \"\\u201cI was simple enough to think, that because my _ faith _ was plighted to another, there could be no danger in my being with you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139594,\n            \"I felt that I admired you, but I told myself it was only friendship;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139610,\n            \"and till I began to make comparisons between yourself and Lucy, I did not know how far I was got.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139929,\n            \"Edward had two thousand pounds, and Elinor one, which, with Delaford living, was all that they could call their own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140318,\n            \"Every thing was explained to him by Mrs. Dashwood, and he found fresh reason to rejoice in what he had done for Mr. Ferrars, since eventually it promoted the interest of Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140932,\n            \"and he called on Elinor to join with him in regretting that Lucy\\u2019s engagement with Edward had not rather been fulfilled, than that she should thus be the means of spreading misery farther in the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141255,\n            \"\\u2014 and I should think you might _ now _ venture so far as to profess some concern for having ever formed the engagement which drew on you your mother\\u2019s anger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141815,\n            \"_ but when she found that, though perfectly admitting the truth of her representation, he was by no means inclined to be guided by it, she judged it wisest, from the experience of the past, to submit \\u2014 and therefore, after such an ungracious delay as she owed to her own dignity, and as served to prevent every suspicion of good-will, she issued her decree of consent to the marriage of Edward and Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142046,\n            \"With an income quite sufficient to their wants thus secured to them, they had nothing to wait for after Edward was in possession of the living, but the readiness of the house, to which Colonel Brandon, with an eager desire for the accommodation of Elinor, was making considerable improvements;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142101,\n            \"and after waiting some time for their completion, after experiencing, as usual, a thousand disappointments and delays from the unaccountable dilatoriness of the workmen, Elinor, as usual, broke through the first positive resolution of not marrying till every thing was ready, and the ceremony took place in Barton church early in the autumn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142230,\n            \"for she was able to visit Edward and his wife in their Parsonage by Michaelmas, and she found in Elinor and her husband, as she really believed, one of the happiest couples in the world.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 3]\": [\n        [\n            85671,\n            \"So well had they recommended themselves to Lady Middleton, so agreeable had their assiduities made them to her, that though Lucy was certainly not so elegant, and her sister not even genteel, she was as ready as Sir John to ask them to spend a week or two in Conduit Street;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87947,\n            \"and Sir John felt so desperately enraged against the author of this nervous distress, that he instantly changed his seat to one close by Lucy Steele, and gave her, in a whisper, a brief account of the whole shocking affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104771,\n            \"for, on Elinor\\u2019s moving to the window to take more expeditiously the dimensions of a print, which she was going to copy for her friend, he followed her to it with a look of particular meaning, and conversed with her there for several minutes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139248,\n            \"And even now, I cannot comprehend on what motive she acted, or what fancied advantage it could be to her, to be fettered to a man for whom she had not the smallest regard, and who had only two thousand pounds in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139297,\n            \"She could not foresee that Colonel Brandon would give me a living.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143593,\n            \"Precious as was the company of her daughter to her, she desired nothing so much as to give up its constant enjoyment to her valued friend;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 4]\": [\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51755,\n            \"\\u201cI am glad,\\u201dsaid Lady Middleton to Lucy, \\u201cyou are not going to finish poor little Annamaria\\u2019s basket this evening;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51826,\n            \"\\u201d This hint was enough, Lucy recollected herself instantly and replied, \\u201cIndeed you are very much mistaken, Lady Middleton;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51850,\n            \"I am only waiting to know whether you can make your party without me, or I should have been at my filigree already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51875,\n            \"I would not disappoint the little angel for all the world: and if you want me at the card-table now, I am resolved to finish the basket after supper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51909,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are very good, I hope it won\\u2019t hurt your eyes \\u2014 will you ring the bell for some working candles?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51936,\n            \"My poor little girl would be sadly disappointed, I know, if the basket was not finished tomorrow, for though I told her it certainly would not, I am sure she depends upon having it done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53404,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut what,\\u201dsaid she after a short silence, \\u201care your views?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53576,\n            \"\\u201d Lucy looked at Elinor again, and was silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53794,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor blushed in spite of herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85820,\n            \"and Lucy, who had long wanted to be personally known to the family, to have a nearer view of their characters and her own difficulties, and to have an opportunity of endeavouring to please them, had seldom been happier in her life, than she was on receiving Mrs. John Dashwood\\u2019s card.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86068,\n            \"\\u201cPity me, dear Miss Dashwood!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86076,\n            \"\\u201d said Lucy, as they walked up the stairs together \\u2014 for the Middletons arrived so directly after Mrs. Jennings, that they all followed the servant at the same time: \\u2014 \\u201cthere is nobody here but you, that can feel for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88401,\n            \"But that it was so, had not only been declared by Lucy\\u2019s eyes at the time, but was declared over again the next morning more openly, for at her particular desire, Lady Middleton set her down in Berkeley Street on the chance of seeing Elinor alone, to tell her how happy she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89019,\n            \"But now there is one good thing, we shall be able to meet, and meet pretty often, for Lady Middleton\\u2019s delighted with Mrs. Dashwood, so we shall be a good deal in Harley Street, I dare say, and Edward spends half his time with his sister \\u2014 besides, Lady Middleton and Mrs. Ferrars will visit now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90437,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, Miss Marianne,\\u201dcried Lucy, eager to take some revenge on her, \\u201cyou think young men never stand upon engagements, if they have no mind to keep them, little as well as great.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91388,\n            \"Their presence was a restraint both on her and on Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91414,\n            \"Lady Middleton was ashamed of doing nothing before them, and the flattery which Lucy was proud to think of and administer at other times, she feared they would despise her for offering.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94254,\n            \"Fanny, rejoicing in her escape, and proud of the ready wit that had procured it, wrote the next morning to Lucy, to request her company and her sister\\u2019s, for some days, in Harley Street, as soon as Lady Middleton could spare them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94317,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood seemed actually working for her, herself;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 6]\": [\n        [\n            44889,\n            \"\\u201cWe have heard Sir John admire it excessively,\\u201dsaid Lucy, who seemed to think some apology necessary for the freedom of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52964,\n            \"I have been always used to a very small income, and could struggle with any poverty for him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52984,\n            \"but I love him too well to be the selfish means of robbing him, perhaps, of all that his mother might give him if he married to please her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55475,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have a notion,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cthat Miss Marianne would not object to such a scheme, if her elder sister would come into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99277,\n            \"Miss Lucy Steele is, I dare say, a very deserving young woman, but in the present case you know, the connection must be impossible.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 7]\": [\n        [\n            92805,\n            \"He addressed her with easy civility, and twisted his head into a bow which assured her as plainly as words could have done, that he was exactly the coxcomb she had heard him described to be by Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95201,\n            \"Mr. Edward Ferrars, the very young man I used to joke with you about (but however, as it turns out, I am monstrous glad there was never any thing in it), Mr. Edward Ferrars, it seems, has been engaged above this twelvemonth to my cousin Lucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140826,\n            \"Robert\\u2019s offence was unpardonable, but Lucy\\u2019s was infinitely worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140855,\n            \"and even, if she might hereafter be induced to forgive her son, his wife should never be acknowledged as her daughter, nor be permitted to appear in her presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142864,\n            \"for though Lucy soon gave him hopes that his eloquence would convince her in _ time _, another visit, another conversation, was always wanted to produce this conviction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143198,\n            \"Lucy became as necessary to Mrs. Ferrars, as either Robert or Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143291,\n            \"and setting aside the jealousies and ill-will continually subsisting between Fanny and Lucy, in which their husbands of course took a part, as well as the frequent domestic disagreements between Robert and Lucy themselves, nothing could exceed the harmony in which they all lived together.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 10]\": [\n        [\n            44889,\n            \"\\u201cWe have heard Sir John admire it excessively,\\u201dsaid Lucy, who seemed to think some apology necessary for the freedom of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44996,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut why should you think,\\u201dsaid Lucy, looking ashamed of her sister, \\u201cthat there are not as many genteel young men in Devonshire as Sussex?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141015,\n            \"Perhaps, however, he is kept silent by his fear of offending, and I shall, therefore, give him a hint, by a line to Oxford, that his sister and I both think a letter of proper submission from him, addressed perhaps to Fanny, and by her shown to her mother, might not be taken amiss;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143198,\n            \"Lucy became as necessary to Mrs. Ferrars, as either Robert or Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143291,\n            \"and setting aside the jealousies and ill-will continually subsisting between Fanny and Lucy, in which their husbands of course took a part, as well as the frequent domestic disagreements between Robert and Lucy themselves, nothing could exceed the harmony in which they all lived together.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 12]\": [\n        [\n            55255,\n            \"I am sure your mother can spare you very well, and I _ do _ beg you will favour me with your company, for I\\u2019ve quite set my heart upon it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55560,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cI am sure I shall be monstrous glad of Miss Marianne\\u2019s company, whether Miss Dashwood will go or not, only the more the merrier say I, and I thought it would be more comfortable for them to be together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55719,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thank you, ma\\u2019am, sincerely thank you,\\u201dsaid Marianne, with warmth: \\u201cyour invitation has insured my gratitude for ever, and it would give me such happiness, yes, almost the greatest happiness I am capable of, to be able to accept it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91726,\n            \"but wherever it was, she always came in excellent spirits, full of delight and importance, attributing Charlotte\\u2019s well doing to her own care, and ready to give so exact, so minute a detail of her situation, as only Miss Steele had curiosity enough to desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 She listened to her praise of Lucy with only moving from one chair to another, and when Mrs. Jennings talked of Edward\\u2019s affection, it cost her only a spasm in her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99176,\n            \"I have some little concern in the business, as well as yourself, for Lucy Steele is my cousin, and I believe there is not a better kind of girl in the world, nor one who more deserves a good husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103884,\n            \"She calls me dear Mrs. Jennings, you see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109735,\n            \"and she joined Mrs. Jennings most heartily in her expectation of their being all comfortably together in Delaford Parsonage before Michaelmas.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140495,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings wrote to tell the wonderful tale, to vent her honest indignation against the jilting girl, and pour forth her compassion towards poor Mr. Edward, who, she was sure, had quite doted upon the worthless hussy, and was now, by all accounts, almost broken-hearted, at Oxford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140574,\n            \"for it was but two days before Lucy called and sat a couple of hours with me.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 15]\": [\n        [\n            47178,\n            \"Are you acquainted with Mr. Robert Ferrars?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47211,\n            \"\\u201cNo,\\u201dreplied Lucy, \\u201cnot to Mr. _ Robert _ Ferrars \\u2014 I never saw him in my life;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 16]\": [\n        [\n            46356,\n            \"and to the invariable coldness of her behaviour towards them, which checked every endeavour at intimacy on their side, Elinor principally attributed that preference of herself which soon became evident in the manners of both, but especially of Lucy, who missed no opportunity of engaging her in conversation, or of striving to improve their acquaintance by an easy and frank communication of her sentiments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53823,\n            \"Lucy first put an end to it by saying in a lower tone, though Marianne was then giving them the powerful protection of a very magnificent concerto, \\u2014 \\u201cI will honestly tell you of one scheme which has lately come into my head, for bringing matters to bear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55475,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have a notion,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cthat Miss Marianne would not object to such a scheme, if her elder sister would come into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55560,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cI am sure I shall be monstrous glad of Miss Marianne\\u2019s company, whether Miss Dashwood will go or not, only the more the merrier say I, and I thought it would be more comfortable for them to be together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55719,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thank you, ma\\u2019am, sincerely thank you,\\u201dsaid Marianne, with warmth: \\u201cyour invitation has insured my gratitude for ever, and it would give me such happiness, yes, almost the greatest happiness I am capable of, to be able to accept it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90104,\n            \"\\u201d This remark was not calculated to make Edward or Elinor more easy, nor to conciliate the good will of Lucy, who looked up at Marianne with no very benignant expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90770,\n            \"\\u201d said Marianne, on her leaving them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90923,\n            \"and Elinor dared not follow her to say more, for bound as she was by her promise of secrecy to Lucy, she could give no information that would convince Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91532,\n            \"for though she often threw out expressions of pity for her sister to Elinor, and more than once dropt a reflection on the inconstancy of beaux before Marianne, no effect was produced, but a look of indifference from the former, or of disgust in the latter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96291,\n            \"though she earnestly tried to drive away the notion of its being possible to end otherwise at last, than in the marriage of Edward and Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96366,\n            \"\\u2014 for Lucy very little \\u2014 and it cost her some pains to procure that little;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102975,\n            \"Edward\\u2019s marriage with Lucy was as firmly determined on, and the time of its taking place remained as absolutely uncertain, as she had concluded it would be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103053,\n            \"but as Elinor wished to spread as little as possible intelligence that had in the first place been so unfairly obtained, she confined herself to the brief repetition of such simple particulars, as she felt assured that Lucy, for the sake of her own consequence, would choose to have known.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137446,\n            \"and her joy, though sincere as her love for her sister, was of a kind to give her neither spirits nor language.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144380,\n            \"and among the merits and the happiness of Elinor and Marianne, let it not be ranked as the least considerable, that though sisters, and living almost within sight of each other, they could live without disagreement between themselves, or producing coolness between their husbands.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 17]\": [\n        [\n            46709,\n            \"\\u201cI wonder at that, for I thought you must have seen her at Norland sometimes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46727,\n            \"Then, perhaps, you cannot tell me what sort of a woman she is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46781,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sure you think me very strange, for enquiring about her in such a way,\\u201dsaid Lucy, eyeing Elinor attentively as she spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46979,\n            \"I am sorry you do not happen to know Mrs. Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46992,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry I do _ not _,\\u201dsaid Elinor, in great astonishment, \\u201cif it could be of any use to YOU to know my opinion of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47028,\n            \"But really I never understood that you were at all connected with that family, and therefore I am a little surprised, I confess, at so serious an inquiry into her character.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47100,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars is certainly nothing to me at present \\u2014 but the time _ may _ come \\u2014 how soon it will come must depend upon herself \\u2014 when we may be very intimately connected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47439,\n            \"and I really thought my behaviour in asking so many questions about Mrs. Ferrars must seem so odd, that it ought to be explained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52911,\n            \"Mr. Ferrars, I believe, is entirely dependent on his mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53422,\n            \"or have you none but that of waiting for Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s death, which is a melancholy and shocking extremity?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53446,\n            \"\\u2014 Is her son determined to submit to this, and to all the tediousness of the many years of suspense in which it may involve you, rather than run the risk of her displeasure for a while by owning the truth?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53506,\n            \"But Mrs. Ferrars is a very headstrong proud woman, and in her first fit of anger upon hearing it, would very likely secure every thing to Robert, and the idea of that, for Edward\\u2019s sake, frightens away all my inclination for hasty measures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134325,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThey come straight from town, as Miss Lucy \\u2014 Mrs. Ferrars told me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140855,\n            \"and even, if she might hereafter be induced to forgive her son, his wife should never be acknowledged as her daughter, nor be permitted to appear in her presence.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 18]\": [\n        [\n            47236,\n            \"but,\\u201dfixing her eyes upon Elinor, \\u201cto his eldest brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47355,\n            \"for I dare say he never dropped the smallest hint of it to you or any of your family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47466,\n            \"And I do not think Mr. Ferrars can be displeased, when he knows I have trusted you, because I know he has the highest opinion in the world of all your family, and looks upon yourself and the other Miss Dashwoods quite as his own sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47735,\n            \"It was there our acquaintance begun, for my sister and me was often staying with my uncle, and it was there our engagement was formed, though not till a year after he had quitted as a pupil;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47808,\n            \"but I was too young, and loved him too well, to be so prudent as I ought to have been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47831,\n            \"Though you do not know him so well as me, Miss Dashwood, you must have seen enough of him to be sensible he is very capable of making a woman sincerely attached to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47882,\n            \"but after a moment\\u2019s reflection, she added, with revived security of Edward\\u2019s honour and love, and her companion\\u2019s falsehood \\u2014 \\u201cEngaged to Mr. Edward Ferrars!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48014,\n            \"you must allow that I am not likely to be deceived as to the name of the man on who all my happiness depends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48039,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt is strange,\\u201dreplied Elinor, in a most painful perplexity, \\u201cthat I should never have heard him even mention your name.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48246,\n            \"It does not do him justice, to be sure, but yet I think you cannot be deceived as to the person it was drew for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48295,\n            \"and when Elinor saw the painting, whatever other doubts her fear of a too hasty decision, or her wish of detecting falsehood might suffer to linger in her mind, she could have none of its being Edward\\u2019s face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48349,\n            \"\\u201cI have never been able,\\u201dcontinued Lucy, \\u201cto give him my picture in return, which I am very much vexed at, for he has been always so anxious to get it!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48777,\n            \"She does not know how to hold her tongue, as you must perceive, and I am sure I was in the greatest fright in the world t\\u2019other day, when Edward\\u2019s name was mentioned by Sir John, lest she should out with it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48846,\n            \"I only wonder that I am alive after what I have suffered for Edward\\u2019s sake these last four years.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48978,\n            \"I cannot bear the thoughts of making him so miserable, as I know the very mention of such a thing would do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49002,\n            \"And on my own account too \\u2014 so dear as he is to me \\u2014 I don\\u2019t think I could be equal to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49083,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTo be sure,\\u201dcontinued Lucy, after a few minutes silence on both sides, \\u201chis mother must provide for him sometime or other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49138,\n            \"He was so miserable when he left us at Longstaple, to go to you, that I was afraid you would think him quite ill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49310,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI begged him to exert himself for fear you should suspect what was the matter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49328,\n            \"but it made him so melancholy, not being able to stay more than a fortnight with us, and seeing me so much affected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49357,\n            \"I am afraid it is just the same with him now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49376,\n            \"I heard from him just before I left Exeter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49401,\n            \"\\u201cYou know his hand, I dare say, \\u2014 a charming one it is;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49428,\n            \"He was tired, I dare say, for he had just filled the sheet to me as full as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49598,\n            \"Yes, _ I _ have one other comfort in his picture, but poor Edward has not even _ that _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49621,\n            \"If he had but my picture, he says he should be easy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49635,\n            \"I gave him a lock of my hair set in a ring when he was at Longstaple last, and that was some comfort to him, he said, but not equal to a picture.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50044,\n            \"Was his engagement to Lucy an engagement of the heart?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50260,\n            \"could he, were his affection for herself out of the question, with his integrity, his delicacy, and well-informed mind, be satisfied with a wife like her \\u2014 illiterate, artful, and selfish?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50301,\n            \"The youthful infatuation of nineteen would naturally blind him to every thing but her beauty and good nature;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50320,\n            \"but the four succeeding years \\u2014 years, which if rationally spent, give such improvement to the understanding, must have opened his eyes to her defects of education, while the same period of time, spent on her side in inferior society and more frivolous pursuits, had perhaps robbed her of that simplicity which might once have given an interesting character to her beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50389,\n            \"If in the supposition of his seeking to marry herself, his difficulties from his mother had seemed great, how much greater were they now likely to be, when the object of his engagement was undoubtedly inferior in connections, and probably inferior in fortune to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50439,\n            \"These difficulties, indeed, with a heart so alienated from Lucy, might not press very hard upon his patience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50891,\n            \"She wanted to hear many particulars of their engagement repeated again, she wanted more clearly to understand what Lucy really felt for Edward, whether there were any sincerity in her declaration of tender regard for him, and she particularly wanted to convince Lucy, by her readiness to enter on the matter again, and her calmness in conversing on it, that she was no otherwise interested in it than as a friend, which she very much feared her involuntary agitation, in their morning discourse, must have left at least doubtful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50990,\n            \"That Lucy was disposed to be jealous of her appeared very probable: it was plain that Edward had always spoken highly in her praise, not merely from Lucy\\u2019s assertion, but from her venturing to trust her on so short a personal acquaintance, with a secret so confessedly and evidently important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51061,\n            \"But indeed, while Elinor remained so well assured within herself of being really beloved by Edward, it required no other consideration of probabilities to make it natural that Lucy should be jealous;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51109,\n            \"What other reason for the disclosure of the affair could there be, but that Elinor might be informed by it of Lucy\\u2019s superior claims on Edward, and be taught to avoid him in future?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51148,\n            \"She had little difficulty in understanding thus much of her rival\\u2019s intentions, and while she was firmly resolved to act by her as every principle of honour and honesty directed, to combat her own affection for Edward and to see him as little as possible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53043,\n            \"but Edward\\u2019s affection and constancy nothing can deprive me of I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53069,\n            \"and he is undoubtedly supported by the same trust in your\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53147,\n            \"\\u201cEdward\\u2019s love for me,\\u201dsaid Lucy, \\u201chas been pretty well put to the test, by our long, very long absence since we were first engaged, and it has stood the trial so well, that I should be unpardonable to doubt it now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53201,\n            \"I can safely say that he has never gave me one moment\\u2019s alarm on that account from the first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53240,\n            \"\\u201cI am rather of a jealous temper too by nature, and from our different situations in life, from his being so much more in the world than me, and our continual separation, I was enough inclined for suspicion, to have found out the truth in an instant, if there had been the slightest alteration in his behaviour to me when we met, or any lowness of spirits that I could not account for, or if he had talked more of one lady than another, or seemed in any respect less happy at Longstaple than he used to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53446,\n            \"\\u2014 Is her son determined to submit to this, and to all the tediousness of the many years of suspense in which it may involve you, rather than run the risk of her displeasure for a while by owning the truth?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53506,\n            \"But Mrs. Ferrars is a very headstrong proud woman, and in her first fit of anger upon hearing it, would very likely secure every thing to Robert, and the idea of that, for Edward\\u2019s sake, frightens away all my inclination for hasty measures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53587,\n            \"\\u201cDo you know Mr. Robert Ferrars?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53600,\n            \"\\u201cNot at all \\u2014 I never saw him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53610,\n            \"but I fancy he is very unlike his brother \\u2014 silly and a great coxcomb.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53894,\n            \"I dare say you have seen enough of Edward to know that he would prefer the church to every other profession;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53916,\n            \"now my plan is that he should take orders as soon as he can, and then through your interest, which I am sure you would be kind enough to use out of friendship for him, and I hope out of some regard to me, your brother might be persuaded to give him Norland living;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54282,\n            \"and I do really believe, that if you was to say to me, \\u2018 I advise you by all means to put an end to your engagement with Edward Ferrars, it will be more for the happiness of both of you,\\u2019I should resolve upon doing it immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54667,\n            \"But I only go for the sake of seeing Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54849,\n            \"From this time the subject was never revived by Elinor, and when entered on by Lucy, who seldom missed an opportunity of introducing it, and was particularly careful to inform her confidante, of her happiness whenever she received a letter from Edward, it was treated by the former with calmness and caution, and dismissed as soon as civility would allow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56715,\n            \"To this determination she was the more easily reconciled, by recollecting that Edward Ferrars, by Lucy\\u2019s account, was not to be in town before February;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85918,\n            \"and to see him for the first time, after all that passed, in the company of Lucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85968,\n            \"They were relieved however, not by her own recollection, but by the good will of Lucy, who believed herself to be inflicting a severe disappointment when she told her that Edward certainly would not be in Harley Street on Tuesday, and even hoped to be carrying the pain still farther by persuading her that he was kept away by the extreme affection for herself, which he could not conceal when they were together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88282,\n            \"Or at least, if she did not bring herself quite to rejoice in Edward\\u2019s being fettered to Lucy, she determined, that had Lucy been more amiable, she _ ought _ to have rejoiced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88976,\n            \"But it seemed to satisfy Lucy, for she directly replied, \\u201cIndeed I am perfectly convinced of your regard for me, and next to Edward\\u2019s love, it is the greatest comfort I have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89019,\n            \"But now there is one good thing, we shall be able to meet, and meet pretty often, for Lady Middleton\\u2019s delighted with Mrs. Dashwood, so we shall be a good deal in Harley Street, I dare say, and Edward spends half his time with his sister \\u2014 besides, Lady Middleton and Mrs. Ferrars will visit now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89438,\n            \"She could therefore only _ look _ her tenderness, and after slightly addressing him, said no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89523,\n            \"She would not allow the presence of Lucy, nor the consciousness of some injustice towards herself, to deter her from saying that she was happy to see him, and that she had very much regretted being from home, when he called before in Berkeley Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89573,\n            \"She would not be frightened from paying him those attentions which, as a friend and almost a relation, were his due, by the observant eyes of Lucy, though she soon perceived them to be narrowly watching her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89661,\n            \"for his heart had not the indifference of Lucy\\u2019s, nor could his conscience have quite the ease of Elinor\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89983,\n            \"while Marianne was looking with the most speaking tenderness, sometimes at Edward and sometimes at Elinor, regretting only that their delight in each other should be checked by Lucy\\u2019s unwelcome presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90104,\n            \"\\u201d This remark was not calculated to make Edward or Elinor more easy, nor to conciliate the good will of Lucy, who looked up at Marianne with no very benignant expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90709,\n            \"\\u201d And drawing him a little aside, she whispered her persuasion that Lucy could not stay much longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90801,\n            \"\\u2014 we were all his friends, and Lucy has been the longest known to him of any.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90820,\n            \"It is but natural that he should like to see her as well as ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94339,\n            \"Such an opportunity of being with Edward and his family was, above all things, the most material to her interest, and such an invitation the most gratifying to her feelings!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95997,\n            \"There is no reason on earth why Mr. Edward and Lucy should not marry;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96013,\n            \"for I am sure Mrs. Ferrars may afford to do very well by her son, and though Lucy has next to nothing herself, she knows better than any body how to make the most of every thing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96291,\n            \"though she earnestly tried to drive away the notion of its being possible to end otherwise at last, than in the marriage of Edward and Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96765,\n            \"As for Lucy Steele, she considered her so totally unamiable, so absolutely incapable of attaching a sensible man, that she could not be persuaded at first to believe, and afterwards to pardon, any former affection of Edward for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97450,\n            \"Edward will marry Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 She listened to her praise of Lucy with only moving from one chair to another, and when Mrs. Jennings talked of Edward\\u2019s affection, it cost her only a spasm in her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101176,\n            \"\\u201cWell, but Miss Dashwood,\\u201dspeaking triumphantly, \\u201cpeople may say what they chuse about Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s declaring he would not have Lucy, for it is no such thing I can tell you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101308,\n            \"for Miss Godby told Miss Sparks, that nobody in their senses could expect Mr. Ferrars to give up a woman like Miss Morton, with thirty thousand pounds to her fortune, for Lucy Steele that had nothing at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101458,\n            \"Once Lucy thought to write to him, but then her spirits rose against that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101487,\n            \"and then it all came out, how he had been sent for Wednesday to Harley Street, and been talked to by his mother and all of them, and how he had declared before them all that he loved nobody but Lucy, and nobody but Lucy would he have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101607,\n            \"And after thinking it all over and over again, he said, it seemed to him as if, now he had no fortune, and no nothing at all, it would be quite unkind to keep her on to the engagement, because it must be for her loss, for he had nothing but two thousand pounds, and no hope of any thing else;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102017,\n            \"so I was forced to go into the room and interrupt them, to ask Lucy if she would like to go, but she did not care to leave Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102975,\n            \"Edward\\u2019s marriage with Lucy was as firmly determined on, and the time of its taking place remained as absolutely uncertain, as she had concluded it would be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103153,\n            \"\\u2014 ay, we all know how _ that _ will end: \\u2014 they will wait a twelvemonth, and finding no good comes of it, will set down upon a curacy of fifty pounds a-year, with the interest of his two thousand pounds, and what little matter Mr. Steele and Mr. Pratt can give her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103868,\n            \"I wish I _ could _ get him a living, with all my heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109667,\n            \"and such was the excess of it by the time he reached Bartlett\\u2019s Buildings, that she was able to assure Mrs. Jennings, who called on her again the next day with her congratulations, that she had never seen him in such spirits before in her life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109758,\n            \"So far was she, at the same time, from any backwardness to give Elinor that credit which Edward _ would _ give her, that she spoke of her friendship for them both with the most grateful warmth, was ready to own all their obligation to her, and openly declared that no exertion for their good on Miss Dashwood\\u2019s part, either present or future, would ever surprise her, for she believed her capable of doing any thing in the world for those she really valued.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113297,\n            \"She had no such object for her lingering thoughts to fix on, she left no creature behind, from whom it would give her a moment\\u2019s regret to be divided for ever, she was pleased to be free herself from the persecution of Lucy\\u2019s friendship, she was grateful for bringing her sister away unseen by Willoughby since his marriage, and she looked forward with hope to what a few months of tranquility at Barton might do towards restoring Marianne\\u2019s peace of mind, and confirming her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134403,\n            \"She recognised the whole of Lucy in the message, and was very confident that Edward would never come near them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134914,\n            \"She now found, that in spite of herself, she had always admitted a hope, while Edward remained single, that something would occur to prevent his marrying Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134946,\n            \"that some resolution of his own, some mediation of friends, or some more eligible opportunity of establishment for the lady, would arise to assist the happiness of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135042,\n            \"But she soon saw how likely it was that Lucy, in her self-provident care, in her haste to secure him, should overlook every thing but the risk of delay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135095,\n            \"What had Edward felt on being within four miles from Barton, on seeing her mother\\u2019s servant, on hearing Lucy\\u2019s message!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136212,\n            \"took up a pair of scissors that lay there, and while spoiling both them and their sheath by cutting the latter to pieces as he spoke, said, in a hurried voice, \\u2014 \\u201cPerhaps you do not know: you may not have heard that my brother is lately married to \\u2014 to the youngest \\u2014 to Miss Lucy Steele.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136901,\n            \"His heart was now open to Elinor, all its weaknesses, all its errors confessed, and his first boyish attachment to Lucy treated with all the philosophic dignity of twenty-four.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137484,\n            \"From the moment of learning that Lucy was married to another, that Edward was free, to the moment of his justifying the hopes which had so instantly followed, she was every thing by turns but tranquil.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138064,\n            \"And Lucy perhaps at first might think only of procuring his good offices in my favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138112,\n            \"for at Oxford, where he had remained for choice ever since his quitting London, he had had no means of hearing of her but from herself, and her letters to the very last were neither less frequent, nor less affectionate than usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138176,\n            \"\\u2014 and when at last it burst on him in a letter from Lucy herself, he had been for some time, he believed, half stupified between the wonder, the horror, and the joy of such a deliverance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138681,\n            \"She will hardly be less hurt, I suppose, by Robert\\u2019s marrying Lucy, than she would have been by your marrying her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138776,\n            \"He had quitted Oxford within four and twenty hours after Lucy\\u2019s letter arrived, and with only one object before him, the nearest road to Barton, had had no leisure to form any scheme of conduct, with which that road did not hold the most intimate connection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138829,\n            \"He could do nothing till he were assured of his fate with Miss Dashwood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138958,\n            \"That Lucy had certainly meant to deceive, to go off with a flourish of malice against him in her message by Thomas, was perfectly clear to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139138,\n            \"\\u201cI thought it my duty,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cindependent of my feelings, to give her the option of continuing the engagement or not, when I was renounced by my mother, and stood to all appearance without a friend in the world to assist me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139402,\n            \"\\u201d Edward was, of course, immediately convinced that nothing could have been more natural than Lucy\\u2019s conduct, nor more self-evident than the motive of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140932,\n            \"and he called on Elinor to join with him in regretting that Lucy\\u2019s engagement with Edward had not rather been fulfilled, than that she should thus be the means of spreading misery farther in the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141015,\n            \"Perhaps, however, he is kept silent by his fear of offending, and I shall, therefore, give him a hint, by a line to Oxford, that his sister and I both think a letter of proper submission from him, addressed perhaps to Fanny, and by her shown to her mother, might not be taken amiss;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141755,\n            \"\\u2014 told him, that in Miss Morton he would have a woman of higher rank and larger fortune;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[2, 19]\": [\n        [\n            44694,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have a notion,\\u201dsaid Lucy, \\u201cyou think the little Middletons rather too much indulged;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44996,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut why should you think,\\u201dsaid Lucy, looking ashamed of her sister, \\u201cthat there are not as many genteel young men in Devonshire as Sussex?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45029,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay, my dear, I\\u2019m sure I don\\u2019t pretend to say that there an\\u2019t.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46356,\n            \"and to the invariable coldness of her behaviour towards them, which checked every endeavour at intimacy on their side, Elinor principally attributed that preference of herself which soon became evident in the manners of both, but especially of Lucy, who missed no opportunity of engaging her in conversation, or of striving to improve their acquaintance by an easy and frank communication of her sentiments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46439,\n            \"and as a companion for half an hour Elinor frequently found her agreeable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46506,\n            \"Elinor saw, and pitied her for, the neglect of abilities which education might have rendered so respectable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46526,\n            \"but she saw, with less tenderness of feeling, the thorough want of delicacy, of rectitude, and integrity of mind, which her attentions, her assiduities, her flatteries at the Park betrayed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46614,\n            \"\\u201cYou will think my question an odd one, I dare say,\\u201dsaid Lucy to her one day, as they were walking together from the park to the cottage \\u2014 \\u201cbut pray, are you personally acquainted with your sister-in-law\\u2019s mother, Mrs. Ferrars?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46709,\n            \"\\u201cI wonder at that, for I thought you must have seen her at Norland sometimes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46727,\n            \"Then, perhaps, you cannot tell me what sort of a woman she is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46781,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sure you think me very strange, for enquiring about her in such a way,\\u201dsaid Lucy, eyeing Elinor attentively as she spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46826,\n            \"but however I hope you will do me the justice of believing that I do not mean to be impertinent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46847,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor made her a civil reply, and they walked on for a few minutes in silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46866,\n            \"It was broken by Lucy, who renewed the subject again by saying, with some hesitation, \\u201cI cannot bear to have you think me impertinently curious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46896,\n            \"I am sure I would rather do any thing in the world than be thought so by a person whose good opinion is so well worth having as yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46926,\n            \"And I am sure I should not have the smallest fear of trusting _ you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46942,\n            \"_ indeed, I should be very glad of your advice how to manage in such an uncomfortable situation as I am;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46979,\n            \"I am sorry you do not happen to know Mrs. Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46992,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry I do _ not _,\\u201dsaid Elinor, in great astonishment, \\u201cif it could be of any use to YOU to know my opinion of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47137,\n            \"\\u201d She looked down as she said this, amiably bashful, with only one side glance at her companion to observe its effect on her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47168,\n            \"\\u201d cried Elinor, \\u201cwhat do you mean?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47236,\n            \"but,\\u201dfixing her eyes upon Elinor, \\u201cto his eldest brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47283,\n            \"She turned towards Lucy in silent amazement, unable to divine the reason or object of such a declaration;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47329,\n            \"\\u201cYou may well be surprised,\\u201dcontinued Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47355,\n            \"for I dare say he never dropped the smallest hint of it to you or any of your family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47401,\n            \"Not a soul of all my relations know of it but Anne, and I never should have mentioned it to you, if I had not felt the greatest dependence in the world upon your secrecy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47466,\n            \"And I do not think Mr. Ferrars can be displeased, when he knows I have trusted you, because I know he has the highest opinion in the world of all your family, and looks upon yourself and the other Miss Dashwoods quite as his own sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47619,\n            \"\\u201cI did not know,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cthat you were even acquainted till the other day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47693,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI think I have,\\u201dreplied Elinor, with an exertion of spirits, which increased with her increase of emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47831,\n            \"Though you do not know him so well as me, Miss Dashwood, you must have seen enough of him to be sensible he is very capable of making a woman sincerely attached to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47882,\n            \"but after a moment\\u2019s reflection, she added, with revived security of Edward\\u2019s honour and love, and her companion\\u2019s falsehood \\u2014 \\u201cEngaged to Mr. Edward Ferrars!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48014,\n            \"you must allow that I am not likely to be deceived as to the name of the man on who all my happiness depends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48039,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt is strange,\\u201dreplied Elinor, in a most painful perplexity, \\u201cthat I should never have heard him even mention your name.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48092,\n            \"You knew nothing of me, or my family, and, therefore, there could be no _ occasion _ for ever mentioning my name to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48173,\n            \"\\u201cFour years you have been engaged,\\u201dsaid she with a firm voice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48246,\n            \"It does not do him justice, to be sure, but yet I think you cannot be deceived as to the person it was drew for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48284,\n            \"\\u201d She put it into her hands as she spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48295,\n            \"and when Elinor saw the painting, whatever other doubts her fear of a too hasty decision, or her wish of detecting falsehood might suffer to linger in her mind, she could have none of its being Edward\\u2019s face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48401,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are quite in the right,\\u201dreplied Elinor calmly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48428,\n            \"\\u201cI am sure,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cI have no doubt in the world of your faithfully keeping this secret, because you must know of what importance it is to us, not to have it reach his mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48500,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI certainly did not seek your confidence,\\u201dsaid Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48514,\n            \"\\u201cbut you do me no more than justice in imagining that I may be depended on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48532,\n            \"Your secret is safe with me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48553,\n            \"You must at least have felt that my being acquainted with it could not add to its safety.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48572,\n            \"\\u201d As she said this, she looked earnestly at Lucy, hoping to discover something in her countenance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48615,\n            \"\\u201cI was afraid you would think I was taking a great liberty with you,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cin telling you all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48951,\n            \"\\u201d As she said this, she looked directly at her companion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49029,\n            \"What would you advise me to do in such a case, Miss Dashwood?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49064,\n            \"\\u201cbut I can give you no advice under such circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49138,\n            \"He was so miserable when he left us at Longstaple, to go to you, that I was afraid you would think him quite ill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49207,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo,\\u201dreplied Elinor, most feelingly sensible of every fresh circumstance in favour of Lucy\\u2019s veracity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49386,\n            \"\\u201d taking a letter from her pocket and carelessly showing the direction to Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49779,\n            \"However small Elinor\\u2019s general dependence on Lucy\\u2019s veracity might be, it was impossible for her on serious reflection to suspect it in the present case, where no temptation could be answerable to the folly of inventing a falsehood of such a description.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49828,\n            \"What Lucy had asserted to be true, therefore, Elinor could not, dared not longer doubt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50858,\n            \"Much as she had suffered from her first conversation with Lucy on the subject, she soon felt an earnest wish of renewing it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50891,\n            \"She wanted to hear many particulars of their engagement repeated again, she wanted more clearly to understand what Lucy really felt for Edward, whether there were any sincerity in her declaration of tender regard for him, and she particularly wanted to convince Lucy, by her readiness to enter on the matter again, and her calmness in conversing on it, that she was no otherwise interested in it than as a friend, which she very much feared her involuntary agitation, in their morning discourse, must have left at least doubtful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50990,\n            \"That Lucy was disposed to be jealous of her appeared very probable: it was plain that Edward had always spoken highly in her praise, not merely from Lucy\\u2019s assertion, but from her venturing to trust her on so short a personal acquaintance, with a secret so confessedly and evidently important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51061,\n            \"But indeed, while Elinor remained so well assured within herself of being really beloved by Edward, it required no other consideration of probabilities to make it natural that Lucy should be jealous;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51109,\n            \"What other reason for the disclosure of the affair could there be, but that Elinor might be informed by it of Lucy\\u2019s superior claims on Edward, and be taught to avoid him in future?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51148,\n            \"She had little difficulty in understanding thus much of her rival\\u2019s intentions, and while she was firmly resolved to act by her as every principle of honour and honesty directed, to combat her own affection for Edward and to see him as little as possible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51198,\n            \"she could not deny herself the comfort of endeavouring to convince Lucy that her heart was unwounded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51253,\n            \"But it was not immediately that an opportunity of doing so could be commanded, though Lucy was as well disposed as herself to take advantage of any that occurred;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51637,\n            \"it produced not one novelty of thought or expression, and nothing could be less interesting than the whole of their discourse both in the dining parlour and drawing room: to the latter, the children accompanied them, and while they remained there, she was too well convinced of the impossibility of engaging Lucy\\u2019s attention to attempt it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52183,\n            \"\\u201cPerhaps,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cif I should happen to cut out, I may be of some use to Miss Lucy Steele, in rolling her papers for her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52217,\n            \"and there is so much still to be done to the basket, that it must be impossible I think for her labour singly, to finish it this evening.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52248,\n            \"I should like the work exceedingly, if she would allow me a share in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52265,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed I shall be very much obliged to you for your help,\\u201dcried Lucy, \\u201cfor I find there is more to be done to it than I thought there was;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52430,\n            \"Lucy made room for her with ready attention, and the two fair rivals were thus seated side by side at the same table, and, with the utmost harmony, engaged in forwarding the same work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52554,\n            \"\\u201cI should be undeserving of the confidence you have honoured me with, if I felt no desire for its continuance, or no farther curiosity on its subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52596,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThank you,\\u201dcried Lucy warmly, \\u201cfor breaking the ice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52612,\n            \"you have set my heart at ease by it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52622,\n            \"for I was somehow or other afraid I had offended you by what I told you that Monday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52652,\n            \"Believe me,\\u201dand Elinor spoke it with the truest sincerity, \\u201cnothing could be farther from my intention than to give you such an idea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52681,\n            \"Could you have a motive for the trust, that was not honourable and flattering to me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52699,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd yet I do assure you,\\u201dreplied Lucy, her little sharp eyes full of meaning, \\u201cthere seemed to me to be a coldness and displeasure in your manner that made me quite uncomfortable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52740,\n            \"I felt sure that you was angry with me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52750,\n            \"and have been quarrelling with myself ever since, for having took such a liberty as to trouble you with my affairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52773,\n            \"But I am very glad to find it was only my own fancy, and that you really do not blame me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52796,\n            \"If you knew what a consolation it was to me to relieve my heart speaking to you of what I am always thinking of every moment of my life, your compassion would make you overlook every thing else I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52839,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed, I can easily believe that it was a very great relief to you, to acknowledge your situation to me, and be assured that you shall never have reason to repent it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53916,\n            \"now my plan is that he should take orders as soon as he can, and then through your interest, which I am sure you would be kind enough to use out of friendship for him, and I hope out of some regard to me, your brother might be persuaded to give him Norland living;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54045,\n            \"but do you not perceive that my interest on such an occasion would be perfectly unnecessary?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54186,\n            \"But you will not give me your advice, Miss Dashwood?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54226,\n            \"You know very well that my opinion would have no weight with you, unless it were on the side of your wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54250,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed you wrong me,\\u201dreplied Lucy, with great solemnity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54265,\n            \"\\u201cI know nobody of whose judgment I think so highly as I do of yours;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54282,\n            \"and I do really believe, that if you was to say to me, \\u2018 I advise you by all means to put an end to your engagement with Edward Ferrars, it will be more for the happiness of both of you,\\u2019I should resolve upon doing it immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54396,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201c\\u2019Tis because you are an indifferent person,\\u201dsaid Lucy, with some pique, and laying a particular stress on those words, \\u201cthat your judgment might justly have such weight with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54547,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry for that,\\u201dreturned the other, while her eyes brightened at the information, \\u201cit would have gave me such pleasure to meet you there!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54581,\n            \"But I dare say you will go for all that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54632,\n            \"I had quite depended upon meeting you there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54849,\n            \"From this time the subject was never revived by Elinor, and when entered on by Lucy, who seldom missed an opportunity of introducing it, and was particularly careful to inform her confidante, of her happiness whenever she received a letter from Edward, it was treated by the former with calmness and caution, and dismissed as soon as civility would allow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54916,\n            \"for she felt such conversations to be an indulgence which Lucy did not deserve, and which were dangerous to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55776,\n            \"But my mother, my dearest, kindest mother, \\u2014 I feel the justice of what Elinor has urged, and if she were to be made less happy, less comfortable by our absence \\u2014 Oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55815,\n            \"no, nothing should tempt me to leave her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56715,\n            \"To this determination she was the more easily reconciled, by recollecting that Edward Ferrars, by Lucy\\u2019s account, was not to be in town before February;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60650,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd now,\\u201dsilently conjectured Elinor, \\u201cshe will write to Combe by this day\\u2019s post.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85297,\n            \"Lucy came very shortly to claim Elinor\\u2019s compassion on being unable to see Edward, though he had arrived in town with Mr. and Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85968,\n            \"They were relieved however, not by her own recollection, but by the good will of Lucy, who believed herself to be inflicting a severe disappointment when she told her that Edward certainly would not be in Harley Street on Tuesday, and even hoped to be carrying the pain still farther by persuading her that he was kept away by the extreme affection for herself, which he could not conceal when they were together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86076,\n            \"\\u201d said Lucy, as they walked up the stairs together \\u2014 for the Middletons arrived so directly after Mrs. Jennings, that they all followed the servant at the same time: \\u2014 \\u201cthere is nobody here but you, that can feel for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86157,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor could have given her immediate relief by suggesting the possibility of its being Miss Morton\\u2019s mother, rather than her own, whom they were about to behold;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86190,\n            \"but instead of doing that, she assured her, and with great sincerity, that she did pity her \\u2014 to the utter amazement of Lucy, who, though really uncomfortable herself, hoped at least to be an object of irrepressible envy to Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87947,\n            \"and Sir John felt so desperately enraged against the author of this nervous distress, that he instantly changed his seat to one close by Lucy Steele, and gave her, in a whisper, a brief account of the whole shocking affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88343,\n            \"\\u2014 that her interest and her vanity should so very much blind her as to make the attention which seemed only paid her because she was _ not Elinor _, appear a compliment to herself \\u2014 or to allow her to derive encouragement from a preference only given her, because her real situation was unknown.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88401,\n            \"But that it was so, had not only been declared by Lucy\\u2019s eyes at the time, but was declared over again the next morning more openly, for at her particular desire, Lady Middleton set her down in Berkeley Street on the chance of seeing Elinor alone, to tell her how happy she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88487,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear friend,\\u201dcried Lucy, as soon as they were by themselves, \\u201cI come to talk to you of my happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88539,\n            \"You know how I dreaded the thoughts of seeing her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88664,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor wished to talk of something else, but Lucy still pressed her to own that she had reason for her happiness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88696,\n            \"\\u201cUndoubtedly, if they had known your engagement,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cnothing could be more flattering than their treatment of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88722,\n            \"\\u2014 but as that was not the case \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cI guessed you would say so,\\u201d\\u2014 replied Lucy quickly \\u2014 \\u201cbut there was no reason in the world why Mrs. Ferrars should seem to like me, if she did not, and her liking me is every thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88778,\n            \"You shan\\u2019t talk me out of my satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88836,\n            \"\\u2014 I wonder I should never hear you say how agreeable Mrs. Dashwood was!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88949,\n            \"\\u2014 Heaven knows what I should have done without your friendship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88976,\n            \"But it seemed to satisfy Lucy, for she directly replied, \\u201cIndeed I am perfectly convinced of your regard for me, and next to Edward\\u2019s love, it is the greatest comfort I have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89661,\n            \"for his heart had not the indifference of Lucy\\u2019s, nor could his conscience have quite the ease of Elinor\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89983,\n            \"while Marianne was looking with the most speaking tenderness, sometimes at Edward and sometimes at Elinor, regretting only that their delight in each other should be checked by Lucy\\u2019s unwelcome presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90104,\n            \"\\u201d This remark was not calculated to make Edward or Elinor more easy, nor to conciliate the good will of Lucy, who looked up at Marianne with no very benignant expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90923,\n            \"and Elinor dared not follow her to say more, for bound as she was by her promise of secrecy to Lucy, she could give no information that would convince Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91532,\n            \"for though she often threw out expressions of pity for her sister to Elinor, and more than once dropt a reflection on the inconstancy of beaux before Marianne, no effect was produced, but a look of indifference from the former, or of disgust in the latter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92805,\n            \"He addressed her with easy civility, and twisted his head into a bow which assured her as plainly as words could have done, that he was exactly the coxcomb she had heard him described to be by Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94424,\n            \"When the note was shown to Elinor, as it was within ten minutes after its arrival, it gave her, for the first time, some share in the expectations of Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101176,\n            \"\\u201cWell, but Miss Dashwood,\\u201dspeaking triumphantly, \\u201cpeople may say what they chuse about Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s declaring he would not have Lucy, for it is no such thing I can tell you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103296,\n            \"\\u201d The next morning brought Elinor a letter by the two-penny post from Lucy herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104771,\n            \"for, on Elinor\\u2019s moving to the window to take more expeditiously the dimensions of a print, which she was going to copy for her friend, he followed her to it with a look of particular meaning, and conversed with her there for several minutes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113297,\n            \"She had no such object for her lingering thoughts to fix on, she left no creature behind, from whom it would give her a moment\\u2019s regret to be divided for ever, she was pleased to be free herself from the persecution of Lucy\\u2019s friendship, she was grateful for bringing her sister away unseen by Willoughby since his marriage, and she looked forward with hope to what a few months of tranquility at Barton might do towards restoring Marianne\\u2019s peace of mind, and confirming her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136901,\n            \"His heart was now open to Elinor, all its weaknesses, all its errors confessed, and his first boyish attachment to Lucy treated with all the philosophic dignity of twenty-four.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138498,\n            \"\\u2014 \\u201cFor worlds would not I have had a letter of hers seen by _ you _ in former days.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138681,\n            \"She will hardly be less hurt, I suppose, by Robert\\u2019s marrying Lucy, than she would have been by your marrying her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138958,\n            \"That Lucy had certainly meant to deceive, to go off with a flourish of malice against him in her message by Thomas, was perfectly clear to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139610,\n            \"and till I began to make comparisons between yourself and Lucy, I did not know how far I was got.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140932,\n            \"and he called on Elinor to join with him in regretting that Lucy\\u2019s engagement with Edward had not rather been fulfilled, than that she should thus be the means of spreading misery farther in the family.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 4]\": [\n        [\n            10775,\n            \"Her manners had all the elegance which her husband\\u2019s wanted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10850,\n            \"Conversation however was not wanted, for Sir John was very chatty, and Lady Middleton had taken the wise precaution of bringing with her their eldest child, a fine little boy about six years old, by which means there was one subject always to be recurred to by the ladies in case of extremity, for they had to enquire his name and age, admire his beauty, and ask him questions which his mother answered for him, while he hung about her and held down his head, to the great surprise of her ladyship, who wondered at his being so shy before company, as he could make noise enough at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11143,\n            \"The former was for Sir John\\u2019s gratification, the latter for that of his lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11240,\n            \"Sir John was a sportsman, Lady Middleton a mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12137,\n            \"but the cold insipidity of Lady Middleton was so particularly repulsive, that in comparison of it the gravity of Colonel Brandon, and even the boisterous mirth of Sir John and his mother-in-law was interesting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22544,\n            \"\\u201cI hope he has had no bad news,\\u201dsaid Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22559,\n            \"\\u201cIt must be something extraordinary that could make Colonel Brandon leave my breakfast table so suddenly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22813,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am particularly sorry, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid he, addressing Lady Middleton, \\u201cthat I should receive this letter today, for it is on business which requires my immediate attendance in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114045,\n            \"they talked of the friends they had left behind, arranged Lady Middleton\\u2019s engagements, and wondered whether Mr. Palmer and Colonel Brandon would get farther than Reading that night.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 6]\": [\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12137,\n            \"but the cold insipidity of Lady Middleton was so particularly repulsive, that in comparison of it the gravity of Colonel Brandon, and even the boisterous mirth of Sir John and his mother-in-law was interesting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16212,\n            \"he is quite smitten already, and he is very well worth setting your cap at, I can tell you, in spite of all this tumbling about and spraining of ankles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23183,\n            \"\\u201cThere is no persuading you to change your mind, Brandon, I know of old,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cwhen once you are determined on anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23387,\n            \"he must and shall come back,\\u201dcried Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23399,\n            \"\\u201cIf he is not here by the end of the week, I shall go after him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23418,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, so do, Sir John,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cand then perhaps you may find out what his business is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23538,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI assure you it is not in my power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23645,\n            \"\\u201d He wished her a good morning, and, attended by Sir John, left the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40440,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not I tell you, Sir John, when you spoke to me about it before, that it could not be done?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40473,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou and I, Sir John,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cshould not stand upon such ceremony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42602,\n            \"He was a particular friend of Sir John\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42650,\n            \"But mama did not think the match good enough for me, otherwise Sir John would have mentioned it to the Colonel, and we should have been married immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42681,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not Colonel Brandon know of Sir John\\u2019s proposal to your mother before it was made?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42702,\n            \"Had he never owned his affection to yourself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142407,\n            \"But, I confess, it would give me great pleasure to call Colonel Brandon brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142444,\n            \"And his woods, \\u2014 I have not seen such timber any where in Dorsetshire, as there is now standing in Delaford Hanger!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142469,\n            \"And though, perhaps, Marianne may not seem exactly the person to attract him, yet I think it would altogether be advisable for you to have them now frequently staying with you, for as Colonel Brandon seems a great deal at home, nobody can tell what may happen;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 7]\": [\n        [\n            143561,\n            \"for her wish of bringing Marianne and Colonel Brandon together was hardly less earnest, though rather more liberal than what John had expressed.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 8]\": [\n        [\n            22049,\n            \"The idea however started by her, was immediately pursued by Colonel Brandon, who was on every occasion mindful of the feelings of others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144323,\n            \"and fortunately for Sir John and Mrs. Jennings, when Marianne was taken from them, Margaret had reached an age highly suitable for dancing, and not very ineligible for being supposed to have a lover.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 9]\": [\n        [\n            24707,\n            \"I value not her censure any more than I should do her commendation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25886,\n            \"and on Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s happening to mention her design of improving the cottage in the spring, he warmly opposed every alteration of a place which affection had established as perfect with him.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 10]\": [\n        [\n            40513,\n            \"\\u201cMy love you contradict every body,\\u201dsaid his wife with her usual laugh.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 12]\": [\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12137,\n            \"but the cold insipidity of Lady Middleton was so particularly repulsive, that in comparison of it the gravity of Colonel Brandon, and even the boisterous mirth of Sir John and his mother-in-law was interesting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19341,\n            \"and had Elinor\\u2019s memory been equal to her means of improvement, she might have known very early in their acquaintance all the particulars of Mr. Jennings\\u2019 s last illness, and what he said to his wife a few minutes before he died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22585,\n            \"\\u201cNo bad news, Colonel, I hope;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22595,\n            \"\\u201d said Mrs. Jennings, as soon as he entered the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22609,\n            \"\\u201cNone at all, ma\\u2019am, I thank you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22763,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, then, I know who it is from, Colonel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22807,\n            \"you know who I mean.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22813,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am particularly sorry, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid he, addressing Lady Middleton, \\u201cthat I should receive this letter today, for it is on business which requires my immediate attendance in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23033,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you would but let us know what your business is,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cwe might see whether it could be put off or not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23418,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, so do, Sir John,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cand then perhaps you may find out what his business is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23620,\n            \"\\u201cCome Colonel,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cbefore you go, do let us know what you are going about.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23645,\n            \"\\u201d He wished her a good morning, and, attended by Sir John, left the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23695,\n            \"\\u201cI can guess what his business is, however,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings exultingly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25040,\n            \"The sudden termination of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s visit at the park, with his steadiness in concealing its cause, filled the mind, and raised the wonder of Mrs. Jennings for two or three days;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25172,\n            \"\\u201cI could see it in his face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25184,\n            \"I am afraid his circumstances may be bad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25215,\n            \"I do think he must have been sent for about money matters, for what else can it be?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25253,\n            \"Perhaps it is about Miss Williams and, by the bye, I dare say it is, because he looked so conscious when I mentioned her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25441,\n            \"Elinor, though she felt really interested in the welfare of Colonel Brandon, could not bestow all the wonder on his going so suddenly away, which Mrs. Jennings was desirous of her feeling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38368,\n            \"perhaps it is Colonel Brandon come back again \\u2014\\u201dElinor was obliged to turn from her, in the middle of her story, to receive the rest of the party;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40473,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou and I, Sir John,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cshould not stand upon such ceremony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40558,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, you may abuse me as you please,\\u201dsaid the good-natured old lady, \\u201cyou have taken Charlotte off my hands, and cannot give her back again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40595,\n            \"So there I have the whip hand of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58839,\n            \"\\u201d This, and the manner in which it was said, immediately brought back to her remembrance all the circumstances of his quitting that place, with the uneasiness and suspicions they had caused to Mrs. Jennings, and she was fearful that her question had implied much more curiosity on the subject than she had ever felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58910,\n            \"Colonel,\\u201dsaid she, with her usual noisy cheerfulness, \\u201cI am monstrous glad to see you \\u2014 sorry I could not come before \\u2014 beg your pardon, but I have been forced to look about me a little, and settle my matters;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59019,\n            \"But pray, Colonel, how came you to conjure out that I should be in town today?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59038,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI had the pleasure of hearing it at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s, where I have been dining.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59096,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMrs. Palmer appeared quite well, and I am commissioned to tell you, that you will certainly see her to-morrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59136,\n            \"Well, Colonel, I have brought two young ladies with me, you see \\u2014 that is, you see but one of them now, but there is another somewhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59341,\n            \"After her entrance, Colonel Brandon became more thoughtful and silent than he had been before, and Mrs. Jennings could not prevail on him to stay long.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74705,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe will not come in, as Mrs. Jennings is from home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74837,\n            \"\\u201cI met Mrs. Jennings in Bond Street,\\u201dsaid he, after the first salutation, \\u201cand she encouraged me to come on;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79963,\n            \"but Mrs. Jennings, who knew nothing of all this, who knew only that the Colonel continued as grave as ever, and that she could neither prevail on him to make the offer himself, nor commission her to make it for him, began, at the end of two days, to think that, instead of Midsummer, they would not be married till Michaelmas, and by the end of a week that it would not be a match at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84677,\n            \"and an offer from Colonel Brandon, or a legacy from Mrs. Jennings, was the easiest means of atoning for his own neglect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105211,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings was delighted with her gratitude, and only wondered that after hearing such a sentence, the Colonel should be able to take leave of them, as he immediately did, with the utmost _ sang-froid _, and go away without making her any reply!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106378,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, sagaciously smiling, as soon as the gentleman had withdrawn, \\u201cI do not ask you what the Colonel has been saying to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106416,\n            \"for though, upon my honour, I _ tried _ to keep out of hearing, I could not help catching enough to understand his business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou judged from your knowledge of the Colonel\\u2019s general benevolence;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 14]\": [\n        [\n            40022,\n            \"\\u201cOh, my love,\\u201dcried Mrs. Palmer to her husband, who just then entered the room \\u2014 \\u201cyou must help me to persuade the Miss Dashwoods to go to town this winter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40226,\n            \"\\u201cfor we know all about it, I assure you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40238,\n            \"and I admire your taste very much, for I think he is extremely handsome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40301,\n            \"I never was at his house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40318,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAs vile a spot as I ever saw in my life,\\u201dsaid Mr. Palmer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40440,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not I tell you, Sir John, when you spoke to me about it before, that it could not be done?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40473,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou and I, Sir John,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cshould not stand upon such ceremony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40513,\n            \"\\u201cMy love you contradict every body,\\u201dsaid his wife with her usual laugh.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40558,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, you may abuse me as you please,\\u201dsaid the good-natured old lady, \\u201cyou have taken Charlotte off my hands, and cannot give her back again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40667,\n            \"The studied indifference, insolence, and discontent of her husband gave her no pain;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41018,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere now,\\u201d\\u2014 said his lady, \\u201cyou see Mr. Palmer expects you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41272,\n            \"\\u201cHe cannot bear writing, you know,\\u201dshe continued \\u2014 \\u201che says it is quite shocking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41293,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cI never said any thing so irrational.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 15]\": [\n        [\n            16063,\n            \"You will be setting your cap at him now, and never think of poor Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17698,\n            \"and that however a general resemblance of disposition between the parties might forward the affection of Mr. Willoughby, an equally striking opposition of character was no hindrance to the regard of Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18599,\n            \"I have three unanswerable reasons for disliking Colonel Brandon;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20801,\n            \"I should hold myself guilty of greater impropriety in accepting a horse from my brother, than from Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23066,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou would not be six hours later,\\u201dsaid Willoughby, \\u201cif you were to defer your journey till our return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26032,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThank you, Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26313,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThere certainly are circumstances,\\u201dsaid Willoughby, \\u201cwhich might greatly endear it to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75038,\n            \"\\u201cYou have something to tell me of Mr. Willoughby, that will open his character farther.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75451,\n            \"Hers, for me, was, I believe, fervent as the attachment of your sister to Mr. Willoughby and it was, though from a different cause, no less unfortunate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77190,\n            \"Little did Mr. Willoughby imagine, I suppose, when his looks censured me for incivility in breaking up the party, that I was called away to the relief of one whom he had made poor and miserable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77368,\n            \"Knowing all this, as I have now known it many weeks, guess what I must have felt on seeing your sister as fond of him as ever, and on being assured that she was to marry him: guess what I must have felt for all your sakes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77498,\n            \"and sometimes I thought your sister\\u2019s influence might yet reclaim him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77862,\n            \"Have you,\\u201dshe continued, after a short silence, \\u201cever seen Mr. Willoughby since you left him at Barton?\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 16]\": [\n        [\n            118,\n            \"for to supply her loss, he invited and received into his house the family of his nephew Mr. Henry Dashwood, the legal inheritor of the Norland estate, and the person to whom he intended to bequeath it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1765,\n            \"She could consult with her brother, could receive her sister-in-law on her arrival, and treat her with proper attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            9050,\n            \"The man and one of the maids were sent off immediately into Devonshire, to prepare the house for their mistress\\u2019 s arrival;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12660,\n            \"and this kind of discernment enabled her soon after her arrival at Barton decisively to pronounce that Colonel Brandon was very much in love with Marianne Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15794,\n            \"Brandon will be jealous, if she does not take care.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16063,\n            \"You will be setting your cap at him now, and never think of poor Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16212,\n            \"he is quite smitten already, and he is very well worth setting your cap at, I can tell you, in spite of all this tumbling about and spraining of ankles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20801,\n            \"I should hold myself guilty of greater impropriety in accepting a horse from my brother, than from Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22934,\n            \"\\u201cBut if you write a note to the housekeeper, Mr. Brandon,\\u201dsaid Marianne, eagerly, \\u201cwill it not be sufficient?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23609,\n            \"\\u201d To Marianne, he merely bowed and said nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24707,\n            \"I value not her censure any more than I should do her commendation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40558,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, you may abuse me as you please,\\u201dsaid the good-natured old lady, \\u201cyou have taken Charlotte off my hands, and cannot give her back again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40605,\n            \"\\u201d Charlotte laughed heartily to think that her husband could not get rid of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40621,\n            \"and exultingly said, she did not care how cross he was to her, as they must live together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58481,\n            \"\\u201d and seemed almost ready to throw herself into his arms, when Colonel Brandon appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58565,\n            \"She instantly saw that it was not unnoticed by him, that he even observed Marianne as she quitted the room, with such astonishment and concern, as hardly left him the recollection of what civility demanded towards herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59169,\n            \"Your friend, Miss Marianne, too \\u2014 which you will not be sorry to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59341,\n            \"After her entrance, Colonel Brandon became more thoughtful and silent than he had been before, and Mrs. Jennings could not prevail on him to stay long.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75073,\n            \"_ My _ gratitude will be insured immediately by any information tending to that end, and _ hers _ must be gained by it in time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75221,\n            \"\\u201cYou have probably entirely forgotten a conversation \\u2014 (it is not to be supposed that it could make any impression on you) \\u2014 a conversation between us one evening at Barton Park \\u2014 it was the evening of a dance \\u2014 in which I alluded to a lady I had once known, as resembling, in some measure, your sister Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75362,\n            \"This lady was one of my nearest relations, an orphan from her infancy, and under the guardianship of my father.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75403,\n            \"I cannot remember the time when I did not love Eliza;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75415,\n            \"and my affection for her, as we grew up, was such, as perhaps, judging from my present forlorn and cheerless gravity, you might think me incapable of having ever felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75451,\n            \"Hers, for me, was, I believe, fervent as the attachment of your sister to Mr. Willoughby and it was, though from a different cause, no less unfortunate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75486,\n            \"At seventeen she was lost to me for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75561,\n            \"I had hoped that her regard for me would support her under any difficulty, and for some time it did;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75583,\n            \"but at last the misery of her situation, for she experienced great unkindness, overcame all her resolution, and though she had promised me that nothing \\u2014 but how blindly I relate!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75657,\n            \"I was banished to the house of a relation far distant, and she was allowed no liberty, no society, no amusement, till my father\\u2019s point was gained.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75691,\n            \"I had depended on her fortitude too far, and the blow was a severe one \\u2014 but had her marriage been happy, so young as I then was, a few months must have reconciled me to it, or at least I should not have now to lament it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76335,\n            \"What I endured in so beholding her \\u2014 but I have no right to wound your feelings by attempting to describe it \\u2014 I have pained you too much already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76366,\n            \"That she was, to all appearance, in the last stage of a consumption, was \\u2014 yes, in such a situation it was my greatest comfort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76481,\n            \"\\u201cYour sister, I hope, cannot be offended,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cby the resemblance I have fancied between her and my poor disgraced relation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76612,\n            \"She left to my care her only child, a little girl, the offspring of her first guilty connection, who was then about three years old.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76665,\n            \"and gladly would I have discharged it in the strictest sense, by watching over her education myself, had the nature of our situations allowed it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76712,\n            \"I saw her there whenever I could, and after the death of my brother, (which happened about five years ago, and which left to me the possession of the family property,) she visited me at Delaford.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76755,\n            \"I called her a distant relation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76762,\n            \"but I am well aware that I have in general been suspected of a much nearer connection with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76782,\n            \"It is now three years ago (she had just reached her fourteenth year,) that I removed her from school, to place her under the care of a very respectable woman, residing in Dorsetshire, who had the charge of four or five other girls of about the same time of life;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78105,\n            \"\\u201d Recollecting, soon afterwards, that he was probably dividing Elinor from her sister, he put an end to his visit, receiving from her again the same grateful acknowledgments, and leaving her full of compassion and esteem for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79743,\n            \"and having thus supported the dignity of her own sex, and spoken her decided censure of what was wrong in the other, she thought herself at liberty to attend to the interest of her own assemblies, and therefore determined (though rather against the opinion of Sir John) that as Mrs. Willoughby would at once be a woman of elegance and fortune, to leave her card with her as soon as she married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79874,\n            \"His chief reward for the painful exertion of disclosing past sorrows and present humiliations, was given in the pitying eye with which Marianne sometimes observed him, and the gentleness of her voice whenever (though it did not often happen) she was obliged, or could oblige herself to speak to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87703,\n            \"but Colonel Brandon\\u2019s eyes, as they were fixed on Marianne, declared that he noticed only what was amiable in it, the affectionate heart which could not bear to see a sister slighted in the smallest point.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88037,\n            \"\\u201d said her brother to Colonel Brandon, in a low voice, as soon as he could secure his attention: \\u201cShe has not such good health as her sister, \\u2014 she is very nervous, \\u2014 she has not Elinor\\u2019s constitution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104822,\n            \"The effect of his discourse on the lady too, could not escape her observation, for though she was too honorable to listen, and had even changed her seat, on purpose that she might _ not _ hear, to one close by the piano forte on which Marianne was playing, she could not keep herself from seeing that Elinor changed colour, attended with agitation, and was too intent on what he said to pursue her employment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104906,\n            \"Still farther in confirmation of her hopes, in the interval of Marianne\\u2019s turning from one lesson to another, some words of the Colonel\\u2019s inevitably reached her ear, in which he seemed to be apologising for the badness of his house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105030,\n            \"They then talked on for a few minutes longer without her catching a syllable, when another lucky stop in Marianne\\u2019s performance brought her these words in the Colonel\\u2019s calm voice, \\u2014 \\u201cI am afraid it cannot take place very soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105358,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor told him that it was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105738,\n            \"but whatever minor feelings less pure, less pleasing, might have a share in that emotion, her esteem for the general benevolence, and her gratitude for the particular friendship, which together prompted Colonel Brandon to this act, were strongly felt, and warmly expressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106079,\n            \"\\u201d By which the Colonel was surprised to find that _ she _ was considering Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s marriage as the certain consequence of the presentation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106318,\n            \"but after this narration of what really passed between Colonel Brandon and Elinor, while they stood at the window, the gratitude expressed by the latter on their parting, may perhaps appear in general, not less reasonably excited, nor less properly worded than if it had arisen from an offer of marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106378,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, sagaciously smiling, as soon as the gentleman had withdrawn, \\u201cI do not ask you what the Colonel has been saying to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140190,\n            \"A three weeks\\u2019 residence at Delaford, where, in his evening hours at least, he had little to do but to calculate the disproportion between thirty-six and seventeen, brought him to Barton in a temper of mind which needed all the improvement in Marianne\\u2019s looks, all the kindness of her welcome, and all the encouragement of her mother\\u2019s language, to make it cheerful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142269,\n            \"They had in fact nothing to wish for, but the marriage of Colonel Brandon and Marianne, and rather better pasturage for their cows.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142469,\n            \"And though, perhaps, Marianne may not seem exactly the person to attract him, yet I think it would altogether be advisable for you to have them now frequently staying with you, for as Colonel Brandon seems a great deal at home, nobody can tell what may happen;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143561,\n            \"for her wish of bringing Marianne and Colonel Brandon together was hardly less earnest, though rather more liberal than what John had expressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143986,\n            \"and that Marianne found her own happiness in forming his, was equally the persuasion and delight of each observing friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144050,\n            \"and his punishment was soon afterwards complete in the voluntary forgiveness of Mrs. Smith, who, by stating his marriage with a woman of character, as the source of her clemency, gave him reason for believing that had he behaved with honour towards Marianne, he might at once have been happy and rich.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144130,\n            \"\\u2014 nor that he long thought of Colonel Brandon with envy, and of Marianne with regret.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144239,\n            \"For Marianne, however, in spite of his incivility in surviving her loss, he always retained that decided regard which interested him in every thing that befell her, and made her his secret standard of perfection in woman;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144323,\n            \"and fortunately for Sir John and Mrs. Jennings, when Marianne was taken from them, Margaret had reached an age highly suitable for dancing, and not very ineligible for being supposed to have a lover.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 17]\": [\n        [\n            83149,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars, with the utmost liberality, will come forward, and settle on him a thousand a year, if the match takes place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105291,\n            \"\\u201cI have heard,\\u201dsaid he, with great compassion, \\u201cof the injustice your friend Mr. Ferrars has suffered from his family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105319,\n            \"for if I understand the matter right, he has been entirely cast off by them for persevering in his engagement with a very deserving young woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105423,\n            \"I have seen Mr. Ferrars two or three times in Harley Street, and am much pleased with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105444,\n            \"He is not a young man with whom one can be intimately acquainted in a short time, but I have seen enough of him to wish him well for his own sake, and as a friend of yours, I wish it still more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105491,\n            \"I understand that he intends to take orders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105500,\n            \"Will you be so good as to tell him that the living of Delaford, now just vacant, as I am informed by this day\\u2019s post, is his, if he think it worth his acceptance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107238,\n            \"\\u201cColonel Brandon is so delicate a man, that he rather wished any one to announce his intentions to Mr. Ferrars than himself.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 18]\": [\n        [\n            565,\n            \"The whole was tied up for the benefit of this child, who, in occasional visits with his father and mother at Norland, had so far gained on the affections of his uncle, by such attractions as are by no means unusual in children of two or three years old;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            10850,\n            \"Conversation however was not wanted, for Sir John was very chatty, and Lady Middleton had taken the wise precaution of bringing with her their eldest child, a fine little boy about six years old, by which means there was one subject always to be recurred to by the ladies in case of extremity, for they had to enquire his name and age, admire his beauty, and ask him questions which his mother answered for him, while he hung about her and held down his head, to the great surprise of her ladyship, who wondered at his being so shy before company, as he could make noise enough at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13511,\n            \"But I must object to your dooming Colonel Brandon and his wife to the constant confinement of a sick chamber, merely because he chanced to complain yesterday (a very cold damp day) of a slight rheumatic feel in one of his shoulders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13978,\n            \"And Elinor, in quitting Norland and Edward, cried not as I did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58481,\n            \"\\u201d and seemed almost ready to throw herself into his arms, when Colonel Brandon appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58743,\n            \"Elinor wished very much to ask whether Willoughby were then in town, but she was afraid of giving him pain by any enquiry after his rival;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58771,\n            \"and at length, by way of saying something, she asked if he had been in London ever since she had seen him last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88037,\n            \"\\u201d said her brother to Colonel Brandon, in a low voice, as soon as he could secure his attention: \\u201cShe has not such good health as her sister, \\u2014 she is very nervous, \\u2014 she has not Elinor\\u2019s constitution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105651,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s astonishment at this commission could hardly have been greater, had the Colonel been really making her an offer of his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105788,\n            \"She thanked him for it with all her heart, spoke of Edward\\u2019s principles and disposition with that praise which she knew them to deserve;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106079,\n            \"\\u201d By which the Colonel was surprised to find that _ she _ was considering Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s marriage as the certain consequence of the presentation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106108,\n            \"for he did not suppose it possible that Delaford living could supply such an income, as anybody in his style of life would venture to settle on, and he said so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106189,\n            \"If, however, by an unforeseen chance it should be in my power to serve him farther, I must think very differently of him from what I now do, if I am not as ready to be useful to him then as I sincerely wish I could be at present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106243,\n            \"What I am now doing indeed, seems nothing at all, since it can advance him so little towards what must be his principal, his only object of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108041,\n            \"Allow me to congratulate you on having so respectable and well-judging a friend, and to join in his wish that the living \\u2014 it is about two hundred a-year \\u2014 were much more considerable, and such as might better enable you to \\u2014 as might be more than a temporary accommodation to yourself \\u2014 such, in short, as might establish all your views of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108163,\n            \"but he said only these two words, \\u2014 \\u201cColonel Brandon!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108176,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, gathering more resolution, as some of the worst was over, \\u201cColonel Brandon means it as a testimony of his concern for what has lately passed \\u2014 for the cruel situation in which the unjustifiable conduct of your family has placed you \\u2014 a concern which I am sure Marianne, myself, and all your friends, must share;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108247,\n            \"and likewise as a proof of his high esteem for your general character, and his particular approbation of your behaviour on the present occasion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108273,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cColonel Brandon give _ me _ a living!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108381,\n            \"I do assure you that you owe it entirely, at least almost entirely, to your own merit, and Colonel Brandon\\u2019s discernment of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108568,\n            \"\\u2014 at last, and as if it were rather an effort, he said, \\u201cColonel Brandon seems a man of great worth and respectability.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108596,\n            \"I have always heard him spoken of as such, and your brother I know esteems him highly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108630,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cI believe that you will find him, on farther acquaintance, all that you have heard him to be, and as you will be such very near neighbours (for I understand the parsonage is almost close to the mansion-house,) it is particularly important that he _ should _ be all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108784,\n            \"\\u201cI must hurry away then, to give him those thanks which you will not allow me to give _ you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114531,\n            \"Of Edward, or at least of some of his concerns, she now received intelligence from Colonel Brandon, who had been into Dorsetshire lately;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138844,\n            \"and by his rapidity in seeking _ that _ fate, it is to be supposed, in spite of the jealousy with which he had once thought of Colonel Brandon, in spite of the modesty with which he rated his own deserts, and the politeness with which he talked of his doubts, he did not, upon the whole, expect a very cruel reception.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139696,\n            \"Edward heard with pleasure of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s being expected at the Cottage, as he really wished not only to be better acquainted with him, but to have an opportunity of convincing him that he no longer resented his giving him the living of Delaford \\u2014 \\u201cWhich, at present,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cafter thanks so ungraciously delivered as mine were on the occasion, he must think I have never forgiven him for offering.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139797,\n            \"But so little interest had he taken in the matter, that he owed all his knowledge of the house, garden, and glebe, extent of the parish, condition of the land, and rate of the tithes, to Elinor herself, who had heard so much of it from Colonel Brandon, and heard it with so much attention, as to be entirely mistress of the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140089,\n            \"About four days after Edward\\u2019s arrival Colonel Brandon appeared, to complete Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s satisfaction, and to give her the dignity of having, for the first time since her living at Barton, more company with her than her house would hold.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140139,\n            \"Edward was allowed to retain the privilege of first comer, and Colonel Brandon therefore walked every night to his old quarters at the Park;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141473,\n            \"They were to go immediately to Delaford, that Edward might have some personal knowledge of his future home, and assist his patron and friend in deciding on what improvements were needed to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142046,\n            \"With an income quite sufficient to their wants thus secured to them, they had nothing to wait for after Edward was in possession of the living, but the readiness of the house, to which Colonel Brandon, with an eager desire for the accommodation of Elinor, was making considerable improvements;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[3, 19]\": [\n        [\n            1380,\n            \"So acutely did Mrs. Dashwood feel this ungracious behaviour, and so earnestly did she despise her daughter-in-law for it, that, on the arrival of the latter, she would have quitted the house for ever, had not the entreaty of her eldest girl induced her first to reflect on the propriety of going, and her own tender love for all her three children determined her afterwards to stay, and for their sakes avoid a breach with their brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1765,\n            \"She could consult with her brother, could receive her sister-in-law on her arrival, and treat her with proper attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8279,\n            \"The house, too, as described by Sir John, was on so simple a scale, and the rent so uncommonly moderate, as to leave her no right of objection on either point;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13511,\n            \"But I must object to your dooming Colonel Brandon and his wife to the constant confinement of a sick chamber, merely because he chanced to complain yesterday (a very cold damp day) of a slight rheumatic feel in one of his shoulders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13978,\n            \"And Elinor, in quitting Norland and Edward, cried not as I did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19341,\n            \"and had Elinor\\u2019s memory been equal to her means of improvement, she might have known very early in their acquaintance all the particulars of Mr. Jennings\\u2019 s last illness, and what he said to his wife a few minutes before he died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25253,\n            \"Perhaps it is about Miss Williams and, by the bye, I dare say it is, because he looked so conscious when I mentioned her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25363,\n            \"May be his sister is worse at Avignon, and has sent for him over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25441,\n            \"Elinor, though she felt really interested in the welfare of Colonel Brandon, could not bestow all the wonder on his going so suddenly away, which Mrs. Jennings was desirous of her feeling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26274,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI flatter myself,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cthat even under the disadvantage of better rooms and a broader staircase, you will hereafter find your own house as faultless as you now do this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38368,\n            \"perhaps it is Colonel Brandon come back again \\u2014\\u201dElinor was obliged to turn from her, in the middle of her story, to receive the rest of the party;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41310,\n            \"Don\\u2019t palm all your abuses of language upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42109,\n            \"but he looked as if he knew it to be true, so from that moment I set it down as certain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42148,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMr. Brandon was very well I hope?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42168,\n            \"and so full of your praises, he did nothing but say fine things of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42185,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am flattered by his commendation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42502,\n            \"You can\\u2019t think how much I longed to see you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42573,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou have been long acquainted with Colonel Brandon, have not you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42613,\n            \"I believe,\\u201dshe added in a low voice, \\u201che would have been very glad to have had me, if he could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42650,\n            \"But mama did not think the match good enough for me, otherwise Sir John would have mentioned it to the Colonel, and we should have been married immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42702,\n            \"Had he never owned his affection to yourself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42717,\n            \"but if mama had not objected to it, I dare say he would have liked it of all things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42738,\n            \"He had not seen me then above twice, for it was before I left school.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58522,\n            \"but at the same time her regard for Colonel Brandon ensured his welcome with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58538,\n            \"and she felt particularly hurt that a man so partial to her sister should perceive that she experienced nothing but grief and disappointment in seeing him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58565,\n            \"She instantly saw that it was not unnoticed by him, that he even observed Marianne as she quitted the room, with such astonishment and concern, as hardly left him the recollection of what civility demanded towards herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58656,\n            \"He heard her with the most earnest attention, but seeming to recollect himself, said no more on the subject, and began directly to speak of his pleasure at seeing them in London, making the usual inquiries about their journey, and the friends they had left behind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58743,\n            \"Elinor wished very much to ask whether Willoughby were then in town, but she was afraid of giving him pain by any enquiry after his rival;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58771,\n            \"and at length, by way of saying something, she asked if he had been in London ever since she had seen him last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58839,\n            \"\\u201d This, and the manner in which it was said, immediately brought back to her remembrance all the circumstances of his quitting that place, with the uneasiness and suspicions they had caused to Mrs. Jennings, and she was fearful that her question had implied much more curiosity on the subject than she had ever felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59306,\n            \"\\u201d He replied with his accustomary mildness to all her inquiries, but without satisfying her in any.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63314,\n            \"she was left, on the contrary, with a melancholy impression of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s unhappiness, and was prevented even from wishing it removed, by her anxiety for the very event that must confirm it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75029,\n            \"\\u201cI understand you,\\u201dsaid Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77711,\n            \"but had I not seriously, and from my heart believed it might be of service, might lessen her regrets, I would not have suffered myself to trouble you with this account of my family afflictions, with a recital which may seem to have been intended to raise myself at the expense of others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77862,\n            \"Have you,\\u201dshe continued, after a short silence, \\u201cever seen Mr. Willoughby since you left him at Barton?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77906,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, startled by his manner, looked at him anxiously, saying, \\u201cWhat?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78105,\n            \"\\u201d Recollecting, soon afterwards, that he was probably dividing Elinor from her sister, he put an end to his visit, receiving from her again the same grateful acknowledgments, and leaving her full of compassion and esteem for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78244,\n            \"But though this behaviour assured Elinor that the conviction of this guilt _ was _ carried home to her mind, though she saw with satisfaction the effect of it, in her no longer avoiding Colonel Brandon when he called, in her speaking to him, even voluntarily speaking, with a kind of compassionate respect, and though she saw her spirits less violently irritated than before, she did not see her less wretched.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79823,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s delicate, unobtrusive enquiries were never unwelcome to Miss Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79838,\n            \"He had abundantly earned the privilege of intimate discussion of her sister\\u2019s disappointment, by the friendly zeal with which he had endeavoured to soften it, and they always conversed with confidence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79930,\n            \"_ These _ assured him that his exertion had produced an increase of good-will towards himself, and _ these _ gave Elinor hopes of its being farther augmented hereafter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82655,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe likes you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82746,\n            \"\\u201cbut I am very sure that Colonel Brandon has not the smallest wish of marrying _ me _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82780,\n            \"A very little trouble on your side secures him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82799,\n            \"the smallness of your fortune may make him hang back;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82842,\n            \"And there can be no reason why you should not try for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82914,\n            \"and no civility shall be wanting on my part to make him pleased with you and your family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83104,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIs Mr. Edward Ferrars,\\u201dsaid Elinor, with resolution, \\u201cgoing to be married?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84594,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor tried very seriously to convince him that there was no likelihood of her marrying Colonel Brandon;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85208,\n            \"but nothing would have induced Fanny voluntarily to mention his name before her, till able to tell her that his marriage with Miss Morton was resolved on, or till her husband\\u2019s expectations on Colonel Brandon were answered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87947,\n            \"and Sir John felt so desperately enraged against the author of this nervous distress, that he instantly changed his seat to one close by Lucy Steele, and gave her, in a whisper, a brief account of the whole shocking affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88037,\n            \"\\u201d said her brother to Colonel Brandon, in a low voice, as soon as he could secure his attention: \\u201cShe has not such good health as her sister, \\u2014 she is very nervous, \\u2014 she has not Elinor\\u2019s constitution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104771,\n            \"for, on Elinor\\u2019s moving to the window to take more expeditiously the dimensions of a print, which she was going to copy for her friend, he followed her to it with a look of particular meaning, and conversed with her there for several minutes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104822,\n            \"The effect of his discourse on the lady too, could not escape her observation, for though she was too honorable to listen, and had even changed her seat, on purpose that she might _ not _ hear, to one close by the piano forte on which Marianne was playing, she could not keep herself from seeing that Elinor changed colour, attended with agitation, and was too intent on what he said to pursue her employment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105319,\n            \"for if I understand the matter right, he has been entirely cast off by them for persevering in his engagement with a very deserving young woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105651,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s astonishment at this commission could hardly have been greater, had the Colonel been really making her an offer of his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108041,\n            \"Allow me to congratulate you on having so respectable and well-judging a friend, and to join in his wish that the living \\u2014 it is about two hundred a-year \\u2014 were much more considerable, and such as might better enable you to \\u2014 as might be more than a temporary accommodation to yourself \\u2014 such, in short, as might establish all your views of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108176,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, gathering more resolution, as some of the worst was over, \\u201cColonel Brandon means it as a testimony of his concern for what has lately passed \\u2014 for the cruel situation in which the unjustifiable conduct of your family has placed you \\u2014 a concern which I am sure Marianne, myself, and all your friends, must share;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108381,\n            \"I do assure you that you owe it entirely, at least almost entirely, to your own merit, and Colonel Brandon\\u2019s discernment of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108630,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cI believe that you will find him, on farther acquaintance, all that you have heard him to be, and as you will be such very near neighbours (for I understand the parsonage is almost close to the mansion-house,) it is particularly important that he _ should _ be all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108784,\n            \"\\u201cI must hurry away then, to give him those thanks which you will not allow me to give _ you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116785,\n            \"and as soon she had rung up the maid to take her place by her sister, she hastened down to the drawing-room, where she knew he was generally to be found at a much later hour than the present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117192,\n            \"Hour after hour passed away in sleepless pain and delirium on Marianne\\u2019s side, and in the most cruel anxiety on Elinor\\u2019s, before Mr. Harris appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117372,\n            \"She was on the point of sending again for Mr. Harris, or if _ he _ could not come, for some other advice, when the former \\u2014 but not till after five o\\u2019clock \\u2014 arrived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117414,\n            \"His opinion, however, made some little amends for his delay, for though acknowledging a very unexpected and unpleasant alteration in his patient, he would not allow the danger to be material, and talked of the relief which a fresh mode of treatment must procure, with a confidence which, in a lesser degree, was communicated to Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117479,\n            \"He promised to call again in the course of three or four hours, and left both the patient and her anxious attendant more composed than he had found them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117767,\n            \"Elinor, catching all, and more than all, his fears in a moment, proposed to call in further advice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139797,\n            \"But so little interest had he taken in the matter, that he owed all his knowledge of the house, garden, and glebe, extent of the parish, condition of the land, and rate of the tithes, to Elinor herself, who had heard so much of it from Colonel Brandon, and heard it with so much attention, as to be entirely mistress of the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142046,\n            \"With an income quite sufficient to their wants thus secured to them, they had nothing to wait for after Edward was in possession of the living, but the readiness of the house, to which Colonel Brandon, with an eager desire for the accommodation of Elinor, was making considerable improvements;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 6]\": [\n        [\n            10654,\n            \"Lady Middleton had sent a very civil message by him, denoting her intention of waiting on Mrs. Dashwood as soon as she could be assured that her visit would be no inconvenience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11251,\n            \"He hunted and shot, and she humoured her children;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11269,\n            \"Lady Middleton had the advantage of being able to spoil her children all the year round, while Sir John\\u2019s independent employments were in existence only half the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11319,\n            \"supported the good spirits of Sir John, and gave exercise to the good breeding of his wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12137,\n            \"but the cold insipidity of Lady Middleton was so particularly repulsive, that in comparison of it the gravity of Colonel Brandon, and even the boisterous mirth of Sir John and his mother-in-law was interesting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12369,\n            \"Lady Middleton frequently called him to order, wondered how any one\\u2019s attention could be diverted from music for a moment, and asked Marianne to sing a particular song which Marianne had just finished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42640,\n            \"Sir John and Lady Middleton wished it very much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42951,\n            \"Their engagements at Exeter instantly gave way before such an invitation, and Lady Middleton was thrown into no little alarm on the return of Sir John, by hearing that she was very soon to receive a visit from two girls whom she had never seen in her life, and of whose elegance, \\u2014 whose tolerable gentility even, she could have no proof;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43089,\n            \"As it was impossible, however, now to prevent their coming, Lady Middleton resigned herself to the idea of it, with all the philosophy of a well-bred woman, contenting herself with merely giving her husband a gentle reprimand on the subject five or six times every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43997,\n            \"\\u201d said she, on his taking Miss Steeles\\u2019 s pocket handkerchief, and throwing it out of window \\u2014 \\u201cHe is full of monkey tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44618,\n            \"She merely observed that he was perfectly good humoured and friendly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51347,\n            \"Such a thought would never enter either Sir John or Lady Middleton\\u2019s head;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51494,\n            \"Elinor, who foresaw a fairer opening for the point she had in view, in such a party as this was likely to be, more at liberty among themselves under the tranquil and well-bred direction of Lady Middleton than when her husband united them together in one noisy purpose, immediately accepted the invitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61669,\n            \"Business on Sir John\\u2019s part, and a violent cold on her own, prevented their calling in Berkeley Street.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84732,\n            \"Sir John was ready to like anybody, and though Mr. Dashwood did not seem to know much about horses, he soon set him down as a very good-natured fellow: while Lady Middleton saw enough of fashion in his appearance to think his acquaintance worth having;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94153,\n            \"indeed, you _ do _ like them, you know, very much already, and so does my mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103740,\n            \"and begging to be most gratefully and respectfully remembered to her, and to Sir John, and Lady Middleton, and the dear children, when you chance to see them, and love to Miss Marianne, \\u201cI am, & c.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 7]\": [\n        [\n            93073,\n            \"and so I often tell my mother, when she is grieving about it.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 10]\": [\n        [\n            87313,\n            \"and after they had received gratifying testimony of Lady Middletons\\u2019 s approbation, Fanny presented them to her mother, considerately informing her, at the same time, that they were done by Miss Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93902,\n            \"\\u201cI do not see how it can be done,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwithout affronting Lady Middleton, for they spend every day with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93974,\n            \"How can I ask them away from her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94254,\n            \"Fanny, rejoicing in her escape, and proud of the ready wit that had procured it, wrote the next morning to Lucy, to request her company and her sister\\u2019s, for some days, in Harley Street, as soon as Lady Middleton could spare them.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 12]\": [\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12137,\n            \"but the cold insipidity of Lady Middleton was so particularly repulsive, that in comparison of it the gravity of Colonel Brandon, and even the boisterous mirth of Sir John and his mother-in-law was interesting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18049,\n            \"Who would submit to the indignity of being approved by such a woman as Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, that could command the indifference of any body else?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19283,\n            \"Neither Lady Middleton nor Mrs. Jennings could supply to her the conversation she missed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19299,\n            \"although the latter was an everlasting talker, and from the first had regarded her with a kindness which ensured her a large share of her discourse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22706,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear madam,\\u201dsaid Lady Middleton, \\u201crecollect what you are saying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22813,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am particularly sorry, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid he, addressing Lady Middleton, \\u201cthat I should receive this letter today, for it is on business which requires my immediate attendance in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43048,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s attempts at consolation were therefore unfortunately founded, when she advised her daughter not to care about their being so fashionable;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56518,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is very true,\\u201dreplied her mother, \\u201cbut of her society, separately from that of other people, you will scarcely have any thing at all, and you will almost always appear in public with Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60964,\n            \"Every thing in her household arrangements was conducted on the most liberal plan, and excepting a few old city friends, whom, to Lady Middleton\\u2019s regret, she had never dropped, she visited no one to whom an introduction could at all discompose the feelings of her young companions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63389,\n            \"They were engaged about the end of that time to attend Lady Middleton to a party, from which Mrs. Jennings was kept away by the indisposition of her youngest daughter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93814,\n            \"The consideration of Mrs. Dennison\\u2019s mistake, in supposing his sisters their guests, had suggested the propriety of their being really invited to become such, while Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s engagements kept her from home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100802,\n            \"You see I cannot leave Mrs. Clarke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102763,\n            \"I have not time to speak to Mrs. Jennings about it myself, but pray tell her I am quite happy to hear she is not in anger against us, and Lady Middleton the same;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 14]\": [\n        [\n            38454,\n            \"Mrs. Palmer was several years younger than Lady Middleton, and totally unlike her in every respect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39095,\n            \"Lady Middleton could no longer endure such a conversation, and therefore exerted herself to ask Mr. Palmer if there was any news in the paper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39327,\n            \"When Lady Middleton rose to go away, Mr. Palmer rose also, laid down the newspaper, stretched himself and looked at them all around.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94700,\n            \"and, contenting herself with visiting her once or twice a day, returned from that period to her own home, and her own habits, in which she found the Miss Dashwoods very ready to resume their former share.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94742,\n            \"About the third or fourth morning after their being thus resettled in Berkeley Street, Mrs. Jennings, on returning from her ordinary visit to Mrs. Palmer, entered the drawing-room, where Elinor was sitting by herself, with an air of such hurrying importance as prepared her to hear something wonderful;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 15]\": [\n        [\n            18080,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut perhaps the abuse of such people as yourself and Marianne will make amends for the regard of Lady Middleton and her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 16]\": [\n        [\n            12240,\n            \"The instrument was unlocked, every body prepared to be charmed, and Marianne, who sang very well, at their request went through the chief of the songs which Lady Middleton had brought into the family on her marriage, and which perhaps had lain ever since in the same position on the pianoforte, for her ladyship had celebrated that event by giving up music, although by her mother\\u2019s account, she had played extremely well, and by her own was very fond of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12369,\n            \"Lady Middleton frequently called him to order, wondered how any one\\u2019s attention could be diverted from music for a moment, and asked Marianne to sing a particular song which Marianne had just finished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18080,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut perhaps the abuse of such people as yourself and Marianne will make amends for the regard of Lady Middleton and her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52026,\n            \"No one made any objection but Marianne, who with her usual inattention to the forms of general civility, exclaimed, \\u201cYour Ladyship will have the goodness to excuse _ me _ \\u2014 you know I detest cards.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52101,\n            \"Lady Middleton looked as if she thanked heaven that _ she _ had never made so rude a speech.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52121,\n            \"\\u201cMarianne can never keep long from that instrument you know, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Elinor, endeavouring to smooth away the offence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52389,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor joyfully profited by the first of these proposals, and thus by a little of that address which Marianne could never condescend to practise, gained her own end, and pleased Lady Middleton at the same time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63460,\n            \"She sat by the drawing-room fire after tea, till the moment of Lady Middleton\\u2019s arrival, without once stirring from her seat, or altering her attitude, lost in her own thoughts, and insensible of her sister\\u2019s presence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63508,\n            \"and when at last they were told that Lady Middleton waited for them at the door, she started as if she had forgotten that any one was expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63645,\n            \"After some time spent in saying little or doing less, Lady Middleton sat down to Cassino, and as Marianne was not in spirits for moving about, she and Elinor luckily succeeding to chairs, placed themselves at no great distance from the table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91301,\n            \"Though nothing could be more polite than Lady Middleton\\u2019s behaviour to Elinor and Marianne, she did not really like them at all.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 17]\": [\n        [\n            51798,\n            \"And we will make the dear little love some amends for her disappointment to-morrow, and then I hope she will not much mind it.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 18]\": [\n        [\n            10850,\n            \"Conversation however was not wanted, for Sir John was very chatty, and Lady Middleton had taken the wise precaution of bringing with her their eldest child, a fine little boy about six years old, by which means there was one subject always to be recurred to by the ladies in case of extremity, for they had to enquire his name and age, admire his beauty, and ask him questions which his mother answered for him, while he hung about her and held down his head, to the great surprise of her ladyship, who wondered at his being so shy before company, as he could make noise enough at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93122,\n            \"Why would you be persuaded by my uncle, Sir Robert, against your own judgment, to place Edward under private tuition, at the most critical time of his life?\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 19]\": [\n        [\n            19283,\n            \"Neither Lady Middleton nor Mrs. Jennings could supply to her the conversation she missed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19299,\n            \"although the latter was an everlasting talker, and from the first had regarded her with a kindness which ensured her a large share of her discourse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19404,\n            \"Elinor needed little observation to perceive that her reserve was a mere calmness of manner with which sense had nothing to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21989,\n            \"\\u201d Most grateful did Elinor feel to Lady Middleton for observing, at this moment, \\u201cthat it rained very hard,\\u201dthough she believed the interruption to proceed less from any attention to her, than from her ladyship\\u2019s great dislike of all such inelegant subjects of raillery as delighted her husband and mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43710,\n            \"Their manners were particularly civil, and Elinor soon allowed them credit for some kind of sense, when she saw with what constant and judicious attention they were making themselves agreeable to Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44547,\n            \"She did her best when thus called on, by speaking of Lady Middleton with more warmth than she felt, though with far less than Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51494,\n            \"Elinor, who foresaw a fairer opening for the point she had in view, in such a party as this was likely to be, more at liberty among themselves under the tranquil and well-bred direction of Lady Middleton than when her husband united them together in one noisy purpose, immediately accepted the invitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52121,\n            \"\\u201cMarianne can never keep long from that instrument you know, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Elinor, endeavouring to smooth away the offence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52343,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are very kind,\\u201dsaid Lady Middleton to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52389,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor joyfully profited by the first of these proposals, and thus by a little of that address which Marianne could never condescend to practise, gained her own end, and pleased Lady Middleton at the same time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62650,\n            \"After a pause of several minutes, their silence was broken, by his asking her in a voice of some agitation, when he was to congratulate her on the acquisition of a brother?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63645,\n            \"After some time spent in saying little or doing less, Lady Middleton sat down to Cassino, and as Marianne was not in spirits for moving about, she and Elinor luckily succeeding to chairs, placed themselves at no great distance from the table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79528,\n            \"The calm and polite unconcern of Lady Middleton on the occasion was a happy relief to Elinor\\u2019s spirits, oppressed as they often were by the clamorous kindness of the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82529,\n            \"After staying with them half an hour, he asked Elinor to walk with him to Conduit Street, and introduce him to Sir John and Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85045,\n            \"Lady Middleton was equally pleased with Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85092,\n            \"The same manners, however, which recommended Mrs. John Dashwood to the good opinion of Lady Middleton did not suit the fancy of Mrs. Jennings, and to _ her _ she appeared nothing more than a little proud-looking woman of uncordial address, who met her husband\\u2019s sisters without any affection, and almost without having anything to say to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86076,\n            \"\\u201d said Lucy, as they walked up the stairs together \\u2014 for the Middletons arrived so directly after Mrs. Jennings, that they all followed the servant at the same time: \\u2014 \\u201cthere is nobody here but you, that can feel for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88401,\n            \"But that it was so, had not only been declared by Lucy\\u2019s eyes at the time, but was declared over again the next morning more openly, for at her particular desire, Lady Middleton set her down in Berkeley Street on the chance of seeing Elinor alone, to tell her how happy she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91301,\n            \"Though nothing could be more polite than Lady Middleton\\u2019s behaviour to Elinor and Marianne, she did not really like them at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94742,\n            \"About the third or fourth morning after their being thus resettled in Berkeley Street, Mrs. Jennings, on returning from her ordinary visit to Mrs. Palmer, entered the drawing-room, where Elinor was sitting by herself, with an air of such hurrying importance as prepared her to hear something wonderful;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 7]\": [\n        [\n            111987,\n            \"\\u2014 and when to that was added the fanciful imagery of Edward reading prayers in a white surplice, and publishing the banns of marriage between John Smith and Mary Brown, he could conceive nothing more ridiculous.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 8]\": [\n        [\n            12063,\n            \"His appearance however was not unpleasing, in spite of his being in the opinion of Marianne and Margaret an absolute old bachelor, for he was on the wrong side of five and thirty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14836,\n            \"Then passing through the garden, the gate of which had been left open by Margaret, he bore her directly into the house, whither Margaret was just arrived, and quitted not his hold till he had seated her in a chair in the parlour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20266,\n            \"The lady would probably have passed without suspicion, had he not convinced Miss Dashwood that what concerned her ought not to escape his lips.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38408,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and Margaret came down stairs at the same time, and they all sat down to look at one another, while Mrs. Jennings continued her story as she walked through the passage into the parlour, attended by Sir John.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 10]\": [\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44576,\n            \"\\u201cAnd Sir John too,\\u201dcried the elder sister, \\u201cwhat a charming man he is!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44889,\n            \"\\u201cWe have heard Sir John admire it excessively,\\u201dsaid Lucy, who seemed to think some apology necessary for the freedom of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82032,\n            \"I am come here to bespeak Fanny a seal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93789,\n            \"and a thought struck him during the evening, which he communicated to his wife, for her approbation, when they got home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93983,\n            \"\\u201d Her husband, but with great humility, did not see the force of her objection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94035,\n            \"\\u201d Fanny paused a moment, and then, with fresh vigor, said, \\u201cMy love, I would ask them with all my heart, if it was in my power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94145,\n            \"I am sure you will like them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98357,\n            \"\\u201cYour sister,\\u201dhe continued, \\u201chas suffered dreadfully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98656,\n            \"While she with the truest affection had been planning a most eligible connection for him, was it to be supposed that he could be all the time secretly engaged to another person!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100036,\n            \"and with repeated assurances to his sisters that he really believed there was no material danger in Fanny\\u2019s indisposition, and that they need not therefore be very uneasy about it, he went away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112946,\n            \"\\u2014 and a faint invitation from Fanny, to come to Norland whenever it should happen to be in their way, which of all things was the most unlikely to occur, with a more warm, though less public, assurance, from John to Elinor, of the promptitude with which he should come to see her at Delaford, was all that foretold any meeting in the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131131,\n            \"To John, to Fanny, yes, even to them, little as they deserve, I had given less than their due.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 12]\": [\n        [\n            11806,\n            \"Luckily Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother had arrived at Barton within the last hour, and as she was a very cheerful agreeable woman, he hoped the young ladies would not find it so very dull as they might imagine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12014,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, the friend of Sir John, seemed no more adapted by resemblance of manner to be his friend, than Lady Middleton was to be his wife, or Mrs. Jennings to be Lady Middleton\\u2019s mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12137,\n            \"but the cold insipidity of Lady Middleton was so particularly repulsive, that in comparison of it the gravity of Colonel Brandon, and even the boisterous mirth of Sir John and his mother-in-law was interesting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12776,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings had been anxious to see Colonel Brandon well married, ever since her connection with Sir John first brought him to her knowledge;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23418,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, so do, Sir John,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cand then perhaps you may find out what his business is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23645,\n            \"\\u201d He wished her a good morning, and, attended by Sir John, left the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35608,\n            \"With the assistance of his mother-in-law, Sir John was not long in discovering that the name of Ferrars began with an F.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38408,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and Margaret came down stairs at the same time, and they all sat down to look at one another, while Mrs. Jennings continued her story as she walked through the passage into the parlour, attended by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40473,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou and I, Sir John,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cshould not stand upon such ceremony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42894,\n            \"In a morning\\u2019s excursion to Exeter, they had met with two young ladies, whom Mrs. Jennings had the satisfaction of discovering to be her relations, and this was enough for Sir John to invite them directly to the park, as soon as their present engagements at Exeter were over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43019,\n            \"for the assurances of her husband and mother on that subject went for nothing at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55530,\n            \"So I would advise you two, to set off for town, when you are tired of Barton, without saying a word to Miss Dashwood about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60326,\n            \"\\u201cIf this open weather holds much longer,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, when they met at breakfast the following morning, \\u201cSir John will not like leaving Barton next week;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82067,\n            \"I understand she is a woman of very good fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82285,\n            \"and was not sorry to be spared the necessity of answering him, by the arrival of Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s servant, who came to tell her that his mistress waited for them at the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82324,\n            \"Mr. Dashwood attended them down stairs, was introduced to Mrs. Jennings at the door of her carriage, and repeating his hope of being able to call on them the next day, took leave.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99152,\n            \"I beg your pardon, Mr. Dashwood, but if he had done otherwise, I should have thought him a rascal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99176,\n            \"I have some little concern in the business, as well as yourself, for Lucy Steele is my cousin, and I believe there is not a better kind of girl in the world, nor one who more deserves a good husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99253,\n            \"He therefore replied, without any resentment, \\u201cI would by no means speak disrespectfully of any relation of yours, madam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103598,\n            \"and should it ever be in your power to recommend him to any body that has a living to bestow, am very sure you will not forget us, and dear Mrs. Jennings too, trust she will speak a good word for us to Sir John, or Mr. Palmer, or any friend that may be able to assist us.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 14]\": [\n        [\n            40404,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear,\\u201dsaid he to his lady, \\u201cit is very provoking that we should be so few.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40440,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not I tell you, Sir John, when you spoke to me about it before, that it could not be done?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40473,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou and I, Sir John,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cshould not stand upon such ceremony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 15]\": [\n        [\n            15412,\n            \"I will ride over tomorrow, and ask him to dinner on Thursday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15426,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou know him then,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15501,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd is _ that _ all you can say for him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15549,\n            \"\\u201cUpon my soul,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cI do not know much about him as to all _ that _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15573,\n            \"But he is a pleasant, good humoured fellow, and has got the nicest little black bitch of a pointer I ever saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15605,\n            \"\\u201d But Marianne could no more satisfy him as to the colour of Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s pointer, than he could describe to her the shades of his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15673,\n            \"and he told them that Mr. Willoughby had no property of his own in the country;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15721,\n            \"adding, \\u201cYes, yes, he is very well worth catching I can tell you, Miss Dashwood;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15755,\n            \"and if I were you, I would not give him up to my younger sister, in spite of all this tumbling down hills.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15806,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not believe,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, with a good humoured smile, \\u201cthat Mr. Willoughby will be incommoded by the attempts of either of _ my _ daughters towards what you call _ catching him _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15879,\n            \"I am glad to find, however, from what you say, that he is a respectable young man, and one whose acquaintance will not be ineligible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15909,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe is as good a sort of fellow, I believe, as ever lived,\\u201drepeated Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15932,\n            \"\\u201cI remember last Christmas at a little hop at the park, he danced from eight o\\u2019clock till four, without once sitting down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16293,\n            \"with a kindness which Sir John\\u2019s account of him and her own gratitude prompted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17830,\n            \"Sir John had dropped hints of past injuries and disappointments, which justified her belief of his being an unfortunate man, and she regarded him with respect and compassion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25612,\n            \"His estate had been rated by Sir John at about six or seven hundred a year;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35886,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI wish with all my soul,\\u201dcried Sir John, \\u201cthat Willoughby were among us again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45989,\n            \"\\u201cHis name is Ferrars,\\u201dsaid he, in a very audible whisper;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46261,\n            \"\\u2014 But her curiosity was unavailing, for no farther notice was taken of Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s name by Miss Steele when alluded to, or even openly mentioned by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62251,\n            \"\\u201cSo my daughter Middleton told me, for it seems Sir John met him somewhere in the street this morning.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 16]\": [\n        [\n            12063,\n            \"His appearance however was not unpleasing, in spite of his being in the opinion of Marianne and Margaret an absolute old bachelor, for he was on the wrong side of five and thirty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12369,\n            \"Lady Middleton frequently called him to order, wondered how any one\\u2019s attention could be diverted from music for a moment, and asked Marianne to sing a particular song which Marianne had just finished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12423,\n            \"He paid her only the compliment of attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12432,\n            \"and she felt a respect for him on the occasion, which the others had reasonably forfeited by their shameless want of taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12456,\n            \"His pleasure in music, though it amounted not to that ecstatic delight which alone could sympathize with her own, was estimable when contrasted against the horrible insensibility of the others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12518,\n            \"She was perfectly disposed to make every allowance for the colonel\\u2019s advanced state of life which humanity required.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14733,\n            \"A gentleman carrying a gun, with two pointers playing round him, was passing up the hill and within a few yards of Marianne, when her accident happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14764,\n            \"He put down his gun and ran to her assistance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14807,\n            \"and perceiving that her modesty declined what her situation rendered necessary, took her up in his arms without farther delay, and carried her down the hill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14836,\n            \"Then passing through the garden, the gate of which had been left open by Margaret, he bore her directly into the house, whither Margaret was just arrived, and quitted not his hold till he had seated her in a chair in the parlour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15125,\n            \"His manly beauty and more than common gracefulness were instantly the theme of general admiration, and the laugh which his gallantry raised against Marianne received particular spirit from his exterior attractions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15158,\n            \"Marianne herself had seen less of his person than the rest, for the confusion which crimsoned over her face, on his lifting her up, had robbed her of the power of regarding him after their entering the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15200,\n            \"But she had seen enough of him to join in all the admiration of the others, and with an energy which always adorned her praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15227,\n            \"His person and air were equal to what her fancy had ever drawn for the hero of a favourite story;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15248,\n            \"and in his carrying her into the house with so little previous formality, there was a rapidity of thought which particularly recommended the action to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15284,\n            \"His name was good, his residence was in their favourite village, and she soon found out that of all manly dresses a shooting-jacket was the most becoming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15360,\n            \"and Marianne\\u2019s accident being related to him, he was eagerly asked whether he knew any gentleman of the name of Willoughby at Allenham.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15605,\n            \"\\u201d But Marianne could no more satisfy him as to the colour of Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s pointer, than he could describe to her the shades of his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16080,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is an expression, Sir John,\\u201dsaid Marianne, warmly, \\u201cwhich I particularly dislike.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16177,\n            \"but he laughed as heartily as if he did, and then replied, \\u201cAy, you will make conquests enough, I dare say, one way or other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16212,\n            \"he is quite smitten already, and he is very well worth setting your cap at, I can tell you, in spite of all this tumbling about and spraining of ankles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18769,\n            \"When Marianne was recovered, the schemes of amusement at home and abroad, which Sir John had been previously forming, were put into execution.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19659,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, unfortunately for himself, had no such encouragement to think only of Marianne, and in conversing with Elinor he found the greatest consolation for the indifference of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19754,\n            \"His eyes were fixed on Marianne, and, after a silence of some minutes, he said, with a faint smile, \\u201cYour sister, I understand, does not approve of second attachments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19830,\n            \"But how she contrives it without reflecting on the character of her own father, who had himself two wives, I know not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19995,\n            \"and a better acquaintance with the world is what I look forward to as her greatest possible advantage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20014,\n            \"\\u201d After a short pause he resumed the conversation by saying, \\u2014 \\u201cDoes your sister make no distinction in her objections against a second attachment?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20821,\n            \"Of John I know very little, though we have lived together for years;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39138,\n            \"\\u201cHere comes Marianne,\\u201dcried Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39161,\n            \"\\u201d He immediately went into the passage, opened the front door, and ushered her in himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40171,\n            \"\\u201cI am afraid, Miss Marianne,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cyou have not been able to take your usual walk to Allenham today.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45770,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor could not suppose that Sir John would be more nice in proclaiming his suspicions of her regard for Edward, than he had been with respect to Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55475,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have a notion,\\u201dsaid Sir John, \\u201cthat Miss Marianne would not object to such a scheme, if her elder sister would come into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62251,\n            \"\\u201cSo my daughter Middleton told me, for it seems Sir John met him somewhere in the street this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125059,\n            \"As bluntly as he could speak it, therefore, he told me that Marianne Dashwood was dying of a putrid fever at Cleveland \\u2014 a letter that morning received from Mrs. Jennings declared her danger most imminent \\u2014 the Palmers are all gone off in a fright, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133550,\n            \"Some letters had passed between her and her brother, in consequence of Marianne\\u2019s illness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142469,\n            \"And though, perhaps, Marianne may not seem exactly the person to attract him, yet I think it would altogether be advisable for you to have them now frequently staying with you, for as Colonel Brandon seems a great deal at home, nobody can tell what may happen;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142558,\n            \"In short, you may as well give her a chance: you understand me.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 17]\": [\n        [\n            35608,\n            \"With the assistance of his mother-in-law, Sir John was not long in discovering that the name of Ferrars began with an F.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 18]\": [\n        [\n            12776,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings had been anxious to see Colonel Brandon well married, ever since her connection with Sir John first brought him to her knowledge;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35567,\n            \"Before the middle of the day, they were visited by Sir John and Mrs. Jennings, who, having heard of the arrival of a gentleman at the cottage, came to take a survey of the guest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35726,\n            \"On the present occasion, for the better entertainment of their visitor, towards whose amusement he felt himself bound to contribute, he wished to engage them for both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99152,\n            \"I beg your pardon, Mr. Dashwood, but if he had done otherwise, I should have thought him a rascal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99786,\n            \"\\u201cIf he would only have done as well by himself,\\u201dsaid John Dashwood, \\u201cas all his friends were disposed to do by him, he might now have been in his proper situation, and would have wanted for nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99974,\n            \"\\u201cCan anything be more galling to the spirit of a man,\\u201dcontinued John, \\u201cthan to see his younger brother in possession of an estate which might have been his own?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100013,\n            \"I feel for him sincerely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103598,\n            \"and should it ever be in your power to recommend him to any body that has a living to bestow, am very sure you will not forget us, and dear Mrs. Jennings too, trust she will speak a good word for us to Sir John, or Mr. Palmer, or any friend that may be able to assist us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133568,\n            \"and in the first of John\\u2019s, there had been this sentence: \\u2014 \\u201cWe know nothing of our unfortunate Edward, and can make no enquiries on so prohibited a subject, but conclude him to be still at Oxford;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 19]\": [\n        [\n            14884,\n            \"Elinor and her mother rose up in amazement at their entrance, and while the eyes of both were fixed on him with an evident wonder and a secret admiration which equally sprung from his appearance, he apologized for his intrusion by relating its cause, in a manner so frank and so graceful that his person, which was uncommonly handsome, received additional charms from his voice and expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15470,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAs good a kind of fellow as ever lived, I assure you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15605,\n            \"\\u201d But Marianne could no more satisfy him as to the colour of Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s pointer, than he could describe to her the shades of his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17830,\n            \"Sir John had dropped hints of past injuries and disappointments, which justified her belief of his being an unfortunate man, and she regarded him with respect and compassion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19570,\n            \"In Colonel Brandon alone, of all her new acquaintance, did Elinor find a person who could in any degree claim the respect of abilities, excite the interest of friendship, or give pleasure as a companion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19659,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, unfortunately for himself, had no such encouragement to think only of Marianne, and in conversing with Elinor he found the greatest consolation for the indifference of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19693,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s compassion for him increased, as she had reason to suspect that the misery of disappointed love had already been known to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19754,\n            \"His eyes were fixed on Marianne, and, after a silence of some minutes, he said, with a faint smile, \\u201cYour sister, I understand, does not approve of second attachments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19830,\n            \"But how she contrives it without reflecting on the character of her own father, who had himself two wives, I know not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19942,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI cannot agree with you there,\\u201dsaid Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20236,\n            \"appeared to think that he had said too much, and by his countenance gave rise to conjectures, which might not otherwise have entered Elinor\\u2019s head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20266,\n            \"The lady would probably have passed without suspicion, had he not convinced Miss Dashwood that what concerned her ought not to escape his lips.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30256,\n            \"\\u201cRemember, Elinor,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201chow very often Sir John fetches our letters himself from the post, and carries them to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38014,\n            \"She was sitting near the window, and as soon as Sir John perceived her, he left the rest of the party to the ceremony of knocking at the door, and stepping across the turf, obliged her to open the casement to speak to him, though the space was so short between the door and the window, as to make it hardly possible to speak at one without being heard at the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38093,\n            \"\\u201cWell,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cwe have brought you some strangers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38137,\n            \"Charlotte is very pretty, I can tell you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41882,\n            \"\\u2014 I met Colonel Brandon Monday morning in Bond-street, just before we left town, and he told me of it directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41916,\n            \"Colonel Brandon tell you of it!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41929,\n            \"To give such intelligence to a person who could not be interested in it, even if it were true, is not what I should expect Colonel Brandon to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42650,\n            \"But mama did not think the match good enough for me, otherwise Sir John would have mentioned it to the Colonel, and we should have been married immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42702,\n            \"Had he never owned his affection to yourself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45509,\n            \"And to be better acquainted therefore, Elinor soon found was their inevitable lot, for as Sir John was entirely on the side of the Miss Steeles, their party would be too strong for opposition, and that kind of intimacy must be submitted to, which consists of sitting an hour or two together in the same room almost every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45770,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor could not suppose that Sir John would be more nice in proclaiming his suspicions of her regard for Edward, than he had been with respect to Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46261,\n            \"\\u2014 But her curiosity was unavailing, for no farther notice was taken of Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s name by Miss Steele when alluded to, or even openly mentioned by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51414,\n            \"One or two meetings of this kind had taken place, without affording Elinor any chance of engaging Lucy in private, when Sir John called at the cottage one morning, to beg, in the name of charity, that they would all dine with Lady Middleton that day, as he was obliged to attend the club at Exeter, and she would otherwise be quite alone, except her mother and the two Miss Steeles.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51494,\n            \"Elinor, who foresaw a fairer opening for the point she had in view, in such a party as this was likely to be, more at liberty among themselves under the tranquil and well-bred direction of Lady Middleton than when her husband united them together in one noisy purpose, immediately accepted the invitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61773,\n            \"Elinor found, when the evening was over, that disposition is not materially altered by a change of abode, for although scarcely settled in town, Sir John had contrived to collect around him, nearly twenty young people, and to amuse them with a ball.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81927,\n            \"Elinor found that he and Fanny had been in town two days.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82274,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor did feel a little ashamed of her brother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93209,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor would not oppose his opinion, because, whatever might be her general estimation of the advantage of a public school, she could not think of Edward\\u2019s abode in Mr. Pratt\\u2019s family, with any satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93254,\n            \"\\u201cYou reside in Devonshire, I think,\\u201d\\u2014 was his next observation, \\u201cin a cottage near Dawlish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93277,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor set him right as to its situation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93742,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor agreed to it all, for she did not think he deserved the compliment of rational opposition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93762,\n            \"As John Dashwood had no more pleasure in music than his eldest sister, his mind was equally at liberty to fix on any thing else;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112946,\n            \"\\u2014 and a faint invitation from Fanny, to come to Norland whenever it should happen to be in their way, which of all things was the most unlikely to occur, with a more warm, though less public, assurance, from John to Elinor, of the promptitude with which he should come to see her at Delaford, was all that foretold any meeting in the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133550,\n            \"Some letters had passed between her and her brother, in consequence of Marianne\\u2019s illness;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 10]\": [\n        [\n            143198,\n            \"Lucy became as necessary to Mrs. Ferrars, as either Robert or Fanny;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143291,\n            \"and setting aside the jealousies and ill-will continually subsisting between Fanny and Lucy, in which their husbands of course took a part, as well as the frequent domestic disagreements between Robert and Lucy themselves, nothing could exceed the harmony in which they all lived together.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 16]\": [\n        [\n            143561,\n            \"for her wish of bringing Marianne and Colonel Brandon together was hardly less earnest, though rather more liberal than what John had expressed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143621,\n            \"and to see Marianne settled at the mansion-house was equally the wish of Edward and Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143640,\n            \"They each felt his sorrows, and their own obligations, and Marianne, by general consent, was to be the reward of all.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 17]\": [\n        [\n            99850,\n            \"And there is one thing more preparing against him, which must be worse than all \\u2014 his mother has determined, with a very natural kind of spirit, to settle _ that _ estate upon Robert immediately, which might have been Edward\\u2019s, on proper conditions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141628,\n            \"the similar annihilation of Robert had left her for a fortnight without any;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 18]\": [\n        [\n            92755,\n            \"She perceived him soon afterwards looking at herself, and speaking familiarly to her brother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92771,\n            \"and had just determined to find out his name from the latter, when they both came towards her, and Mr. Dashwood introduced him to her as Mr. Robert Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92969,\n            \"for, talking of his brother, and lamenting the extreme _ gaucherie _ which he really believed kept him from mixing in proper society, he candidly and generously attributed it much less to any natural deficiency, than to the misfortune of a private education;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99850,\n            \"And there is one thing more preparing against him, which must be worse than all \\u2014 his mother has determined, with a very natural kind of spirit, to settle _ that _ estate upon Robert immediately, which might have been Edward\\u2019s, on proper conditions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111963,\n            \"The idea of Edward\\u2019s being a clergyman, and living in a small parsonage-house, diverted him beyond measure;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111987,\n            \"\\u2014 and when to that was added the fanciful imagery of Edward reading prayers in a white surplice, and publishing the banns of marriage between John Smith and Mary Brown, he could conceive nothing more ridiculous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138627,\n            \"The independence she settled on Robert, through resentment against you, has put it in his power to make his own choice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138681,\n            \"She will hardly be less hurt, I suppose, by Robert\\u2019s marrying Lucy, than she would have been by your marrying her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141127,\n            \"It determined him to attempt a reconciliation, though not exactly in the manner pointed out by their brother and sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141160,\n            \"\\u201cwould they have me beg my mother\\u2019s pardon for Robert\\u2019s ingratitude to _ her _, and breach of honour to _ me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141939,\n            \"for while Robert was inevitably endowed with a thousand pounds a-year, not the smallest objection was made against Edward\\u2019s taking orders for the sake of two hundred and fifty at the utmost;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 19]\": [\n        [\n            92755,\n            \"She perceived him soon afterwards looking at herself, and speaking familiarly to her brother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92771,\n            \"and had just determined to find out his name from the latter, when they both came towards her, and Mr. Dashwood introduced him to her as Mr. Robert Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92805,\n            \"He addressed her with easy civility, and twisted his head into a bow which assured her as plainly as words could have done, that he was exactly the coxcomb she had heard him described to be by Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92944,\n            \"Why they _ were _ different, Robert explained to her himself in the course of a quarter of an hour\\u2019s conversation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112026,\n            \"Elinor, while she waited in silence and immovable gravity, the conclusion of such folly, could not restrain her eyes from being fixed on him with a look that spoke all the contempt it excited.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112064,\n            \"It was a look, however, very well bestowed, for it relieved her own feelings, and gave no intelligence to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112089,\n            \"He was recalled from wit to wisdom, not by any reproof of hers, but by his own sensibility.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112746,\n            \"\\u201d He had just settled this point with great composure, when the entrance of Mrs. John Dashwood put an end to the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138681,\n            \"She will hardly be less hurt, I suppose, by Robert\\u2019s marrying Lucy, than she would have been by your marrying her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143621,\n            \"and to see Marianne settled at the mansion-house was equally the wish of Edward and Elinor.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 12]\": [\n        [\n            21608,\n            \"When Mrs. Jennings attacked her one evening at the park, to give the name of the young man who was Elinor\\u2019s particular favourite, which had been long a matter of great curiosity to her, Margaret answered by looking at her sister, and saying, \\u201cI must not tell, may I, Elinor?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21692,\n            \"She was convinced that Margaret had fixed on a person whose name she could not bear with composure to become a standing joke with Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21815,\n            \"pray, Miss Margaret, let us know all about it,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21842,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI must not tell, ma\\u2019am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38408,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and Margaret came down stairs at the same time, and they all sat down to look at one another, while Mrs. Jennings continued her story as she walked through the passage into the parlour, attended by Sir John.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 15]\": [\n        [\n            16250,\n            \"Marianne\\u2019s preserver, as Margaret, with more elegance than precision, styled Willoughby, called at the cottage early the next morning to make his personal enquiries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18547,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMiss Dashwood,\\u201dcried Willoughby, \\u201cyou are now using me unkindly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18564,\n            \"You are endeavouring to disarm me by reason, and to convince me against my will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18587,\n            \"You shall find me as stubborn as you can be artful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18644,\n            \"If it will be any satisfaction to you, however, to be told, that I believe his character to be in other respects irreproachable, I am ready to confess it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18678,\n            \"And in return for an acknowledgment, which must give me some pain, you cannot deny me the privilege of disliking him as much as ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21114,\n            \"and in the whole of the sentence, in his manner of pronouncing it, and in his addressing her sister by her Christian name alone, she instantly saw an intimacy so decided, a meaning so direct, as marked a perfect agreement between them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21303,\n            \"I am sure she will be married to Mr. Willoughby very soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21342,\n            \"and they had not known each other a week, I believe, before you were certain that Marianne wore his picture round her neck;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21392,\n            \"I am sure they will be married very soon, for he has got a lock of her hair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21448,\n            \"I am almost sure it is, for I saw him cut it off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126876,\n            \"for so great was her uneasiness about Marianne, that she had already determined to set out for Cleveland on that very day, without waiting for any further intelligence, and had so far settled her journey before his arrival, that the Careys were then expected every moment to fetch Margaret away, as her mother was unwilling to take her where there might be infection.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 16]\": [\n        [\n            1826,\n            \"but as she had already imbibed a good deal of Marianne\\u2019s romance, without having much of her sense, she did not, at thirteen, bid fair to equal her sisters at a more advanced period of life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12063,\n            \"His appearance however was not unpleasing, in spite of his being in the opinion of Marianne and Margaret an absolute old bachelor, for he was on the wrong side of five and thirty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14392,\n            \"and towards one of these hills did Marianne and Margaret one memorable morning direct their steps, attracted by the partial sunshine of a showery sky, and unable longer to bear the confinement which the settled rain of the two preceding days had occasioned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14710,\n            \"and Margaret, unable to stop herself to assist her, was involuntarily hurried along, and reached the bottom in safety.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14836,\n            \"Then passing through the garden, the gate of which had been left open by Margaret, he bore her directly into the house, whither Margaret was just arrived, and quitted not his hold till he had seated her in a chair in the parlour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16250,\n            \"Marianne\\u2019s preserver, as Margaret, with more elegance than precision, styled Willoughby, called at the cottage early the next morning to make his personal enquiries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18644,\n            \"If it will be any satisfaction to you, however, to be told, that I believe his character to be in other respects irreproachable, I am ready to confess it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21114,\n            \"and in the whole of the sentence, in his manner of pronouncing it, and in his addressing her sister by her Christian name alone, she instantly saw an intimacy so decided, a meaning so direct, as marked a perfect agreement between them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21287,\n            \"\\u201d she cried, \\u201cI have such a secret to tell you about Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21303,\n            \"I am sure she will be married to Mr. Willoughby very soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21342,\n            \"and they had not known each other a week, I believe, before you were certain that Marianne wore his picture round her neck;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21392,\n            \"I am sure they will be married very soon, for he has got a lock of her hair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21923,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMargaret,\\u201dsaid Marianne with great warmth, \\u201cyou know that all this is an invention of your own, and that there is no such person in existence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21957,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, then, he is lately dead, Marianne, for I am sure there was such a man once, and his name begins with an F.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51553,\n            \"Margaret, with her mother\\u2019s permission, was equally compliant, and Marianne, though always unwilling to join any of their parties, was persuaded by her mother, who could not bear to have her seclude herself from any chance of amusement, to go likewise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126876,\n            \"for so great was her uneasiness about Marianne, that she had already determined to set out for Cleveland on that very day, without waiting for any further intelligence, and had so far settled her journey before his arrival, that the Careys were then expected every moment to fetch Margaret away, as her mother was unwilling to take her where there might be infection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133849,\n            \"By that time, Marianne was rather better, and her mother leaving her to the care of Margaret and the maid, returned to Elinor, who, though still much disordered, had so far recovered the use of her reason and voice as to be just beginning an inquiry of Thomas, as to the source of his intelligence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144323,\n            \"and fortunately for Sir John and Mrs. Jennings, when Marianne was taken from them, Margaret had reached an age highly suitable for dancing, and not very ineligible for being supposed to have a lover.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 18]\": [\n        [\n            21862,\n            \"and I know where he is too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21893,\n            \"He is the curate of the parish I dare say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21957,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, then, he is lately dead, Marianne, for I am sure there was such a man once, and his name begins with an F.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135908,\n            \"and Margaret, understanding some part, but not the whole of the case, thought it incumbent on her to be dignified, and therefore took a seat as far from him as she could, and maintained a strict silence.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 19]\": [\n        [\n            20266,\n            \"The lady would probably have passed without suspicion, had he not convinced Miss Dashwood that what concerned her ought not to escape his lips.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21209,\n            \"Margaret related something to her the next day, which placed this matter in a still clearer light.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21287,\n            \"\\u201d she cried, \\u201cI have such a secret to tell you about Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21317,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou have said so,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201calmost every day since they first met on High-church Down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21608,\n            \"When Mrs. Jennings attacked her one evening at the park, to give the name of the young man who was Elinor\\u2019s particular favourite, which had been long a matter of great curiosity to her, Margaret answered by looking at her sister, and saying, \\u201cI must not tell, may I, Elinor?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21692,\n            \"She was convinced that Margaret had fixed on a person whose name she could not bear with composure to become a standing joke with Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21727,\n            \"but she did more harm than good to the cause, by turning very red and saying in an angry manner to Margaret, \\u201cRemember that whatever your conjectures may be, you have no right to repeat them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35667,\n            \"But, as it was, she only learned, from some very significant looks, how far their penetration, founded on Margaret\\u2019s instructions, extended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133849,\n            \"By that time, Marianne was rather better, and her mother leaving her to the care of Margaret and the maid, returned to Elinor, who, though still much disordered, had so far recovered the use of her reason and voice as to be just beginning an inquiry of Thomas, as to the source of his intelligence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134595,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s and Elinor\\u2019s appetites were equally lost, and Margaret might think herself very well off, that with so much uneasiness as both her sisters had lately experienced, so much reason as they had often had to be careless of their meals, she had never been obliged to go without her dinner before.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 14]\": [\n        [\n            39977,\n            \"I am sure I shall be very happy to chaperon you at any time till I am confined, if Mrs. Dashwood should not like to go into public.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 15]\": [\n        [\n            24353,\n            \"Elinor could hardly believe this to be true, as it seemed very unlikely that Willoughby should propose, or Marianne consent, to enter the house while Mrs. Smith was in it, with whom Marianne had not the smallest acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24480,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, Marianne, but I would not go while Mrs. Smith was there, and with no other companion than Mr. Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26352,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Dashwood looked with pleasure at Marianne, whose fine eyes were fixed so expressively on Willoughby, as plainly denoted how well she understood him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26430,\n            \"How little did I then think that the very first news I should hear from Mrs. Smith, when I next came into the country, would be that Barton cottage was taken: and I felt an immediate satisfaction and interest in the event, which nothing but a kind of prescience of what happiness I should experience from it, can account for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26515,\n            \"Then continuing his former tone, he said, \\u201cAnd yet this house you would spoil, Mrs. Dashwood?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26622,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Dashwood again assured him that no alteration of the kind should be attempted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26755,\n            \"\\u201d said Mrs. Dashwood, when he was leaving them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26767,\n            \"\\u201cI do not ask you to come in the morning, for we must walk to the park, to call on Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26885,\n            \"On their return from the park they found Willoughby\\u2019s curricle and servant in waiting at the cottage, and Mrs. Dashwood was convinced that her conjecture had been just.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27125,\n            \"Mrs. Smith has this morning exercised the privilege of riches upon a poor dependent cousin, by sending me on business to London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27214,\n            \"\\u2014 and her business will not detain you from us long I hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27228,\n            \"\\u201d He coloured as he replied, \\u201cYou are very kind, but I have no idea of returning into Devonshire immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27252,\n            \"My visits to Mrs. Smith are never repeated within the twelvemonth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27357,\n            \"\\u201cI have only to add, my dear Willoughby, that at Barton cottage you will always be welcome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27378,\n            \"for I will not press you to return here immediately, because you only can judge how far _ that _ might be pleasing to Mrs. Smith;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27407,\n            \"and on this head I shall be no more disposed to question your judgment than to doubt your inclination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28609,\n            \"It may be proper to conceal their engagement (if they _ are _ engaged) from Mrs. Smith \\u2014 and if that is the case, it must be highly expedient for Willoughby to be but little in Devonshire at present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29365,\n            \"and if he felt obliged, from a fear of offending Mrs. Smith, to resist the temptation of returning here soon, and yet aware that by declining your invitation, by saying that he was going away for some time, he should seem to act an ungenerous, a suspicious part by our family, he might well be embarrassed and disturbed.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 16]\": [\n        [\n            24353,\n            \"Elinor could hardly believe this to be true, as it seemed very unlikely that Willoughby should propose, or Marianne consent, to enter the house while Mrs. Smith was in it, with whom Marianne had not the smallest acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24480,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, Marianne, but I would not go while Mrs. Smith was there, and with no other companion than Mr. Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24707,\n            \"I value not her censure any more than I should do her commendation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24721,\n            \"I am not sensible of having done anything wrong in walking over Mrs. Smith\\u2019s grounds, or in seeing her house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26352,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Dashwood looked with pleasure at Marianne, whose fine eyes were fixed so expressively on Willoughby, as plainly denoted how well she understood him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26515,\n            \"Then continuing his former tone, he said, \\u201cAnd yet this house you would spoil, Mrs. Dashwood?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27046,\n            \"\\u201d cried Mrs. Dashwood as she entered \\u2014 \\u201cis she ill?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28077,\n            \"I am persuaded that Mrs. Smith suspects his regard for Marianne, disapproves of it, (perhaps because she has other views for him,) and on that account is eager to get him away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28146,\n            \"He is, moreover, aware that she _ does _ disapprove the connection, he dares not therefore at present confess to her his engagement with Marianne, and he feels himself obliged, from his dependent situation, to give into her schemes, and absent himself from Devonshire for a while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30434,\n            \"It would be the natural result of your affection for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30499,\n            \"I should never deserve her confidence again, after forcing from her a confession of what is meant at present to be unacknowledged to any one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30526,\n            \"I know Marianne\\u2019s heart: I know that she dearly loves me, and that I shall not be the last to whom the affair is made known, when circumstances make the revealment of it eligible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30687,\n            \"\\u2014 but one evening, Mrs. Dashwood, accidentally taking up a volume of Shakespeare, exclaimed, \\u201cWe have never finished Hamlet, Marianne;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 18]\": [\n        [\n            28077,\n            \"I am persuaded that Mrs. Smith suspects his regard for Marianne, disapproves of it, (perhaps because she has other views for him,) and on that account is eager to get him away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28116,\n            \"\\u2014 and that the business which she sends him off to transact is invented as an excuse to dismiss him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28146,\n            \"He is, moreover, aware that she _ does _ disapprove the connection, he dares not therefore at present confess to her his engagement with Marianne, and he feels himself obliged, from his dependent situation, to give into her schemes, and absent himself from Devonshire for a while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32255,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood was surprised only for a moment at seeing him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32268,\n            \"for his coming to Barton was, in her opinion, of all things the most natural.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32297,\n            \"He received the kindest welcome from her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32319,\n            \"They had begun to fail him before he entered the house, and they were quite overcome by the captivating manners of Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32464,\n            \"\\u201cWhat are Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s views for you at present, Edward?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34275,\n            \"Do not you know she calls every one reserved who does not talk as fast, and admire what she admires as rapturously as herself?\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 19]\": [\n        [\n            24353,\n            \"Elinor could hardly believe this to be true, as it seemed very unlikely that Willoughby should propose, or Marianne consent, to enter the house while Mrs. Smith was in it, with whom Marianne had not the smallest acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24480,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, Marianne, but I would not go while Mrs. Smith was there, and with no other companion than Mr. Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26767,\n            \"\\u201cI do not ask you to come in the morning, for we must walk to the park, to call on Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26809,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s visit to Lady Middleton took place the next day, and two of her daughters went with her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27327,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Dashwood looked at Elinor with surprise.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 12]\": [\n        [\n            38976,\n            \"\\u201cbut, however, I can\\u2019t help wishing they had not travelled quite so fast, nor made such a long journey of it, for they came all round by London upon account of some business, for you know (nodding significantly and pointing to her daughter) it was wrong in her situation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40898,\n            \"\\u201cOh, my dear Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Palmer soon afterwards, \\u201cI have got such a favour to ask of you and your sister.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 14]\": [\n        [\n            38499,\n            \"Her manners were by no means so elegant as her sister\\u2019s, but they were much more prepossessing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38547,\n            \"Her husband was a grave looking young man of five or six and twenty, with an air of more fashion and sense than his wife, but of less willingness to please or be pleased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40513,\n            \"\\u201cMy love you contradict every body,\\u201dsaid his wife with her usual laugh.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40868,\n            \"but the means, however they might succeed by establishing his superiority in ill-breeding, were not likely to attach any one to him except his wife.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 15]\": [\n        [\n            41773,\n            \"your sister is to marry him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42235,\n            \"Mama says _ he _ was in love with your sister too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42330,\n            \"Nobody is more liked than Mr. Willoughby wherever he goes, and so you may tell your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42350,\n            \"She is a monstrous lucky girl to get him, upon my honour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42364,\n            \"not but that he is much more lucky in getting her, because she is so very handsome and agreeable, that nothing can be good enough for her.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 16]\": [\n        [\n            5810,\n            \"I felt for my sister most severely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6398,\n            \"At length she replied: \\u201cDo not be offended, Elinor, if my praise of him is not in every thing equal to your sense of his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6429,\n            \"I have not had so many opportunities of estimating the minuter propensities of his mind, his inclinations and tastes, as you have;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35407,\n            \"the only difference in their conclusions was, that what Marianne considered as a free gift from her sister, Elinor was conscious must have been procured by some theft or contrivance unknown to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37677,\n            \"That her sister\\u2019s affections _ were _ calm, she dared not deny, though she blushed to acknowledge it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37700,\n            \"and of the strength of her own, she gave a very striking proof, by still loving and respecting that sister, in spite of this mortifying conviction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141406,\n            \"\\u201cAnd if they really _ do _ interest themselves,\\u201dsaid Marianne, in her new character of candour, \\u201cin bringing about a reconciliation, I shall think that even John and Fanny are not entirely without merit.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 17]\": [\n        [\n            83021,\n            \"And her mother too, Mrs. Ferrars, a very good-natured woman, I am sure it would give her great pleasure;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87043,\n            \"Elinor, having once delivered her opinion on William\\u2019s side, by which she offended Mrs. Ferrars and Fanny still more, did not see the necessity of enforcing it by any farther assertion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98784,\n            \"All that Mrs. Ferrars could say to make him put an end to the engagement, assisted too as you may well suppose by my arguments, and Fanny\\u2019s entreaties, was of no avail.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140791,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars was the most unfortunate of women \\u2014 poor Fanny had suffered agonies of sensibility \\u2014 and he considered the existence of each, under such a blow, with grateful wonder.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 18]\": [\n        [\n            5581,\n            \"Edward is very amiable, and I love him tenderly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5653,\n            \"And besides all this, I am afraid, Mama, he has no real taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5769,\n            \"He must enter into all my feelings;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5921,\n            \"Elinor has not my feelings, and therefore she may overlook it, and be happy with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5940,\n            \"But it would have broke _ my _ heart, had I loved him, to hear him read with so little sensibility.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6398,\n            \"At length she replied: \\u201cDo not be offended, Elinor, if my praise of him is not in every thing equal to your sense of his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6429,\n            \"I have not had so many opportunities of estimating the minuter propensities of his mind, his inclinations and tastes, as you have;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6454,\n            \"but I have the highest opinion in the world of his goodness and sense.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6469,\n            \"I think him every thing that is worthy and amiable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6533,\n            \"\\u201cOf his sense and his goodness,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cno one can, I think, be in doubt, who has seen him often enough to engage him in unreserved conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6605,\n            \"But of his minuter propensities, as you call them you have from peculiar circumstances been kept more ignorant than myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6627,\n            \"He and I have been at times thrown a good deal together, while you have been wholly engrossed on the most affectionate principle by my mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6655,\n            \"I have seen a great deal of him, have studied his sentiments and heard his opinion on subjects of literature and taste;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6679,\n            \"and, upon the whole, I venture to pronounce that his mind is well-informed, enjoyment of books exceedingly great, his imagination lively, his observation just and correct, and his taste delicate and pure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6779,\n            \"At present, I know him so well, that I think him really handsome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6808,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall very soon think him handsome, Elinor, if I do not now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6826,\n            \"When you tell me to love him as a brother, I shall no more see imperfection in his face, than I now do in his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6966,\n            \"\\u201cI do not attempt to deny,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cthat I think very highly of him \\u2014 that I greatly esteem, that I like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7138,\n            \"I am by no means assured of his regard for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7161,\n            \"and till his sentiments are fully known, you cannot wonder at my wishing to avoid any encouragement of my own partiality, by believing or calling it more than it is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7194,\n            \"In my heart I feel little \\u2014 scarcely any doubt of his preference.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7261,\n            \"and I am very much mistaken if Edward is not himself aware that there would be many difficulties in his way, if he were to wish to marry a woman who had not either a great fortune or high rank.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7354,\n            \"_ I _ shall not lose you so soon, and Edward will have greater opportunity of improving that natural taste for your favourite pursuit which must be so indispensably necessary to your future felicity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35285,\n            \"I remember her promising to give you some.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50088,\n            \"Her mother, sisters, Fanny, all had been conscious of his regard for her at Norland;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94101,\n            \"and I think the attention is due to them, as their uncle did so very well by Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98749,\n            \"We consulted together, however, as to what should be done, and at last she determined to send for Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98784,\n            \"All that Mrs. Ferrars could say to make him put an end to the engagement, assisted too as you may well suppose by my arguments, and Fanny\\u2019s entreaties, was of no avail.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98843,\n            \"His mother explained to him her liberal designs, in case of his marrying Miss Morton;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98929,\n            \"His own two thousand pounds she protested should be his all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98941,\n            \"she would never see him again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98948,\n            \"and so far would she be from affording him the smallest assistance, that if he were to enter into any profession with a view of better support, she would do all in her power to prevent him advancing in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110231,\n            \"\\u201cFanny is in her own room, I suppose,\\u201dsaid he: \\u201cI will go to her presently, for I am sure she will not have the least objection in the world to seeing _ you _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110749,\n            \"\\u2014 You will not mention the matter to Fanny, however, for though I have broke it to her, and she bears it vastly well, \\u2014 she will not like to hear it much talked of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110789,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor had some difficulty here to refrain from observing, that she thought Fanny might have borne with composure, an acquisition of wealth to her brother, by which neither she nor her child could be possibly impoverished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141015,\n            \"Perhaps, however, he is kept silent by his fear of offending, and I shall, therefore, give him a hint, by a line to Oxford, that his sister and I both think a letter of proper submission from him, addressed perhaps to Fanny, and by her shown to her mother, might not be taken amiss;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141350,\n            \"and therefore, to make it easier to him, as he declared a much greater willingness to make mean concessions by word of mouth than on paper, it was resolved that, instead of writing to Fanny, he should go to London, and personally intreat her good offices in his favour.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 19]\": [\n        [\n            5564,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cI may consider it with some surprise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5921,\n            \"Elinor has not my feelings, and therefore she may overlook it, and be happy with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5964,\n            \"Mama, the more I know of the world, the more am I convinced that I shall never see a man whom I can really love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6020,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cRemember, my love, that you are not seventeen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6398,\n            \"At length she replied: \\u201cDo not be offended, Elinor, if my praise of him is not in every thing equal to your sense of his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6480,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sure,\\u201dreplied Elinor, with a smile, \\u201cthat his dearest friends could not be dissatisfied with such commendation as that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6509,\n            \"I do not perceive how you could express yourself more warmly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6533,\n            \"\\u201cOf his sense and his goodness,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cno one can, I think, be in doubt, who has seen him often enough to engage him in unreserved conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6808,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall very soon think him handsome, Elinor, if I do not now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6826,\n            \"When you tell me to love him as a brother, I shall no more see imperfection in his face, than I now do in his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6966,\n            \"\\u201cI do not attempt to deny,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cthat I think very highly of him \\u2014 that I greatly esteem, that I like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7051,\n            \"\\u201cExcuse me,\\u201dsaid she;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7059,\n            \"\\u201cand be assured that I meant no offence to you, by speaking, in so quiet a way, of my own feelings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7138,\n            \"I am by no means assured of his regard for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7354,\n            \"_ I _ shall not lose you so soon, and Edward will have greater opportunity of improving that natural taste for your favourite pursuit which must be so indispensably necessary to your future felicity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35407,\n            \"the only difference in their conclusions was, that what Marianne considered as a free gift from her sister, Elinor was conscious must have been procured by some theft or contrivance unknown to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38976,\n            \"\\u201cbut, however, I can\\u2019t help wishing they had not travelled quite so fast, nor made such a long journey of it, for they came all round by London upon account of some business, for you know (nodding significantly and pointing to her daughter) it was wrong in her situation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40898,\n            \"\\u201cOh, my dear Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Palmer soon afterwards, \\u201cI have got such a favour to ask of you and your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42350,\n            \"She is a monstrous lucky girl to get him, upon my honour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42394,\n            \"However, I don\\u2019t think her hardly at all handsomer than you, I assure you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42537,\n            \"And I am so glad your sister is going to be well married!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44996,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut why should you think,\\u201dsaid Lucy, looking ashamed of her sister, \\u201cthat there are not as many genteel young men in Devonshire as Sussex?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50088,\n            \"Her mother, sisters, Fanny, all had been conscious of his regard for her at Norland;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83251,\n            \"To give you another instance of her liberality: \\u2014 The other day, as soon as we came to town, aware that money could not be very plenty with us just now, she put bank-notes into Fanny\\u2019s hands to the amount of two hundred pounds.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84460,\n            \"I remember Fanny used to say that she would marry sooner and better than you did;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84572,\n            \"and I think I can answer for your having Fanny and myself among the earliest and best pleased of your visitors.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84794,\n            \"\\u201cI shall have a charming account to carry to Fanny,\\u201dsaid he, as he walked back with his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85208,\n            \"but nothing would have induced Fanny voluntarily to mention his name before her, till able to tell her that his marriage with Miss Morton was resolved on, or till her husband\\u2019s expectations on Colonel Brandon were answered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87043,\n            \"Elinor, having once delivered her opinion on William\\u2019s side, by which she offended Mrs. Ferrars and Fanny still more, did not see the necessity of enforcing it by any farther assertion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110231,\n            \"\\u201cFanny is in her own room, I suppose,\\u201dsaid he: \\u201cI will go to her presently, for I am sure she will not have the least objection in the world to seeing _ you _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110749,\n            \"\\u2014 You will not mention the matter to Fanny, however, for though I have broke it to her, and she bears it vastly well, \\u2014 she will not like to hear it much talked of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110789,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor had some difficulty here to refrain from observing, that she thought Fanny might have borne with composure, an acquisition of wealth to her brother, by which neither she nor her child could be possibly impoverished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112946,\n            \"\\u2014 and a faint invitation from Fanny, to come to Norland whenever it should happen to be in their way, which of all things was the most unlikely to occur, with a more warm, though less public, assurance, from John to Elinor, of the promptitude with which he should come to see her at Delaford, was all that foretold any meeting in the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 14]\": [\n        [\n            39554,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings and Mrs. Palmer joined their entreaties, all seemed equally anxious to avoid a family party;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39928,\n            \"\\u201d cried Mrs. Palmer, with a laugh, \\u201cI shall be quite disappointed if you do not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40473,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou and I, Sir John,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cshould not stand upon such ceremony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40496,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen you would be very ill-bred,\\u201dcried Mr. Palmer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40558,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, you may abuse me as you please,\\u201dsaid the good-natured old lady, \\u201cyou have taken Charlotte off my hands, and cannot give her back again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115737,\n            \"for Mr. Palmer, though very unwilling to go as well from real humanity and good-nature, as from a dislike of appearing to be frightened away by his wife, was persuaded at last by Colonel Brandon to perform his promise of following her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115935,\n            \"especially as Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s entreaty was warmly seconded by Mr. Palmer, who seemed to feel a relief to himself, in leaving behind him a person so well able to assist or advise Miss Dashwood in any emergence.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 15]\": [\n        [\n            23808,\n            \"\\u201d Then, lowering her voice a little, she said to Elinor, \\u201cShe is his natural daughter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23848,\n            \"I dare say the Colonel will leave her all his fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24171,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not you know,\\u201dsaid Willoughby, \\u201cthat we had been out in my curricle?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24192,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, yes, Mr. Impudence, I know that very well, and I was determined to find out _ where _ you had been to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36467,\n            \"Disappointed, however, and vexed as she was, and sometimes displeased with his uncertain behaviour to herself, she was very well disposed on the whole to regard his actions with all the candid allowances and generous qualifications, which had been rather more painfully extorted from her, for Willoughby\\u2019s service, by her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61697,\n            \"but when the hour of appointment drew near, necessary as it was in common civility to Mrs. Jennings, that they should both attend her on such a visit, Elinor had some difficulty in persuading her sister to go, for still she had seen nothing of Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61749,\n            \"and therefore was not more indisposed for amusement abroad, than unwilling to run the risk of his calling again in her absence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65592,\n            \"That good lady, however, saw only that Marianne had received a letter from Willoughby, which appeared to her a very good joke, and which she treated accordingly, by hoping, with a laugh, that she would find it to her liking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65732,\n            \"I hope, from the bottom of my heart, he won\\u2019t keep her waiting much longer, for it is quite grievous to see her look so ill and forlorn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65775,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, though never less disposed to speak than at that moment, obliged herself to answer such an attack as this, and, therefore, trying to smile, replied, \\u201cAnd have you really, Ma\\u2019am, talked yourself into a persuasion of my sister\\u2019s being engaged to Mr. Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72728,\n            \"for soon after his entrance, she walked across the room to the tea-table where Elinor presided, and whispered, \\u201cThe Colonel looks as grave as ever you see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128921,\n            \"At his and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s united request in return, Mrs. Dashwood was prevailed on to accept the use of his carriage on her journey back, for the better accommodation of her sick child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128961,\n            \"and the Colonel, at the joint invitation of Mrs. Dashwood and Mrs. Jennings, whose active good-nature made her friendly and hospitable for other people as well as herself, engaged with pleasure to redeem it by a visit at the cottage, in the course of a few weeks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129025,\n            \"and Marianne, after taking so particular and lengthened a leave of Mrs. Jennings, one so earnestly grateful, so full of respect and kind wishes as seemed due to her own heart from a secret acknowledgment of past inattention, and bidding Colonel Brandon farewell with a cordiality of a friend, was carefully assisted by him into the carriage, of which he seemed anxious that she should engross at least half.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 16]\": [\n        [\n            11963,\n            \"Marianne was vexed at it for her sister\\u2019s sake, and turned her eyes towards Elinor to see how she bore these attacks, with an earnestness which gave Elinor far more pain than could arise from such common-place raillery as Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12840,\n            \"At the park she laughed at the colonel, and in the cottage at Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13648,\n            \"\\u201d Soon after this, upon Elinor\\u2019s leaving the room, \\u201cMama,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cI have an alarm on the subject of illness which I cannot conceal from you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23764,\n            \"I am sure you must have heard of her before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24149,\n            \"I know where you spent the morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24223,\n            \"I hope you like your house, Miss Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39180,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings asked her, as soon as she appeared, if she had not been to Allenham;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40558,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, you may abuse me as you please,\\u201dsaid the good-natured old lady, \\u201cyou have taken Charlotte off my hands, and cannot give her back again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55508,\n            \"It is very hard indeed that she should not have a little pleasure, because Miss Dashwood does not wish it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55560,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings, \\u201cI am sure I shall be monstrous glad of Miss Marianne\\u2019s company, whether Miss Dashwood will go or not, only the more the merrier say I, and I thought it would be more comfortable for them to be together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55688,\n            \"Come, Miss Marianne, let us strike hands upon the bargain, and if Miss Dashwood will change her mind by and bye, why so much the better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55719,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thank you, ma\\u2019am, sincerely thank you,\\u201dsaid Marianne, with warmth: \\u201cyour invitation has insured my gratitude for ever, and it would give me such happiness, yes, almost the greatest happiness I am capable of, to be able to accept it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55943,\n            \"Whatever Marianne was desirous of, her mother would be eager to promote \\u2014 she could not expect to influence the latter to cautiousness of conduct in an affair respecting which she had never been able to inspire her with distrust;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56001,\n            \"That Marianne, fastidious as she was, thoroughly acquainted with Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 manners, and invariably disgusted by them, should overlook every inconvenience of that kind, should disregard whatever must be most wounding to her irritable feelings, in her pursuit of one object, was such a proof, so strong, so full, of the importance of that object to her, as Elinor, in spite of all that had passed, was not prepared to witness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56088,\n            \"On being informed of the invitation, Mrs. Dashwood, persuaded that such an excursion would be productive of much amusement to both her daughters, and perceiving through all her affectionate attention to herself, how much the heart of Marianne was in it, would not hear of their declining the offer upon _ her _ account;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56564,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf Elinor is frightened away by her dislike of Mrs. Jennings,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cat least it need not prevent MY accepting her invitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56654,\n            \"and resolved within herself, that if her sister persisted in going, she would go likewise, as she did not think it proper that Marianne should be left to the sole guidance of her own judgment, or that Mrs. Jennings should be abandoned to the mercy of Marianne for all the comfort of her domestic hours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57695,\n            \"They were three days on their journey, and Marianne\\u2019s behaviour as they travelled was a happy specimen of what future complaisance and companionableness to Mrs. Jennings might be expected to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59341,\n            \"After her entrance, Colonel Brandon became more thoughtful and silent than he had been before, and Mrs. Jennings could not prevail on him to stay long.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61250,\n            \"\\u201d But Marianne seemed hardly to hear her, and on Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s entrance, escaped with the precious card.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62375,\n            \"About the middle of the day, Mrs. Jennings went out by herself on business, and Elinor began her letter directly, while Marianne, too restless for employment, too anxious for conversation, walked from one window to the other, or sat down by the fire in melancholy meditation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65592,\n            \"That good lady, however, saw only that Marianne had received a letter from Willoughby, which appeared to her a very good joke, and which she treated accordingly, by hoping, with a laugh, that she would find it to her liking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65667,\n            \"and calmly continuing her talk, as soon as Marianne disappeared, she said, \\u201cUpon my word, I never saw a young woman so desperately in love in my life!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66847,\n            \"In her earnest meditations on the contents of the letter, on the depravity of that mind which could dictate it, and probably, on the very different mind of a very different person, who had no other connection whatever with the affair than what her heart gave him with every thing that passed, Elinor forgot the immediate distress of her sister, forgot that she had three letters on her lap yet unread, and so entirely forgot how long she had been in the room, that when on hearing a carriage drive up to the door, she went to the window to see who could be coming so unreasonably early, she was all astonishment to perceive Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s chariot, which she knew had not been ordered till one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66988,\n            \"Determined not to quit Marianne, though hopeless of contributing, at present, to her ease, she hurried away to excuse herself from attending Mrs. Jennings, on account of her sister being indisposed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67026,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, with a thoroughly good-humoured concern for its cause, admitted the excuse most readily, and Elinor, after seeing her safe off, returned to Marianne, whom she found attempting to rise from the bed, and whom she reached just in time to prevent her from falling on the floor, faint and giddy from a long want of proper rest and food;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67157,\n            \"A glass of wine, which Elinor procured for her directly, made her more comfortable, and she was at last able to express some sense of her kindness, by saying, \\u201cPoor Elinor!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69716,\n            \"and from that time till Mrs. Jennings returned, she continued on the bed quiet and motionless.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70362,\n            \"Their good friend saw that Marianne was unhappy, and felt that every thing was due to her which might make her at all less so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73704,\n            \"In one thing, however, she was uniform, when it came to the point, in avoiding, where it was possible, the presence of Mrs. Jennings, and in a determined silence when obliged to endure it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73747,\n            \"Her heart was hardened against the belief of Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s entering into her sorrows with any compassion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73802,\n            \"All that she wants is gossip, and she only likes me now because I supply it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74558,\n            \"while Marianne, who came into the drawing-room on Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s going away, remained fixed at the table where Elinor wrote, watching the advancement of her pen, grieving over her for the hardship of such a task, and grieving still more fondly over its effect on her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81277,\n            \"After some opposition, Marianne yielded to her sister\\u2019s entreaties, and consented to go out with her and Mrs. Jennings one morning for half an hour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96143,\n            \"\\u201d Here Mrs. Jennings ceased, and as Elinor had had time enough to collect her thoughts, she was able to give such an answer, and make such observations, as the subject might naturally be supposed to produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96201,\n            \"that Mrs. Jennings (as she had of late often hoped might be the case) had ceased to imagine her at all attached to Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96394,\n            \"As Mrs. Jennings could talk on no other subject, Elinor soon saw the necessity of preparing Marianne for its discussion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100124,\n            \"and as her vehemence made reserve impossible in Elinor, and unnecessary in Mrs. Jennings, they all joined in a very spirited critique upon the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100156,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings was very warm in her praise of Edward\\u2019s conduct, but only Elinor and Marianne understood its true merit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103786,\n            \"\\u201d As soon as Elinor had finished it, she performed what she concluded to be its writer\\u2019s real design, by placing it in the hands of Mrs. Jennings, who read it aloud with many comments of satisfaction and praise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106018,\n            \"an evil which Elinor, as Mrs. Jennings had supposed her to do, made very light of, at least as far as regarded its size.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106378,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Jennings, sagaciously smiling, as soon as the gentleman had withdrawn, \\u201cI do not ask you what the Colonel has been saying to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106469,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThank you, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114753,\n            \"\\u2014 and while his looks of anxious solicitude on Marianne\\u2019s feeling, in her head and throat, the beginning of a heavy cold, because unexpressed by words, entirely escaped the latter lady\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115186,\n            \"and when Marianne, after persisting in rising, confessed herself unable to sit up, and returned voluntarily to her bed, Elinor was very ready to adopt Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s advice, of sending for the Palmers\\u2019 apothecary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115295,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, who had been inclined from the first to think Marianne\\u2019s complaint more serious than Elinor, now looked very grave on Mr. Harris\\u2019 s report, and confirming Charlotte\\u2019s fears and caution, urged the necessity of her immediate removal with her infant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115467,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, however, with a kindness of heart which made Elinor really love her, declared her resolution of not stirring from Cleveland as long as Marianne remained ill, and of endeavouring, by her own attentive care, to supply to her the place of the mother she had taken her from;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116115,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings had determined very early in the seizure that Marianne would never get over it, and Colonel Brandon, who was chiefly of use in listening to Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s forebodings, was not in a state of mind to resist their influence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116491,\n            \"her maid, who was one of the principal nurses, was recreating herself in the housekeeper\\u2019s room, and Elinor remained alone with Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117675,\n            \"\\u2014 and as for their mother, when Mrs. Jennings considered that Marianne might probably be to _ her _ what Charlotte was to herself, her sympathy in _ her _ sufferings was very sincere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117860,\n            \"and in this state she continued till noon, scarcely stirring from her sister\\u2019s bed, her thoughts wandering from one image of grief, one suffering friend to another, and her spirits oppressed to the utmost by the conversation of Mrs. Jennings, who scrupled not to attribute the severity and danger of this attack to the many weeks of previous indisposition which Marianne\\u2019s disappointment had brought on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118583,\n            \"At seven o\\u2019clock, leaving Marianne still sweetly asleep, she joined Mrs. Jennings in the drawing-room to tea.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118653,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings would have persuaded her, at its conclusion, to take some rest before her mother\\u2019s arrival, and allow _ her _ to take her place by Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129025,\n            \"and Marianne, after taking so particular and lengthened a leave of Mrs. Jennings, one so earnestly grateful, so full of respect and kind wishes as seemed due to her own heart from a secret acknowledgment of past inattention, and bidding Colonel Brandon farewell with a cordiality of a friend, was carefully assisted by him into the carriage, of which he seemed anxious that she should engross at least half.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 17]\": [\n        [\n            35608,\n            \"With the assistance of his mother-in-law, Sir John was not long in discovering that the name of Ferrars began with an F.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109211,\n            \"\\u2014 And though one would be very glad to do a kindness by poor Mr. Ferrars, I do think it is not worth while to wait two or three months for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109312,\n            \"Sure you do not mean to persuade me that the Colonel only marries you for the sake of giving ten guineas to Mr. Ferrars!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 18]\": [\n        [\n            12776,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings had been anxious to see Colonel Brandon well married, ever since her connection with Sir John first brought him to her knowledge;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12840,\n            \"At the park she laughed at the colonel, and in the cottage at Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12856,\n            \"To the former her raillery was probably, as far as it regarded only himself, perfectly indifferent;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12885,\n            \"and when its object was understood, she hardly knew whether most to laugh at its absurdity, or censure its impertinence, for she considered it as an unfeeling reflection on the colonel\\u2019s advanced years, and on his forlorn condition as an old bachelor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12934,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, who could not think a man five years younger than herself, so exceedingly ancient as he appeared to the youthful fancy of her daughter, ventured to clear Mrs. Jennings from the probability of wishing to throw ridicule on his age.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12982,\n            \"\\u201cBut at least, Mama, you cannot deny the absurdity of the accusation, though you may not think it intentionally ill-natured.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13009,\n            \"Colonel Brandon is certainly younger than Mrs. Jennings, but he is old enough to be _ my _ father;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13082,\n            \"\\u201d said Elinor, \\u201cdo you call Colonel Brandon infirm?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13094,\n            \"I can easily suppose that his age may appear much greater to you than to my mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13112,\n            \"but you can hardly deceive yourself as to his having the use of his limbs!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13128,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDid not you hear him complain of the rheumatism?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35948,\n            \"She gave him a brief reply.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36186,\n            \"he was earnestly pressed by Mrs. Dashwood to stay longer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36467,\n            \"Disappointed, however, and vexed as she was, and sometimes displeased with his uncertain behaviour to herself, she was very well disposed on the whole to regard his actions with all the candid allowances and generous qualifications, which had been rather more painfully extorted from her, for Willoughby\\u2019s service, by her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36528,\n            \"His want of spirits, of openness, and of consistency, were most usually attributed to his want of independence, and his better knowledge of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s disposition and designs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36564,\n            \"The shortness of his visit, the steadiness of his purpose in leaving them, originated in the same fettered inclination, the same inevitable necessity of temporizing with his mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36617,\n            \"She would have been glad to know when these difficulties were to cease, this opposition was to yield, \\u2014 when Mrs. Ferrars would be reformed, and her son be at liberty to be happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36717,\n            \"\\u201cI think, Edward,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, as they were at breakfast the last morning, \\u201cyou would be a happier man if you had any profession to engage your time and give an interest to your plans and actions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36819,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do assure you,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cthat I have long thought on this point, as you think now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37143,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe consequence of which, I suppose, will be,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Dashwood, \\u201csince leisure has not promoted your own happiness, that your sons will be brought up to as many pursuits, employments, professions, and trades as Columella\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54062,\n            \"He is brother to Mrs. John Dashwood \\u2014 _ that _ must be recommendation enough to her husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54082,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut Mrs. John Dashwood would not much approve of Edward\\u2019s going into orders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54764,\n            \"and Elinor sat down to the card table with the melancholy persuasion that Edward was not only without affection for the person who was to be his wife;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96201,\n            \"that Mrs. Jennings (as she had of late often hoped might be the case) had ceased to imagine her at all attached to Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98208,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 She listened to her praise of Lucy with only moving from one chair to another, and when Mrs. Jennings talked of Edward\\u2019s affection, it cost her only a spasm in her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99123,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThen,\\u201dcried Mrs. Jennings with blunt sincerity, no longer able to be silent, \\u201che has acted like an honest man!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99152,\n            \"I beg your pardon, Mr. Dashwood, but if he had done otherwise, I should have thought him a rascal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99489,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry to say, ma\\u2019am, in a most unhappy rupture: \\u2014 Edward is dismissed for ever from his mother\\u2019s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100156,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings was very warm in her praise of Edward\\u2019s conduct, but only Elinor and Marianne understood its true merit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103474,\n            \"I am sure you will be glad to hear, as likewise dear Mrs. Jennings, I spent two happy hours with him yesterday afternoon, he would not hear of our parting, though earnestly did I, as I thought my duty required, urge him to it for prudence sake, and would have parted for ever on the spot, would he consent to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103598,\n            \"and should it ever be in your power to recommend him to any body that has a living to bestow, am very sure you will not forget us, and dear Mrs. Jennings too, trust she will speak a good word for us to Sir John, or Mr. Palmer, or any friend that may be able to assist us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107542,\n            \"He had met Mrs. Jennings at the door in her way to the carriage, as he came to leave his farewell card;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107567,\n            \"and she, after apologising for not returning herself, had obliged him to enter, by saying that Miss Dashwood was above, and wanted to speak with him on very particular business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107796,\n            \"\\u201cMrs. Jennings told me,\\u201dsaid he, \\u201cthat you wished to speak with me, at least I understood her so \\u2014 or I certainly should not have intruded on you in such a manner;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114610,\n            \"\\u2014 His behaviour to her in this, as well as in every other particular, his open pleasure in meeting her after an absence of only ten days, his readiness to converse with her, and his deference for her opinion, might very well justify Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s persuasion of his attachment, and would have been enough, perhaps, had not Elinor still, as from the first, believed Marianne his real favourite, to make her suspect it herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114737,\n            \"\\u2014 she watched his eyes, while Mrs. Jennings thought only of his behaviour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114753,\n            \"\\u2014 and while his looks of anxious solicitude on Marianne\\u2019s feeling, in her head and throat, the beginning of a heavy cold, because unexpressed by words, entirely escaped the latter lady\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115349,\n            \"and Mr. Palmer, though treating their apprehensions as idle, found the anxiety and importunity of his wife too great to be withstood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115826,\n            \"for to send the Colonel away while his love was in so much uneasiness on her sister\\u2019s account, would be to deprive them both, she thought, of every comfort;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115935,\n            \"especially as Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s entreaty was warmly seconded by Mr. Palmer, who seemed to feel a relief to himself, in leaving behind him a person so well able to assist or advise Miss Dashwood in any emergence.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 19]\": [\n        [\n            11963,\n            \"Marianne was vexed at it for her sister\\u2019s sake, and turned her eyes towards Elinor to see how she bore these attacks, with an earnestness which gave Elinor far more pain than could arise from such common-place raillery as Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13082,\n            \"\\u201d said Elinor, \\u201cdo you call Colonel Brandon infirm?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13094,\n            \"I can easily suppose that his age may appear much greater to you than to my mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13151,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dearest child,\\u201dsaid her mother, laughing, \\u201cat this rate you must be in continual terror of _ my _ decay;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13180,\n            \"and it must seem to you a miracle that my life has been extended to the advanced age of forty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13201,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMama, you are not doing me justice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13648,\n            \"\\u201d Soon after this, upon Elinor\\u2019s leaving the room, \\u201cMama,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cI have an alarm on the subject of illness which I cannot conceal from you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19283,\n            \"Neither Lady Middleton nor Mrs. Jennings could supply to her the conversation she missed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19299,\n            \"although the latter was an everlasting talker, and from the first had regarded her with a kindness which ensured her a large share of her discourse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19327,\n            \"She had already repeated her own history to Elinor three or four times;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19341,\n            \"and had Elinor\\u2019s memory been equal to her means of improvement, she might have known very early in their acquaintance all the particulars of Mr. Jennings\\u2019 s last illness, and what he said to his wife a few minutes before he died.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21608,\n            \"When Mrs. Jennings attacked her one evening at the park, to give the name of the young man who was Elinor\\u2019s particular favourite, which had been long a matter of great curiosity to her, Margaret answered by looking at her sister, and saying, \\u201cI must not tell, may I, Elinor?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21692,\n            \"She was convinced that Margaret had fixed on a person whose name she could not bear with composure to become a standing joke with Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23730,\n            \"it is about Miss Williams, I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23764,\n            \"I am sure you must have heard of her before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23808,\n            \"\\u201d Then, lowering her voice a little, she said to Elinor, \\u201cShe is his natural daughter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23848,\n            \"I dare say the Colonel will leave her all his fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24096,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings sat on Elinor\\u2019s right hand;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24223,\n            \"I hope you like your house, Miss Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24243,\n            \"and when I come to see you, I hope you will have new-furnished it, for it wanted it very much when I was there six years ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24289,\n            \"and Elinor found that in her resolution to know where they had been, she had actually made her own woman enquire of Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s groom;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24414,\n            \"and great was her surprise when she found that every circumstance related by Mrs. Jennings was perfectly true.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25253,\n            \"Perhaps it is about Miss Williams and, by the bye, I dare say it is, because he looked so conscious when I mentioned her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25289,\n            \"nothing in the world more likely, for I have a notion she is always rather sickly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25307,\n            \"I would lay any wager it is about Miss Williams.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25441,\n            \"Elinor, though she felt really interested in the welfare of Colonel Brandon, could not bestow all the wonder on his going so suddenly away, which Mrs. Jennings was desirous of her feeling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36412,\n            \"Elinor placed all that was astonishing in this way of acting to his mother\\u2019s account;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36467,\n            \"Disappointed, however, and vexed as she was, and sometimes displeased with his uncertain behaviour to herself, she was very well disposed on the whole to regard his actions with all the candid allowances and generous qualifications, which had been rather more painfully extorted from her, for Willoughby\\u2019s service, by her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36617,\n            \"She would have been glad to know when these difficulties were to cease, this opposition was to yield, \\u2014 when Mrs. Ferrars would be reformed, and her son be at liberty to be happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37397,\n            \"\\u201d This desponding turn of mind, though it could not be communicated to Mrs. Dashwood, gave additional pain to them all in the parting, which shortly took place, and left an uncomfortable impression on Elinor\\u2019s feelings especially, which required some trouble and time to subdue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37983,\n            \"Amongst them were Sir John and Lady Middleton and Mrs. Jennings, but there were two others, a gentleman and lady, who were quite unknown to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38242,\n            \"She came hallooing to the window, \\u201cHow do you do, my dear?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38289,\n            \"I have brought my other son and daughter to see you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38368,\n            \"perhaps it is Colonel Brandon come back again \\u2014\\u201dElinor was obliged to turn from her, in the middle of her story, to receive the rest of the party;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38923,\n            \"\\u201cYou may believe how glad we all were to see them,\\u201dadded Mrs. Jennings, leaning forward towards Elinor, and speaking in a low voice as if she meant to be heard by no one else, though they were seated on different sides of the room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38976,\n            \"\\u201cbut, however, I can\\u2019t help wishing they had not travelled quite so fast, nor made such a long journey of it, for they came all round by London upon account of some business, for you know (nodding significantly and pointing to her daughter) it was wrong in her situation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39036,\n            \"I wanted her to stay at home and rest this morning, but she would come with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39080,\n            \"\\u201cShe expects to be confined in February,\\u201dcontinued Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40898,\n            \"\\u201cOh, my dear Miss Dashwood,\\u201dsaid Mrs. Palmer soon afterwards, \\u201cI have got such a favour to ask of you and your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54764,\n            \"and Elinor sat down to the card table with the melancholy persuasion that Edward was not only without affection for the person who was to be his wife;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55943,\n            \"Whatever Marianne was desirous of, her mother would be eager to promote \\u2014 she could not expect to influence the latter to cautiousness of conduct in an affair respecting which she had never been able to inspire her with distrust;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56001,\n            \"That Marianne, fastidious as she was, thoroughly acquainted with Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 manners, and invariably disgusted by them, should overlook every inconvenience of that kind, should disregard whatever must be most wounding to her irritable feelings, in her pursuit of one object, was such a proof, so strong, so full, of the importance of that object to her, as Elinor, in spite of all that had passed, was not prepared to witness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56485,\n            \"though I think very well of Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s heart, she is not a woman whose society can afford us pleasure, or whose protection will give us consequence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56564,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf Elinor is frightened away by her dislike of Mrs. Jennings,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cat least it need not prevent MY accepting her invitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56654,\n            \"and resolved within herself, that if her sister persisted in going, she would go likewise, as she did not think it proper that Marianne should be left to the sole guidance of her own judgment, or that Mrs. Jennings should be abandoned to the mercy of Marianne for all the comfort of her domestic hours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57349,\n            \"Elinor could not find herself in the carriage with Mrs. Jennings, and beginning a journey to London under her protection, and as her guest, without wondering at her own situation, so short had their acquaintance with that lady been, so wholly unsuited were they in age and disposition, and so many had been her objections against such a measure only a few days before!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57775,\n            \"To atone for this conduct therefore, Elinor took immediate possession of the post of civility which she had assigned herself, behaved with the greatest attention to Mrs. Jennings, talked with her, laughed with her, and listened to her whenever she could;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58307,\n            \"It was a great satisfaction to Elinor that Mrs. Jennings, by being much engaged in her own room, could see little of what was passing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58839,\n            \"\\u201d This, and the manner in which it was said, immediately brought back to her remembrance all the circumstances of his quitting that place, with the uneasiness and suspicions they had caused to Mrs. Jennings, and she was fearful that her question had implied much more curiosity on the subject than she had ever felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59579,\n            \"\\u201d After an hour or two spent in what her mother called comfortable chat, or in other words, in every variety of inquiry concerning all their acquaintance on Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s side, and in laughter without cause on Mrs. Palmer\\u2019s, it was proposed by the latter that they should all accompany her to some shops where she had business that morning, to which Mrs. Jennings and Elinor readily consented, as having likewise some purchases to make themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60628,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, my dear, I\\u2019ll warrant you we do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61250,\n            \"\\u201d But Marianne seemed hardly to hear her, and on Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s entrance, escaped with the precious card.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61697,\n            \"but when the hour of appointment drew near, necessary as it was in common civility to Mrs. Jennings, that they should both attend her on such a visit, Elinor had some difficulty in persuading her sister to go, for still she had seen nothing of Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62375,\n            \"About the middle of the day, Mrs. Jennings went out by herself on business, and Elinor began her letter directly, while Marianne, too restless for employment, too anxious for conversation, walked from one window to the other, or sat down by the fire in melancholy meditation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62822,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBy many \\u2014 by some of whom you know nothing, by others with whom you are most intimate, Mrs. Jennings, Mrs. Palmer, and the Middletons.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65420,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s attention was then all employed, not in urging her, not in pitying her, nor in appearing to regard her, but in endeavouring to engage Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s notice entirely to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65528,\n            \"Elinor, who saw as plainly by this, as if she had seen the direction, that it must come from Willoughby, felt immediately such a sickness at heart as made her hardly able to hold up her head, and sat in such a general tremour as made her fear it impossible to escape Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65775,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, though never less disposed to speak than at that moment, obliged herself to answer such an attack as this, and, therefore, trying to smile, replied, \\u201cAnd have you really, Ma\\u2019am, talked yourself into a persuasion of my sister\\u2019s being engaged to Mr. Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66847,\n            \"In her earnest meditations on the contents of the letter, on the depravity of that mind which could dictate it, and probably, on the very different mind of a very different person, who had no other connection whatever with the affair than what her heart gave him with every thing that passed, Elinor forgot the immediate distress of her sister, forgot that she had three letters on her lap yet unread, and so entirely forgot how long she had been in the room, that when on hearing a carriage drive up to the door, she went to the window to see who could be coming so unreasonably early, she was all astonishment to perceive Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s chariot, which she knew had not been ordered till one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67026,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, with a thoroughly good-humoured concern for its cause, admitted the excuse most readily, and Elinor, after seeing her safe off, returned to Marianne, whom she found attempting to rise from the bed, and whom she reached just in time to prevent her from falling on the floor, faint and giddy from a long want of proper rest and food;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67157,\n            \"A glass of wine, which Elinor procured for her directly, made her more comfortable, and she was at last able to express some sense of her kindness, by saying, \\u201cPoor Elinor!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70160,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, pleased to have her governed for a moment by such a motive, though believing it hardly possible that she could sit out the dinner, said no more;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70315,\n            \"Elinor, who did justice to Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s kindness, though its effusions were often distressing, and sometimes almost ridiculous, made her those acknowledgments, and returned her those civilities, which her sister could not make or return for herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70453,\n            \"Had not Elinor, in the sad countenance of her sister, seen a check to all mirth, she could have been entertained by Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s endeavours to cure a disappointment in love, by a variety of sweetmeats and olives, and a good fire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70690,\n            \"\\u2014\\u201d\\u201cThe lady then \\u2014 Miss Grey I think you called her \\u2014 is very rich?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72390,\n            \"In the drawing-room, whither she then repaired, she was soon joined by Mrs. Jennings, with a wine-glass, full of something, in her hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72424,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear,\\u201dsaid she, entering, \\u201cI have just recollected that I have some of the finest old Constantia wine in the house that ever was tasted, so I have brought a glass of it for your sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72513,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDear Ma\\u2019am,\\u201dreplied Elinor, smiling at the difference of the complaints for which it was recommended, \\u201chow good you are!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72728,\n            \"for soon after his entrance, she walked across the room to the tea-table where Elinor presided, and whispered, \\u201cThe Colonel looks as grave as ever you see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80091,\n            \"_ and Mrs. Jennings had, for some time ceased to think at all of Mrs. Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81277,\n            \"After some opposition, Marianne yielded to her sister\\u2019s entreaties, and consented to go out with her and Mrs. Jennings one morning for half an hour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83940,\n            \"Having now said enough to make his poverty clear, and to do away the necessity of buying a pair of ear-rings for each of his sisters, in his next visit at Gray\\u2019s, his thoughts took a cheerfuller turn, and he began to congratulate Elinor on having such a friend as Mrs. Jennings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84842,\n            \"And Mrs. Jennings too, an exceedingly well-behaved woman, though not so elegant as her daughter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84967,\n            \"Mrs. John Dashwood had so much confidence in her husband\\u2019s judgment, that she waited the very next day both on Mrs. Jennings and her daughter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84998,\n            \"and her confidence was rewarded by finding even the former, even the woman with whom her sisters were staying, by no means unworthy her notice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85092,\n            \"The same manners, however, which recommended Mrs. John Dashwood to the good opinion of Lady Middleton did not suit the fancy of Mrs. Jennings, and to _ her _ she appeared nothing more than a little proud-looking woman of uncordial address, who met her husband\\u2019s sisters without any affection, and almost without having anything to say to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100124,\n            \"and as her vehemence made reserve impossible in Elinor, and unnecessary in Mrs. Jennings, they all joined in a very spirited critique upon the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100156,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings was very warm in her praise of Edward\\u2019s conduct, but only Elinor and Marianne understood its true merit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100590,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings and Elinor were of the number;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100637,\n            \"An intimate acquaintance of Mrs. Jennings joined them soon after they entered the Gardens, and Elinor was not sorry that by her continuing with them, and engaging all Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s conversation, she was herself left to quiet reflection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100716,\n            \"But at last she found herself with some surprise, accosted by Miss Steele, who, though looking rather shy, expressed great satisfaction in meeting them, and on receiving encouragement from the particular kindness of Mrs. Jennings, left her own party for a short time, to join their\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100773,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings immediately whispered to Elinor, \\u201cGet it all out of her, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100811,\n            \"\\u201d It was lucky, however, for Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s curiosity and Elinor\\u2019s too, that she would tell any thing _ without _ being asked;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102801,\n            \"and if anything should happen to take you and your sister away, and Mrs. Jennings should want company, I am sure we should be very glad to come and stay with her for as long a time as she likes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103474,\n            \"I am sure you will be glad to hear, as likewise dear Mrs. Jennings, I spent two happy hours with him yesterday afternoon, he would not hear of our parting, though earnestly did I, as I thought my duty required, urge him to it for prudence sake, and would have parted for ever on the spot, would he consent to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107205,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor did not quite understand the beginning of Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s speech, neither did she think it worth inquiring into;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109024,\n            \"\\u201cWell, my dear,\\u201dshe cried, \\u201cI sent you up the young man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109049,\n            \"\\u2014 And I suppose you had no great difficulty \\u2014 You did not find him very unwilling to accept your proposal?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109265,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy dear ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cwhat can you be thinking of?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109312,\n            \"Sure you do not mean to persuade me that the Colonel only marries you for the sake of giving ten guineas to Mr. Ferrars!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110033,\n            \"and Mrs. Jennings, though her carriage was always at Elinor\\u2019s service, so very much disliked Mrs. John Dashwood, that not even her curiosity to see how she looked after the late discovery, nor her strong desire to affront her by taking Edward\\u2019s part, could overcome her unwillingness to be in her company again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114610,\n            \"\\u2014 His behaviour to her in this, as well as in every other particular, his open pleasure in meeting her after an absence of only ten days, his readiness to converse with her, and his deference for her opinion, might very well justify Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s persuasion of his attachment, and would have been enough, perhaps, had not Elinor still, as from the first, believed Marianne his real favourite, to make her suspect it herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115186,\n            \"and when Marianne, after persisting in rising, confessed herself unable to sit up, and returned voluntarily to her bed, Elinor was very ready to adopt Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s advice, of sending for the Palmers\\u2019 apothecary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115295,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, who had been inclined from the first to think Marianne\\u2019s complaint more serious than Elinor, now looked very grave on Mr. Harris\\u2019 s report, and confirming Charlotte\\u2019s fears and caution, urged the necessity of her immediate removal with her infant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115467,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, however, with a kindness of heart which made Elinor really love her, declared her resolution of not stirring from Cleveland as long as Marianne remained ill, and of endeavouring, by her own attentive care, to supply to her the place of the mother she had taken her from;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115525,\n            \"and Elinor found her on every occasion a most willing and active helpmate, desirous to share in all her fatigues, and often by her better experience in nursing, of material use.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116491,\n            \"her maid, who was one of the principal nurses, was recreating herself in the housekeeper\\u2019s room, and Elinor remained alone with Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117557,\n            \"and though trying to speak comfort to Elinor, her conviction of her sister\\u2019s danger would not allow her to offer the comfort of hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129102,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood and Elinor then followed, and the others were left by themselves, to talk of the travellers, and feel their own dullness, till Mrs. Jennings was summoned to her chaise to take comfort in the gossip of her maid for the loss of her two young companions;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 15]\": [\n        [\n            41723,\n            \"but if he were ever so much there, I do not think Mr. Palmer would visit him, for he is in the opposition, you know, and besides it is such a way off.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 16]\": [\n        [\n            39148,\n            \"\\u201cNow, Palmer, you shall see a monstrous pretty girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39218,\n            \"Mr. Palmer looked up on her entering the room, stared at her some minutes, and then returned to his newspaper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39371,\n            \"He made her no answer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39777,\n            \"\\u201d said she, seating herself between Elinor and Marianne, \\u201cfor it is so bad a day I was afraid you might not come, which would be a shocking thing, as we go away again tomorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40558,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, you may abuse me as you please,\\u201dsaid the good-natured old lady, \\u201cyou have taken Charlotte off my hands, and cannot give her back again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41374,\n            \"\\u201d She surprised Elinor very much as they returned into the drawing-room, by asking her whether she did not like Mr. Palmer excessively.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116021,\n            \"It gave her no surprise that she saw nothing of Mrs. Palmer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116050,\n            \"Two days passed away from the time of Mr. Palmer\\u2019s departure, and her situation continued, with little variation, the same.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 18]\": [\n        [\n            115935,\n            \"especially as Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s entreaty was warmly seconded by Mr. Palmer, who seemed to feel a relief to himself, in leaving behind him a person so well able to assist or advise Miss Dashwood in any emergence.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 19]\": [\n        [\n            39064,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Palmer laughed, and said it would not do her any harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39777,\n            \"\\u201d said she, seating herself between Elinor and Marianne, \\u201cfor it is so bad a day I was afraid you might not come, which would be a shocking thing, as we go away again tomorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40704,\n            \"\\u201d said she, in a whisper, to Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40723,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was not inclined, after a little observation, to give him credit for being so genuinely and unaffectedly ill-natured or ill-bred as he wished to appear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40757,\n            \"His temper might perhaps be a little soured by finding, like many others of his sex, that through some unaccountable bias in favour of beauty, he was the husband of a very silly woman \\u2014 but she knew that this kind of blunder was too common for any sensible man to be lastingly hurt by it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            40817,\n            \"It was rather a wish of distinction, she believed, which produced his contemptuous treatment of every body, and his general abuse of every thing before him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41327,\n            \"you see how droll he is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41374,\n            \"\\u201d She surprised Elinor very much as they returned into the drawing-room, by asking her whether she did not like Mr. Palmer excessively.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41426,\n            \"I thought you would, he is so pleasant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41436,\n            \"and Mr. Palmer is excessively pleased with you and your sisters I can tell you, and you can\\u2019t think how disappointed he will be if you don\\u2019t come to Cleveland.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41723,\n            \"but if he were ever so much there, I do not think Mr. Palmer would visit him, for he is in the opposition, you know, and besides it is such a way off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42413,\n            \"for I think you both excessively pretty, and so does Mr. Palmer too I am sure, though we could not get him to own it last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42765,\n            \"Mr. Palmer is the kind of man I like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42810,\n            \"Elinor had hardly got their last visitors out of her head, had hardly done wondering at Charlotte\\u2019s being so happy without a cause, at Mr. Palmer\\u2019s acting so simply, with good abilities, and at the strange unsuitableness which often existed between husband and wife, before Sir John\\u2019s and Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s active zeal in the cause of society, procured her some other new acquaintance to see and observe.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[15, 16]\": [\n        [\n            15605,\n            \"\\u201d But Marianne could no more satisfy him as to the colour of Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s pointer, than he could describe to her the shades of his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16063,\n            \"You will be setting your cap at him now, and never think of poor Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16250,\n            \"Marianne\\u2019s preserver, as Margaret, with more elegance than precision, styled Willoughby, called at the cottage early the next morning to make his personal enquiries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16518,\n            \"But when this passed away, when her spirits became collected, when she saw that to the perfect good-breeding of the gentleman, he united frankness and vivacity, and above all, when she heard him declare, that of music and dancing he was passionately fond, she gave him such a look of approbation as secured the largest share of his discourse to herself for the rest of his stay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16662,\n            \"Encouraged by this to a further examination of his opinions, she proceeded to question him on the subject of books;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16779,\n            \"He acquiesced in all her decisions, caught all her enthusiasm;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16810,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Marianne,\\u201dsaid Elinor, as soon as he had left them, \\u201cfor _ one _ morning I think you have done pretty well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16841,\n            \"You have already ascertained Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s opinion in almost every matter of importance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16858,\n            \"You know what he thinks of Cowper and Scott;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16868,\n            \"you are certain of his estimating their beauties as he ought, and you have received every assurance of his admiring Pope no more than is proper.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16925,\n            \"Another meeting will suffice to explain his sentiments on picturesque beauty, and second marriages, and then you can have nothing farther to ask.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17082,\n            \"I should scold her myself, if she were capable of wishing to check the delight of your conversation with our new friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17147,\n            \"To enquire after Marianne was at first his excuse;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17157,\n            \"but the encouragement of his reception, to which every day gave greater kindness, made such an excuse unnecessary before it had ceased to be possible, by Marianne\\u2019s perfect recovery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17232,\n            \"He was exactly formed to engage Marianne\\u2019s heart, for with all this, he joined not only a captivating person, but a natural ardour of mind which was now roused and increased by the example of her own, and which recommended him to her affection beyond every thing else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17287,\n            \"His society became gradually her most exquisite enjoyment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17327,\n            \"In Mrs. Dashwood\\u2019s estimation he was as faultless as in Marianne\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17385,\n            \"In hastily forming and giving his opinion of other people, in sacrificing general politeness to the enjoyment of undivided attention where his heart was engaged, and in slighting too easily the forms of worldly propriety, he displayed a want of caution which Elinor could not approve, in spite of all that he and Marianne could say in its support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17486,\n            \"Willoughby was all that her fancy had delineated in that unhappy hour and in every brighter period, as capable of attaching her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17861,\n            \"Perhaps she pitied and esteemed him the more because he was slighted by Willoughby and Marianne, who, prejudiced against him for being neither lively nor young, seemed resolved to undervalue his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17947,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is exactly what I think of him,\\u201dcried Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18080,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut perhaps the abuse of such people as yourself and Marianne will make amends for the regard of Lady Middleton and her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18147,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy _ prot\\u00e9g\\u00e9 _, as you call him, is a sensible man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18240,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is to say,\\u201dcried Marianne contemptuously, \\u201che has told you, that in the East Indies the climate is hot, and the mosquitoes are troublesome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18336,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI may venture to say that _ his _ observations have stretched much further than _ your _ candour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18427,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAdd to which,\\u201dcried Marianne, \\u201cthat he has neither genius, taste, nor spirit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18467,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou decide on his imperfections so much in the mass,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cand so much on the strength of your own imagination, that the commendation _ I _ am able to give of him is comparatively cold and insipid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18609,\n            \"he threatened me with rain when I wanted it to be fine;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18622,\n            \"he has found fault with the hanging of my curricle, and I cannot persuade him to buy my brown mare.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18644,\n            \"If it will be any satisfaction to you, however, to be told, that I believe his character to be in other respects irreproachable, I am ready to confess it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18833,\n            \"and the ease and familiarity which naturally attended these parties were exactly calculated to give increasing intimacy to his acquaintance with the Dashwoods, to afford him opportunity of witnessing the excellencies of Marianne, of marking his animated admiration of her, and of receiving, in her behaviour to himself, the most pointed assurance of her affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19001,\n            \"When he was present she had no eyes for any one else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19030,\n            \"If their evenings at the park were concluded with cards, he cheated himself and all the rest of the party to get her a good hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19177,\n            \"Her heart was devoted to Willoughby, and the fond attachment to Norland, which she brought with her from Sussex, was more likely to be softened than she had thought it possible before, by the charms which his society bestowed on her present home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19638,\n            \"his attentions were wholly Marianne\\u2019s, and a far less agreeable man might have been more generally pleasing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20413,\n            \"Marianne told her, with the greatest delight, that Willoughby had given her a horse, one that he had bred himself on his estate in Somersetshire, and which was exactly calculated to carry a woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20527,\n            \"\\u201cHe intends to send his groom into Somersetshire immediately for it,\\u201dshe added, \\u201cand when it arrives we will ride every day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20555,\n            \"You shall share its use with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20704,\n            \"\\u201cYou are mistaken, Elinor,\\u201dsaid she warmly, \\u201cin supposing I know very little of Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20726,\n            \"I have not known him long indeed, but I am much better acquainted with him, than I am with any other creature in the world, except yourself and mama.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20801,\n            \"I should hold myself guilty of greater impropriety in accepting a horse from my brother, than from Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20929,\n            \"and she promised not to tempt her mother to such imprudent kindness by mentioning the offer, and to tell Willoughby when she saw him next, that it must be declined.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20969,\n            \"and when Willoughby called at the cottage, the same day, Elinor heard her express her disappointment to him in a low voice, on being obliged to forego the acceptance of his present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21038,\n            \"and after expressing it with earnestness, he added, in the same low voice, \\u2014 \\u201cBut, Marianne, the horse is still yours, though you cannot use it now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21073,\n            \"I shall keep it only till you can claim it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21114,\n            \"and in the whole of the sentence, in his manner of pronouncing it, and in his addressing her sister by her Christian name alone, she instantly saw an intimacy so decided, a meaning so direct, as marked a perfect agreement between them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21303,\n            \"I am sure she will be married to Mr. Willoughby very soon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21342,\n            \"and they had not known each other a week, I believe, before you were certain that Marianne wore his picture round her neck;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21392,\n            \"I am sure they will be married very soon, for he has got a lock of her hair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21463,\n            \"Last night after tea, when you and mama went out of the room, they were whispering and talking together as fast as could be, and he seemed to be begging something of her, and presently he took up her scissors and cut off a long lock of her hair, for it was all tumbled down her back;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            22089,\n            \"Willoughby opened the piano-forte, and asked Marianne to sit down to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23104,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor then heard Willoughby say, in a low voice to Marianne, \\u201cThere are some people who cannot bear a party of pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23775,\n            \"She is a relation of the Colonel\\u2019s, my dear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23941,\n            \"Willoughby\\u2019s was first, and Marianne never looked happier than when she got into it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24353,\n            \"Elinor could hardly believe this to be true, as it seemed very unlikely that Willoughby should propose, or Marianne consent, to enter the house while Mrs. Smith was in it, with whom Marianne had not the smallest acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24480,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, Marianne, but I would not go while Mrs. Smith was there, and with no other companion than Mr. Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24746,\n            \"They will one day be Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s, and \\u2014\\u201d\\u201cIf they were one day to be your own, Marianne, you would not be justified in what you have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24962,\n            \"I did not see it to advantage, for nothing could be more forlorn than the furniture, \\u2014 but if it were newly fitted up \\u2014 a couple of hundred pounds, Willoughby says, would make it one of the pleasantest summer-rooms in England.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25801,\n            \"and if no general engagement collected them at the park, the exercise which called him out in the morning was almost certain of ending there, where the rest of the day was spent by himself at the side of Marianne, and by his favourite pointer at her feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26352,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Dashwood looked with pleasure at Marianne, whose fine eyes were fixed so expressively on Willoughby, as plainly denoted how well she understood him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26515,\n            \"Then continuing his former tone, he said, \\u201cAnd yet this house you would spoil, Mrs. Dashwood?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26639,\n            \"\\u201cYou are a good woman,\\u201dhe warmly replied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26651,\n            \"\\u201cYour promise makes me easy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26671,\n            \"Tell me that not only your house will remain the same, but that I shall ever find you and yours as unchanged as your dwelling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26698,\n            \"and that you will always consider me with the kindness which has made everything belonging to you so dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26850,\n            \"and her mother, who concluded that a promise had been made by Willoughby the night before of calling on her while they were absent, was perfectly satisfied with her remaining at home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26979,\n            \"Surprised and alarmed they proceeded directly into the room she had just quitted, where they found only Willoughby, who was leaning against the mantel-piece with his back towards them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27013,\n            \"He turned round on their coming in, and his countenance showed that he strongly partook of the emotion which over-powered Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27309,\n            \"and with his eyes fixed on the ground he only replied, \\u201cYou are too good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27607,\n            \"Willoughby\\u2019s behaviour in taking leave of them, his embarrassment, and affectation of cheerfulness, and, above all, his unwillingness to accept her mother\\u2019s invitation, a backwardness so unlike a lover, so unlike himself, greatly disturbed her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27655,\n            \"One moment she feared that no serious design had ever been formed on his side;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27687,\n            \"\\u2014 the distress in which Marianne had quitted the room was such as a serious quarrel could most reasonably account for, though when she considered what Marianne\\u2019s love for him was, a quarrel seemed almost impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27802,\n            \"\\u201cOur dear Willoughby is now some miles from Barton, Elinor,\\u201dsaid she, as she sat down to work, \\u201cand with how heavy a heart does he travel?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28305,\n            \"You had rather look out for misery for Marianne, and guilt for poor Willoughby, than an apology for the latter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28672,\n            \"my dear child, do you accuse Willoughby and Marianne of concealment?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28767,\n            \"Has not his behaviour to Marianne and to all of us, for at least the last fortnight, declared that he loved and considered her as his future wife, and that he felt for us the attachment of the nearest relation?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29792,\n            \"The slightest mention of anything relative to Willoughby overpowered her in an instant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29806,\n            \"and though her family were most anxiously attentive to her comfort, it was impossible for them, if they spoke at all, to keep clear of every subject which her feelings connected with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29846,\n            \"Marianne would have thought herself very inexcusable had she been able to sleep at all the first night after parting from Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30032,\n            \"She played over every favourite song that she had been used to play to Willoughby, every air in which their voices had been oftenest joined, and sat at the instrument gazing on every line of music that he had written out for her, till her heart was so heavy that no farther sadness could be gained;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30386,\n            \"\\u201cWhy do you not ask Marianne at once,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwhether she is or she is not engaged to Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30644,\n            \"It was several days before Willoughby\\u2019s name was mentioned before Marianne by any of her family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30786,\n            \"but it gave Elinor pleasure, as it produced a reply from Marianne so expressive of confidence in Willoughby and knowledge of his intentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30811,\n            \"One morning, about a week after his leaving the country, Marianne was prevailed on to join her sisters in their usual walk, instead of wandering away by herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31197,\n            \"and Elinor, to screen Marianne from particularity, as she felt almost certain of its not being Willoughby, quickened her pace and kept up with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31269,\n            \"a third, almost as well known as Willoughby\\u2019s, joined them in begging her to stop, and she turned round with surprise to see and welcome Edward Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31536,\n            \"and it ended, as every feeling must end with her, by carrying back her thoughts to Willoughby, whose manners formed a contrast sufficiently striking to those of his brother elect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36104,\n            \"I am sure you will like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36132,\n            \"for had he not imagined it to be a joke for the good of her acquaintance in general, founded only on a something or a nothing between Mr. Willoughby and herself, he would not have ventured to mention it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41554,\n            \"and she was eager to gain from any one, such a confirmation of his merits as might remove the possibility of fear from Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61207,\n            \"\\u201d cried Marianne, \\u201che has been here while we were out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62001,\n            \"Marianne gave one glance round the apartment as she entered: it was enough \\u2014 _ he _ was not there \\u2014 and she sat down, equally ill-disposed to receive or communicate pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62198,\n            \"if a certain person who shall be nameless, had been there, you would not have been a bit tired: and to say the truth it was not very pretty of him not to give you the meeting when he was invited.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62251,\n            \"\\u201cSo my daughter Middleton told me, for it seems Sir John met him somewhere in the street this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62336,\n            \"and she was still more eagerly bent on this measure by perceiving after breakfast on the morrow, that Marianne was again writing to Willoughby, for she could not suppose it to be to any other person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62430,\n            \"Elinor was very earnest in her application to her mother, relating all that had passed, her suspicions of Willoughby\\u2019s inconstancy, urging her by every plea of duty and affection to demand from Marianne an account of her real situation with respect to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63122,\n            \"Yet as she was convinced that Marianne\\u2019s affection for Willoughby, could leave no hope of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s success, whatever the event of that affection might be, and at the same time wished to shield her conduct from censure, she thought it most prudent and kind, after some consideration, to say more than she really knew or believed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63275,\n            \"to Willoughby that he may endeavour to deserve her,\\u201d\\u2014 took leave, and went away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63725,\n            \"She soon caught his eye, and he immediately bowed, but without attempting to speak to her, or to approach Marianne, though he could not but see her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63821,\n            \"\\u201d she exclaimed, \\u201che is there \\u2014 he is there \\u2014 Oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63836,\n            \"why does he not look at me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63844,\n            \"why cannot I speak to him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63876,\n            \"Perhaps he has not observed you yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63942,\n            \"she started up, and pronouncing his name in a tone of affection, held out her hand to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64081,\n            \"Will you not shake hands with me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64089,\n            \"\\u201d He could not then avoid it, but her touch seemed painful to him, and he held her hand only for a moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64193,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut have you not received my notes?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64232,\n            \"Tell me, Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64265,\n            \"but as if, on catching the eye of the young lady with whom he had been previously talking, he felt the necessity of instant exertion, he recovered himself again, and after saying, \\u201cYes, I had the pleasure of receiving the information of your arrival in town, which you were so good as to send me,\\u201dturned hastily away with a slight bow and joined his friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64387,\n            \"\\u201cGo to him, Elinor,\\u201dshe cried, as soon as she could speak, \\u201cand force him to come to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64414,\n            \"Tell him I must see him again \\u2014 must speak to him instantly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64565,\n            \"In a short time Elinor saw Willoughby quit the room by the door towards the staircase, and telling Marianne that he was gone, urged the impossibility of speaking to him again that evening, as a fresh argument for her to be calm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65024,\n            \"But every circumstance that could embitter such an evil seemed uniting to heighten the misery of Marianne in a final separation from Willoughby \\u2014 in an immediate and irreconcilable rupture with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65592,\n            \"That good lady, however, saw only that Marianne had received a letter from Willoughby, which appeared to her a very good joke, and which she treated accordingly, by hoping, with a laugh, that she would find it to her liking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66089,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings laughed again, but Elinor had not spirits to say more, and eager at all events to know what Willoughby had written, hurried away to their room, where, on opening the door, she saw Marianne stretched on the bed, almost choked by grief, one letter in her hand, and two or three others lying by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66260,\n            \"Elinor, who knew that such grief, shocking as it was to witness it, must have its course, watched by her till this excess of suffering had somewhat spent itself, and then turning eagerly to Willoughby\\u2019s letter, read as follows: \\u201cBond Street, January.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66756,\n            \"but every perusal only served to increase her abhorrence of the man, and so bitter were her feelings against him, that she dared not trust herself to speak, lest she might wound Marianne still deeper by treating their disengagement, not as a loss to her of any possible good but as an escape from the worst and most irremediable of all evils, a connection, for life, with an unprincipled man, as a deliverance the most real, a blessing the most important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67527,\n            \"\\u201cNo, no, no,\\u201dcried Marianne wildly, \\u201che loves you, and only you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68438,\n            \"If your sentiments are no longer what they were, you will return my notes, and the lock of my hair which is in your possession.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68585,\n            \"\\u201cI felt myself,\\u201dshe added, \\u201cto be as solemnly engaged to him, as if the strictest legal covenant had bound us to each other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68657,\n            \"I know he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68662,\n            \"Whatever may have changed him now, (and nothing but the blackest art employed against me can have done it), I was once as dear to him as my own soul could wish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68699,\n            \"This lock of hair, which now he can so readily give up, was begged of me with the most earnest supplication.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68761,\n            \"When he told me that it might be many weeks before we met again \\u2014 his distress \\u2014 can I ever forget his distress?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68828,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDearest Marianne, who but himself?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68859,\n            \"I could rather believe every creature of my acquaintance leagued together to ruin me in his opinion, than believe his nature capable of such cruelty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68924,\n            \"Beyond you three, is there a creature in the world whom I would not rather suspect of evil than Willoughby, whose heart I know so well?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69192,\n            \"and Marianne, seated at the foot of the bed, with her head leaning against one of its posts, again took up Willoughby\\u2019s letter, and, after shuddering over every sentence, exclaimed, \\u2014 \\u201cIt is too much!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71763,\n            \"since, though Marianne might lose much, he could gain very little by the enforcement of the real truth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72664,\n            \"Colonel Brandon came in while the party were at tea, and by his manner of looking round the room for Marianne, Elinor immediately fancied that he neither expected nor wished to see her there, and, in short, that he was already aware of what occasioned her absence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73639,\n            \"Sometimes she could believe Willoughby to be as unfortunate and as innocent as herself, and at others, lost every consolation in the impossibility of acquitting him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74061,\n            \"In one moment her imagination placed before her a letter from Willoughby, full of tenderness and contrition, explanatory of all that had passed, satisfactory, convincing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74277,\n            \"Her mother, still confident of their engagement, and relying as warmly as ever on his constancy, had only been roused by Elinor\\u2019s application, to intreat from Marianne greater openness towards them both;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75451,\n            \"Hers, for me, was, I believe, fervent as the attachment of your sister to Mr. Willoughby and it was, though from a different cause, no less unfortunate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77940,\n            \"Eliza had confessed to me, though most reluctantly, the name of her lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78189,\n            \"Not that Marianne appeared to distrust the truth of any part of it, for she listened to it all with the most steady and submissive attention, made neither objection nor remark, attempted no vindication of Willoughby, and seemed to show by her tears that she felt it to be impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78585,\n            \"Against the interest of her own individual comfort, Mrs. Dashwood had determined that it would be better for Marianne to be any where, at that time, than at Barton, where every thing within her view would be bringing back the past in the strongest and most afflicting manner, by constantly placing Willoughby before her, such as she had always seen him there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78764,\n            \"From all danger of seeing Willoughby again, her mother considered her to be at least equally safe in town as in the country, since his acquaintance must now be dropped by all who called themselves her friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79064,\n            \"and Elinor, on the other hand, suspecting that it would not be in her power to avoid Edward entirely, comforted herself by thinking, that though their longer stay would therefore militate against her own happiness, it would be better for Marianne than an immediate return into Devonshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79488,\n            \"She could soon tell at what coachmaker\\u2019s the new carriage was building, by what painter Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s portrait was drawn, and at what warehouse Miss Grey\\u2019s clothes might be seen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91476,\n            \"Would either of them only have given her a full and minute account of the whole affair between Marianne and Mr. Willoughby, she would have thought herself amply rewarded for the sacrifice of the best place by the fire after dinner, which their arrival occasioned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120119,\n            \"for Marianne _ does _, she has _ long _ forgiven you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120148,\n            \"\\u201cThen she has forgiven me before she ought to have done it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120162,\n            \"But she shall forgive me again, and on more reasonable grounds.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121863,\n            \"My affection for Marianne, my thorough conviction of her attachment to me \\u2014 it was all insufficient to outweigh that dread of poverty, or get the better of those false ideas of the necessity of riches, which I was naturally inclined to feel, and expensive society had increased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122011,\n            \"To see Marianne, I felt, would be dreadful, and I even doubted whether I could see her again, and keep to my resolution.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122688,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhen the first of hers reached me (as it immediately did, for I was in town the whole time,) what I felt is \\u2014 in the common phrase, not to be expressed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122802,\n            \"\\u2014 what a reproof would she have given me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122913,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMarianne\\u2019s note, by assuring me that I was still as dear to her as in former days, \\u2014 that in spite of the many, many weeks we had been separated, she was as constant in her own feelings, and as full of faith in the constancy of mine as ever, \\u2014 awakened all my remorse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123150,\n            \"I sent no answer to Marianne, intending by that to preserve myself from her farther notice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123452,\n            \"The next morning brought another short note from Marianne \\u2014 still affectionate, open, artless, confiding \\u2014 everything that could make _ my _ conduct most hateful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123498,\n            \"But I thought of her, I believe, every moment of the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123600,\n            \"Marianne, beautiful as an angel on one side, calling me Willoughby in such a tone!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123622,\n            \"holding out her hand to me, asking me for an explanation, with those bewitching eyes fixed in such speaking solicitude on my face!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123693,\n            \"but not before I had seen Marianne\\u2019s sweet face as white as death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123709,\n            \"_ That _ was the last, last look I ever had of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123724,\n            \"the last manner in which she appeared to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123740,\n            \"yet when I thought of her to-day as really dying, it was a kind of comfort to me to imagine that I knew exactly how she would appear to those, who saw her last in this world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123782,\n            \"She was before me, constantly before me, as I travelled, in the same look and hue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124237,\n            \"And after all, what did it signify to my character in the opinion of Marianne and her friends, in what language my answer was couched?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124346,\n            \"\\u2019 Such were my reasonings, as, in a sort of desperate carelessness, I copied my wife\\u2019s words, and parted with the last relics of Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124565,\n            \"To treat her with unkindness, to speak of her slightingly is no atonement to Marianne \\u2014 nor can I suppose it a relief to your own conscience.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125764,\n            \"Marianne to be sure is lost to me for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126197,\n            \"The past, the present, the future, Willoughby\\u2019s visit, Marianne\\u2019s safety, and her mother\\u2019s expected arrival, threw her altogether into an agitation of spirits which kept off every indication of fatigue, and made her only fearful of betraying herself to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126801,\n            \"Then, remembering Colonel Brandon, reproved herself, felt that to _ his _ sufferings and _ his _ constancy far more than to his rival\\u2019s, the reward of her sister was due, and wished any thing rather than Mrs. Willoughby\\u2019s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126876,\n            \"for so great was her uneasiness about Marianne, that she had already determined to set out for Cleveland on that very day, without waiting for any further intelligence, and had so far settled her journey before his arrival, that the Careys were then expected every moment to fetch Margaret away, as her mother was unwilling to take her where there might be infection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127044,\n            \"Marianne was restored to her from a danger in which, as she now began to feel, her own mistaken judgment in encouraging the unfortunate attachment to Willoughby, had contributed to place her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127135,\n            \"Colonel Brandon loves Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127221,\n            \"And I believe Marianne will be the most happy with him of the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127348,\n            \"I saw that it equalled my own, and he perhaps, thinking that mere friendship, as the world now goes, would not justify so warm a sympathy \\u2014 or rather, not thinking at all, I suppose \\u2014 giving way to irresistible feelings, made me acquainted with his earnest, tender, constant, affection for Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127411,\n            \"He has loved her, my Elinor, ever since the first moment of seeing her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127471,\n            \"\\u201cHis regard for her, infinitely surpassing anything that Willoughby ever felt or feigned, as much more warm, as more sincere or constant \\u2014 which ever we are to call it \\u2014 has subsisted through all the knowledge of dear Marianne\\u2019s unhappy prepossession for that worthless young man!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127660,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHis character, however,\\u201danswered Elinor, \\u201cdoes not rest on _ one _ act of kindness, to which his affection for Marianne, were humanity out of the case, would have prompted him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127742,\n            \"and so highly do _ I _ value and esteem him, that if Marianne can be happy with him, I shall be as ready as yourself to think our connection the greatest blessing to us in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127939,\n            \"Marianne\\u2019s heart is not to be wasted for ever on such a man as Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127991,\n            \"He thinks Marianne\\u2019s affection too deeply rooted for any change in it under a great length of time, and even supposing her heart again free, is too diffident of himself to believe, that with such a difference of age and disposition he could ever attach her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128174,\n            \"but her mother, without waiting for her assent, continued, \\u201cAnd his manners, the Colonel\\u2019s manners are not only more pleasing to me than Willoughby\\u2019s ever were, but they are of a kind I well know to be more solidly attaching to Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128267,\n            \"I am very sure myself, that had Willoughby turned out as really amiable, as he has proved himself the contrary, Marianne would yet never have been so happy with _ him _ as she will be with Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128628,\n            \"His emotion on entering the room, in seeing her altered looks, and in receiving the pale hand which she immediately held out to him, was such, as, in Elinor\\u2019s conjecture, must arise from something more than his affection for Marianne, or the consciousness of its being known to others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128687,\n            \"and she soon discovered in his melancholy eye and varying complexion as he looked at her sister, the probable recurrence of many past scenes of misery to his mind, brought back by that resemblance between Marianne and Eliza already acknowledged, and now strengthened by the hollow eye, the sickly skin, the posture of reclining weakness, and the warm acknowledgment of peculiar obligation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128756,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, not less watchful of what passed than her daughter, but with a mind very differently influenced, and therefore watching to very different effect, saw nothing in the Colonel\\u2019s behaviour but what arose from the most simple and self-evident sensations, while in the actions and words of Marianne she persuaded herself to think that something more than gratitude already dawned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129025,\n            \"and Marianne, after taking so particular and lengthened a leave of Mrs. Jennings, one so earnestly grateful, so full of respect and kind wishes as seemed due to her own heart from a secret acknowledgment of past inattention, and bidding Colonel Brandon farewell with a cordiality of a friend, was carefully assisted by him into the carriage, of which he seemed anxious that she should engross at least half.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129441,\n            \"for no sooner had they entered their common sitting-room, than Marianne turned her eyes around it with a look of resolute firmness, as if determined at once to accustom herself to the sight of every object with which the remembrance of Willoughby could be connected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130004,\n            \"Her smile however changed to a sigh when she remembered that promise to Willoughby was yet unfulfilled, and feared she had that to communicate which might again unsettle the mind of Marianne, and ruin at least for a time this fair prospect of busy tranquillity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130345,\n            \"\\u201cAs for regret,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cI have done with that, as far as _ he _ is concerned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130651,\n            \"\\u201cI am not wishing him too much good,\\u201dsaid Marianne at last with a sigh, \\u201cwhen I wish his secret reflections may be no more unpleasant than my own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132012,\n            \"\\u2014 Nothing could restore him with a faith unbroken \\u2014 a character unblemished, to Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132214,\n            \"In the evening, when they were all three together, Marianne began voluntarily to speak of him again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132519,\n            \"\\u2014 Her conscience, her sensitive conscience, would have felt all that the conscience of her husband ought to have felt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134043,\n            \"so I took off my hat, and she knew me and called to me, and inquired after you, ma\\u2019am, and the young ladies, especially Miss Marianne, and bid me I should give her compliments and Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s, their best compliments and service, and how sorry they was they had not time to come on and see you, but they was in a great hurry to go forwards, for they was going further down for a little while, but howsever, when they come back, they\\u2019d make sure to come and see you.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[15, 18]\": [\n        [\n            17312,\n            \"and he read with all the sensibility and spirit which Edward had unfortunately wanted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17568,\n            \"and secretly to congratulate herself on having gained two such sons-in-law as Edward and Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31137,\n            \"The person is not tall enough for him, and has not his air.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31269,\n            \"a third, almost as well known as Willoughby\\u2019s, joined them in begging her to stop, and she turned round with surprise to see and welcome Edward Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31302,\n            \"He was the only person in the world who could at that moment be forgiven for not being Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31536,\n            \"and it ended, as every feeling must end with her, by carrying back her thoughts to Willoughby, whose manners formed a contrast sufficiently striking to those of his brother elect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36045,\n            \"I guess that Mr. Willoughby hunts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36104,\n            \"I am sure you will like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36132,\n            \"for had he not imagined it to be a joke for the good of her acquaintance in general, founded only on a something or a nothing between Mr. Willoughby and herself, he would not have ventured to mention it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36467,\n            \"Disappointed, however, and vexed as she was, and sometimes displeased with his uncertain behaviour to herself, she was very well disposed on the whole to regard his actions with all the candid allowances and generous qualifications, which had been rather more painfully extorted from her, for Willoughby\\u2019s service, by her mother.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[15, 19]\": [\n        [\n            15605,\n            \"\\u201d But Marianne could no more satisfy him as to the colour of Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s pointer, than he could describe to her the shades of his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16810,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Marianne,\\u201dsaid Elinor, as soon as he had left them, \\u201cfor _ one _ morning I think you have done pretty well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17082,\n            \"I should scold her myself, if she were capable of wishing to check the delight of your conversation with our new friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17344,\n            \"and Elinor saw nothing to censure in him but a propensity, in which he strongly resembled and peculiarly delighted her sister, of saying too much what he thought on every occasion, without attention to persons or circumstances.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17385,\n            \"In hastily forming and giving his opinion of other people, in sacrificing general politeness to the enjoyment of undivided attention where his heart was engaged, and in slighting too easily the forms of worldly propriety, he displayed a want of caution which Elinor could not approve, in spite of all that he and Marianne could say in its support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17666,\n            \"Elinor was obliged, though unwillingly, to believe that the sentiments which Mrs. Jennings had assigned him for her own satisfaction, were now actually excited by her sister;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17764,\n            \"and as she could not even wish him successful, she heartily wished him indifferent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17780,\n            \"She liked him \\u2014 in spite of his gravity and reserve, she beheld in him an object of interest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17830,\n            \"Sir John had dropped hints of past injuries and disappointments, which justified her belief of his being an unfortunate man, and she regarded him with respect and compassion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17861,\n            \"Perhaps she pitied and esteemed him the more because he was slighted by Willoughby and Marianne, who, prejudiced against him for being neither lively nor young, seemed resolved to undervalue his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17985,\n            \"He is highly esteemed by all the family at the park, and I never see him myself without taking pains to converse with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18011,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat he is patronised by _ you _,\\u201dreplied Willoughby, \\u201cis certainly in his favour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18147,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy _ prot\\u00e9g\\u00e9 _, as you call him, is a sensible man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18240,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is to say,\\u201dcried Marianne contemptuously, \\u201che has told you, that in the East Indies the climate is hot, and the mosquitoes are troublesome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18274,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe _ would _ have told me so, I doubt not, had I made any such inquiries, but they happened to be points on which I had been previously informed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18358,\n            \"But why should you dislike him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18365,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not dislike him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18373,\n            \"I consider him, on the contrary, as a very respectable man, who has every body\\u2019s good word, and nobody\\u2019s notice;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18467,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou decide on his imperfections so much in the mass,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cand so much on the strength of your own imagination, that the commendation _ I _ am able to give of him is comparatively cold and insipid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18514,\n            \"I can only pronounce him to be a sensible man, well-bred, well-informed, of gentle address, and, I believe, possessing an amiable heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19617,\n            \"Her admiration and regard, even her sisterly regard, was all his own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20413,\n            \"Marianne told her, with the greatest delight, that Willoughby had given her a horse, one that he had bred himself on his estate in Somersetshire, and which was exactly calculated to carry a woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20555,\n            \"You shall share its use with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20671,\n            \"Elinor then ventured to doubt the propriety of her receiving such a present from a man so little, or at least so lately known to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20704,\n            \"\\u201cYou are mistaken, Elinor,\\u201dsaid she warmly, \\u201cin supposing I know very little of Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20726,\n            \"I have not known him long indeed, but I am much better acquainted with him, than I am with any other creature in the world, except yourself and mama.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20969,\n            \"and when Willoughby called at the cottage, the same day, Elinor heard her express her disappointment to him in a low voice, on being obliged to forego the acceptance of his present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23104,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor then heard Willoughby say, in a low voice to Marianne, \\u201cThere are some people who cannot bear a party of pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23775,\n            \"She is a relation of the Colonel\\u2019s, my dear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23808,\n            \"\\u201d Then, lowering her voice a little, she said to Elinor, \\u201cShe is his natural daughter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23839,\n            \"and as like him as she can stare.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23848,\n            \"I dare say the Colonel will leave her all his fortune.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24353,\n            \"Elinor could hardly believe this to be true, as it seemed very unlikely that Willoughby should propose, or Marianne consent, to enter the house while Mrs. Smith was in it, with whom Marianne had not the smallest acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24480,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, Marianne, but I would not go while Mrs. Smith was there, and with no other companion than Mr. Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24845,\n            \"but Mr. Willoughby wanted particularly to show me the place;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25504,\n            \"It was engrossed by the extraordinary silence of her sister and Willoughby on the subject, which they must know to be peculiarly interesting to them all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26767,\n            \"\\u201cI do not ask you to come in the morning, for we must walk to the park, to call on Lady Middleton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27954,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt was not inclination that he wanted, Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28305,\n            \"You had rather look out for misery for Marianne, and guilt for poor Willoughby, than an apology for the latter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28328,\n            \"You are resolved to think him blameable, because he took leave of us with less affection than his usual behaviour has shown.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28426,\n            \"And, after all, what is it you suspect him of?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28578,\n            \"But you really do admit the justice of what I have said in his defence?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28594,\n            \"\\u2014 I am happy \\u2014 and he is acquitted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28672,\n            \"my dear child, do you accuse Willoughby and Marianne of concealment?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28965,\n            \"You must think wretchedly indeed of Willoughby, if, after all that has openly passed between them, you can doubt the nature of the terms on which they are together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29014,\n            \"Do you suppose him really indifferent to her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29032,\n            \"He must and does love her I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29042,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut with a strange kind of tenderness, if he can leave her with such indifference, such carelessness of the future, as you attribute to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29206,\n            \"It must be Willoughby therefore whom you suspect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29268,\n            \"and suspicion of his integrity cannot be more painful to yourself than to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30386,\n            \"\\u201cWhy do you not ask Marianne at once,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwhether she is or she is not engaged to Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30786,\n            \"but it gave Elinor pleasure, as it produced a reply from Marianne so expressive of confidence in Willoughby and knowledge of his intentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31197,\n            \"and Elinor, to screen Marianne from particularity, as she felt almost certain of its not being Willoughby, quickened her pace and kept up with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36467,\n            \"Disappointed, however, and vexed as she was, and sometimes displeased with his uncertain behaviour to herself, she was very well disposed on the whole to regard his actions with all the candid allowances and generous qualifications, which had been rather more painfully extorted from her, for Willoughby\\u2019s service, by her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41509,\n            \"She thought it probable that as they lived in the same county, Mrs. Palmer might be able to give some more particular account of Willoughby\\u2019s general character, than could be gathered from the Middletons\\u2019 partial acquaintance with him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41554,\n            \"and she was eager to gain from any one, such a confirmation of his merits as might remove the possibility of fear from Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41580,\n            \"She began by inquiring if they saw much of Mr. Willoughby at Cleveland, and whether they were intimately acquainted with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41723,\n            \"but if he were ever so much there, I do not think Mr. Palmer would visit him, for he is in the opposition, you know, and besides it is such a way off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41762,\n            \"I know why you inquire about him, very well;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41998,\n            \"and so we began talking of my brother and sister, and one thing and another, and I said to him, \\u2018 So, Colonel, there is a new family come to Barton cottage, I hear, and mama sends me word they are very pretty, and that one of them is going to be married to Mr. Willoughby of Combe Magna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42200,\n            \"and I think him uncommonly pleasing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42248,\n            \"I assure you it was a great compliment if he was, for he hardly ever falls in love with any body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42271,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIs Mr. Willoughby much known in your part of Somersetshire?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42297,\n            \"that is, I do not believe many people are acquainted with him, because Combe Magna is so far off;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42319,\n            \"but they all think him extremely agreeable I assure you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            42350,\n            \"She is a monstrous lucky girl to get him, upon my honour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45820,\n            \"and since Edward\\u2019s visit, they had never dined together without his drinking to her best affections with so much significancy and so many nods and winks, as to excite general attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45892,\n            \"The Miss Steeles, as she expected, had now all the benefit of these jokes, and in the eldest of them they raised a curiosity to know the name of the gentleman alluded to, which, though often impertinently expressed, was perfectly of a piece with her general inquisitiveness into the concerns of their family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46214,\n            \"The manner in which Miss Steele had spoken of Edward, increased her curiosity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46229,\n            \"for it struck her as being rather ill-natured, and suggested the suspicion of that lady\\u2019s knowing, or fancying herself to know something to his disadvantage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46261,\n            \"\\u2014 But her curiosity was unavailing, for no farther notice was taken of Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s name by Miss Steele when alluded to, or even openly mentioned by Sir John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61221,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, rejoiced to be assured of his being in London, now ventured to say, \\u201cDepend upon it, he will call again tomorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61311,\n            \"the expectation of seeing him every hour of the day, made her unfit for any thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61364,\n            \"but a moment\\u2019s glance at her sister when they returned was enough to inform her, that Willoughby had paid no second visit there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61697,\n            \"but when the hour of appointment drew near, necessary as it was in common civility to Mrs. Jennings, that they should both attend her on such a visit, Elinor had some difficulty in persuading her sister to go, for still she had seen nothing of Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62336,\n            \"and she was still more eagerly bent on this measure by perceiving after breakfast on the morrow, that Marianne was again writing to Willoughby, for she could not suppose it to be to any other person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62430,\n            \"Elinor was very earnest in her application to her mother, relating all that had passed, her suspicions of Willoughby\\u2019s inconstancy, urging her by every plea of duty and affection to demand from Marianne an account of her real situation with respect to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62856,\n            \"But still I might not have believed it, for where the mind is perhaps rather unwilling to be convinced, it will always find something to support its doubts, if I had not, when the servant let me in today, accidentally seen a letter in his hand, directed to Mr. Willoughby in your sister\\u2019s writing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63027,\n            \"\\u201d These words, which conveyed to Elinor a direct avowal of his love for her sister, affected her very much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63085,\n            \"The real state of things between Willoughby and her sister was so little known to herself, that in endeavouring to explain it, she might be as liable to say too much as too little.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63122,\n            \"Yet as she was convinced that Marianne\\u2019s affection for Willoughby, could leave no hope of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s success, whatever the event of that affection might be, and at the same time wished to shield her conduct from censure, she thought it most prudent and kind, after some consideration, to say more than she really knew or believed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63692,\n            \"They had not remained in this manner long, before Elinor perceived Willoughby, standing within a few yards of them, in earnest conversation with a very fashionable looking young woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63783,\n            \"At that moment she first perceived him, and her whole countenance glowing with sudden delight, she would have moved towards him instantly, had not her sister caught hold of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63942,\n            \"she started up, and pronouncing his name in a tone of affection, held out her hand to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64387,\n            \"\\u201cGo to him, Elinor,\\u201dshe cried, as soon as she could speak, \\u201cand force him to come to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64492,\n            \"\\u201d With difficulty however could she prevent her from following him herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64565,\n            \"In a short time Elinor saw Willoughby quit the room by the door towards the staircase, and telling Marianne that he was gone, urged the impossibility of speaking to him again that evening, as a fresh argument for her to be calm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64788,\n            \"That some kind of engagement had subsisted between Willoughby and Marianne she could not doubt, and that Willoughby was weary of it, seemed equally clear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64854,\n            \"Her indignation would have been still stronger than it was, had she not witnessed that embarrassment which seemed to speak a consciousness of his own misconduct, and prevented her from believing him so unprincipled as to have been sporting with the affections of her sister from the first, without any design that would bear investigation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65528,\n            \"Elinor, who saw as plainly by this, as if she had seen the direction, that it must come from Willoughby, felt immediately such a sickness at heart as made her hardly able to hold up her head, and sat in such a general tremour as made her fear it impossible to escape Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65775,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, though never less disposed to speak than at that moment, obliged herself to answer such an attack as this, and, therefore, trying to smile, replied, \\u201cAnd have you really, Ma\\u2019am, talked yourself into a persuasion of my sister\\u2019s being engaged to Mr. Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66089,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings laughed again, but Elinor had not spirits to say more, and eager at all events to know what Willoughby had written, hurried away to their room, where, on opening the door, she saw Marianne stretched on the bed, almost choked by grief, one letter in her hand, and two or three others lying by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66260,\n            \"Elinor, who knew that such grief, shocking as it was to witness it, must have its course, watched by her till this excess of suffering had somewhat spent itself, and then turning eagerly to Willoughby\\u2019s letter, read as follows: \\u201cBond Street, January.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67527,\n            \"\\u201cNo, no, no,\\u201dcried Marianne wildly, \\u201che loves you, and only you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68471,\n            \"\\u201d That such letters, so full of affection and confidence, could have been so answered, Elinor, for Willoughby\\u2019s sake, would have been unwilling to believe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68504,\n            \"But her condemnation of him did not blind her to the impropriety of their having been written at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68637,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe _ did _ feel the same, Elinor \\u2014 for weeks and weeks he felt it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68723,\n            \"Had you seen his look, his manner, had you heard his voice at that moment!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68886,\n            \"This woman of whom he writes \\u2014 whoever she be \\u2014 or any one, in short, but your own dear self, mama, and Edward, may have been so barbarous to bely me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69344,\n            \"\\u2014 Elinor, can he be justified?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71669,\n            \"I must do _ this _ justice to Mr. Willoughby \\u2014 he has broken no positive engagement with my sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71732,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, for her sister\\u2019s sake, could not press the subject farther, and she hoped it was not required of her for Willoughby\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72201,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAy, if we can do _ that _, Ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cwe shall do very well with or without Colonel Brandon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72664,\n            \"Colonel Brandon came in while the party were at tea, and by his manner of looking round the room for Marianne, Elinor immediately fancied that he neither expected nor wished to see her there, and, in short, that he was already aware of what occasioned her absence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72728,\n            \"for soon after his entrance, she walked across the room to the tea-table where Elinor presided, and whispered, \\u201cThe Colonel looks as grave as ever you see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72927,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou mean,\\u201danswered Elinor, with forced calmness, \\u201cMr. Willoughby\\u2019s marriage with Miss Grey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74277,\n            \"Her mother, still confident of their engagement, and relying as warmly as ever on his constancy, had only been roused by Elinor\\u2019s application, to intreat from Marianne greater openness towards them both;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77802,\n            \"\\u201cI have been more pained,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cby her endeavors to acquit him than by all the rest;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77862,\n            \"Have you,\\u201dshe continued, after a short silence, \\u201cever seen Mr. Willoughby since you left him at Barton?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78360,\n            \"his seduction and desertion of Miss Williams, the misery of that poor girl, and the doubt of what his designs might _ once _ have been on herself, preyed altogether so much on her spirits, that she could not bring herself to speak of what she felt even to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79064,\n            \"and Elinor, on the other hand, suspecting that it would not be in her power to avoid Edward entirely, comforted herself by thinking, that though their longer stay would therefore militate against her own happiness, it would be better for Marianne than an immediate return into Devonshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80111,\n            \"Early in February, within a fortnight from the receipt of Willoughby\\u2019s letter, Elinor had the painful office of informing her sister that he was married.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119277,\n            \"My business is with you, and only you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119428,\n            \"\\u201cPray be quick, sir,\\u201d\\u2014 said Elinor, impatiently;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119658,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor looked at him with greater astonishment than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120832,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou did then,\\u201dsaid Elinor, a little softened, \\u201cbelieve yourself at one time attached to her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121239,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI have,\\u201dreturned Elinor, colouring likewise, and hardening her heart anew against any compassion for him, \\u201cI have heard it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122624,\n            \"\\u201cWell, sir,\\u201dsaid Elinor, who, though pitying him, grew impatient for his departure, \\u201cand this is all?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122979,\n            \"I say awakened, because time and London, business and dissipation, had in some measure quieted it, and I had been growing a fine hardened villain, fancying myself indifferent to her, and chusing to fancy that she too must have become indifferent to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124469,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou are very wrong, Mr. Willoughby, very blamable,\\u201dsaid Elinor, while her voice, in spite of herself, betrayed her compassionate emotion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125490,\n            \"From a reverie of this kind she was recalled at the end of some minutes by Willoughby, who, rousing himself from a reverie at least equally painful, started up in preparation for going, and said \\u2014 \\u201cThere is no use in staying here;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125586,\n            \"She could not refuse to give him hers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125602,\n            \"\\u201cAnd you _ do _ think something better of me than you did?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125640,\n            \"Elinor assured him that she did;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125647,\n            \"\\u2014 that she forgave, pitied, wished him well \\u2014 was even interested in his happiness \\u2014 and added some gentle counsel as to the behaviour most likely to promote it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125717,\n            \"If, however, I am allowed to think that you and yours feel an interest in my fate and actions, it may be the means \\u2014 it may put me on my guard \\u2014 at least, it may be something to live for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125775,\n            \"Were I even by any blessed chance at liberty again \\u2014\\u201dElinor stopped him with a reproof.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125821,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWhat do you mean?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125868,\n            \"And if that some one should be the very he whom, of all others, I could least bear \\u2014 but I will not stay to rob myself of all your compassionate goodwill, by showing that where I have most injured I can least forgive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125941,\n            \"Elinor, for some time after he left her, for some time even after the sound of his carriage had died away, remained too much oppressed by a crowd of ideas, widely differing in themselves, but of which sadness was the general result, to think even of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125996,\n            \"Willoughby, he, whom only half an hour ago she had abhorred as the most worthless of men, Willoughby, in spite of all his faults, excited a degree of commiseration for the sufferings produced by them, which made her think of him as now separated for ever from her family, with a tenderness, a regret, rather in proportion, as she soon acknowledged within herself \\u2014 to his wishes than to his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126078,\n            \"She felt that his influence over her mind was heightened by circumstances which ought not in reason to have weight;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126140,\n            \"But she felt that it was so, long, long before she could feel his influence less.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126197,\n            \"The past, the present, the future, Willoughby\\u2019s visit, Marianne\\u2019s safety, and her mother\\u2019s expected arrival, threw her altogether into an agitation of spirits which kept off every indication of fatigue, and made her only fearful of betraying herself to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126252,\n            \"Short was the time, however, in which that fear could affect her, for within half an hour after Willoughby\\u2019s leaving the house, she was again called down stairs by the sound of another carriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126437,\n            \"and there, shedding tears of joy, though still unable to speak, embraced Elinor again and again, turning from her at intervals to press Colonel Brandon\\u2019s hand, with a look which spoke at once her gratitude, and her conviction of his sharing with herself in the bliss of the moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126801,\n            \"Then, remembering Colonel Brandon, reproved herself, felt that to _ his _ sufferings and _ his _ constancy far more than to his rival\\u2019s, the reward of her sister was due, and wished any thing rather than Mrs. Willoughby\\u2019s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126985,\n            \"Elinor could not hear the declaration, nor witness its proofs without sometimes wondering whether her mother ever recollected Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127188,\n            \"Had I sat down to wish for any possible good to my family, I should have fixed on Colonel Brandon\\u2019s marrying one of you as the object most desirable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127411,\n            \"He has loved her, my Elinor, ever since the first moment of seeing her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127428,\n            \"\\u201d Here, however, Elinor perceived, \\u2014 not the language, not the professions of Colonel Brandon, but the natural embellishments of her mother\\u2019s active fancy, which fashioned every thing delightful to her as it chose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127568,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cColonel Brandon\\u2019s character,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cas an excellent man, is well established.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127660,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHis character, however,\\u201danswered Elinor, \\u201cdoes not rest on _ one _ act of kindness, to which his affection for Marianne, were humanity out of the case, would have prompted him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128141,\n            \"There was always a something, if you remember, in Willoughby\\u2019s eyes at times, which I did not like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128174,\n            \"but her mother, without waiting for her assent, continued, \\u201cAnd his manners, the Colonel\\u2019s manners are not only more pleasing to me than Willoughby\\u2019s ever were, but they are of a kind I well know to be more solidly attaching to Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128479,\n            \"\\u201d Here they were interrupted by the entrance of a third person, and Elinor withdrew to think it all over in private, to wish success to her friend, and yet in wishing it, to feel a pang for Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128628,\n            \"His emotion on entering the room, in seeing her altered looks, and in receiving the pale hand which she immediately held out to him, was such, as, in Elinor\\u2019s conjecture, must arise from something more than his affection for Marianne, or the consciousness of its being known to others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131808,\n            \"and till they reached the door of the cottage, easily conjecturing what her curiosity must be though no question was suffered to speak it, talked of nothing but Willoughby, and their conversation together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132158,\n            \"Reflection had given calmness to her judgment, and sobered her own opinion of Willoughby\\u2019s deserts;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132177,\n            \"\\u2014 she wished, therefore, to declare only the simple truth, and lay open such facts as were really due to his character, without any embellishment of tenderness to lead the fancy astray.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132900,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThe whole of his behaviour,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cfrom the beginning to the end of the affair, has been grounded on selfishness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133001,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt present,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201che regrets what he has done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133277,\n            \"she, therefore, pursuing the first subject, immediately continued, \\u201c_ One _ observation may, I think, be fairly drawn from the whole of the story \\u2014 that all Willoughby\\u2019s difficulties have arisen from the first offence against virtue, in his behaviour to Eliza Williams.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[16, 17]\": [\n        [\n            87507,\n            \"\\u2014 She was already greatly displeased with Mrs. Ferrars;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96319,\n            \"What Mrs. Ferrars would say and do, though there could not be a doubt of its nature, she was anxious to hear;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[16, 18]\": [\n        [\n            4665,\n            \"This circumstance was a growing attachment between her eldest girl and the brother of Mrs. John Dashwood, a gentleman-like and pleasing young man, who was introduced to their acquaintance soon after his sister\\u2019s establishment at Norland, and who had since spent the greatest part of his time there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4792,\n            \"It was enough for her that he appeared to be amiable, that he loved her daughter, and that Elinor returned the partiality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5168,\n            \"She was first called to observe and approve him farther, by a reflection which Elinor chanced one day to make on the difference between him and his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5220,\n            \"\\u201cto say that he is unlike Fanny is enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6077,\n            \"\\u201cWhat a pity it is, Elinor,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cthat Edward should have no taste for drawing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6279,\n            \"Yet, though smiling within herself at the mistake, she honoured her sister for that blind partiality to Edward which produced it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6398,\n            \"At length she replied: \\u201cDo not be offended, Elinor, if my praise of him is not in every thing equal to your sense of his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6429,\n            \"I have not had so many opportunities of estimating the minuter propensities of his mind, his inclinations and tastes, as you have;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6997,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne here burst forth with indignation \\u2014 \\u201cEsteem him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7591,\n            \"She was far from depending on that result of his preference of her, which her mother and sister still considered as certain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7651,\n            \"But, whatever might really be its limits, it was enough, when perceived by his sister, to make her uneasy, and at the same time, (which was still more common,) to make her uncivil.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8002,\n            \"He seemed really anxious to accommodate them and the whole of his letter was written in so friendly a style as could not fail of giving pleasure to his cousin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12688,\n            \"She rather suspected it to be so, on the very first evening of their being together, from his listening so attentively while she sang to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12717,\n            \"and when the visit was returned by the Middletons\\u2019 dining at the cottage, the fact was ascertained by his listening to her again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12755,\n            \"It would be an excellent match, for _ he _ was rich, and _ she _ was handsome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            12840,\n            \"At the park she laughed at the colonel, and in the cottage at Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13557,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut he talked of flannel waistcoats,\\u201dsaid Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13601,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHad he been only in a violent fever, you would not have despised him half so much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13685,\n            \"I am sure Edward Ferrars is not well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13728,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHad you any idea of his coming so soon?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21957,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, then, he is lately dead, Marianne, for I am sure there was such a man once, and his name begins with an F.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28077,\n            \"I am persuaded that Mrs. Smith suspects his regard for Marianne, disapproves of it, (perhaps because she has other views for him,) and on that account is eager to get him away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28146,\n            \"He is, moreover, aware that she _ does _ disapprove the connection, he dares not therefore at present confess to her his engagement with Marianne, and he feels himself obliged, from his dependent situation, to give into her schemes, and absent himself from Devonshire for a while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31107,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 and was hastening to meet him, when Elinor cried out, \\u201cIndeed, Marianne, I think you are mistaken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31152,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe has, he has,\\u201dcried Marianne, \\u201cI am sure he has.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31180,\n            \"I knew how soon he would come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31269,\n            \"a third, almost as well known as Willoughby\\u2019s, joined them in begging her to stop, and she turned round with surprise to see and welcome Edward Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31334,\n            \"but she dispersed her tears to smile on _ him _, and in her sister\\u2019s happiness forgot for a time her own disappointment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31388,\n            \"He was welcomed by them all with great cordiality, but especially by Marianne, who showed more warmth of regard in her reception of him than even Elinor herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31419,\n            \"To Marianne, indeed, the meeting between Edward and her sister was but a continuation of that unaccountable coldness which she had often observed at Norland in their mutual behaviour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31526,\n            \"She began almost to feel a dislike of Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31536,\n            \"and it ended, as every feeling must end with her, by carrying back her thoughts to Willoughby, whose manners formed a contrast sufficiently striking to those of his brother elect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31570,\n            \"After a short silence which succeeded the first surprise and enquiries of meeting, Marianne asked Edward if he came directly from London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31608,\n            \"\\u201d she repeated, surprised at his being so long in the same county with Elinor without seeing her before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31865,\n            \"\\u2014 but rousing herself again, \\u201cNow, Edward,\\u201dsaid she, calling his attention to the prospect, \\u201chere is Barton valley.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32196,\n            \"His coldness and reserve mortified her severely;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32211,\n            \"but resolving to regulate her behaviour to him by the past rather than the present, she avoided every appearance of resentment or displeasure, and treated him as she thought he ought to be treated from the family connection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32621,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou have no ambition, I well know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32981,\n            \"\\u201d repeated Edward \\u2014 \\u201cbut why must you have hunters?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33225,\n            \"You, Miss Dashwood, would give a general commission for every new print of merit to be sent you \\u2014 and as for Marianne, I know her greatness of soul, there would not be music enough in London to content her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33273,\n            \"\\u2014 Thomson, Cowper, Scott \\u2014 she would buy them all over and over again: she would buy up every copy, I believe, to prevent their falling into unworthy hands;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33340,\n            \"But I was willing to show you that I had not forgot our old disputes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33356,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI love to be reminded of the past, Edward \\u2014 whether it be melancholy or gay, I love to recall it \\u2014 and you will never offend me by talking of former times.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33550,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMarianne is as steadfast as ever, you see,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cshe is not at all altered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33588,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNay, Edward,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201c_ you _ need not reproach me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33701,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe you are right,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cand yet I have always set her down as a lively girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34112,\n            \"\\u201cShe knows her own worth too well for false shame,\\u201dreplied Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34165,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut you would still be reserved,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cand that is worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34191,\n            \"Am I reserved, Marianne?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34431,\n            \"He joined her and Marianne in the breakfast-room the next morning before the others were down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34473,\n            \"But before she was half way upstairs she heard the parlour door open, and, turning round, was astonished to see Edward himself come out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34593,\n            \"This was a subject which ensured Marianne\\u2019s attention, and she was beginning to describe her own admiration of these scenes, and to question him more minutely on the objects that had particularly struck him, when Edward interrupted her by saying, \\u201cYou must not enquire too far, Marianne \\u2014 remember I have no knowledge in the picturesque, and I shall offend you by my ignorance and want of taste if we come to particulars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34723,\n            \"You must be satisfied with such admiration as I can honestly give.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34778,\n            \"It exactly answers my idea of a fine country, because it unites beauty with utility \\u2014 and I dare say it is a picturesque one too, because you admire it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35033,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am convinced,\\u201dsaid Edward, \\u201cthat you really feel all the delight in a fine prospect which you profess to feel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35174,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne looked with amazement at Edward, with compassion at her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35214,\n            \"She was sitting by Edward, and in taking his tea from Mrs. Dashwood, his hand passed so directly before her, as to make a ring, with a plait of hair in the centre, very conspicuous on one of his fingers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35261,\n            \"\\u201cI never saw you wear a ring before, Edward,\\u201dshe cried.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35305,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne spoke inconsiderately what she really felt \\u2014 but when she saw how much she had pained Edward, her own vexation at her want of thought could not be surpassed by his.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35908,\n            \"\\u201d This, and Marianne\\u2019s blushing, gave new suspicions to Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35963,\n            \"Edward saw enough to comprehend, not only the meaning of others, but such of Marianne\\u2019s expressions as had puzzled him before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35989,\n            \"and when their visitors left them, he went immediately round her, and said, in a whisper, \\u201cI have been guessing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36015,\n            \"Shall I tell you my guess?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36029,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cShall I tell you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36053,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne was surprised and confused, yet she could not help smiling at the quiet archness of his manner, and after a moment\\u2019s silence, said, \\u201cOh, Edward!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36104,\n            \"I am sure you will like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36112,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not doubt it,\\u201dreplied he, rather astonished at her earnestness and warmth;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36132,\n            \"for had he not imagined it to be a joke for the good of her acquaintance in general, founded only on a something or a nothing between Mr. Willoughby and herself, he would not have ventured to mention it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37451,\n            \"But as it was her determination to subdue it, and to prevent herself from appearing to suffer more than what all her family suffered on his going away, she did not adopt the method so judiciously employed by Marianne, on a similar occasion, to augment and fix her sorrow, by seeking silence, solitude and idleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50567,\n            \"And so well was she able to answer her own expectations, that when she joined them at dinner only two hours after she had first suffered the extinction of all her dearest hopes, no one would have supposed from the appearance of the sisters, that Elinor was mourning in secret over obstacles which must divide her for ever from the object of her love, and that Marianne was internally dwelling on the perfections of a man, of whose whole heart she felt thoroughly possessed, and whom she expected to see in every carriage which drove near their house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55852,\n            \"and Elinor, who now understood her sister, and saw to what indifference to almost every thing else she was carried by her eagerness to be with Willoughby again, made no farther direct opposition to the plan, and merely referred it to her mother\\u2019s decision, from whom however she scarcely expected to receive any support in her endeavour to prevent a visit, which she could not approve of for Marianne, and which on her own account she had particular reasons to avoid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57446,\n            \"and Elinor, in spite of every occasional doubt of Willoughby\\u2019s constancy, could not witness the rapture of delightful expectation which filled the whole soul and beamed in the eyes of Marianne, without feeling how blank was her own prospect, how cheerless her own state of mind in the comparison, and how gladly she would engage in the solicitude of Marianne\\u2019s situation to have the same animating object in view, the same possibility of hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57558,\n            \"Marianne\\u2019s eagerness to be gone declared her dependence on finding him there;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58336,\n            \"The tea things were brought in, and already had Marianne been disappointed more than once by a rap at a neighbouring door, when a loud one was suddenly heard which could not be mistaken for one at any other house, Elinor felt secure of its announcing Willoughby\\u2019s approach, and Marianne, starting up, moved towards the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58414,\n            \"she opened the door, advanced a few steps towards the stairs, and after listening half a minute, returned into the room in all the agitation which a conviction of having heard him would naturally produce;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58453,\n            \"in the ecstasy of her feelings at that instant she could not help exclaiming, \\u201cOh, Elinor, it is Willoughby, indeed it is!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58481,\n            \"\\u201d and seemed almost ready to throw herself into his arms, when Colonel Brandon appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59186,\n            \"I do not know what you and Mr. Willoughby will do between you about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60003,\n            \"\\u201cIf she had not known him to be in town she would not have written to him, as she did;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89983,\n            \"while Marianne was looking with the most speaking tenderness, sometimes at Edward and sometimes at Elinor, regretting only that their delight in each other should be checked by Lucy\\u2019s unwelcome presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90019,\n            \"Edward was the first to speak, and it was to notice Marianne\\u2019s altered looks, and express his fear of her not finding London agree with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90104,\n            \"\\u201d This remark was not calculated to make Edward or Elinor more easy, nor to conciliate the good will of Lucy, who looked up at Marianne with no very benignant expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90286,\n            \"But Marianne, who saw his agitation, and could easily trace it to whatever cause best pleased herself, was perfectly satisfied, and soon talked of something else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90979,\n            \"All that she could hope, was that Edward would not often expose her or himself to the distress of hearing Marianne\\u2019s mistaken warmth, nor to the repetition of any other part of the pain that had attended their recent meeting \\u2014 and this she had every reason to expect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96201,\n            \"that Mrs. Jennings (as she had of late often hoped might be the case) had ceased to imagine her at all attached to Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96291,\n            \"though she earnestly tried to drive away the notion of its being possible to end otherwise at last, than in the marriage of Edward and Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96357,\n            \"For _ him _ she felt much compassion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96417,\n            \"No time was to be lost in undeceiving her, in making her acquainted with the real truth, and in endeavouring to bring her to hear it talked of by others, without betraying that she felt any uneasiness for her sister, or any resentment against Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96476,\n            \"\\u2014 She was going to remove what she really believed to be her sister\\u2019s chief consolation, \\u2014 to give such particulars of Edward as she feared would ruin him for ever in her good opinion,-and to make Marianne, by a resemblance in their situations, which to _ her _ fancy would seem strong, feel all her own disappointment over again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96570,\n            \"She was very far from wishing to dwell on her own feelings, or to represent herself as suffering much, any otherwise than as the self-command she had practised since her first knowledge of Edward\\u2019s engagement, might suggest a hint of what was practicable to Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96690,\n            \"and all the comfort that could be given by assurances of her own composure of mind, and a very earnest vindication of Edward from every charge but of imprudence, was readily offered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96742,\n            \"and acknowledging as Elinor did, that she _ had _ loved him most sincerely, could she feel less than herself!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96944,\n            \"has he written to you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100156,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings was very warm in her praise of Edward\\u2019s conduct, but only Elinor and Marianne understood its true merit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100231,\n            \"and Marianne forgave all his offences in compassion for his punishment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100278,\n            \"Elinor avoided it upon principle, as tending to fix still more upon her thoughts, by the too warm, too positive assurances of Marianne, that belief of Edward\\u2019s continued affection for herself which she rather wished to do away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102975,\n            \"Edward\\u2019s marriage with Lucy was as firmly determined on, and the time of its taking place remained as absolutely uncertain, as she had concluded it would be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103007,\n            \"\\u2014 every thing depended, exactly after her expectation, on his getting that preferment, of which, at present, there seemed not the smallest chance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106079,\n            \"\\u201d By which the Colonel was surprised to find that _ she _ was considering Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s marriage as the certain consequence of the presentation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113297,\n            \"She had no such object for her lingering thoughts to fix on, she left no creature behind, from whom it would give her a moment\\u2019s regret to be divided for ever, she was pleased to be free herself from the persecution of Lucy\\u2019s friendship, she was grateful for bringing her sister away unseen by Willoughby since his marriage, and she looked forward with hope to what a few months of tranquility at Barton might do towards restoring Marianne\\u2019s peace of mind, and confirming her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114610,\n            \"\\u2014 His behaviour to her in this, as well as in every other particular, his open pleasure in meeting her after an absence of only ten days, his readiness to converse with her, and his deference for her opinion, might very well justify Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s persuasion of his attachment, and would have been enough, perhaps, had not Elinor still, as from the first, believed Marianne his real favourite, to make her suspect it herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114753,\n            \"\\u2014 and while his looks of anxious solicitude on Marianne\\u2019s feeling, in her head and throat, the beginning of a heavy cold, because unexpressed by words, entirely escaped the latter lady\\u2019s observation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115097,\n            \"and when, at last, she went early to bed, more and more indisposed, Colonel Brandon was only astonished at her sister\\u2019s composure, who, though attending and nursing her the whole day, against Marianne\\u2019s inclination, and forcing proper medicines on her at night, trusted, like Marianne, to the certainty and efficacy of sleep, and felt no real alarm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136096,\n            \"\\u2014 but her mother and Marianne both turned their eyes on him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140753,\n            \"I cannot get him out of my head, but you must send for him to Barton, and Miss Marianne must try to comfort him.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[16, 19]\": [\n        [\n            1654,\n            \"Elinor saw, with concern, the excess of her sister\\u2019s sensibility;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1765,\n            \"She could consult with her brother, could receive her sister-in-law on her arrival, and treat her with proper attention;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4792,\n            \"It was enough for her that he appeared to be amiable, that he loved her daughter, and that Elinor returned the partiality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5168,\n            \"She was first called to observe and approve him farther, by a reflection which Elinor chanced one day to make on the difference between him and his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5438,\n            \"\\u201cIn a few months, my dear Marianne,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cElinor will, in all probability be settled for life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5555,\n            \"do you disapprove your sister\\u2019s choice?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6057,\n            \"In one circumstance only, my Marianne, may your destiny be different from hers!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6077,\n            \"\\u201cWhat a pity it is, Elinor,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cthat Edward should have no taste for drawing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6279,\n            \"Yet, though smiling within herself at the mistake, she honoured her sister for that blind partiality to Edward which produced it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6373,\n            \"She would not wound the feelings of her sister on any account, and yet to say what she did not believe was impossible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6398,\n            \"At length she replied: \\u201cDo not be offended, Elinor, if my praise of him is not in every thing equal to your sense of his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6521,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne was rejoiced to find her sister so easily pleased.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6918,\n            \"She knew that what Marianne and her mother conjectured one moment, they believed the next \\u2014 that with them, to wish was to hope, and to hope was to expect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6952,\n            \"She tried to explain the real state of the case to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7415,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor had given her real opinion to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7591,\n            \"She was far from depending on that result of his preference of her, which her mother and sister still considered as certain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7651,\n            \"But, whatever might really be its limits, it was enough, when perceived by his sister, to make her uneasy, and at the same time, (which was still more common,) to make her uncivil.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7773,\n            \"She gave her an answer which marked her contempt, and instantly left the room, resolving that, whatever might be the inconvenience or expense of so sudden a removal, her beloved Elinor should not be exposed another week to such insinuations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            11963,\n            \"Marianne was vexed at it for her sister\\u2019s sake, and turned her eyes towards Elinor to see how she bore these attacks, with an earnestness which gave Elinor far more pain than could arise from such common-place raillery as Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13648,\n            \"\\u201d Soon after this, upon Elinor\\u2019s leaving the room, \\u201cMama,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cI have an alarm on the subject of illness which I cannot conceal from you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13820,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI rather think you are mistaken, for when I was talking to her yesterday of getting a new grate for the spare bedchamber, she observed that there was no immediate hurry for it, as it was not likely that the room would be wanted for some time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15605,\n            \"\\u201d But Marianne could no more satisfy him as to the colour of Mr. Willoughby\\u2019s pointer, than he could describe to her the shades of his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16810,\n            \"\\u201cWell, Marianne,\\u201dsaid Elinor, as soon as he had left them, \\u201cfor _ one _ morning I think you have done pretty well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16951,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cElinor,\\u201dcried Marianne, \\u201cis this fair?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            16974,\n            \"But I see what you mean.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17057,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy love,\\u201dsaid her mother, \\u201cyou must not be offended with Elinor \\u2014 she was only in jest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17082,\n            \"I should scold her myself, if she were capable of wishing to check the delight of your conversation with our new friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17385,\n            \"In hastily forming and giving his opinion of other people, in sacrificing general politeness to the enjoyment of undivided attention where his heart was engaged, and in slighting too easily the forms of worldly propriety, he displayed a want of caution which Elinor could not approve, in spite of all that he and Marianne could say in its support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17861,\n            \"Perhaps she pitied and esteemed him the more because he was slighted by Willoughby and Marianne, who, prejudiced against him for being neither lively nor young, seemed resolved to undervalue his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18147,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy _ prot\\u00e9g\\u00e9 _, as you call him, is a sensible man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18240,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat is to say,\\u201dcried Marianne contemptuously, \\u201che has told you, that in the East Indies the climate is hot, and the mosquitoes are troublesome.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            18467,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou decide on his imperfections so much in the mass,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cand so much on the strength of your own imagination, that the commendation _ I _ am able to give of him is comparatively cold and insipid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19659,\n            \"Colonel Brandon, unfortunately for himself, had no such encouragement to think only of Marianne, and in conversing with Elinor he found the greatest consolation for the indifference of her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19754,\n            \"His eyes were fixed on Marianne, and, after a silence of some minutes, he said, with a faint smile, \\u201cYour sister, I understand, does not approve of second attachments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19792,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cher opinions are all romantic.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19807,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOr rather, as I believe, she considers them impossible to exist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19823,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe she does.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            19830,\n            \"But how she contrives it without reflecting on the character of her own father, who had himself two wives, I know not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20321,\n            \"But Marianne, in her place, would not have done so little.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20364,\n            \"As Elinor and Marianne were walking together the next morning the latter communicated a piece of news to her sister, which in spite of all that she knew before of Marianne\\u2019s imprudence and want of thought, surprised her by its extravagant testimony of both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20413,\n            \"Marianne told her, with the greatest delight, that Willoughby had given her a horse, one that he had bred himself on his estate in Somersetshire, and which was exactly calculated to carry a woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20452,\n            \"Without considering that it was not in her mother\\u2019s plan to keep any horse, that if she were to alter her resolution in favour of this gift, she must buy another for the servant, and keep a servant to ride it, and after all, build a stable to receive them, she had accepted the present without hesitation, and told her sister of it in raptures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20555,\n            \"You shall share its use with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20704,\n            \"\\u201cYou are mistaken, Elinor,\\u201dsaid she warmly, \\u201cin supposing I know very little of Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20726,\n            \"I have not known him long indeed, but I am much better acquainted with him, than I am with any other creature in the world, except yourself and mama.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20866,\n            \"Opposition on so tender a subject would only attach her the more to her own opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            20969,\n            \"and when Willoughby called at the cottage, the same day, Elinor heard her express her disappointment to him in a low voice, on being obliged to forego the acceptance of his present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21228,\n            \"Willoughby had spent the preceding evening with them, and Margaret, by being left some time in the parlour with only him and Marianne, had had opportunity for observations, which, with a most important face, she communicated to her eldest sister, when they were next by themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21287,\n            \"\\u201d she cried, \\u201cI have such a secret to tell you about Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21434,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut, indeed, Elinor, it is Marianne\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21720,\n            \"Marianne felt for her most sincerely;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23104,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor then heard Willoughby say, in a low voice to Marianne, \\u201cThere are some people who cannot bear a party of pleasure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23755,\n            \"do not you know who Miss Williams is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23764,\n            \"I am sure you must have heard of her before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            23775,\n            \"She is a relation of the Colonel\\u2019s, my dear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24107,\n            \"and they had not been long seated, before she leant behind her and Willoughby, and said to Marianne, loud enough for them both to hear, \\u201cI have found you out in spite of all your tricks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24223,\n            \"I hope you like your house, Miss Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24353,\n            \"Elinor could hardly believe this to be true, as it seemed very unlikely that Willoughby should propose, or Marianne consent, to enter the house while Mrs. Smith was in it, with whom Marianne had not the smallest acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24397,\n            \"As soon as they left the dining-room, Elinor enquired of her about it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24434,\n            \"Marianne was quite angry with her for doubting it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24480,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, Marianne, but I would not go while Mrs. Smith was there, and with no other companion than Mr. Willoughby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24800,\n            \"and after a ten minutes\\u2019 interval of earnest thought, she came to her sister again, and said with great good humour, \\u201cPerhaps, Elinor, it _ was _ rather ill-judged in me to go to Allenham;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            24857,\n            \"and it is a charming house, I assure you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25011,\n            \"\\u201d Could Elinor have listened to her without interruption from the others, she would have described every room in the house with equal delight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            25682,\n            \"and it was so wholly contradictory to their general opinions and practice, that a doubt sometimes entered her mind of their being really engaged, and this doubt was enough to prevent her making any inquiry of Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28305,\n            \"You had rather look out for misery for Marianne, and guilt for poor Willoughby, than an apology for the latter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28672,\n            \"my dear child, do you accuse Willoughby and Marianne of concealment?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30386,\n            \"\\u201cWhy do you not ask Marianne at once,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cwhether she is or she is not engaged to Willoughby?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30446,\n            \"She used to be all unreserve, and to you more especially.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30786,\n            \"but it gave Elinor pleasure, as it produced a reply from Marianne so expressive of confidence in Willoughby and knowledge of his intentions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30899,\n            \"But at length she was secured by the exertions of Elinor, who greatly disapproved such continual seclusion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30918,\n            \"They walked along the road through the valley, and chiefly in silence, for Marianne\\u2019s _ mind _ could not be controlled, and Elinor, satisfied with gaining one point, would not then attempt more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31107,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 and was hastening to meet him, when Elinor cried out, \\u201cIndeed, Marianne, I think you are mistaken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31197,\n            \"and Elinor, to screen Marianne from particularity, as she felt almost certain of its not being Willoughby, quickened her pace and kept up with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31388,\n            \"He was welcomed by them all with great cordiality, but especially by Marianne, who showed more warmth of regard in her reception of him than even Elinor herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31608,\n            \"\\u201d she repeated, surprised at his being so long in the same county with Elinor without seeing her before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31805,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt is not every one,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cwho has your passion for dead leaves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33550,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMarianne is as steadfast as ever, you see,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cshe is not at all altered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33643,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNor do I think it a part of Marianne\\u2019s,\\u201dsaid Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33701,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe you are right,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cand yet I have always set her down as a lively girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33819,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut I thought it was right, Elinor,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cto be guided wholly by the opinion of other people.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33986,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cQuite the contrary,\\u201dreplied Elinor, looking expressively at Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34095,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMarianne has not shyness to excuse any inattention of hers,\\u201dsaid Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34431,\n            \"He joined her and Marianne in the breakfast-room the next morning before the others were down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34473,\n            \"But before she was half way upstairs she heard the parlour door open, and, turning round, was astonished to see Edward himself come out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35033,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am convinced,\\u201dsaid Edward, \\u201cthat you really feel all the delight in a fine prospect which you profess to feel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35391,\n            \"That the hair was her own, she instantaneously felt as well satisfied as Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35407,\n            \"the only difference in their conclusions was, that what Marianne considered as a free gift from her sister, Elinor was conscious must have been procured by some theft or contrivance unknown to herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37451,\n            \"But as it was her determination to subdue it, and to prevent herself from appearing to suffer more than what all her family suffered on his going away, she did not adopt the method so judiciously employed by Marianne, on a similar occasion, to augment and fix her sorrow, by seeking silence, solitude and idleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            39777,\n            \"\\u201d said she, seating herself between Elinor and Marianne, \\u201cfor it is so bad a day I was afraid you might not come, which would be a shocking thing, as we go away again tomorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41374,\n            \"\\u201d She surprised Elinor very much as they returned into the drawing-room, by asking her whether she did not like Mr. Palmer excessively.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            41554,\n            \"and she was eager to gain from any one, such a confirmation of his merits as might remove the possibility of fear from Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43964,\n            \"It suggested no other surprise than that Elinor and Marianne should sit so composedly by, without claiming a share in what was passing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45770,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor could not suppose that Sir John would be more nice in proclaiming his suspicions of her regard for Edward, than he had been with respect to Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46356,\n            \"and to the invariable coldness of her behaviour towards them, which checked every endeavour at intimacy on their side, Elinor principally attributed that preference of herself which soon became evident in the manners of both, but especially of Lucy, who missed no opportunity of engaging her in conversation, or of striving to improve their acquaintance by an easy and frank communication of her sentiments.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50567,\n            \"And so well was she able to answer her own expectations, that when she joined them at dinner only two hours after she had first suffered the extinction of all her dearest hopes, no one would have supposed from the appearance of the sisters, that Elinor was mourning in secret over obstacles which must divide her for ever from the object of her love, and that Marianne was internally dwelling on the perfections of a man, of whose whole heart she felt thoroughly possessed, and whom she expected to see in every carriage which drove near their house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50672,\n            \"The necessity of concealing from her mother and Marianne, what had been entrusted in confidence to herself, though it obliged her to unceasing exertion, was no aggravation of Elinor\\u2019s distress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52121,\n            \"\\u201cMarianne can never keep long from that instrument you know, ma\\u2019am,\\u201dsaid Elinor, endeavouring to smooth away the offence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52389,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor joyfully profited by the first of these proposals, and thus by a little of that address which Marianne could never condescend to practise, gained her own end, and pleased Lady Middleton at the same time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55170,\n            \"Elinor, without observing the varying complexion of her sister, and the animated look which spoke no indifference to the plan, immediately gave a grateful but absolute denial for both, in which she believed herself to be speaking their united inclinations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55852,\n            \"and Elinor, who now understood her sister, and saw to what indifference to almost every thing else she was carried by her eagerness to be with Willoughby again, made no farther direct opposition to the plan, and merely referred it to her mother\\u2019s decision, from whom however she scarcely expected to receive any support in her endeavour to prevent a visit, which she could not approve of for Marianne, and which on her own account she had particular reasons to avoid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55943,\n            \"Whatever Marianne was desirous of, her mother would be eager to promote \\u2014 she could not expect to influence the latter to cautiousness of conduct in an affair respecting which she had never been able to inspire her with distrust;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56001,\n            \"That Marianne, fastidious as she was, thoroughly acquainted with Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 manners, and invariably disgusted by them, should overlook every inconvenience of that kind, should disregard whatever must be most wounding to her irritable feelings, in her pursuit of one object, was such a proof, so strong, so full, of the importance of that object to her, as Elinor, in spite of all that had passed, was not prepared to witness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56380,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThough with your usual anxiety for our happiness,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cyou have been obviating every impediment to the present scheme which occurred to you, there is still one objection which, in my opinion, cannot be so easily removed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56564,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf Elinor is frightened away by her dislike of Mrs. Jennings,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cat least it need not prevent MY accepting her invitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56620,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor could not help smiling at this display of indifference towards the manners of a person, to whom she had often had difficulty in persuading Marianne to behave with tolerable politeness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56654,\n            \"and resolved within herself, that if her sister persisted in going, she would go likewise, as she did not think it proper that Marianne should be left to the sole guidance of her own judgment, or that Mrs. Jennings should be abandoned to the mercy of Marianne for all the comfort of her domestic hours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56964,\n            \"Marianne lifted up her eyes in astonishment, and Elinor conjectured that she might as well have held her tongue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57135,\n            \"With regard to herself, it was now a matter of unconcern whether she went to town or not, and when she saw her mother so thoroughly pleased with the plan, and her sister exhilarated by it in look, voice, and manner, restored to all her usual animation, and elevated to more than her usual gaiety, she could not be dissatisfied with the cause, and would hardly allow herself to distrust the consequence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57446,\n            \"and Elinor, in spite of every occasional doubt of Willoughby\\u2019s constancy, could not witness the rapture of delightful expectation which filled the whole soul and beamed in the eyes of Marianne, without feeling how blank was her own prospect, how cheerless her own state of mind in the comparison, and how gladly she would engage in the solicitude of Marianne\\u2019s situation to have the same animating object in view, the same possibility of hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57656,\n            \"should it be otherwise, her exertions would be of a different nature \\u2014 she must then learn to avoid every selfish comparison, and banish every regret which might lessen her satisfaction in the happiness of Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57731,\n            \"She sat in silence almost all the way, wrapt in her own meditations, and scarcely ever voluntarily speaking, except when any object of picturesque beauty within their view drew from her an exclamation of delight exclusively addressed to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58035,\n            \"\\u201c_ I _ am writing home, Marianne,\\u201dsaid Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58336,\n            \"The tea things were brought in, and already had Marianne been disappointed more than once by a rap at a neighbouring door, when a loud one was suddenly heard which could not be mistaken for one at any other house, Elinor felt secure of its announcing Willoughby\\u2019s approach, and Marianne, starting up, moved towards the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58453,\n            \"in the ecstasy of her feelings at that instant she could not help exclaiming, \\u201cOh, Elinor, it is Willoughby, indeed it is!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58565,\n            \"She instantly saw that it was not unnoticed by him, that he even observed Marianne as she quitted the room, with such astonishment and concern, as hardly left him the recollection of what civility demanded towards herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59325,\n            \"Elinor now began to make the tea, and Marianne was obliged to appear again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59849,\n            \"and no sooner had they entered the house than Marianne flew eagerly up stairs, and when Elinor followed, she found her turning from the table with a sorrowful countenance, which declared that no Willoughby had been there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59991,\n            \"\\u201d repeated Elinor within herself, regarding her sister with uneasiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60224,\n            \"but though her time was therefore at her own disposal, the evening was by no means more productive of pleasure to her than to Elinor, for it was spent in all the anxiety of expectation and the pain of disappointment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60578,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAt any rate,\\u201dsaid Elinor, wishing to prevent Mrs. Jennings from seeing her sister\\u2019s thoughts as clearly as she did, \\u201cI dare say we shall have Sir John and Lady Middleton in town by the end of next week.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60701,\n            \"Whatever the truth of it might be, and far as Elinor was from feeling thorough contentment about it, yet while she saw Marianne in spirits, she could not be very uncomfortable herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61093,\n            \"he came to look at Marianne and talk to Elinor, who often derived more satisfaction from conversing with him than from any other daily occurrence, but who saw at the same time with much concern his continued regard for her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61145,\n            \"It grieved her to see the earnestness with which he often watched Marianne, and his spirits were certainly worse than when at Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61250,\n            \"\\u201d But Marianne seemed hardly to hear her, and on Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s entrance, escaped with the precious card.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61274,\n            \"This event, while it raised the spirits of Elinor, restored to those of her sister all, and more than all, their former agitation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61487,\n            \"\\u201cYou have no confidence in me, Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61529,\n            \"\\u201cindeed, Marianne, I have nothing to tell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61568,\n            \"you, because you do not communicate, and I, because I conceal nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61584,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor, distressed by this charge of reserve in herself, which she was not at liberty to do away, knew not how, under such circumstances, to press for greater openness in Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62284,\n            \"Impatient in this situation to be doing something that might lead to her sister\\u2019s relief, Elinor resolved to write the next morning to her mother, and hoped by awakening her fears for the health of Marianne, to procure those inquiries which had been so long delayed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62336,\n            \"and she was still more eagerly bent on this measure by perceiving after breakfast on the morrow, that Marianne was again writing to Willoughby, for she could not suppose it to be to any other person.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62375,\n            \"About the middle of the day, Mrs. Jennings went out by herself on business, and Elinor began her letter directly, while Marianne, too restless for employment, too anxious for conversation, walked from one window to the other, or sat down by the fire in melancholy meditation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62430,\n            \"Elinor was very earnest in her application to her mother, relating all that had passed, her suspicions of Willoughby\\u2019s inconstancy, urging her by every plea of duty and affection to demand from Marianne an account of her real situation with respect to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63122,\n            \"Yet as she was convinced that Marianne\\u2019s affection for Willoughby, could leave no hope of Colonel Brandon\\u2019s success, whatever the event of that affection might be, and at the same time wished to shield her conduct from censure, she thought it most prudent and kind, after some consideration, to say more than she really knew or believed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63645,\n            \"After some time spent in saying little or doing less, Lady Middleton sat down to Cassino, and as Marianne was not in spirits for moving about, she and Elinor luckily succeeding to chairs, placed themselves at no great distance from the table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63767,\n            \"Elinor turned involuntarily to Marianne, to see whether it could be unobserved by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63851,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPray, pray be composed,\\u201dcried Elinor, \\u201cand do not betray what you feel to every body present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63942,\n            \"she started up, and pronouncing his name in a tone of affection, held out her hand to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63963,\n            \"He approached, and addressing himself rather to Elinor than Marianne, as if wishing to avoid her eye, and determined not to observe her attitude, inquired in a hurried manner after Mrs. Dashwood, and asked how long they had been in town.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64387,\n            \"\\u201cGo to him, Elinor,\\u201dshe cried, as soon as she could speak, \\u201cand force him to come to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64565,\n            \"In a short time Elinor saw Willoughby quit the room by the door towards the staircase, and telling Marianne that he was gone, urged the impossibility of speaking to him again that evening, as a fresh argument for her to be calm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65148,\n            \"and after observing her for a few moments with silent anxiety, said, in a tone of the most considerate gentleness, \\u201cMarianne, may I ask \\u2014?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65299,\n            \"and she would have tried to sooth and tranquilize her still more, had not Marianne entreated her, with all the eagerness of the most nervous irritability, not to speak to her for the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66089,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Jennings laughed again, but Elinor had not spirits to say more, and eager at all events to know what Willoughby had written, hurried away to their room, where, on opening the door, she saw Marianne stretched on the bed, almost choked by grief, one letter in her hand, and two or three others lying by her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66207,\n            \"The latter, though unable to speak, seemed to feel all the tenderness of this behaviour, and after some time thus spent in joint affliction, she put all the letters into Elinor\\u2019s hands;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66260,\n            \"Elinor, who knew that such grief, shocking as it was to witness it, must have its course, watched by her till this excess of suffering had somewhat spent itself, and then turning eagerly to Willoughby\\u2019s letter, read as follows: \\u201cBond Street, January.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66847,\n            \"In her earnest meditations on the contents of the letter, on the depravity of that mind which could dictate it, and probably, on the very different mind of a very different person, who had no other connection whatever with the affair than what her heart gave him with every thing that passed, Elinor forgot the immediate distress of her sister, forgot that she had three letters on her lap yet unread, and so entirely forgot how long she had been in the room, that when on hearing a carriage drive up to the door, she went to the window to see who could be coming so unreasonably early, she was all astonishment to perceive Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s chariot, which she knew had not been ordered till one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67026,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, with a thoroughly good-humoured concern for its cause, admitted the excuse most readily, and Elinor, after seeing her safe off, returned to Marianne, whom she found attempting to rise from the bed, and whom she reached just in time to prevent her from falling on the floor, faint and giddy from a long want of proper rest and food;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67157,\n            \"A glass of wine, which Elinor procured for her directly, made her more comfortable, and she was at last able to express some sense of her kindness, by saying, \\u201cPoor Elinor!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67527,\n            \"\\u201cNo, no, no,\\u201dcried Marianne wildly, \\u201che loves you, and only you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68524,\n            \"and she was silently grieving over the imprudence which had hazarded such unsolicited proofs of tenderness, not warranted by anything preceding, and most severely condemned by the event, when Marianne, perceiving that she had finished the letters, observed to her that they contained nothing but what any one would have written in the same situation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68798,\n            \"but when this emotion had passed away, she added, in a firmer tone, \\u201cElinor, I have been cruelly used;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68953,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor would not contend, and only replied, \\u201cWhoever may have been so detestably your enemy, let them be cheated of their malignant triumph, my dear sister, by seeing how nobly the consciousness of your own innocence and good intentions supports your spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69058,\n            \"Elinor, Elinor, they who suffer little may be proud and independent as they like \\u2014 may resist insult, or return mortification \\u2014 but I cannot.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69456,\n            \"\\u201cElinor, I must go home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69622,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor advised her to lie down again, and for a moment she did so;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            69647,\n            \"and in restless pain of mind and body she moved from one posture to another, till growing more and more hysterical, her sister could with difficulty keep her on the bed at all, and for some time was fearful of being constrained to call for assistance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70113,\n            \"Marianne, to the surprise of her sister, determined on dining with them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70128,\n            \"Elinor even advised her against it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70193,\n            \"and adjusting her dress for her as well as she could, while Marianne still remained on the bed, was ready to assist her into the dining room as soon as they were summoned to it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72233,\n            \"\\u201d And then rising, she went away to join Marianne, whom she found, as she expected, in her own room, leaning, in silent misery, over the small remains of a fire, which, till Elinor\\u2019s entrance, had been her only light.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72286,\n            \"\\u201cYou had better leave me,\\u201dwas all the notice that her sister received from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72305,\n            \"\\u201cI will leave you,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cif you will go to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72543,\n            \"But I have just left Marianne in bed, and, I hope, almost asleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72664,\n            \"Colonel Brandon came in while the party were at tea, and by his manner of looking round the room for Marianne, Elinor immediately fancied that he neither expected nor wished to see her there, and, in short, that he was already aware of what occasioned her absence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73579,\n            \"Elinor encouraged her as much as possible to talk of what she felt;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73609,\n            \"and with the same steady conviction and affectionate counsel on Elinor\\u2019s side, the same impetuous feelings and varying opinions on Marianne\\u2019s, as before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74277,\n            \"Her mother, still confident of their engagement, and relying as warmly as ever on his constancy, had only been roused by Elinor\\u2019s application, to intreat from Marianne greater openness towards them both;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78105,\n            \"\\u201d Recollecting, soon afterwards, that he was probably dividing Elinor from her sister, he put an end to his visit, receiving from her again the same grateful acknowledgments, and leaving her full of compassion and esteem for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78152,\n            \"When the particulars of this conversation were repeated by Miss Dashwood to her sister, as they very soon were, the effect on her was not entirely such as the former had hoped to see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78482,\n            \"of a disappointment hardly less painful than Marianne\\u2019s, and an indignation even greater than Elinor\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79064,\n            \"and Elinor, on the other hand, suspecting that it would not be in her power to avoid Edward entirely, comforted herself by thinking, that though their longer stay would therefore militate against her own happiness, it would be better for Marianne than an immediate return into Devonshire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81044,\n            \"\\u201cI am sorry she is not well \\u2014\\u201dfor Marianne had left the room on their arrival.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81277,\n            \"After some opposition, Marianne yielded to her sister\\u2019s entreaties, and consented to go out with her and Mrs. Jennings one morning for half an hour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84338,\n            \"But, my dear Elinor, what is the matter with Marianne?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87518,\n            \"and such ill-timed praise of another, at Elinor\\u2019s expense, though she had not any notion of what was principally meant by it, provoked her immediately to say with warmth, \\u201cThis is admiration of a very particular kind!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87684,\n            \"Elinor was much more hurt by Marianne\\u2019s warmth than she had been by what produced it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87754,\n            \"The cold insolence of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s general behaviour to her sister, seemed, to her, to foretell such difficulties and distresses to Elinor, as her own wounded heart taught her to think of with horror;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87796,\n            \"and urged by a strong impulse of affectionate sensibility, she moved after a moment, to her sister\\u2019s chair, and putting one arm round her neck, and one cheek close to hers, said in a low, but eager, voice, \\u201cDear, dear Elinor, don\\u2019t mind them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87874,\n            \"her spirits were quite overcome, and hiding her face on Elinor\\u2019s shoulder, she burst into tears.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88037,\n            \"\\u201d said her brother to Colonel Brandon, in a low voice, as soon as he could secure his attention: \\u201cShe has not such good health as her sister, \\u2014 she is very nervous, \\u2014 she has not Elinor\\u2019s constitution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89983,\n            \"while Marianne was looking with the most speaking tenderness, sometimes at Edward and sometimes at Elinor, regretting only that their delight in each other should be checked by Lucy\\u2019s unwelcome presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90104,\n            \"\\u201d This remark was not calculated to make Edward or Elinor more easy, nor to conciliate the good will of Lucy, who looked up at Marianne with no very benignant expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90836,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne looked at her steadily, and said, \\u201cYou know, Elinor, that this is a kind of talking which I cannot bear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90923,\n            \"and Elinor dared not follow her to say more, for bound as she was by her promise of secrecy to Lucy, she could give no information that would convince Marianne;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90979,\n            \"All that she could hope, was that Edward would not often expose her or himself to the distress of hearing Marianne\\u2019s mistaken warmth, nor to the repetition of any other part of the pain that had attended their recent meeting \\u2014 and this she had every reason to expect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91301,\n            \"Though nothing could be more polite than Lady Middleton\\u2019s behaviour to Elinor and Marianne, she did not really like them at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91532,\n            \"for though she often threw out expressions of pity for her sister to Elinor, and more than once dropt a reflection on the inconstancy of beaux before Marianne, no effect was produced, but a look of indifference from the former, or of disgust in the latter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94216,\n            \"at the same time, however, slyly suspecting that another year would make the invitation needless, by bringing Elinor to town as Colonel Brandon\\u2019s wife, and Marianne as _ their _ visitor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97949,\n            \"Elinor,\\u201dshe cried, \\u201cyou have made me hate myself for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98047,\n            \"In such a frame of mind as she was now in, Elinor had no difficulty in obtaining from her whatever promise she required;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100124,\n            \"and as her vehemence made reserve impossible in Elinor, and unnecessary in Mrs. Jennings, they all joined in a very spirited critique upon the party.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100156,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings was very warm in her praise of Edward\\u2019s conduct, but only Elinor and Marianne understood its true merit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100278,\n            \"Elinor avoided it upon principle, as tending to fix still more upon her thoughts, by the too warm, too positive assurances of Marianne, that belief of Edward\\u2019s continued affection for herself which she rather wished to do away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100323,\n            \"and Marianne\\u2019s courage soon failed her, in trying to converse upon a topic which always left her more dissatisfied with herself than ever, by the comparison it necessarily produced between Elinor\\u2019s conduct and her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100374,\n            \"but not as her sister had hoped, to urge her to exertion now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102937,\n            \"and Elinor was left in possession of knowledge which might feed her powers of reflection some time, though she had learnt very little more than what had been already foreseen and foreplanned in her own mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104822,\n            \"The effect of his discourse on the lady too, could not escape her observation, for though she was too honorable to listen, and had even changed her seat, on purpose that she might _ not _ hear, to one close by the piano forte on which Marianne was playing, she could not keep herself from seeing that Elinor changed colour, attended with agitation, and was too intent on what he said to pursue her employment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105136,\n            \"\\u201d This delay on the Colonel\\u2019s side, however, did not seem to offend or mortify his fair companion in the least, for on their breaking up the conference soon afterwards, and moving different ways, Mrs. Jennings very plainly heard Elinor say, and with a voice which showed her to feel what she said, \\u201cI shall always think myself very much obliged to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107341,\n            \"but returning again in a moment, \\u201cI have just been thinking of Betty\\u2019s sister, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110281,\n            \"_ Now _ especially there cannot be \\u2014 but however, you and Marianne were always great favourites.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113297,\n            \"She had no such object for her lingering thoughts to fix on, she left no creature behind, from whom it would give her a moment\\u2019s regret to be divided for ever, she was pleased to be free herself from the persecution of Lucy\\u2019s friendship, she was grateful for bringing her sister away unseen by Willoughby since his marriage, and she looked forward with hope to what a few months of tranquility at Barton might do towards restoring Marianne\\u2019s peace of mind, and confirming her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114610,\n            \"\\u2014 His behaviour to her in this, as well as in every other particular, his open pleasure in meeting her after an absence of only ten days, his readiness to converse with her, and his deference for her opinion, might very well justify Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s persuasion of his attachment, and would have been enough, perhaps, had not Elinor still, as from the first, believed Marianne his real favourite, to make her suspect it herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115097,\n            \"and when, at last, she went early to bed, more and more indisposed, Colonel Brandon was only astonished at her sister\\u2019s composure, who, though attending and nursing her the whole day, against Marianne\\u2019s inclination, and forcing proper medicines on her at night, trusted, like Marianne, to the certainty and efficacy of sleep, and felt no real alarm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115186,\n            \"and when Marianne, after persisting in rising, confessed herself unable to sit up, and returned voluntarily to her bed, Elinor was very ready to adopt Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s advice, of sending for the Palmers\\u2019 apothecary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115295,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, who had been inclined from the first to think Marianne\\u2019s complaint more serious than Elinor, now looked very grave on Mr. Harris\\u2019 s report, and confirming Charlotte\\u2019s fears and caution, urged the necessity of her immediate removal with her infant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115467,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings, however, with a kindness of heart which made Elinor really love her, declared her resolution of not stirring from Cleveland as long as Marianne remained ill, and of endeavouring, by her own attentive care, to supply to her the place of the mother she had taken her from;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116491,\n            \"her maid, who was one of the principal nurses, was recreating herself in the housekeeper\\u2019s room, and Elinor remained alone with Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116604,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNot yet,\\u201dcried the other, concealing her terror, and assisting Marianne to lie down again, \\u201cbut she will be here, I hope, before it is long.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117192,\n            \"Hour after hour passed away in sleepless pain and delirium on Marianne\\u2019s side, and in the most cruel anxiety on Elinor\\u2019s, before Mr. Harris appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117276,\n            \"Marianne\\u2019s ideas were still, at intervals, fixed incoherently on her mother, and whenever she mentioned her name, it gave a pang to the heart of poor Elinor, who, reproaching herself for having trifled with so many days of illness, and wretched for some immediate relief, fancied that all relief might soon be in vain, that every thing had been delayed too long, and pictured to herself her suffering mother arriving too late to see this darling child, or to see her rational.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122671,\n            \"Did she show it you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126159,\n            \"When at last she returned to the unconscious Marianne, she found her just awaking, refreshed by so long and sweet a sleep to the extent of her hopes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126197,\n            \"The past, the present, the future, Willoughby\\u2019s visit, Marianne\\u2019s safety, and her mother\\u2019s expected arrival, threw her altogether into an agitation of spirits which kept off every indication of fatigue, and made her only fearful of betraying herself to her sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126333,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, whose terror as they drew near the house had produced almost the conviction of Marianne\\u2019s being no more, had no voice to inquire after her, no voice even for Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126553,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s delight, as she saw what each felt in the meeting, was only checked by an apprehension of its robbing Marianne of farther sleep: but Mrs. Dashwood could be calm, could be even prudent, when the life of a child was at stake, and Marianne, satisfied in knowing her mother was near her, and conscious of being too weak for conversation, submitted readily to the silence and quiet prescribed by every nurse around her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126801,\n            \"Then, remembering Colonel Brandon, reproved herself, felt that to _ his _ sufferings and _ his _ constancy far more than to his rival\\u2019s, the reward of her sister was due, and wished any thing rather than Mrs. Willoughby\\u2019s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127411,\n            \"He has loved her, my Elinor, ever since the first moment of seeing her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127660,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHis character, however,\\u201danswered Elinor, \\u201cdoes not rest on _ one _ act of kindness, to which his affection for Marianne, were humanity out of the case, would have prompted him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128174,\n            \"but her mother, without waiting for her assent, continued, \\u201cAnd his manners, the Colonel\\u2019s manners are not only more pleasing to me than Willoughby\\u2019s ever were, but they are of a kind I well know to be more solidly attaching to Marianne.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128628,\n            \"His emotion on entering the room, in seeing her altered looks, and in receiving the pale hand which she immediately held out to him, was such, as, in Elinor\\u2019s conjecture, must arise from something more than his affection for Marianne, or the consciousness of its being known to others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130140,\n            \"and Marianne, leaning on Elinor\\u2019s arm, was authorised to walk as long as she could without fatigue, in the lane before the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131349,\n            \"and Elinor, impatient to soothe, though too honest to flatter, gave her instantly that praise and support which her frankness and her contrition so well deserved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131379,\n            \"Marianne pressed her hand and replied, \\u2014 \\u201cYou are very good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131776,\n            \"her hand, unknowingly to herself, closely pressed her sister\\u2019s, and tears covered her cheeks.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131796,\n            \"Elinor, dreading her being tired, led her towards home;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131864,\n            \"As soon as they entered the house, Marianne with a kiss of gratitude and these two words just articulate through her tears, \\u201cTell mama,\\u201dwithdrew from her sister and walked slowly up stairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131919,\n            \"and with a mind anxiously pre-arranging its result, and a resolution of reviving the subject again, should Marianne fail to do it, she turned into the parlour to fulfill her parting injunction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132342,\n            \"Marianne slowly continued, \\u2014 \\u201cIt is a great relief to me \\u2014 what Elinor told me this morning \\u2014 I have now heard exactly what I wished to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133404,\n            \"Elinor, according to her expectation, saw on the two or three following days, that Marianne did not continue to gain strength as she had done;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133550,\n            \"Some letters had passed between her and her brother, in consequence of Marianne\\u2019s illness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133720,\n            \"\\u201d Marianne gave a violent start, fixed her eyes upon Elinor, saw her turning pale, and fell back in her chair in hysterics.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133747,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, whose eyes, as she answered the servant\\u2019s inquiry, had intuitively taken the same direction, was shocked to perceive by Elinor\\u2019s countenance how much she really suffered, and a moment afterwards, alike distressed by Marianne\\u2019s situation, knew not on which child to bestow her principal attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133849,\n            \"By that time, Marianne was rather better, and her mother leaving her to the care of Margaret and the maid, returned to Elinor, who, though still much disordered, had so far recovered the use of her reason and voice as to be just beginning an inquiry of Thomas, as to the source of his intelligence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134830,\n            \"\\u2014 that Marianne\\u2019s affliction, because more acknowledged, more immediately before her, had too much engrossed her tenderness, and led her away to forget that in Elinor she might have a daughter suffering almost as much, certainly with less self-provocation, and greater fortitude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143621,\n            \"and to see Marianne settled at the mansion-house was equally the wish of Edward and Elinor.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[17, 18]\": [\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53446,\n            \"\\u2014 Is her son determined to submit to this, and to all the tediousness of the many years of suspense in which it may involve you, rather than run the risk of her displeasure for a while by owning the truth?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53506,\n            \"But Mrs. Ferrars is a very headstrong proud woman, and in her first fit of anger upon hearing it, would very likely secure every thing to Robert, and the idea of that, for Edward\\u2019s sake, frightens away all my inclination for hasty measures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96013,\n            \"for I am sure Mrs. Ferrars may afford to do very well by her son, and though Lucy has next to nothing herself, she knows better than any body how to make the most of every thing;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96054,\n            \"I dare say, if Mrs. Ferrars would only allow him five hundred a-year, she would make as good an appearance with it as any body else would with eight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98784,\n            \"All that Mrs. Ferrars could say to make him put an end to the engagement, assisted too as you may well suppose by my arguments, and Fanny\\u2019s entreaties, was of no avail.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99306,\n            \"And to have entered into a secret engagement with a young man under her uncle\\u2019s care, the son of a woman especially of such very large fortune as Mrs. Ferrars, is perhaps, altogether a little extraordinary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99442,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s heart wrung for the feelings of Edward, while braving his mother\\u2019s threats, for a woman who could not reward him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99489,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry to say, ma\\u2019am, in a most unhappy rupture: \\u2014 Edward is dismissed for ever from his mother\\u2019s notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99520,\n            \"He left her house yesterday, but where he is gone, or whether he is still in town, I do not know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99850,\n            \"And there is one thing more preparing against him, which must be worse than all \\u2014 his mother has determined, with a very natural kind of spirit, to settle _ that _ estate upon Robert immediately, which might have been Edward\\u2019s, on proper conditions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100074,\n            \"leaving the three ladies unanimous in their sentiments on the present occasion, as far at least as it regarded Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s conduct, the Dashwoods \\u2019, and Edward\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110830,\n            \"\\u201cMrs. Ferrars,\\u201dadded he, lowering his voice to the tone becoming so important a subject, \\u201cknows nothing about it at present, and I believe it will be best to keep it entirely concealed from her as long as may be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110904,\n            \"Though it is not to be supposed that Mrs. Ferrars can have the smallest satisfaction in knowing that her son has money enough to live upon, for _ that _ must be quite out of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110960,\n            \"She has done with her son, \\u2014 she cast him off for ever, and has made all those over whom she had any influence, cast him off likewise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110992,\n            \"Surely, after doing so, she cannot be imagined liable to any impression of sorrow or of joy on his account: she cannot be interested in any thing that befalls him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111078,\n            \"When Edward\\u2019s unhappy match takes place, depend upon it his mother will feel as much as if she had never discarded him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111126,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars can never forget that Edward is her son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111160,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou wrong her exceedingly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140972,\n            \"He thus continued: \\u2014 \\u201cMrs. Ferrars has never yet mentioned Edward\\u2019s name, which does not surprise us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141534,\n            \"After a proper resistance on the part of Mrs. Ferrars, just so violent and so steady as to preserve her from that reproach which she always seemed fearful of incurring, the reproach of being too amiable, Edward was admitted to her presence, and pronounced to be again her son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141610,\n            \"but the crime and annihilation of Edward a few weeks ago, had robbed her of one;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141642,\n            \"and now, by the resuscitation of Edward, she had one again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141733,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars at first reasonably endeavoured to dissuade him from marrying Miss Dashwood, by every argument in her power;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141815,\n            \"_ but when she found that, though perfectly admitting the truth of her representation, he was by no means inclined to be guided by it, she judged it wisest, from the experience of the past, to submit \\u2014 and therefore, after such an ungracious delay as she owed to her own dignity, and as served to prevent every suspicion of good-will, she issued her decree of consent to the marriage of Edward and Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141916,\n            \"and here it plainly appeared, that though Edward was now her only son, he was by no means her eldest;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[17, 19]\": [\n        [\n            46671,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor _ did _ think the question a very odd one, and her countenance expressed it, as she answered that she had never seen Mrs. Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46709,\n            \"\\u201cI wonder at that, for I thought you must have seen her at Norland sometimes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46727,\n            \"Then, perhaps, you cannot tell me what sort of a woman she is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46743,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo,\\u201dreturned Elinor, cautious of giving her real opinion of Edward\\u2019s mother, and not very desirous of satisfying what seemed impertinent curiosity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46774,\n            \"\\u201cI know nothing of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46781,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sure you think me very strange, for enquiring about her in such a way,\\u201dsaid Lucy, eyeing Elinor attentively as she spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46979,\n            \"I am sorry you do not happen to know Mrs. Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46992,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am sorry I do _ not _,\\u201dsaid Elinor, in great astonishment, \\u201cif it could be of any use to YOU to know my opinion of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87292,\n            \"Mrs. Ferrars, not aware of their being Elinor\\u2019s work, particularly requested to look at them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88152,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s curiosity to see Mrs. Ferrars was satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89277,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was prevented from making any reply to this civil triumph, by the door\\u2019s being thrown open, the servant\\u2019s announcing Mr. Ferrars, and Edward\\u2019s immediately walking in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99442,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s heart wrung for the feelings of Edward, while braving his mother\\u2019s threats, for a woman who could not reward him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105319,\n            \"for if I understand the matter right, he has been entirely cast off by them for persevering in his engagement with a very deserving young woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109929,\n            \"It was now above a week since John Dashwood had called in Berkeley Street, and as since that time no notice had been taken by them of his wife\\u2019s indisposition, beyond one verbal enquiry, Elinor began to feel it necessary to pay her a visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110098,\n            \"The consequence was, that Elinor set out by herself to pay a visit, for which no one could really have less inclination, and to run the risk of a t\\u00eate-\\u00e0-t\\u00eate with a woman, whom neither of the others had so much reason to dislike.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111414,\n            \"I have good reason to think \\u2014 indeed I have it from the best authority, or I should not repeat it, for otherwise it would be very wrong to say any thing about it, \\u2014 but I have it from the very best authority, \\u2014 not that I ever precisely heard Mrs. Ferrars say it herself \\u2014 but her daughter _ did _, and I have it from her, \\u2014 that in short, whatever objections there might be against a certain \\u2014 a certain connection, you understand me, \\u2014 it would have been far preferable to her, \\u2014 it would not have given her half the vexation that _ this _ does.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140318,\n            \"Every thing was explained to him by Mrs. Dashwood, and he found fresh reason to rejoice in what he had done for Mr. Ferrars, since eventually it promoted the interest of Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141815,\n            \"_ but when she found that, though perfectly admitting the truth of her representation, he was by no means inclined to be guided by it, she judged it wisest, from the experience of the past, to submit \\u2014 and therefore, after such an ungracious delay as she owed to her own dignity, and as served to prevent every suspicion of good-will, she issued her decree of consent to the marriage of Edward and Elinor.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[18, 19]\": [\n        [\n            4792,\n            \"It was enough for her that he appeared to be amiable, that he loved her daughter, and that Elinor returned the partiality.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5168,\n            \"She was first called to observe and approve him farther, by a reflection which Elinor chanced one day to make on the difference between him and his sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5241,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI think you will like him,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cwhen you know more of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5340,\n            \"the persuasion of his regard for Elinor perhaps assisted her penetration;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5404,\n            \"No sooner did she perceive any symptom of love in his behaviour to Elinor, than she considered their serious attachment as certain, and looked forward to their marriage as rapidly approaching.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5670,\n            \"Music seems scarcely to attract him, and though he admires Elinor\\u2019s drawings very much, it is not the admiration of a person who can understand their worth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5702,\n            \"It is evident, in spite of his frequent attention to her while she draws, that in fact he knows nothing of the matter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5921,\n            \"Elinor has not my feelings, and therefore she may overlook it, and be happy with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6077,\n            \"\\u201cWhat a pity it is, Elinor,\\u201dsaid Marianne, \\u201cthat Edward should have no taste for drawing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6118,\n            \"He does not draw himself, indeed, but he has great pleasure in seeing the performances of other people, and I assure you he is by no means deficient in natural taste, though he has not had opportunities of improving it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6163,\n            \"Had he ever been in the way of learning, I think he would have drawn very well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6240,\n            \"but the kind of approbation which Elinor described as excited in him by the drawings of other people, was very far from that rapturous delight, which, in her opinion, could alone be called taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6279,\n            \"Yet, though smiling within herself at the mistake, she honoured her sister for that blind partiality to Edward which produced it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6303,\n            \"\\u201cI hope, Marianne,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cyou do not consider him as deficient in general taste.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6325,\n            \"Indeed, I think I may say that you cannot, for your behaviour to him is perfectly cordial, and if _ that _ were your opinion, I am sure you could never be civil to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6398,\n            \"At length she replied: \\u201cDo not be offended, Elinor, if my praise of him is not in every thing equal to your sense of his merits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6533,\n            \"\\u201cOf his sense and his goodness,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, \\u201cno one can, I think, be in doubt, who has seen him often enough to engage him in unreserved conversation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6808,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall very soon think him handsome, Elinor, if I do not now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6826,\n            \"When you tell me to love him as a brother, I shall no more see imperfection in his face, than I now do in his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6855,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor started at this declaration, and was sorry for the warmth she had been betrayed into, in speaking of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6879,\n            \"She felt that Edward stood very high in her opinion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6966,\n            \"\\u201cI do not attempt to deny,\\u201dsaid she, \\u201cthat I think very highly of him \\u2014 that I greatly esteem, that I like him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7095,\n            \"believe them, in short, to be such as his merit, and the suspicion \\u2014 the hope of his affection for me may warrant, without imprudence or folly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7138,\n            \"I am by no means assured of his regard for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7323,\n            \"\\u201cAnd you really are not engaged to him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7354,\n            \"_ I _ shall not lose you so soon, and Edward will have greater opportunity of improving that natural taste for your favourite pursuit which must be so indispensably necessary to your future felicity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7392,\n            \"if he should be so far stimulated by your genius as to learn to draw himself, how delightful it would be!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7426,\n            \"She could not consider her partiality for Edward in so prosperous a state as Marianne had believed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7473,\n            \"A doubt of her regard, supposing him to feel it, need not give him more than inquietude.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7528,\n            \"She knew that his mother neither behaved to him so as to make his home comfortable at present, nor to give him any assurance that he might form a home for himself, without strictly attending to her views for his aggrandizement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7591,\n            \"She was far from depending on that result of his preference of her, which her mother and sister still considered as certain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7651,\n            \"But, whatever might really be its limits, it was enough, when perceived by his sister, to make her uneasy, and at the same time, (which was still more common,) to make her uncivil.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7694,\n            \"She took the first opportunity of affronting her mother-in-law on the occasion, talking to her so expressively of her brother\\u2019s great expectations, of Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s resolution that both her sons should marry well, and of the danger attending any young woman who attempted to _ draw him in;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7892,\n            \"He understood that she was in need of a dwelling;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7903,\n            \"and though the house he now offered her was merely a cottage, he assured her that everything should be done to it which she might think necessary, if the situation pleased her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7938,\n            \"He earnestly pressed her, after giving the particulars of the house and garden, to come with her daughters to Barton Park, the place of his own residence, from whence she might judge, herself, whether Barton Cottage, for the houses were in the same parish, could, by any alteration, be made comfortable to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8663,\n            \"To separate Edward and Elinor was as far from being her object as ever;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13082,\n            \"\\u201d said Elinor, \\u201cdo you call Colonel Brandon infirm?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13094,\n            \"I can easily suppose that his age may appear much greater to you than to my mother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13212,\n            \"I know very well that Colonel Brandon is not old enough to make his friends yet apprehensive of losing him in the course of nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13282,\n            \"But if there should by any chance happen to be a woman who is single at seven and twenty, I should not think Colonel Brandon\\u2019s being thirty-five any objection to his marrying _ her _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13462,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt would be impossible, I know,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cto convince you that a woman of seven and twenty could feel for a man of thirty-five anything near enough to love, to make him a desirable companion to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13511,\n            \"But I must object to your dooming Colonel Brandon and his wife to the constant confinement of a sick chamber, merely because he chanced to complain yesterday (a very cold damp day) of a slight rheumatic feel in one of his shoulders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13798,\n            \"Does Elinor expect him already?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13923,\n            \"In Edward\\u2019s farewell there was no distinction between Elinor and me: it was the good wishes of an affectionate brother to both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13978,\n            \"And Elinor, in quitting Norland and Edward, cried not as I did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            17588,\n            \"Colonel Brandon\\u2019s partiality for Marianne, which had so early been discovered by his friends, now first became perceptible to Elinor, when it ceased to be noticed by them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31107,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 and was hastening to meet him, when Elinor cried out, \\u201cIndeed, Marianne, I think you are mistaken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31388,\n            \"He was welcomed by them all with great cordiality, but especially by Marianne, who showed more warmth of regard in her reception of him than even Elinor herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31479,\n            \"He was confused, seemed scarcely sensible of pleasure in seeing them, looked neither rapturous nor gay, said little but what was forced from him by questions, and distinguished Elinor by no mark of affection.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31608,\n            \"\\u201d she repeated, surprised at his being so long in the same county with Elinor without seeing her before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32158,\n            \"and directing her attention to their visitor, endeavoured to support something like discourse with him, by talking of their present residence, its conveniences, & c.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32368,\n            \"and Elinor had the satisfaction of seeing him soon become more like himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33467,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cPerhaps, then, you would bestow it as a reward on that person who wrote the ablest defence of your favourite maxim, that no one can ever be in love more than once in their life \\u2014 your opinion on that point is unchanged, I presume?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33550,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMarianne is as steadfast as ever, you see,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cshe is not at all altered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33701,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI believe you are right,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cand yet I have always set her down as a lively girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33954,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou have not been able to bring your sister over to your plan of general civility,\\u201dsaid Edward to Elinor, \\u201cDo you gain no ground?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34001,\n            \"\\u201cMy judgment,\\u201dhe returned, \\u201cis all on your side of the question;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34203,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI do not understand you,\\u201dreplied he, colouring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34227,\n            \"What am I to tell you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34239,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor looked surprised at his emotion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34247,\n            \"but trying to laugh off the subject, she said to him, \\u201cDo not you know my sister well enough to understand what she means?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34345,\n            \"His visit afforded her but a very partial satisfaction, while his own enjoyment in it appeared so imperfect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34373,\n            \"she wished it were equally evident that he still distinguished her by the same affection which once she had felt no doubt of inspiring;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34409,\n            \"and the reservedness of his manner towards her contradicted one moment what a more animated look had intimated the preceding one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34431,\n            \"He joined her and Marianne in the breakfast-room the next morning before the others were down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34473,\n            \"But before she was half way upstairs she heard the parlour door open, and, turning round, was astonished to see Edward himself come out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34869,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI suspect,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cthat to avoid one kind of affectation, Edward here falls into another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35033,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am convinced,\\u201dsaid Edward, \\u201cthat you really feel all the delight in a fine prospect which you profess to feel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35340,\n            \"He coloured very deeply, and giving a momentary glance at Elinor, replied, \\u201cYes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35379,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor had met his eye, and looked conscious likewise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35636,\n            \"and this prepared a future mine of raillery against the devoted Elinor, which nothing but the newness of their acquaintance with Edward could have prevented from being immediately sprung.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36430,\n            \"and it was happy for her that he had a mother whose character was so imperfectly known to her, as to be the general excuse for every thing strange on the part of her son.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36467,\n            \"Disappointed, however, and vexed as she was, and sometimes displeased with his uncertain behaviour to herself, she was very well disposed on the whole to regard his actions with all the candid allowances and generous qualifications, which had been rather more painfully extorted from her, for Willoughby\\u2019s service, by her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36617,\n            \"She would have been glad to know when these difficulties were to cease, this opposition was to yield, \\u2014 when Mrs. Ferrars would be reformed, and her son be at liberty to be happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36656,\n            \"But from such vain wishes she was forced to turn for comfort to the renewal of her confidence in Edward\\u2019s affection, to the remembrance of every mark of regard in look or word which fell from him while at Barton, and above all to that flattering proof of it which he constantly wore round his finger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37451,\n            \"But as it was her determination to subdue it, and to prevent herself from appearing to suffer more than what all her family suffered on his going away, she did not adopt the method so judiciously employed by Marianne, on a similar occasion, to augment and fix her sorrow, by seeking silence, solitude and idleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37531,\n            \"Elinor sat down to her drawing-table as soon as he was out of the house, busily employed herself the whole day, neither sought nor avoided the mention of his name, appeared to interest herself almost as much as ever in the general concerns of the family, and if, by this conduct, she did not lessen her own grief, it was at least prevented from unnecessary increase, and her mother and sisters were spared much solicitude on her account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37730,\n            \"Without shutting herself up from her family, or leaving the house in determined solitude to avoid them, or lying awake the whole night to indulge meditation, Elinor found every day afforded her leisure enough to think of Edward, and of Edward\\u2019s behaviour, in every possible variety which the different state of her spirits at different times could produce, \\u2014 with tenderness, pity, approbation, censure, and doubt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            37901,\n            \"From a reverie of this kind, as she sat at her drawing-table, she was roused one morning, soon after Edward\\u2019s leaving them, by the arrival of company.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47236,\n            \"but,\\u201dfixing her eyes upon Elinor, \\u201cto his eldest brother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47355,\n            \"for I dare say he never dropped the smallest hint of it to you or any of your family;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47466,\n            \"And I do not think Mr. Ferrars can be displeased, when he knows I have trusted you, because I know he has the highest opinion in the world of all your family, and looks upon yourself and the other Miss Dashwoods quite as his own sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47682,\n            \"Did you never hear him talk of Mr. Pratt?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47831,\n            \"Though you do not know him so well as me, Miss Dashwood, you must have seen enough of him to be sensible he is very capable of making a woman sincerely attached to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47882,\n            \"but after a moment\\u2019s reflection, she added, with revived security of Edward\\u2019s honour and love, and her companion\\u2019s falsehood \\u2014 \\u201cEngaged to Mr. Edward Ferrars!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47975,\n            \"\\u201cMr. Edward Ferrars, the eldest son of Mrs. Ferrars, of Park Street, and brother of your sister-in-law, Mrs. John Dashwood, is the person I mean;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48014,\n            \"you must allow that I am not likely to be deceived as to the name of the man on who all my happiness depends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48039,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIt is strange,\\u201dreplied Elinor, in a most painful perplexity, \\u201cthat I should never have heard him even mention your name.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48246,\n            \"It does not do him justice, to be sure, but yet I think you cannot be deceived as to the person it was drew for.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48295,\n            \"and when Elinor saw the painting, whatever other doubts her fear of a too hasty decision, or her wish of detecting falsehood might suffer to linger in her mind, she could have none of its being Edward\\u2019s face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49123,\n            \"Did you not think him dreadful low-spirited when he was at Barton?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49138,\n            \"He was so miserable when he left us at Longstaple, to go to you, that I was afraid you would think him quite ill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49198,\n            \"Did you think he came directly from town?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49230,\n            \"\\u201cI remember he told us, that he had been staying a fortnight with some friends near Plymouth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49250,\n            \"\\u201d She remembered too, her own surprise at the time, at his mentioning nothing farther of those friends, at his total silence with respect even to their names.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49282,\n            \"\\u201cDid not you think him sadly out of spirits?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49450,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor saw that it _ was _ his hand, and she could doubt no longer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49672,\n            \"Perhaps you might notice the ring when you saw him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49894,\n            \"and Edward\\u2019s visit near Plymouth, his melancholy state of mind, his dissatisfaction at his own prospects, his uncertain behaviour towards herself, the intimate knowledge of the Miss Steeles as to Norland and their family connections, which had often surprised her, the picture, the letter, the ring, formed altogether such a body of evidence, as overcame every fear of condemning him unfairly, and established as a fact, which no partiality could set aside, his ill-treatment of herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49988,\n            \"\\u2014 Her resentment of such behaviour, her indignation at having been its dupe, for a short time made her feel only for herself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50024,\n            \"Had Edward been intentionally deceiving her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50031,\n            \"Had he feigned a regard for her which he did not feel?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50073,\n            \"His affection was all her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50088,\n            \"Her mother, sisters, Fanny, all had been conscious of his regard for her at Norland;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50117,\n            \"He certainly loved her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50142,\n            \"He had been blamable, highly blamable, in remaining at Norland after he first felt her influence over him to be more than it ought to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50180,\n            \"but if he had injured her, how much more had he injured himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50195,\n            \"if her case were pitiable, his was hopeless.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50205,\n            \"His imprudence had made her miserable for a while;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50486,\n            \"As these considerations occurred to her in painful succession, she wept for him, more than for herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50506,\n            \"Supported by the conviction of having done nothing to merit her present unhappiness, and consoled by the belief that Edward had done nothing to forfeit her esteem, she thought she could even now, under the first smart of the heavy blow, command herself enough to guard every suspicion of the truth from her mother and sisters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50567,\n            \"And so well was she able to answer her own expectations, that when she joined them at dinner only two hours after she had first suffered the extinction of all her dearest hopes, no one would have supposed from the appearance of the sisters, that Elinor was mourning in secret over obstacles which must divide her for ever from the object of her love, and that Marianne was internally dwelling on the perfections of a man, of whose whole heart she felt thoroughly possessed, and whom she expected to see in every carriage which drove near their house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50708,\n            \"On the contrary it was a relief to her, to be spared the communication of what would give such affliction to them, and to be saved likewise from hearing that condemnation of Edward, which would probably flow from the excess of their partial affection for herself, and which was more than she felt equal to support.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50891,\n            \"She wanted to hear many particulars of their engagement repeated again, she wanted more clearly to understand what Lucy really felt for Edward, whether there were any sincerity in her declaration of tender regard for him, and she particularly wanted to convince Lucy, by her readiness to enter on the matter again, and her calmness in conversing on it, that she was no otherwise interested in it than as a friend, which she very much feared her involuntary agitation, in their morning discourse, must have left at least doubtful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50990,\n            \"That Lucy was disposed to be jealous of her appeared very probable: it was plain that Edward had always spoken highly in her praise, not merely from Lucy\\u2019s assertion, but from her venturing to trust her on so short a personal acquaintance, with a secret so confessedly and evidently important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51061,\n            \"But indeed, while Elinor remained so well assured within herself of being really beloved by Edward, it required no other consideration of probabilities to make it natural that Lucy should be jealous;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51109,\n            \"What other reason for the disclosure of the affair could there be, but that Elinor might be informed by it of Lucy\\u2019s superior claims on Edward, and be taught to avoid him in future?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51148,\n            \"She had little difficulty in understanding thus much of her rival\\u2019s intentions, and while she was firmly resolved to act by her as every principle of honour and honesty directed, to combat her own affection for Edward and to see him as little as possible;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53916,\n            \"now my plan is that he should take orders as soon as he can, and then through your interest, which I am sure you would be kind enough to use out of friendship for him, and I hope out of some regard to me, your brother might be persuaded to give him Norland living;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54018,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI should always be happy,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cto show any mark of my esteem and friendship for Mr. Ferrars;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54282,\n            \"and I do really believe, that if you was to say to me, \\u2018 I advise you by all means to put an end to your engagement with Edward Ferrars, it will be more for the happiness of both of you,\\u2019I should resolve upon doing it immediately.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54678,\n            \"He will be there in February, otherwise London would have no charms for me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54764,\n            \"and Elinor sat down to the card table with the melancholy persuasion that Edward was not only without affection for the person who was to be his wife;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54793,\n            \"but that he had not even the chance of being tolerably happy in marriage, which sincere affection on _ her _ side would have given, for self-interest alone could induce a woman to keep a man to an engagement, of which she seemed so thoroughly aware that he was weary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54849,\n            \"From this time the subject was never revived by Elinor, and when entered on by Lucy, who seldom missed an opportunity of introducing it, and was particularly careful to inform her confidante, of her happiness whenever she received a letter from Edward, it was treated by the former with calmness and caution, and dismissed as soon as civility would allow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55852,\n            \"and Elinor, who now understood her sister, and saw to what indifference to almost every thing else she was carried by her eagerness to be with Willoughby again, made no farther direct opposition to the plan, and merely referred it to her mother\\u2019s decision, from whom however she scarcely expected to receive any support in her endeavour to prevent a visit, which she could not approve of for Marianne, and which on her own account she had particular reasons to avoid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56715,\n            \"To this determination she was the more easily reconciled, by recollecting that Edward Ferrars, by Lucy\\u2019s account, was not to be in town before February;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56842,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor had often wished for an opportunity of attempting to weaken her mother\\u2019s dependence on the attachment of Edward and herself, that the shock might be less when the whole truth were revealed, and now on this attack, though almost hopeless of success, she forced herself to begin her design by saying, as calmly as she could, \\u201cI like Edward Ferrars very much, and shall always be glad to see him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57446,\n            \"and Elinor, in spite of every occasional doubt of Willoughby\\u2019s constancy, could not witness the rapture of delightful expectation which filled the whole soul and beamed in the eyes of Marianne, without feeling how blank was her own prospect, how cheerless her own state of mind in the comparison, and how gladly she would engage in the solicitude of Marianne\\u2019s situation to have the same animating object in view, the same possibility of hope.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57573,\n            \"and Elinor was resolved not only upon gaining every new light as to his character which her own observation or the intelligence of others could give her, but likewise upon watching his behaviour to her sister with such zealous attention, as to ascertain what he was and what he meant, before many meetings had taken place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58098,\n            \"it immediately struck her that she must then be writing to Willoughby;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58336,\n            \"The tea things were brought in, and already had Marianne been disappointed more than once by a rap at a neighbouring door, when a loud one was suddenly heard which could not be mistaken for one at any other house, Elinor felt secure of its announcing Willoughby\\u2019s approach, and Marianne, starting up, moved towards the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58453,\n            \"in the ecstasy of her feelings at that instant she could not help exclaiming, \\u201cOh, Elinor, it is Willoughby, indeed it is!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58743,\n            \"Elinor wished very much to ask whether Willoughby were then in town, but she was afraid of giving him pain by any enquiry after his rival;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58771,\n            \"and at length, by way of saying something, she asked if he had been in London ever since she had seen him last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85186,\n            \"Elinor wanted very much to know, though she did not chuse to ask, whether Edward was then in town;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85208,\n            \"but nothing would have induced Fanny voluntarily to mention his name before her, till able to tell her that his marriage with Miss Morton was resolved on, or till her husband\\u2019s expectations on Colonel Brandon were answered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85297,\n            \"Lucy came very shortly to claim Elinor\\u2019s compassion on being unable to see Edward, though he had arrived in town with Mr. and Mrs. Dashwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85407,\n            \"Elinor was pleased that he had called;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85968,\n            \"They were relieved however, not by her own recollection, but by the good will of Lucy, who believed herself to be inflicting a severe disappointment when she told her that Edward certainly would not be in Harley Street on Tuesday, and even hoped to be carrying the pain still farther by persuading her that he was kept away by the extreme affection for herself, which he could not conceal when they were together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88037,\n            \"\\u201d said her brother to Colonel Brandon, in a low voice, as soon as he could secure his attention: \\u201cShe has not such good health as her sister, \\u2014 she is very nervous, \\u2014 she has not Elinor\\u2019s constitution;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88976,\n            \"But it seemed to satisfy Lucy, for she directly replied, \\u201cIndeed I am perfectly convinced of your regard for me, and next to Edward\\u2019s love, it is the greatest comfort I have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89277,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor was prevented from making any reply to this civil triumph, by the door\\u2019s being thrown open, the servant\\u2019s announcing Mr. Ferrars, and Edward\\u2019s immediately walking in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89661,\n            \"for his heart had not the indifference of Lucy\\u2019s, nor could his conscience have quite the ease of Elinor\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89983,\n            \"while Marianne was looking with the most speaking tenderness, sometimes at Edward and sometimes at Elinor, regretting only that their delight in each other should be checked by Lucy\\u2019s unwelcome presence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90089,\n            \"Elinor is well, you see.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90104,\n            \"\\u201d This remark was not calculated to make Edward or Elinor more easy, nor to conciliate the good will of Lucy, who looked up at Marianne with no very benignant expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90211,\n            \"\\u201cI think, Elinor,\\u201dshe presently added, \\u201cwe must employ Edward to take care of us in our return to Barton.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90979,\n            \"All that she could hope, was that Edward would not often expose her or himself to the distress of hearing Marianne\\u2019s mistaken warmth, nor to the repetition of any other part of the pain that had attended their recent meeting \\u2014 and this she had every reason to expect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92755,\n            \"She perceived him soon afterwards looking at herself, and speaking familiarly to her brother;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92771,\n            \"and had just determined to find out his name from the latter, when they both came towards her, and Mr. Dashwood introduced him to her as Mr. Robert Ferrars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92846,\n            \"Happy had it been for her, if her regard for Edward had depended less on his own merit, than on the merit of his nearest relations!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92903,\n            \"But while she wondered at the difference of the two young men, she did not find that the emptiness and conceit of the one, put her out of all charity with the modesty and worth of the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93209,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor would not oppose his opinion, because, whatever might be her general estimation of the advantage of a public school, she could not think of Edward\\u2019s abode in Mr. Pratt\\u2019s family, with any satisfaction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99442,\n            \"and Elinor\\u2019s heart wrung for the feelings of Edward, while braving his mother\\u2019s threats, for a woman who could not reward him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99761,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s heart thanked her for such kindness towards Edward, though she could not forbear smiling at the form of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100156,\n            \"Mrs. Jennings was very warm in her praise of Edward\\u2019s conduct, but only Elinor and Marianne understood its true merit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100225,\n            \"Elinor gloried in his integrity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100278,\n            \"Elinor avoided it upon principle, as tending to fix still more upon her thoughts, by the too warm, too positive assurances of Marianne, that belief of Edward\\u2019s continued affection for herself which she rather wished to do away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100683,\n            \"She saw nothing of the Willoughbys, nothing of Edward, and for some time nothing of anybody who could by any chance whether grave or gay, be interesting to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101176,\n            \"\\u201cWell, but Miss Dashwood,\\u201dspeaking triumphantly, \\u201cpeople may say what they chuse about Mr. Ferrars\\u2019 s declaring he would not have Lucy, for it is no such thing I can tell you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102185,\n            \"\\u201chave you been repeating to me what you only learnt yourself by listening at the door?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103345,\n            \"but I know your friendship for me will make you pleased to hear such a good account of myself and my dear Edward, after all the troubles we have went through lately, therefore will make no more apologies, but proceed to say that, thank God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103423,\n            \"We have had great trials, and great persecutions, but however, at the same time, gratefully acknowledge many friends, yourself not the least among them, whose great kindness I shall always thankfully remember, as will Edward too, who I have told of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103474,\n            \"I am sure you will be glad to hear, as likewise dear Mrs. Jennings, I spent two happy hours with him yesterday afternoon, he would not hear of our parting, though earnestly did I, as I thought my duty required, urge him to it for prudence sake, and would have parted for ever on the spot, would he consent to it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105651,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor\\u2019s astonishment at this commission could hardly have been greater, had the Colonel been really making her an offer of his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107458,\n            \"How she should begin \\u2014 how she should express herself in her note to Edward, was now all her concern.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107602,\n            \"Elinor had just been congratulating herself, in the midst of her perplexity, that however difficult it might be to express herself properly by letter, it was at least preferable to giving the information by word of mouth, when her visitor entered, to force her upon this greatest exertion of all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107992,\n            \") Colonel Brandon, who was here only ten minutes ago, has desired me to say, that understanding you mean to take orders, he has great pleasure in offering you the living of Delaford now just vacant, and only wishes it were more valuable.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108041,\n            \"Allow me to congratulate you on having so respectable and well-judging a friend, and to join in his wish that the living \\u2014 it is about two hundred a-year \\u2014 were much more considerable, and such as might better enable you to \\u2014 as might be more than a temporary accommodation to yourself \\u2014 such, in short, as might establish all your views of happiness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108176,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes,\\u201dcontinued Elinor, gathering more resolution, as some of the worst was over, \\u201cColonel Brandon means it as a testimony of his concern for what has lately passed \\u2014 for the cruel situation in which the unjustifiable conduct of your family has placed you \\u2014 a concern which I am sure Marianne, myself, and all your friends, must share;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108308,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo,\\u201dreplied he, with sudden consciousness, \\u201cnot to find it in _ you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108329,\n            \"_ for I cannot be ignorant that to you, to your goodness, I owe it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108348,\n            \"\\u2014 I feel it \\u2014 I would express it if I could \\u2014 but, as you well know, I am no orator.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108381,\n            \"I do assure you that you owe it entirely, at least almost entirely, to your own merit, and Colonel Brandon\\u2019s discernment of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108498,\n            \"\\u201d Truth obliged her to acknowledge some small share in the action, but she was at the same time so unwilling to appear as the benefactress of Edward, that she acknowledged it with hesitation;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108551,\n            \"For a short time he sat deep in thought, after Elinor had ceased to speak;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108630,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIndeed,\\u201dreplied Elinor, \\u201cI believe that you will find him, on farther acquaintance, all that you have heard him to be, and as you will be such very near neighbours (for I understand the parsonage is almost close to the mansion-house,) it is particularly important that he _ should _ be all this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108704,\n            \"but when she had turned away her head, gave her a look so serious, so earnest, so uncheerful, as seemed to say, that he might hereafter wish the distance between the parsonage and the mansion-house much greater.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108775,\n            \"Elinor told him the number of the house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108784,\n            \"\\u201cI must hurry away then, to give him those thanks which you will not allow me to give _ you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108918,\n            \"\\u201d And with this pleasing anticipation, she sat down to reconsider the past, recall the words and endeavour to comprehend all the feelings of Edward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109758,\n            \"So far was she, at the same time, from any backwardness to give Elinor that credit which Edward _ would _ give her, that she spoke of her friendship for them both with the most grateful warmth, was ready to own all their obligation to her, and openly declared that no exertion for their good on Miss Dashwood\\u2019s part, either present or future, would ever surprise her, for she believed her capable of doing any thing in the world for those she really valued.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109929,\n            \"It was now above a week since John Dashwood had called in Berkeley Street, and as since that time no notice had been taken by them of his wife\\u2019s indisposition, beyond one verbal enquiry, Elinor began to feel it necessary to pay her a visit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110173,\n            \"He expressed great pleasure in meeting Elinor, told her that he had been just going to call in Berkeley Street, and, assuring her that Fanny would be very glad to see her, invited her to come in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110231,\n            \"\\u201cFanny is in her own room, I suppose,\\u201dsaid he: \\u201cI will go to her presently, for I am sure she will not have the least objection in the world to seeing _ you _.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110316,\n            \"\\u201cI am not sorry to see you alone,\\u201dhe replied, \\u201cfor I have a good deal to say to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110364,\n            \"\\u2014 I heard it yesterday by chance, and was coming to you on purpose to enquire farther about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110646,\n            \"and by relating that she had herself been employed in conveying the offer from Colonel Brandon to Edward, and, therefore, must understand the terms on which it was given, obliged him to submit to her authority.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110693,\n            \"\\u201d \\u2014 he cried, after hearing what she said \\u2014 \\u201cwhat could be the Colonel\\u2019s motive?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110749,\n            \"\\u2014 You will not mention the matter to Fanny, however, for though I have broke it to her, and she bears it vastly well, \\u2014 she will not like to hear it much talked of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110789,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor had some difficulty here to refrain from observing, that she thought Fanny might have borne with composure, an acquisition of wealth to her brother, by which neither she nor her child could be possibly impoverished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111055,\n            \"Elinor,\\u201dsaid John, \\u201cyour reasoning is very good, but it is founded on ignorance of human nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111261,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI only mean that I suppose, from your manner of speaking, it must be the same to Miss Morton whether she marry Edward or Robert.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111345,\n            \"\\u201d Elinor said no more, and John was also for a short time silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112200,\n            \"You must not judge of him, Miss Dashwood, from _ your _ slight acquaintance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113297,\n            \"She had no such object for her lingering thoughts to fix on, she left no creature behind, from whom it would give her a moment\\u2019s regret to be divided for ever, she was pleased to be free herself from the persecution of Lucy\\u2019s friendship, she was grateful for bringing her sister away unseen by Willoughby since his marriage, and she looked forward with hope to what a few months of tranquility at Barton might do towards restoring Marianne\\u2019s peace of mind, and confirming her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114610,\n            \"\\u2014 His behaviour to her in this, as well as in every other particular, his open pleasure in meeting her after an absence of only ten days, his readiness to converse with her, and his deference for her opinion, might very well justify Mrs. Jennings\\u2019 s persuasion of his attachment, and would have been enough, perhaps, had not Elinor still, as from the first, believed Marianne his real favourite, to make her suspect it herself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115097,\n            \"and when, at last, she went early to bed, more and more indisposed, Colonel Brandon was only astonished at her sister\\u2019s composure, who, though attending and nursing her the whole day, against Marianne\\u2019s inclination, and forcing proper medicines on her at night, trusted, like Marianne, to the certainty and efficacy of sleep, and felt no real alarm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133516,\n            \"Elinor grew impatient for some tidings of Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133525,\n            \"She had heard nothing of him since her leaving London, nothing new of his plans, nothing certain even of his present abode.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135723,\n            \"His countenance, as he entered the room, was not too happy, even for Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135833,\n            \"Elinor\\u2019s lips had moved with her mother\\u2019s, and, when the moment of action was over, she wished that she had shaken hands with him too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136170,\n            \"and though Elinor could not speak, even _ her _ eyes were fixed on him with the same impatient wonder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136277,\n            \"\\u201d His words were echoed with unspeakable astonishment by all but Elinor, who sat with her head leaning over her work, in a state of such agitation as made her hardly know where she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136602,\n            \"It was only to ask Elinor to marry him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136702,\n            \"\\u2014 that when they all sat down to table at four o\\u2019clock, about three hours after his arrival, he had secured his lady, engaged her mother\\u2019s consent, and was not only in the rapturous profession of the lover, but, in the reality of reason and truth, one of the happiest of men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136901,\n            \"His heart was now open to Elinor, all its weaknesses, all its errors confessed, and his first boyish attachment to Lucy treated with all the philosophic dignity of twenty-four.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137003,\n            \"for though I left Longstaple with what I thought, at the time, a most unconquerable preference for his niece, yet had I then had any pursuit, any object to engage my time and keep me at a distance from her for a few months, I should very soon have outgrown the fancied attachment, especially by mixing more with the world, as in such case I must have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137364,\n            \"Mrs. Dashwood, too happy to be comfortable, knew not how to love Edward, nor praise Elinor enough, how to be enough thankful for his release without wounding his delicacy, nor how at once to give them leisure for unrestrained conversation together, and yet enjoy, as she wished, the sight and society of both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137658,\n            \"\\u2014 for whatever other claims might be made on him, it was impossible that less than a week should be given up to the enjoyment of Elinor\\u2019s company, or suffice to say half that was to be said of the past, the present, and the future;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137935,\n            \"Edward could only attempt an explanation by supposing, that, perhaps, at first accidentally meeting, the vanity of the one had been so worked on by the flattery of the other, as to lead by degrees to all the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137980,\n            \"Elinor remembered what Robert had told her in Harley Street, of his opinion of what his own mediation in his brother\\u2019s affairs might have done, if applied to in time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138219,\n            \"He put the letter into Elinor\\u2019s hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138229,\n            \"\\u201cDEAR SIR, \\u201cBeing very sure I have long lost your affections, I have thought myself at liberty to bestow my own on another, and have no doubt of being as happy with him as I once used to think I might be with you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138481,\n            \"\\u201cI will not ask your opinion of it as a composition,\\u201dsaid Edward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138681,\n            \"She will hardly be less hurt, I suppose, by Robert\\u2019s marrying Lucy, than she would have been by your marrying her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138958,\n            \"That Lucy had certainly meant to deceive, to go off with a flourish of malice against him in her message by Thomas, was perfectly clear to Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138988,\n            \"and Edward himself, now thoroughly enlightened on her character, had no scruple in believing her capable of the utmost meanness of wanton ill-nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139016,\n            \"Though his eyes had been long opened, even before his acquaintance with Elinor began, to her ignorance and a want of liberality in some of her opinions \\u2014 they had been equally imputed, by him, to her want of education;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139061,\n            \"and till her last letter reached him, he had always believed her to be a well-disposed, good-hearted girl, and thoroughly attached to himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139435,\n            \"Elinor scolded him, harshly as ladies always scold the imprudence which compliments themselves, for having spent so much time with them at Norland, when he must have felt his own inconstancy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139797,\n            \"But so little interest had he taken in the matter, that he owed all his knowledge of the house, garden, and glebe, extent of the parish, condition of the land, and rate of the tithes, to Elinor herself, who had heard so much of it from Colonel Brandon, and heard it with so much attention, as to be entirely mistress of the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139929,\n            \"Edward had two thousand pounds, and Elinor one, which, with Delaford living, was all that they could call their own;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140033,\n            \"for since Edward would still be unable to marry Miss Morton, and his chusing herself had been spoken of in Mrs. Ferrars\\u2019 s flattering language as only a lesser evil than his chusing Lucy Steele, she feared that Robert\\u2019s offence would serve no other purpose than to enrich Fanny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140932,\n            \"and he called on Elinor to join with him in regretting that Lucy\\u2019s engagement with Edward had not rather been fulfilled, than that she should thus be the means of spreading misery farther in the family.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141235,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou may certainly ask to be forgiven,\\u201dsaid Elinor, \\u201cbecause you have offended;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141255,\n            \"\\u2014 and I should think you might _ now _ venture so far as to profess some concern for having ever formed the engagement which drew on you your mother\\u2019s anger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141815,\n            \"_ but when she found that, though perfectly admitting the truth of her representation, he was by no means inclined to be guided by it, she judged it wisest, from the experience of the past, to submit \\u2014 and therefore, after such an ungracious delay as she owed to her own dignity, and as served to prevent every suspicion of good-will, she issued her decree of consent to the marriage of Edward and Elinor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142002,\n            \"It was as much, however, as was desired, and more than was expected, by Edward and Elinor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142046,\n            \"With an income quite sufficient to their wants thus secured to them, they had nothing to wait for after Edward was in possession of the living, but the readiness of the house, to which Colonel Brandon, with an eager desire for the accommodation of Elinor, was making considerable improvements;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142230,\n            \"for she was able to visit Edward and his wife in their Parsonage by Michaelmas, and she found in Elinor and her husband, as she really believed, one of the happiest couples in the world.\"\n        ]\n    ]\n}"